B041C007V009	41	7	9	"It is praiseworthy, is it," he exclaimed, "to reject the command of God that you may keep your tradition!
B041C007V010	41	7	10	For although Moses said, Honor your father and mother, and Let him who curses father or mother suffer death,
B041C007V011	41	7	11	you say that if a man tells his father or mother, This money which otherwise you would have received from me, is Korban (that is, a thing devoted to God),
B041C007V012	41	7	12	you exempt him from doing any service for his father or mother.
B041C007V013	41	7	13	Thus by your tradition which you have handed down you set at naught the word of God; and you do many other things like that."
B041C007V014	41	7	14	Then again he called the crowd to him and said.
B041C007V015	41	7	15	"Listen to me, all of you, and understand; there is nothing outside a man which by entering in can defile him; but it is what comes from him that defiled him."
B041C007V017	41	7	17	After he had left the crowd and gone indoors his disciples began asking him about the parable.
B041C007V018	41	7	18	"Are even you without understanding?" he said. "Do you not perceive that nothing whatever from without can defile a man by entering him,
B041C007V019	41	7	19	because it does not go into his heart, but into his belly, and passes away, ejected from him?" By these words he pronounced all foods clean.
B041C007V020	41	7	20	"What comes out of a man," he continued, "is what defiles him.
B041C007V021	41	7	21	From within, from the heart of man, proceed evil purposes -
B041C007V022	41	7	22	fornication, theft, murder, adultery, greed, malice, deceit,  wantonness, envy, slander, arrogance, reckless folly -
B041C007V023	41	7	23	all these wicked things issue from within and defile a man."
B041C007V024	41	7	24	After he rose and left that place, he went away into the region of Tyre and Sidon. Here he went into a house and wished no one to know it but he could not be hid.
B041C007V025	41	7	25	Forthwith a woman whose little daughter was possessed by an unclean spirit, heard of him, and came and fell at his feet
B041C007V026	41	7	26	(the woman was a Greek, a Syro-phoenician by race), and again and again she begged him to cast the demon out of her daughter.
B041C007V027	41	7	27	"Let the children be filled first," he said to her. "It is unseemly to take the childrens bread and throw it to the dogs."
B041C007V028	41	7	28	"True, Master," she answered, "but the dogs under the table do pick up the childrens crumbs."
B041C007V029	41	7	29	"For that saying of yours, go home," he replied; "the demon has departed from your daughter."
B041C007V030	41	7	30	So she went home, and found the child lying in her bed and the demon departed.
