B044C011V012	44	11	12	"And the Spirit bade me accompany them without misgiving. There also accompanied me these six brothers, and we went into the mans house.
B044C011V013	44	11	13	"Then he told us how he had seen the angel standing in his house and saying. "Send to Joppa and fetch Simon who is also called Peter.
B044C011V014	44	11	14	"He will speak words to you by which you and all your family will be saved.
B044C011V015	44	11	15	"And," said Peter, "as soon as I began to speak, the Holy Spirit fell upon them, just as he fell upon us at the beginning.
B044C011V016	44	11	16	"Then I remembered the words of the Lord, how he used to say, "John indeed baptized in water, but you shall be baptized in the Holy Spirit.
B044C011V017	44	11	17	"So if God gave them the same gift as he gave to us, when we first believed on the Lord Jesus Christ, who was I that I could withstand God?"
B044C011V018	44	11	18	On hearing this they held their peace and glorified God, saying,  "Forsooth then, to the Gentiles also God has granted repentance unto life."
B044C011V019	44	11	19	Then those who had been scattered by the trouble that arose over Stephen, traveled as far as Phoenicia and Cyprus and Antioch; but they preached the word to none except Jews.
B044C011V020	44	11	20	Some of them, however, were Cyprians and Cyrenaeans, who, on reaching Antioch, began to tell the Greeks also the Good News concerning the Lord Jesus.
B044C011V021	44	11	21	The hand of the Lord was with them, and a great number who believed turned to the Lord.
B044C011V022	44	11	22	When news of this reached the ears of the church at Jerusalem, they sent Barnabas as far as Antioch.
B044C011V023	44	11	23	When he arrived, and saw the grace of God, he was glad, and he encouraged them all to remain faithful to the Lord, with full purpose of heart;
B044C011V024	44	11	24	for he was a good man, and full of faith and the Holy Spirit. And a great multitude was added to the Lord.
B044C011V025	44	11	25	Then Barnabas visited Tarsus, to try to find Saul,
B044C011V026	44	11	26	and when he had found him he brought him to Antioch, where for a whole year they were guests of the church, and taught many people.  And it was in Antioch that the disciples first received the name of "Christians."
B044C011V027	44	11	27	At that time some prophets came down from Jerusalem to Antioch.
B044C011V028	44	11	28	One of them, who was Agabus, rose up, and being instructed by the Spirit, predicted that a great famine was about to come upon the whole inhabited earth. (It came in the reign of Claudius.)
B044C011V029	44	11	29	So the disciples decided to send relief, every man according to his means, to the brothers in Judea.
B044C011V030	44	11	30	This they did, forwarding their contributions to the elders by the hand of Barnabas and Saul.
B044C012V001	44	12	1	Now, at about that time, Herod the king put forth his hands to ill-  treat certain members of the church;
B044C012V002	44	12	2	and beheaded James, the brother of John, with the sword.
B044C012V003	44	12	3	And when he saw that it pleased the Jews, he proceeded to seize Peter also. (This was during the days of unleavened bread.)
B044C012V004	44	12	4	He had him arrested and thrown in prison, and put under guard of sixteen soldiers. He intended, after the Passover, to bring him forth to the people.
B044C012V005	44	12	5	So Peter was kept in prison, but earnest prayer to God was made by the church for him.
B044C012V006	44	12	6	Now when Herod was about to bring him forth, on that very night,  while Peter was sleeping between two soldiers, bound with chains, and sentries before the door were guarding the prison,
B044C012V007	44	12	7	suddenly an angel of the Lord stood by him, and a light shone in the cell. Striking Peter on the side, he woke him saying, "Rise up quickly." At once the chains dropped from his hands.
B044C012V008	44	12	8	"Gird yourself," said the angel, "and put on your sandals." He did so. Then he said unto him, "Throw your cloak about you, and follow me."
B044C012V009	44	12	9	So Peter went out, following him, but did not realize that what the angel was doing was real, but supposed that he was seeing a vision.
B044C012V010	44	12	10	And when they had passed the first guard and the second, they came to the iron gate that led to the city. This opened to them of its own accord; and they went out passed on through one street; and suddenly the angel left him.
B044C012V011	44	12	11	Peter, coming to himself, said, "Now I know for a certainty that the Lord has sent his angel and released me from the hand of Herod, and from all that the Jewish people were anticipating."
B044C012V012	44	12	12	So, after he had thought things over, he went to the house of Mary,  the mother of John, surnamed Mark, where a large number of people were assembled, praying.
B044C012V013	44	12	13	When he knocked at the door of the gate, a maid servant named Rhoda came to answer.
B044C012V014	44	12	14	And when she recognized Peters voice, for very joy she did not open the door, but ran in and told them that Peter was standing in front of the gate.
B044C012V015	44	12	15	"You are mad," they said. But she confidently insisted that it was so. "It is his angel," they said.
B044C012V016	44	12	16	Meanwhile Peter continued to knock, until at last they opened the door, and were amazed to see that it was really he.
B044C012V017	44	12	17	He motioned to them to keep quiet, and told them how the Lord had brought him out of prison. "Tell all this to James," he said, "and to the brothers," and away he went to another place.
B044C012V018	44	12	18	When morning came there was no small stir among the soldiers as to what could possibly have become of Peter.
B044C012V019	44	12	19	Then Herod had search made for him, and could not find him. After sharply questioning the guards, he ordered them off to execution. He then went down from Judea to Caesarea, where he stayed for some time.
B044C012V020	44	12	20	Now Herod was violently displeased with the people of Tyre and Sidon. So they came to him, with one accord, and after conciliating Blastus, the royal chamberlain, they begged for peace because their country depended upon the kings country for its food supply.
B044C012V021	44	12	21	So on the appointed day, Herod put on his royal robes, and after taking his seat upon the throne, began to harangue them.
B044C012V022	44	12	22	"The voice of a god, and not of a man," the people kept shouting.
B044C012V023	44	12	23	Instantly an angel of the Lord smote him, because he had not given God the glory, and being eaten up by worms, he died.
B044C012V024	44	12	24	But the word of God grew and multiplied;
B044C012V025	44	12	25	and after discharging their mission, Barnabas and Saul returned from Jerusalem, bringing with them John, surnamed Mark.
B044C013V001	44	13	1	Now there were in the church in Antioch prophets and teachers;  Barnabas and Symeon, surnamed "the Black," Lucius of Cyrene, Manaen,  the foster-brother of Herod the Tetrarch, and Saul.
B044C013V002	44	13	2	And as they were worshiping the Lord, and fasting, the Holy Spirit said to them, "Separate me Barnabas and Saul for the work to which I have called them."
B044C013V003	44	13	3	So after fasting and praying, they laid their hands on them, and let them go.
B044C013V004	44	13	4	So they, sent forth by the Holy Spirit, went down to Seleucia, and from thence they sailed to Cyprus.
B044C013V005	44	13	5	And while they were in Salamis, they proclaimed the word of God in the synagogues of the Jews.
B044C013V006	44	13	6	They had John Mark as an assistant; and after going through the whole island as far as Paphos, they found a certain Jewish sorcerer and false prophet, named Bar-Jesus,
B044C013V007	44	13	7	who belonged to the suite of the proconsul, Sergius Paulus, an intelligent man. He summoned Barnabas and Saul, and sought to hear the word of God.
B044C013V008	44	13	8	But Elymas, "the sorcerer," for that is the translation of his name,  opposed them, and tried to divert the proconsul from the faith.
B044C013V009	44	13	9	So Saul, who is also called Paul, filled with the Holy Spirit, gazed steadily at him, and said.
B044C013V010	44	13	10	"O full of all craft and cunning, you son of the devil! You enemy of all goodness! Will you never stop perverting the right ways of the Lord?
B044C013V011	44	13	11	"The Lords hand is now upon you, and you shall be blind, not seeing the sun for a season." Instantly there fell on him a mist and a darkness, and groping about, he sought some one to lead him by the hand.
B044C013V012	44	13	12	Then the proconsul, seeing what had happened, believed. He was astounded at the teaching of the Lord.
B044C013V013	44	13	13	From Paphos Paul and his party set sail for Perga in Pamphylia; but John Mark left them and went back to Jerusalem.
B044C013V014	44	13	14	Then they themselves, passing through from Perga, came to Antioch in Pisidia. Here they went into the synagogue on the Sabbath Day and sat down.
B044C013V015	44	13	15	And, after the reading of the Law and the Prophets, the wardens of the synagogue sent word to them. "Brothers," they said, "if you have any word of encouragement to the people, say it."
B044C013V016	44	13	16	So Paul stood up, and motioning with his hand, said. "Men of Israel,  and you who fear God, listen.
B044C013V017	44	13	17	"The God of this people of Israel chose our forefathers and made this people great, while they sojourned in the land of Egypt. And with an uplifted arm he led them out of it.
B044C013V018	44	13	18	"For about forty years he bore with them in the desert,
B044C013V019	44	13	19	"and when he had destroyed seven nations in the land of Canaan, he gave them their land as an inheritance for about four hundred and fifty years.
B044C013V020	44	13	20	"And afterwards he gave them Judges, until Samuel, the prophet.
B044C013V021	44	13	21	"Then they asked for a king, and he gave them Saul, the son of Kish,  a Benjamite for forty years.
B044C013V022	44	13	22	After deposing him, he raised up David to be their king, to whom he also bore witness, when he said, "I have found David, the son of Jesse, a man after my own heart, and who will obey all my will.
B044C013V023	44	13	23	"Of this mans descendants God has brought unto Israel, according to his promise, a Savior, Jesus;
B044C013V024	44	13	24	"before whose coming John had already preached a baptism of repentance to all the people of Israel.
B044C013V025	44	13	25	"And John, when he was finishing his race, repeatedly asked the people. "Who do you suppose that I am? I am not He. But behold there comes One after me, whose sandal I am not worthy to unfasten.
B044C013V026	44	13	26	"Brothers, sons of Abrahams race, and all among you who reverence God, to us has the word of this salvation been sent.
B044C013V027	44	13	27	"For those who dwell in Jerusalem, and their rulers, because they knew him not, nor the utterances of the prophets which are read every Sabbath, fulfilled them by condemning him.
B044C013V028	44	13	28	"Though they found no cause of death in him, yet they asked Pilate to put him to death.
B044C013V029	44	13	29	"And when they had fulfilled everything which had been written concerning him, they took him down from the tree and laid him in a tomb.
B044C013V030	44	13	30	"But God raised him from the dead.
B044C013V031	44	13	31	"For many days he was seen by those that came up with him from Galilee to Jerusalem, and are now his witnesses to the people.
B044C013V032	44	13	32	"And we bring you glad tidings of the promise made to our forefathers,
B044C013V033	44	13	33	"how that God fulfilled it for us their children in raising up Jesus; as it is also written in the second Psalm, "Thou art my son,  today have I become thy Father.
B044C013V034	44	13	34	"And as to his having raised him from among the dead, now no more to return to corruption, he has said this, "I will give thee the holy and sure blessings of David.
B044C013V035	44	13	35	"Because in another psalm he says, "Thou wilt not give thy Holy One to see corruption.
B044C013V036	44	13	36	"For David, after he had served his own generation according to the will of God, fell on sleep, and was gathered to his forefathers, and did see corruption;
B044C013V037	44	13	37	but he whom God raised up saw no corruption.
B044C013V038	44	13	38	"Be it known unto you therefore, brothers, that remission of sins is proclaimed to you through this man;
B044C013V039	44	13	39	"and that by him every one that believes is justified from all things from which you could never be justified by the law of Moses.
B044C013V040	44	13	40	"Beware, then, lest that spoken of in the prophets come upon you.
B044C013V041	44	13	41	"Behold, ye despisers, and wonder, and perish, For in your days I will do a deed, A deed which you will never believe, Though one should declare it unto you."
B044C013V042	44	13	42	As Paul and Barnabas left the synagogue, the people earnestly begged that these words might be repeated to them on the following Sabbath.
B044C013V043	44	13	43	When the congregation broke up, many of the Jews, and of the devout proselytes, followed Paul and Barnabas, who talked to them, and urged them to continue in the grace of God.
B044C013V044	44	13	44	On the next Sabbath almost the entire city was gathered together to know the word of God.
B044C013V045	44	13	45	When they saw the crowds, the Jews were filled with jealousy, and began to contradict Pauls statements, and to abuse him.
B044C013V046	44	13	46	So Paul and Barnabas spoke out boldly. "It was necessary," they said, "first to proclaim the word of God to you. But since you push it away from you, and judge yourselves unworthy of eternal life, lo,  we turn to the Gentiles.
B044C013V047	44	13	47	"For such is Gods command to us, saying, "I have set thee for a light to the Gentiles, That thou shouldest be for salvation to the uttermost part of the earth."
B044C013V048	44	13	48	When the Gentiles heard this, they were glad, and glorified the word of the Lord, and all who had been ordained to eternal life, believed.
B044C013V049	44	13	49	So the Lords message went far and wide, through the whole district.
B044C013V050	44	13	50	But the Jews urged on the devout women of high rank, and the leading citizens, and stirred up a persecution against Paul and Barnabas, and drove them out of the district,
B044C013V051	44	13	51	But they shook off the dust of their feet against them, and came to Iconium.
B044C013V052	44	13	52	As for the disciples, they were continually filled with joy, and with the Holy Spirit.
B044C014V001	44	14	1	In Iconium it happened that they went together to the synagogue of the Jews, and so spoke that a great number both of Jews and of Gentiles believed.
B044C014V002	44	14	2	But the disobedient Jews stirred up the souls of the Gentiles, and embittered them against them against the brothers.
B044C014V003	44	14	3	Long time, therefore, they tarried there, speaking fearlessly in the Lord, who attested the word of his grace by permitting signs and wonders to be performed by their hands.
B044C014V004	44	14	4	But the mass of the citys people was divided; part held with the Jews, and part with the apostles.
B044C014V005	44	14	5	And when both the Gentiles and the Jews with their ruler made a hostile move to maltreat and to stone them,
B044C014V006	44	14	6	the apostles got wind of it, and made their escape to the Lycaonian towns of Derbe and Lystra and the neighboring country.
B044C014V007	44	14	7	And there they continued to proclaim the gospel.
B044C014V008	44	14	8	Now at Lystra there used to sit a certain man, lame in his feet, a cripple from birth, who had never walked.
B044C014V009	44	14	9	He was listening while Paul was preaching, and Paul, looking intently at him, and perceiving that he had faith to be made whole,
B044C014V010	44	14	10	said in a loud voice, "Stand upright on your feet!"
B044C014V011	44	14	11	And he sprang up and began to walk about. Then the crowds, when they saw what Paul had done, shouted in the Lycaonian tongue, saying, "The gods are come down to us in human form."
B044C014V012	44	14	12	And they began to call Barnabas "Zeus," and Paul, since he was the principal speaker, "Hermes";
B044C014V013	44	14	13	and the priest of Zeus, whose temple was at the entrance to the city, brought oxen and garlands to the gates, and along with the crowds was about to offer sacrifices.
B044C014V014	44	14	14	But when the apostles, Paul and Barnabas, heard of it, they rent their garments and rushed out among the crowd, shouting and crying.
B044C014V015	44	14	15	"Men, why are you doing all this? We also are men, with natures like your own! We are bringing you good tidings, that you are to turn from these empty things to the living God, who made heaven and earth and the sea and all that in them is.
B044C014V016	44	14	16	In bygone generations he allowed all the nations to walk in their own ways,
B044C014V017	44	14	17	and yet he left not himself without witness, in that he did good,  and gave you rain from heaven and fruitful seasons, filling your hearts with food and gladness."
B044C014V018	44	14	18	Even with saying this they with difficulty restrained the crowds from sacrificing to them.
B044C014V019	44	14	19	And now a party of Jews came down form Antioch and Iconium, and after persuading the crowds, they stoned Paul and dragged him out of the city, supposing him to be dead.
B044C014V020	44	14	20	But as the disciples collected around him, he rose and went back into the city. The next day he went off with Barnabas into Derbe;
B044C014V021	44	14	21	and after preaching the gospel to that town, and winning many converts, they went back to Lystra and Iconium and Antioch,
B044C014V022	44	14	22	Everywhere they strengthened the souls of the disciples, encouraging them to hold to the faith. "It is through many tribulations," they said, "that we must enter into the kingdom of God."
B044C014V023	44	14	23	They chose elders for them in every church, after prayer and fasting, and commended them to the Lord in whom they had believed.
B044C014V024	44	14	24	Then passing through Pisidia they came to Pamphylia and,
B044C014V025	44	14	25	after preaching the word in Perga, they came down to Attaleia.
B044C014V026	44	14	26	Thence they sailed to Antioch, from whence they had been commended to the grace of God, for the work which they had now completed.
B044C014V027	44	14	27	On their arrival they assembled the church and reported all things that God had done through them, and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.
B044C014V028	44	14	28	And they tarried no little time with the disciples.
B044C015V001	44	15	1	But some men came down from Judea and attempted to teach the brethren, saying, "Unless you are circumcised according to Moses  custom, you cannot be saved."
B044C015V002	44	15	2	Now when dispute and controversy sprang up between them and Paul and Barnabas, the brethren appointed Paul and Barnabas, and certain others, to go up to Jerusalem to see the apostles and elders about this question.
B044C015V003	44	15	3	So the church saw them off on their journey, and they passed through both Phoenicia and Samaria. Here they set forth the conversion of the Gentiles, and brought great joy to all the brothers.
B044C015V004	44	15	4	Upon their arrival in Jerusalem they were received by the church and the apostles and elders, and they told them all things that God had done with them.
B044C015V005	44	15	5	But certain men who had belonged to the sect of the Pharisees, but were now believers, stood up and said, "It is necessary to circumcise Gentile, and to order them to keep the Law of Moses."
B044C015V006	44	15	6	The apostles and elders met to consider the matter;
B044C015V007	44	15	7	and after there had been a long discussion, Peter rose and said.  "Brothers, you know how a good while ago God made choice among you,  that from my lips the Gentiles were to hear the message of the gospel and believe.
B044C015V008	44	15	8	"And God, who knows the hearts of all, gave this testimony in their behalf, by bestowing upon them the Holy Spirit just as he did upon us;
B044C015V009	44	15	9	"and he made no distinction between us and them, in cleansing their hearts by faith.
B044C015V010	44	15	10	"Now then, why are you tempting God by laying on the necks of these disciples a yoke which neither our forefathers nor we have been able to bear?
B044C015V011	44	15	11	"On the contrary we believe that it is by the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ that we and they shall be saved."
B044C015V012	44	15	12	Then the whole assembly remained silent, and listened to Barnabas and Saul as they told the signs and wonders which God had wrought among the Gentiles through them.
B044C015V013	44	15	13	When they had finished speaking, James said.
B044C015V014	44	15	14	"Brothers, listen to me. Symeon has told how God first looked graciously upon the Gentiles, to take out from among them a people to be called by his name.
B044C015V015	44	15	15	"And this is in harmony with the language of the prophets, which says.
B044C015V016	44	15	16	"After these things I will return, And I will rebuild Davids fallen tent; And I will build again its ruins, And I will set it up;
B044C015V017	44	15	17	"So that the rest of men may seek after the Lord, Even all the Gentiles, who are called by my name,
B044C015V018	44	15	18	"Says the Lord, who has been making this known from the beginning of the world.
B044C015V019	44	15	19	"My judgment therefore, is against troubling those who turn to God from among the Gentiles;
B044C015V020	44	15	20	"but that we should write to them to abstain from the pollution of idols and from fornication, from meat killed by strangling, and from blood.
B044C015V021	44	15	21	"For Moses from the earliest times has had his preachers in every town where he is read aloud, Sabbath after Sabbath, in the synagogues."
B044C015V022	44	15	22	Then it seemed good to the apostles and the elders, together with the whole church, to select some of their number, and to send them to Antioch with Paul and Barnabas. The men chosen were Judas called Bar-  Sabbas, and Silas, leading men among the brethren.
B044C015V023	44	15	23	They took with them the following letter. "The apostles and older brothers send greeting to the Gentile Brotherhood throughout Antioch and Syria and Cilicia;
B044C015V024	44	15	24	"as we have heard that some of your number who went out from us have troubled you with words and upset your souls, without having received any such instruction from us;
B044C015V025	44	15	25	"we have unanimously decided to select certain men, and to send them to you with our beloved Barnabas and Paul;
B044C015V026	44	15	26	"men who have risked their very lives for the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B044C015V027	44	15	27	"So we have sent Judas and Silas to tell you the same things by word of mouth.
B044C015V028	44	15	28	"For it has seemed good to the Holy Ghost and to us, to lay upon you no greater burden than these necessary things;
B044C015V029	44	15	29	"that you abstain from food that has been sacrificed to idols, and from tasting blood, and from things strangled, and from fornication.  Keep yourselves clear from these things and it will be well with you.  Farewell."
B044C015V030	44	15	30	So they, when they had been despatched, went down to Antioch, and after gathering the whole multitude together, they handed them the letter,
B044C015V031	44	15	31	and when they had read it they rejoiced at the comfort it brought.
B044C015V032	44	15	32	And Judas and Silas, who were themselves prophets, encouraged and strengthened the brothers with many a good counsel.
B044C015V033	44	15	33	After spending some time there the brothers let them go with a greeting of peace to those who had sent them.
B044C015V034	44	15	34	Silas, however, stayed with them.
B044C015V035	44	15	35	Paul and Barnabas also stayed in Antioch teaching and proclaiming the word of the Lord, in company with others.
B044C015V036	44	15	36	And after some days Paul said to Barnabas, "Let is go back and visit the brothers in every city in which we have proclaimed the word of the Lord. Let us see how they fare."
B044C015V037	44	15	37	Now Barnabas wanted to take with them John, who was called Mark.
B044C015V038	44	15	38	But Paul thought it unwise to take with them one who had deserted them to the Pamphylia, and had not gone on with them to the work.
B044C015V039	44	15	39	So there arose a sharp irritation, so that they parted company;  Barnabas taking Mark with him, sailed away to Cyprus;
B044C015V040	44	15	40	while Paul chose Silas, and set forth commended by the brothers to the grace of God.
B044C015V041	44	15	41	He went through Syria and Cilicia, strengthening the churches.
B044C016V001	44	16	1	And he came also to Derbe and Lystra, where there was a certain disciple named Timothy, the son of a believing Jewess, and of a Greek father.
B044C016V002	44	16	2	He was well spoken of by the brothers in Lystra and Iconiun.
B044C016V003	44	16	3	Now Paul, wishing that this man should accompany him on his journey,  took him and circumcised him because of the local Jews, who all knew that his father was a Greek.
B044C016V004	44	16	4	And as they went on their way through the cities they handed them the resolutions which the apostles and the elders in Jerusalem had ordained for them to keep.
B044C016V005	44	16	5	So the churches were strengthened in the faith and continued to increase in number daily.
B044C016V006	44	16	6	Then they went through Phrygia and Galatia, the Holy Spirit having forbidden them to proclaim the message in Asia.
B044C016V007	44	16	7	When they got as far as Mysia, they attempted to enter Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus would not permit it;
B044C016V008	44	16	8	and so they passed by Mysia and went on down to Troas.
B044C016V009	44	16	9	Here a vision appeared to Paul in the night. There stood a man of Macedonia, entreating him and saying, "Come over into Macedonia and help us!"
B044C016V010	44	16	10	So when he had seen the vision, we sought at once to go forth into Macedonia, because we concluded that God had called us to preach the gospel to them.
B044C016V011	44	16	11	So we set sail from Troas and ran a straight course to Samothrace.  The next day we arrived in Neapolis,
B044C016V012	44	16	12	and thence came to Philippi, a city of Macedonia, the fore most in its district, a Roman colony. There we stayed for some time.
B044C016V013	44	16	13	On the Sabbath Day we went outside the city gate, to a riverside,  where we supposed there was a place of prayer; and we sat down and talked to the women who had gathered there.
B044C016V014	44	16	14	Among them was a certain woman named Lydia, a seller of purple, who belonged to the town of Thyatira. She, since she was a worshiper of God, listened to us, and the Lord opened her heart to attend to what Paul said.
B044C016V015	44	16	15	When she was baptized, and her household, she urged us, saying, "If in your judgment I am a believer in the Lord, come and stay at my house." And she compelled us to come.
B044C016V016	44	16	16	Now as we were going to the place of prayer, a certain slave girl met us, who had a spirit of divination, and who brought her masters great gain by fortune-telling.
B044C016V017	44	16	17	She used to follow after Paul and us, crying out again and again,  "These men are servants of the most high God, who proclaimed to you the way of salvation."
B044C016V018	44	16	18	She persisted in this for many days, until Paul, worn out, turned round and said to the spirit, "I charge you, in the name of Jesus Christ, to come out of her." In that very hour it came out of her.
B044C016V019	44	16	19	But when her owners saw that their hopes of gain were gone, they seized Paul and Silas, and dragged them before the magistrates, into the market-place.
B044C016V020	44	16	20	Then they brought them before the praetors, saying. "These fellows are Jews, who are making a great disturbance in our city.
B044C016V021	44	16	21	"They are teaching customs which it is not lawful for us as Romans to adopt or practise."
B044C016V022	44	16	22	The crowd, too, rose up together against them, and the praetors,  after having them stripped, and after ordering them to be flogged,
B044C016V023	44	16	23	had many lashes inflicted upon them, and put them in prison, with a charge to the jailer to keep them safe.
B044C016V024	44	16	24	On receiving so strict an order he cast them into the inner prison,  and made their feet fast in the stocks.
B044C016V025	44	16	25	But at midnight, while Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the prisoners were listening to them,
B044C016V026	44	16	26	suddenly there was a great earthquake, so that the very foundations of the prison-house were shaken; and instantly all the doors were opened, and every ones chains fell off.
B044C016V027	44	16	27	The jailer, roused from sleep, and seeing the doors wide open, drew his sword and was about to kill himself, because he thought that the prisoners had escaped.
B044C016V028	44	16	28	But Paul shouted loudly to him. "Do yourself no harm; for we are all here!"
B044C016V029	44	16	29	So he called for lights, and sprang in, and, trembling for fear,  fell down before Paul and Silas,
B044C016V030	44	16	30	and brought them out, saying, "Sirs, what must I do to be saved?"
B044C016V031	44	16	31	"Believe on the Lord Jesus," they answered, "and you will be saved,  you and all your household."
B044C016V032	44	16	32	Then they spoke the message of the Lord to him, as well as to all who were in his house.
B044C016V033	44	16	33	And he took them, the same hour of the night, and washed their wounds, and he was baptized at once, he and all his.
B044C016V034	44	16	34	And after bringing them up into his house, he set food before them,  overjoyed with all his household in having believed in God.
B044C016V035	44	16	35	But in the morning the praetors sent their lictors with the order,  "Let these men go."
B044C016V036	44	16	36	The jailer reported the words to Paul, saying. "The praetors have sent to release you; so come out, and go in peace."
B044C016V037	44	16	37	But Paul said. "They have flogged us publicly, uncondemned, men that are Roman citizens; and have thrown us into prison. Are they now going to get rid of us secretly? No, indeed! Let them come here,  themselves and take us out."
B044C016V038	44	16	38	The lictors reported these words to the praetors, who were frightened when they heard that they were Romans.
B044C016V039	44	16	39	So they came and conciliated them, and after taking them out of prison, begged them to leave the town.
B044C016V040	44	16	40	So Paul and Silas came out of the prison, and went to Lydias house;  and after they had seen the brethren and encouraged them, they left Philippi.
B044C017V001	44	17	1	Now when they had gone through Amphipolis and Apollonia, they came to Thessalonica. Here there was a Jewish synagogue,
B044C017V002	44	17	2	and Paul, according to his usual custom, went in to them and, for three Sabbath Days, he reasoned with them out of the Scriptures,
B044C017V003	44	17	3	explaining and quoting passages to prove that the Messiah had to suffer and to rise again from the dead and that "This Jesus whom I am proclaiming unto you is the Messiah."
B044C017V004	44	17	4	Some were persuaded and attached themselves to Paul and Silas,  including a number of devout Greeks, and a large number of the leading women.
B044C017V005	44	17	5	But the Jews, moved with jealousy, called to their aid certain ill-  favored and idle fellows, formed a mob, and began to set the town in an uproar. Assaulting the house of Jason, they sought to bring them out to the people.
B044C017V006	44	17	6	And when they had failed to find Paul and Silas, they began to drag Jason and some of the brethren before the politarchs, shouting.  "These fellows who have upset the habitable earth are come hither also.
B044C017V007	44	17	7	"Jason has received them, and they all act contrary to the decrees of Caesar, saying that there is another king, one Jesus."
B044C017V008	44	17	8	Both the crowd and the politarchs were disturbed when they heard this,
B044C017V009	44	17	9	but when they had taken security from Jason and the rest, they let them go.
B044C017V010	44	17	10	Now the brothers sent Paul and Silas away by night to Berea. When they got there they betook themselves to the Jewish synagogue.
B044C017V011	44	17	11	The Jews of Berea were more noble than those in Thessalonica, in that they very readily received the message with all readiness of mind, and day after day searched the Scriptures to see whether these things were so.
B044C017V012	44	17	12	So many of them became believers, and so did not a few Greeks, women of honorable estate, and men.
B044C017V013	44	17	13	As soon as the Jews in Thessalonica learned that the word of God was preached by Paul in Berea also, they came there, and stirred up and troubled the crowds.
B044C017V014	44	17	14	Then the brothers at once sent Paul down to the sea, but Silas and Timothy remained behind.
B044C017V015	44	17	15	Those who were caring for Paul brought him as far as Athens, and there left him, with instructions to Silas and Timothy to come to him with all speed.
B044C017V016	44	17	16	While Paul was waiting for them at Athens, his spirit was stirred within him, when he noticed that the city was full of idols.
B044C017V017	44	17	17	He argued in the synagogues with the Jews and the devout proselytes,  and also daily in the market-place with those that met him there.
B044C017V018	44	17	18	A few of the Epicurean and Stoic philosophers also encountered him again and again. Some were saying, "What has this beggarly fellow to say?" Others said, "He seems to be a setter forth of strange gods,"  because he preached Jesus and the resurrection.
B044C017V019	44	17	19	Then they laid hold of him and brought him up to Mars Hill, saying.  "May we be told what this new teaching of yours is?
B044C017V020	44	17	20	"For you are bringing certain strange things to our ears. We want to know, therefore, what these things mean."
B044C017V021	44	17	21	(Now all the Athenians and the strangers sojourning there spent their time in nothing else, but to tell or to hear some new thing.)
B044C017V022	44	17	22	So Paul stood up in the center of Mars Hill, and said. "Men of Athens, I perceive that in all respects you are remarkably religious.
B044C017V023	44	17	23	"For as I was passing along and observing your objects of worship, I found also an altar with this inscription, TO AN UNKNOWN GOD. What you are worshiping in ignorance, this I am proclaiming to you.
B044C017V024	44	17	24	"The God who made the universe and all things in it, he, being Lord of heaven and earth, does not dwell in temples made with hands,
B044C017V025	44	17	25	"neither is he served by mens hands, as though he needed anything,  since he himself gives to all life and breath and all things.
B044C017V026	44	17	26	"He has made of one blood every nation of men to dwell on all the face of the earth, having determined their appointed seasons and the bounds of their habitation,
B044C017V027	44	17	27	"so that they might seek God, if perhaps they might feel after him and find him, though he is not far from every on of us;
B044C017V028	44	17	28	"for in him we live and move and have our being; as certain even of your own poets have said, "For we also are his offspring.
B044C017V029	44	17	29	"Since then we are Gods offspring, we ought not to imagine that the Godhead is like to gold, or silver, or stone, graven by art and device of man.
B044C017V030	44	17	30	"The times of ignorance God overlooked, but he now commands all men that they should all, everywhere, repent;
B044C017V031	44	17	31	inasmuch as he has fixed a day in which he will judge the world justly, by the Man whom he has ordained, and he has given proof of all this by raising him from the dead."
B044C017V032	44	17	32	But on hearing of the resurrection of the dead, some began to mock;  but others said, "We will hear you again on that subject."
B044C017V033	44	17	33	So Paul withdrew from them.
B044C017V034	44	17	34	A few, however, attached themselves to him and believed, among whom was Dionysius the Areopagite, and a woman named Damaris, and some others.
B044C018V001	44	18	1	After this Paul left Athens and went to Corinth.
B044C018V002	44	18	2	Here he found a certain Jew named Aquila, a native of Pontus, who had recently come from Italy with his wife, Priscilla, because Claudius had ordered all Jews to leave Rome.
B044C018V003	44	18	3	Paul came to them, and because he was of the same trade with them,  he lodged with them, and worked with them - for by trade they were tentmakers.
B044C018V004	44	18	4	Every Sabbath he used to preach in the synagogue, and tried to persuade both Jews and Greeks.
B044C018V005	44	18	5	And when Silas and Timothy arrived from Macedonia, Paul was engrossed in his message, earnestly testifying to the Jews that Jesus was the Messiah.
B044C018V006	44	18	6	But as they opposed him and abused him, he shook out his garments in protest, and said. "Your blood be upon your own hands. I am clean.  From now on I will go to the Gentiles."
B044C018V007	44	18	7	So he left the place, and went into the house of a man named Titus Justus, a worshiper of God, whose house adjoined the synagogue.
B044C018V008	44	18	8	And Crispus, the warden of the synagogue, believed on the Lord, with all his household; and many of the Corinthians from time to time listened, believed, and were baptized.
B044C018V009	44	18	9	And the Lord said to Paul in a vision, by night. "Have no fear; go on speaking, and do not keep silent;
B044C018V010	44	18	10	"for I am with you, and no one shall set upon you to injure you; for I have very many people in this city."
B044C018V011	44	18	11	So he lived there a year and six months and continued to teach them the word of God.
B044C018V012	44	18	12	But when Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews with one accord rose against Paul, and brought him before the tribunal.
B044C018V013	44	18	13	"This fellow," they said, "is persuading men to offer unlawful worship to God."
B044C018V014	44	18	14	Paul was about to open his mouth, when Gallio said to the Jews. "If it had been some misdemeanor or wicked villainy, it would have been within reason for me to listen to you Jews;
B044C018V015	44	18	15	but as these are merely questions about words and names and your own law, you yourselves must see to it. I am not willing to be a judge of these matters."
B044C018V016	44	18	16	And he drove them from the tribunal.
B044C018V017	44	18	17	Then they all laid hold of Sosthenes, the warden of the synagogue,  and beat him in front of the tribunal; but Gallio took no notice.
B044C018V018	44	18	18	And Paul after remaining in Corinth some time longer, took leave of the brothers, and sailed away to Syria, accompanied by Priscilla and Aquila. As Paul was under a vow, he had his head shaved at Cenchrea.
B044C018V019	44	18	19	When they came to Ephesus he left them there; but he himself entered into the synagogue and reasoned with the Jews.
B044C018V020	44	18	20	When they begged him to stay longer, he would not consent,
B044C018V021	44	18	21	but said, as he took leave of them, "I will return again to you, if God will."
B044C018V022	44	18	22	Then, setting sail from Ephesus, he landed at Caesarea; he went up to Jerusalem and saluted the church, and came down to Antioch.
B044C018V023	44	18	23	After spending some time there, he set out and went through the region of Galatia and Phrygia, in order, and strengthened all the disciples.
B044C018V024	44	18	24	Now a certain Jew named Apollos, a native of Alexandria, a learned man and mighty in the Scriptures, came to Ephesus.
B044C018V025	44	18	25	He had been instructed in the ways of the Lord, and being full of zeal, he used to speak and to teach accurately the facts about Jesus,  although he knew only the baptism of John.
B044C018V026	44	18	26	He began to speak boldly in the synagogue; and when Priscilla and Aquila heard him they took him home and explained to him more accurately the way of God.
B044C018V027	44	18	27	When he wished to cross over into Achaia, the brothers encouraged him, and wrote to the disciples in Corinth to receive him. On his arrival he mightily helped those who through grace had believed,
B044C018V028	44	18	28	for he powerfully refuted the Jews in public argument, proving to them from the Scriptures that Jesus is the Messiah.
B044C019V001	44	19	1	Now it happened that while Apollos was in Corinth, Paul, after passing through the hinterland, came to Ephesus, where he found a few disciples.
B044C019V002	44	19	2	"Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?" he asked them.  "No" said they, "we did not even hear that there is a Holy Spirit."
B044C019V003	44	19	3	"Into what, then, were you baptized?" he asked. And they said, "Into the baptism of John."
B044C019V004	44	19	4	"John indeed baptized with the baptism of repentance," answered Paul, "telling the people to believe on One who was coming after him,  namely, on Jesus."
B044C019V005	44	19	5	When they heard this they were baptized into the name of the Lord Jesus;
B044C019V006	44	19	6	and after Paul had laid his hands on them, the Holy Spirit came upon them, and they began to speak with tongues, and to prophesy.
B044C019V007	44	19	7	They were in all about twelve men.
B044C019V008	44	19	8	Then Paul went into the synagogue, and there continued to preach fearlessly for about three months, reasoning and persuading them about the kingdom of God.
B044C019V009	44	19	9	But when some grew hardened and disobedient, and spoke evil of the Way before the crowd, he left them, withdrew the disciples, and continued to hold discussions daily in the lecture-hall of Tyrannus.
B044C019V010	44	19	10	This went on for two years, so that all the inhabitants of Asia heard the Lords message, Jews as well as Greeks.
B044C019V011	44	19	11	God also wrought extraordinary miracles by the hand of Paul;
B044C019V012	44	19	12	so much so, that handkerchiefs or aprons were carried away from his body to the sick; and their diseases departed from them, and the evil spirits went out.
B044C019V013	44	19	13	But there were also some strolling Jewish exorcists, who took it upon them to invoke the name of Jesus over those who had evil spirits, saying, "I adjure you by that Jesus whom Paul preaches."
B044C019V014	44	19	14	There were seven sons of one Sceva, a Jewish high priest who used to do this.
B044C019V015	44	19	15	But the evil spirit answered, "Jesus I know, and Paul I have heard of, but who are you?"
B044C019V016	44	19	16	And the man in whom the evil spirit was sprang on two of them,  overpowered them and prevailed against them, so that they fled out of the house naked and wounded.
B044C019V017	44	19	17	And this became known to all the people of Ephesus, both Jews and Greeks. Awe fell on them all, and the name of the Lord Jesus began to be held in honor.
B044C019V018	44	19	18	Many also of those who became believers used to come to confess and to declare their deeds.
B044C019V019	44	19	19	And some of them who had practised magic arts, collected their books, and burned them in the presence of all. And they counted the price of them, and found it to be fifty thousand silver coins.
B044C019V020	44	19	20	So mightily the word of the Lord continued to grow and to prevail.
B044C019V021	44	19	21	Now after these things were ended, Paul resolved in his spirit to travel through Macedonia and Achaia on his way to Jerusalem. "After I get there," he said, "I must see Rome, too."
B044C019V022	44	19	22	So he sent two of his assistants, Timothy and Erastus, into Macedonia, while he himself kept back for a time on his way into Asia.
B044C019V023	44	19	23	Now just at this time, there arose no small commotion concerning the Way.
B044C019V024	44	19	24	There was a man named Demetrius, a silversmith, who made silver shrines of Diana, and brought rich profit to his workmen.
B044C019V025	44	19	25	He gathered them together with others of like occupation, and said.  "Men, you know that by this business we make our money.
B044C019V026	44	19	26	"And you see and hear that not only in Ephesus, but almost throughout all of Asia, this fellow Paul has persuaded and turned away many people, by telling them that they are no gods at all who are made with hands.
B044C019V027	44	19	27	"So there is danger not only that our trade come into disrepute, but also that the temple of the great goddess Diana will be brought into disrepute, and that she herself may even be deposed from her magnificence, she whom all Asia and the world now worships."
B044C019V028	44	19	28	After listening to this they were filled with rage, and cried out again and again, saying,
B044C019V029	44	19	29	The city was filled with commotion. They rushed like one man into the theater, dragging with them Gaius and Aristarchus, Macedonians,  Pauls companions in travel.
B044C019V030	44	19	30	When Paul wanted to go in to the people, the disciples would not let him,
B044C019V031	44	19	31	and some of the Asiarchs, too, who were his friends, sent word to him repeatedly, entreating him not to venture into the theater.
B044C019V032	44	19	32	Now some were shouting one thing, some another, for the assembly was in an uproar, and the majority had no idea why they were come together.
B044C019V033	44	19	33	And they brought Alexander out of the crowd, whom the Jews had pushed forward. And Alexander, motioning with his hand, would have made a defense to the people,
B044C019V034	44	19	34	but when they saw that he was a Jew they all, with one voice, for about two hours, shouted,
B044C019V035	44	19	35	At length the recorder got them quiet. "Men of Ephesus," he said,  "who here does not know that the city of the Ephesians is temple-  guardian of the great Diana and of the image which fell down from Jupiter?
B044C019V036	44	19	36	"Since these facts cannot be gainsaid, you ought to be calm and do nothing reckless.
B044C019V037	44	19	37	"For you have brought these men here, who are neither robbers of temples nor blasphemers of our goddess.
B044C019V038	44	19	38	If then Demetrius and his craftsmen have a grievance against any one, the courts are open and there are the proconsuls; let them accuse one another.
B044C019V039	44	19	39	But if you desire anything further, it must be settled in the regular assembly.
B044C019V040	44	19	40	For indeed we are in danger of being accused in regard to this days riot, since there is no cause for it, nor shall we be able to give account for this disorderly gathering."
B044C019V041	44	19	41	With these words he dismissed the assembly.
B044C020V001	44	20	1	After the uproar had ceased, Paul sent for the disciples and, after embracing them, bade them farewell, and started for Macedonia.
B044C020V002	44	20	2	And when he had passed through those districts and encouraged the disciples in many addresses, he came into Greece where he spent three months.
B044C020V003	44	20	3	Just as he was about to set sail for Syria, the Jews laid a plot against him, and he determined to return through Macedonia.
B044C020V004	44	20	4	There accompanied him as far as Asia, Sopater of Berea, the son of Pyrrhus; and of the Thessalonians, Aristarchus and Secundus; and Gaius of Derbe, and Timothy; and the Asians, Tychicus and Trophimus.
B044C020V005	44	20	5	Now these had gone on, and were awaiting us at Troas;
B044C020V006	44	20	6	but we ourselves set sail from Philippi, after the days of unleavened bread, and joined them five days later at Troas. There we remained for a week.
B044C020V007	44	20	7	On the first day of the week we met for the breaking of bread, and Paul, who was going away the next morning, began preaching to them,  and prolonged his discourse until midnight.
B044C020V008	44	20	8	Now there were many lamps in the upper room where we were assembled,
B044C020V009	44	20	9	and a young man named Eutychus was sitting in a window, overborne by deep sleep, while Paul continued to preach at length. Overcome at last by sleep, he fell down from the third story, and was taken up dead.
B044C020V010	44	20	10	Then Paul went down, threw himself upon him, and embracing him,  said. "Do not lament; his life is still in him."
B044C020V011	44	20	11	Then he went upstairs again, broke bread and took some food, and after talking with them a long time, even until daybreak, he left them.
B044C020V012	44	20	12	They had taken the lad home alive, and were not a little comforted.
B044C020V013	44	20	13	The rest of us going before to the ship, set sail for Assos,  intending to take Paul on board there; for so he had appointed,  because he intended to go by land.
B044C020V014	44	20	14	And when he met us at Assos, we took him in, and came to Mitylene.
B044C020V015	44	20	15	We sailed from thence, and arrived next day off Chios; and the day after we touched at Samos; and the following day we came to Mitylene.
B044C020V016	44	20	16	For Paul had determined to sail past Ephesus, so as not to spend time in Asia, for he was hurrying to get to Jerusalem, if it were possible, by the day of Pentecost.
B044C020V017	44	20	17	From Miletus he sent to Ephesus for the elders of the church to come to him;
B044C020V018	44	20	18	and when they arrived, he said to them. "You yourselves know quite well, how I lived among you, from the first day that I set foot in Asia,
B044C020V019	44	20	19	"serving the Lord with all lowliness of mind, and with tears, and amid trials that befell me through the plots of the Jews.
B044C020V020	44	20	20	"You know that I never shrank from declaring to you anything that was profitable, nor from teaching you publicity and in your homes,
B044C020V021	44	20	21	testifying both to Jews and Greeks repentance toward God, and faith toward our Lord Jesus Christ.
B044C020V022	44	20	22	And now I am going to Jerusalem, bound in the Spirit, not knowing what will befall me there,
B044C020V023	44	20	23	except that in city after city the Holy Spirit is warning me that bonds and afflictions are awaiting me.
B044C020V024	44	20	24	But I hold not my life of any account, as dear unto myself, if only I may run my race, and accomplish the ministry which I received from the Lord Jesus, to attest the gospel of the grace of God.
B044C020V025	44	20	25	And now I know that not one of you among whom I went about preaching the kingdom, will ever see my face again.
B044C020V026	44	20	26	So I testify to you this day that I am clear from the blood of all men;
B044C020V027	44	20	27	I never shrank from telling you the whole counsel of God.
B044C020V028	44	20	28	Take heed to yourselves and to all the flock of which the Holy Spirit has appointed you overseers, and be shepherds of the church of God which he has purchased with his own blood.
B044C020V029	44	20	29	I know that after my departure fierce wolves will come among you,  and they will not spare the flock;
B044C020V030	44	20	30	and that from among your own number, men will arise, perverting the truth, to draw away the disciples after them.
B044C020V031	44	20	31	So be on guard; and remember that for three years I ceased not to admonish you all, night and day, even with tears.
B044C020V032	44	20	32	"And now I commend you to God and to the word of his grace. He is able to build you up, and to give you your inheritance among all those who are consecrated.
B044C020V033	44	20	33	"No mans silver or gold of clothing did I ever covet.
B044C020V034	44	20	34	"You yourselves know how these hands of mine provided for my needs,  and those of my companions.
B044C020V035	44	20	35	"In all things I have set you an example, how that so toiling, you ought to help the weak and to remember the words of the Lord Jesus,  how he himself said, "It is more blessed to give than to receive."
B044C020V036	44	20	36	When he had so said, Paul kneeled down, and prayed with them.
B044C020V037	44	20	37	And they all began, with loud lamentations, to throw their arms about his neck, and to kiss him lovingly, again and again,
B044C020V038	44	20	38	sorrowing most of all for the words that he had spoken, that after that day they should look upon his face no more. And they began to escort him to the ship.
B044C021V001	44	21	1	When at least we had torn ourselves away, and had set sail, we ran a straight course to Cos, and next day to Rhodes, and from there to Patara.
B044C021V002	44	21	2	And when we had found a ship bound for Phoenicia, we went aboard and set sail.
B044C021V003	44	21	3	After sighting Cyprus and leaving it on the left hand, we sailed for Syria, and put in at Tyre; for there the ship was to unload her cargo.
B044C021V004	44	21	4	We looked up the local disciples and remained there seven days; and these disciples kept telling Paul, through the Spirit, that he should not set foot in Jerusalem.
B044C021V005	44	21	5	When, however, our time was up, we left and started on our journey;  and all of them, with wives and children, were escorting us on our way until we were out of the city; then, kneeling down on the beach,  we prayed,
B044C021V006	44	21	6	and said good-bye, and went on board the ship, while they returned home again.
B044C021V007	44	21	7	And when we had finished the voyage from Tyre, we reached Ptolemais,  and greeted the brothers and stayed with them one day.
B044C021V008	44	21	8	On the morrow we started for Caesarea, where we went into the house of Philip, the evangelist, who was one of the seven, and stayed with him.
B044C021V009	44	21	9	Now Philip had four unmarried daughters who prophesied,
B044C021V010	44	21	10	and while we remained there many days, a prophet named Agabus came down from Judea.
B044C021V011	44	21	11	He came to us, and taking Pauls girdle, he bound his own feet and hands, saying, "Thus says the Holy Spirit, so will the Jews at Jerusalem bind the owner of this girdle, and deliver him into the hands of the Gentiles."
B044C021V012	44	21	12	As soon as we heard these words, both we and those who were standing near entreated Paul not to go up to Jerusalem.
B044C021V013	44	21	13	"What do you mean by thus breaking my heart with your grief?"  answered Paul. "For I am ready not to be bound only, but also to die at Jerusalem, for the name of the Lord Jesus."
B044C021V014	44	21	14	And when he would not be persuaded, we ceased, saying, "The will of the Lord be done."
B044C021V015	44	21	15	A few days after this we took up our luggage and went up to Jerusalem.
B044C021V016	44	21	16	And some of the disciples from Caesarea accompanied us. They led us to the house of Mnason, a Cypriote, a disciple of long standing, with whom we were to lodge.
B044C021V017	44	21	17	At length we reached Jerusalem, and the brothers there received us gladly.
B044C021V018	44	21	18	On the following day we went with Paul to call on James, and all the elders were present.
B044C021V019	44	21	19	After saluting them Paul rehearsed, one by one, the things that God had done among the Gentiles by his ministry.
B044C021V020	44	21	20	And they, when they heard it, glorified God, and said to him. "You see, brother, how many thousands there are among the Jews, of those who have believed, and they are all zealous for the Law.
B044C021V021	44	21	21	"Now what they have been told about you, again and again, is that you teach all the Jews who are among the Gentiles, to forsake Moses,  and not to circumcise their children, nor to follow the old customs.
B044C021V022	44	21	22	"What then ought to be done? They will certainly hear that you are come.
B044C021V023	44	21	23	"So do this that we tell you.
B044C021V024	44	21	24	"We have four men here under a vow; associate yourself with them,  purify yourself with them, and pay their expenses so that they may have their heads shaved; then every one will know that there is no truth in the rumors that they have heard about you; but that you yourself walk orderly obeying the law.
B044C021V025	44	21	25	"As for the Gentile believers, we wrote giving judgment that they should abstain from anything sacrificed to an idol, from blood, from what is strangled, and from fornication."
B044C021V026	44	21	26	Then Paul took the men, and after purifying himself with them next day, went into the temple to declare the fulfilment of the days of purification, until the offering was offered for every one of them.
B044C021V027	44	21	27	But when the seven days were almost over, the Asiatic Jews caught sight of him in the temple, and began to stir up all the crowd, and laid hands on him, shouting.
B044C021V028	44	21	28	"Men of Israel, help! This is the man who goes everywhere preaching to everybody against the people, and the Law, and this place. And he has actually brought Gentiles even into the temple, and has desecrated the holy place."
B044C021V029	44	21	29	(For they had formerly seen Trophimus, the Ephesian, with him in the city, and supposed that Paul had brought him into the temple.)
B044C021V030	44	21	30	The whole city was thrown into uproar. The mob surged together,  seized Paul, and began to drag him outside the temple. Whereupon the doors were at once shut.
B044C021V031	44	21	31	While they were attempting to kill him, news came to the tribune commander of the garrison that all Jerusalem was in an uproar.
B044C021V032	44	21	32	At once he took soldiers and centurions, and rushed down upon them.  When they saw the tribune and the troops, they left off beating Paul.
B044C021V033	44	21	33	Then the tribune came up and seized him, and ordered that he be bound with two chains. "Who is he?" he began asking, "and what has he done?"
B044C021V034	44	21	34	Some among the crowd kept shouting one thing, some another; and when the tribune could not learn the facts because of the uproar, he ordered Paul into the barracks.
B044C021V035	44	21	35	When was going up the steps, he had to be carried by the soldiers,  because of the violence of the mob,
B044C021V036	44	21	36	for the whole mass of the people were following him, shouting, "Away with him!"
B044C021V037	44	21	37	Just as he was about to be taken into the barracks, Paul said to the tribune, "May I speak to you?"
B044C021V038	44	21	38	"Do you know Greek?" said the tribune; "Are you not, then, the Egyptian who in days gone by stirred up to sedition, and let into the wilderness the four thousand cutthroats?"
B044C021V039	44	21	39	"I am a Jew," answered Paul, "a native of Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no mean city. And I pray you, give me permission to speak to the people."
B044C021V040	44	21	40	So when he had given leave, Paul stood on the stairs, beckoning with his hands to the people. There came a great hush, and he spoke to them as follows, in Hebrew.
B044C022V001	44	22	1	"Brothers and fathers, listen to the defense which I now make in your presence."
B044C022V002	44	22	2	When they heard him speaking in Hebrew they became the more quiet.
B044C022V003	44	22	3	"I am a Jew," he said, "born in Tarsus of Cilicia, but brought up in this city at the feet of Gamaliel, taught according to the strict manner of the Law of our forefathers, ardent for God, even as you all are this day.
B044C022V004	44	22	4	"I persecuted to the death this way, continually binding and delivering up to prisons both men and women.
B044C022V005	44	22	5	"To this the high priest and all the council of elders are witnesses. It was from them that I received letters to the brothers in Damascus, and I was already on my way to bring those also who were there back to Jerusalem, in bonds, for punishment.
B044C022V006	44	22	6	"But when, on my journey, I was nearing Damascus, about noon,  suddenly a great light from heaven shone round about me.
B044C022V007	44	22	7	"I fell to the ground, and heard a voice saying to me, "Saul! Saul!  why are you persecuting me?
B044C022V008	44	22	8	"Who are you, Lord? I asked. "I am Jesus, the Nazarene, whom you are persecuting, he answered me.
B044C022V009	44	22	9	"Now my companions, though they beheld the light, did not hear the words of Him who spoke to me.
B044C022V010	44	22	10	"And I said, What shall I do, Lord? and the Lord said to me, Rise and go into Damascus, and there you will be told about all that you are destined to do.
B044C022V011	44	22	11	"And as I was seeing nothing for the glory of the light, I was led by the hand of my companions, and so came into Damascus.
B044C022V012	44	22	12	"And a certain Ananias, a pious man according to the Law, well thought of by all the Jews who lived there,
B044C022V013	44	22	13	"came to me, and standing by me, said to me, "Brother Saul, receive your sight "In that very hour I regained my sight and looked up at him.
B044C022V014	44	22	14	"Then he said. "The God of our forefathers has appointed you to know his will; and to see the righteous One, and to hear a voice from his mouth.
B044C022V015	44	22	15	"For before the face of all men you will be a witness for him of what you have seen and heard.
B044C022V016	44	22	16	"And now why do you wait? Rise and be baptized, and wash away your sins, calling upon his name.
B044C022V017	44	22	17	"After my return to Jerusalem, and while I was praying in the temple,
B044C022V018	44	22	18	"I fell into a trance and saw him saying to me, "Make haste and go quickly out of Jerusalem, because they will not receive your testimony concerning me.
B044C022V019	44	22	19	"Lord, I replied, they themselves well know that I was beating and imprisoning in synagogue after synagogue those who believed in you,
B044C022V020	44	22	20	"and when the blood of your martyr Stephen was shed, I also was standing by and consenting, and holding the garments of his murders.
B044C022V021	44	22	21	"Depart, he said to me, for I will send you forth, far hence, to the Gentiles."
B044C022V022	44	22	22	Until they heard this last statement, the people were listening to Paul, but now they roared out. "Away with such a fellow from the earth! He is not fit to live!"
B044C022V023	44	22	23	When they continued to shout, throwing their clothes into the air,  and flinging dust around,
B044C022V024	44	22	24	the tribune ordered him to be brought into the barracks, and examined under the lash, to learn for what reason the people were thus crying out against him.
B044C022V025	44	22	25	But when they had tied him up with the thongs, Paul said to the centurion who was standing near, "If a man is a Roman citizen, and uncondemned, is it lawful for you to scourge him?"
B044C022V026	44	22	26	When the centurion heard that, he went to the tribune and said to him. "What are you intending to do? This man is a Roman citizen."
B044C022V027	44	22	27	So the tribune came to Paul and asked him, "Tell me, are you a Roman citizen?" "Yes," he said.
B044C022V028	44	22	28	"I paid a large sum to get this citizenship," said the tribune. "But I was citizen-born," said Paul.
B044C022V029	44	22	29	Then those who were about to scourge him, immediately left him. And the tribune too, was afraid, when he learned that Paul was a Roman citizen, for he had had him bound.
B044C022V030	44	22	30	The next day, as he wished to learn the real reason why the Jews accused Paul, he unbound him, and commanded the chief priests and all the Sanhedrin to come together, and brought Paul down, and placed him before them.
B044C023V001	44	23	1	With a stedfast gaze at the Sanhedrin, Paul said, "Brothers, I have lived with a good conscience before God to this day."
B044C023V002	44	23	2	Then the High Priest Ananias ordered those who stood near Paul to strike him on the mouth.
B044C023V003	44	23	3	"You whited sepulcher," exclaimed Paul, "God will strike you! You are sitting there to judge me according to the law, are you? And do you command me to be struck, contrary to the Law?"
B044C023V004	44	23	4	"Do you rail at Gods high priest?" said the bystanders.
B044C023V005	44	23	5	"Brothers, I did not know that he was the high priest," exclaimed Paul, "for it is written, Thou shalt not speak evil of a ruler of my people."
B044C023V006	44	23	6	Then perceiving that half the Sanhedrin were Sadducees and the other half Pharisee, he cried out in the Sanhedrin. "Brothers, I am a Pharisee, the son of Pharisees! It is for the hope of the resurrection of the dead that I am on trial!"
B044C023V007	44	23	7	When he said this, there arose a quarrel between the Pharisees and Sadducees; the meeting was divided.
B044C023V008	44	23	8	For the Sadducees say that there is no resurrection, neither angel nor spirit; the Pharisees affirm them all.
B044C023V009	44	23	9	Then a great clamor arose; some of the scribes who belonged to the Pharisaic party stood up, and contended. "We find nothing wrong in this man. What if a spirit has spoken to him, or an angel?"
B044C023V010	44	23	10	But when the dissension became violent, the tribune, fearing that they would tear Paul in pieces, ordered the troops to march down and take him by force from among them, and bring him into the barracks.
B044C023V011	44	23	11	And the following night the Lord stood by him and said. "Be of good courage; for as you have borne faithful witness concerning me at Jerusalem, so you must testify at Rome also."
B044C023V012	44	23	12	When day dawned the Jews made a conspiracy, and bound themselves under a curse, saying that they would neither eat nor drink till they had killed Paul.
B044C023V013	44	23	13	And there were more than forty who had sworn this oath.
B044C023V014	44	23	14	They went to the high priests and elders, and said to them. "We have bound ourselves by a solemn oath to eat nothing until we have killed Paul.
B044C023V015	44	23	15	"Now do you and the Sanhedrin ask the tribune to bring him down to you, as though you would judge his case more exactly; and we are ready to kill him, before he comes near the place."
B044C023V016	44	23	16	But Pauls sisters son heard of their intended attack, and he went and got into the barracks, and told Paul.
B044C023V017	44	23	17	And Paul called one of the centurions, and said, "Take this young man to the tribune, for he has something to tell him."
B044C023V018	44	23	18	So he took him, and brought his to the tribune, and said, "Paul, the prisoner, called me to him, and begged me to bring this young man to you, because he has something to tell you."
B044C023V019	44	23	19	And the tribune took him by the hand, and going aside, asked him privately, "What is it that you have to tell me?"
B044C023V020	44	23	20	"The Jews," he answered, "have agreed to ask you to bring down Paul tomorrow to the Sanhedrin, as though they wish to examine his case in detail.
B044C023V021	44	23	21	"Now do not let them persuade, for more than forty men are lying in wait for him, who have bound themselves under a curse, not to eat nor drink until they have killed him; even now they are all ready,  awaiting your consent."
B044C023V022	44	23	22	So the tribune sent the young man home with the injunction, "Tell no man that you have given me this information."
B044C023V023	44	23	23	Then he called two centurions to him and said. "Get ready by nine oclock tonight two hundred infantry to march as far as Caesarea, and also seventy troopers and two hundred spearmen."
B044C023V024	44	23	24	He further ordered them to provide horses on which to mount Paul, so as to bring him safely to Felix, the governor.
B044C023V025	44	23	25	He also wrote a letter in the following terms.
B044C023V026	44	23	26	"Claudius Lysais unto the Most Excellent Governor Felix, greeting.
B044C023V027	44	23	27	"This man Paul had been seized by the Jews, and was about to be killed by them, when I came upon them with the troops, and rescued him, as I had learned that he was a Roman citizen.
B044C023V028	44	23	28	"Anxious to find out why they had accused him, I brought him down to their Sanhedrin.
B044C023V029	44	23	29	"Here I learned that he was accused about questions of their law,  but was not charged with anything worthy of death or imprisonment.
B044C023V030	44	23	30	"Now when I received information that there would be a plot against the man, I sent him at once to you, charging his accusers also to speak against him before you."
B044C023V031	44	23	31	So the soldiers took Paul, as they were bid, and brought him by night to Antipatris.
B044C023V032	44	23	32	Next day the infantry returned to the barracks, leaving the troopers to ride on with him.
B044C023V033	44	23	33	They reached Caesarea and delivered the letter to the governor, and also presented Paul before him.
B044C023V034	44	23	34	After reading the letter, he asked to what province he belonged, and when he understood that he was of Cilicia, he said,
B044C023V035	44	23	35	"I will hear your case when your accusers also are come." And he ordered him to be kept in custody in Herods palace.
B044C024V001	44	24	1	Five days later, Ananias the high priest came down to Caesarea with some of the elders, and with an orator, named Tertullus. They laid information before the governor against Paul.
B044C024V002	44	24	2	So Paul was sent for, and then Tertullus began to accuse him,  saying. "As it is owing to your excellency that we enjoy profound peace, and that the state of this nation,
B044C024V003	44	24	3	"owing to your wise care, has been improved in every respect and in every place, we accept it with profound thankfulness.
B044C024V004	44	24	4	"But not to weary you too much, I beg of your Excellency to listen to a few words from us.
B044C024V005	44	24	5	"For we have found this fellow a pest, an inciter of insurrection among all the Jews of the empire, and a ringleader in the heresy of the Nazarenes.
B044C024V006	44	24	6	"He even tried to profane the Temple, but we arrested him.
B044C024V007	44	24	7	"Then the chief captain, Lysias came and violently took him from us.
B044C024V008	44	24	8	From him you will be able, by examining Paul yourself, to learn the truth of all these charges we are bringing against him."
B044C024V009	44	24	9	The Jews also joined in the charge, maintaining that these were the facts.
B044C024V010	44	24	10	Then at a nod from the governor, Paul spoke. "Because I know that for many years you have been a judge in this nation, I feel encouraged to make my defense.
B044C024V011	44	24	11	"For you have it in your power to know that it is not more than twelve days ago that I went up to Jerusalem to worship;
B044C024V012	44	24	12	"and that neither in the Temple, nor in the synagogues, nor in the city, did they find me disputing with any man or stirring up a crowd.
B044C024V013	44	24	13	"Nor can they prove the charges which they are now bringing against me.
B044C024V014	44	24	14	"But this I confess to you, that I worship the God of our ancestors,  according to the Way which they call a heresy, believing everything that is according to the Law, or is written in the Prophets,
B044C024V015	44	24	15	"and having hope toward God, which these also themselves look for,  that there is to be a resurrection both of the just and the unjust.
B044C024V016	44	24	16	"Hence I too endeavor to have a conscience void of offense toward God and men alway.
B044C024V017	44	24	17	"Now after many years I came to bring alms to my nation, and to offer sacrifices.
B044C024V018	44	24	18	"While I was thus engaged, they found me in the temple, purified,  with no crowd and no uproar. But there were certain Asiatic Jews
B044C024V019	44	24	19	"who ought to have been here before you, and to have made accusations if they had anything against me.
B044C024V020	44	24	20	"Or let these men themselves say what fault they found, when I appeared before the Sanhedrin!
B044C024V021	44	24	21	"Unless it was for this one sentence which I uttered when I stood and cried, It is for the resurrection of the dead that I am on my trial today before you."
B044C024V022	44	24	22	At this point Felix, who had a pretty accurate knowledge of the Way,  adjourned the case, saying to the Jews, "When Lysias the tribune comes down, I will go carefully into the matter."
B044C024V023	44	24	23	And he gave orders to the centurion that Paul should be kept in custody, but treated with indulgence, and that his personal friends were not to be forbidden to minister to him.
B044C024V024	44	24	24	Some days later Felix came, with his wife Drusilla, a Jewess; he sent for Paul, and listened to him concerning the faith in Christ Jesus.
B044C024V025	44	24	25	And as he reasoned about morality, self-control, and the future judgment, Felix was terrified, and said, "For the present go on your way, and when I find a convenient season, I will send for you."
B044C024V026	44	24	26	He was hoping that Paul would give him money, and for this reason he used to send for him often to converse with him.
B044C024V027	44	24	27	But after two full years Felix was succeeded by Porcius Festus, and because he wished to curry favor with the Jews, Felix left Paul still in prison.
B044C025V001	44	25	1	Three days after Festus entered his province, he went up from Caesarea to Jerusalem.
B044C025V002	44	25	2	The high priest and the Jewish leaders laid charges against Paul before him.
B044C025V003	44	25	3	They urged him, asking it as a favor, to send for him to Jerusalem.  They meant to lay in wait for him and kill him on the way.
B044C025V004	44	25	4	But Festus answered that Paul was in custody at Caesarea, and that he himself was going there soon.
B044C025V005	44	25	5	"Let those then," he said, "who are in authority among you, go down with me, and if there is anything amiss in the man, let them accuse him."
B044C025V006	44	25	6	After staying not more than eight or ten days among them, he went down to Caesarea, and the next day, after taking his seat upon the tribunal, he ordered Paul to be brought.
B044C025V007	44	25	7	When he came in, the Jews who had come down from Jerusalem stood around him and brought a number of serious charges against him, which they could not prove.
B044C025V008	44	25	8	Paul said in his defense, "I have committed no crime against the Law of the Jews, against the Temple, or against Caesar."
B044C025V009	44	25	9	But Festus, wishing to ingratiate himself with the Jews, answered Paul and said, "Will you go up to Jerusalem and be tried there by me upon these charges?"
B044C025V010	44	25	10	"I am standing before Caesars tribunal," answered Paul, "where I ought to be tried. I have done no wrong to the Jews, as you very well know.
B044C025V011	44	25	11	"If I am a criminal and have done anything for which I ought to die,  I do not object to die. But if none of their charges is true, no man can give me up to them. I appeal to Caesar."
B044C025V012	44	25	12	Then Festus, after conferring with the council, answered. "You have appealed to Caesar; to Caesar you shall go."
B044C025V013	44	25	13	A short time after this King Agrippa and Bernice came to Caesarea to pay their respects to Festus.
B044C025V014	44	25	14	And while they tarried many days, Festus laid Pauls case before the king. "There is a man here," he said, "whom Felix left a prisoner.
B044C025V015	44	25	15	"The chief priests and the elders of the Jews informed me about him,  when I was at Jerusalem, demanding a sentence against him.
B044C025V016	44	25	16	I told them that it was not the custom of the Romans to give any man up for punishment, before the accused had his accusers face to face,  and had opportunity of defending himself against the charges that had been brought against him.
B044C025V017	44	25	17	"So when a number of them came together here, I made no delay, but the next day took my seat in the tribunal, and commanded the man to be brought.
B044C025V018	44	25	18	"But when his accusers stood up, they did not begin charging him with any of the crimes that I was expecting,
B044C025V019	44	25	19	but they kept quarreling with him about certain matters connected with their own religion, and about one Jesus who had died, but whom Paul affirmed over and over was alive.
B044C025V020	44	25	20	I was perplexed how to investigate such questions, and asked Paul whether he would go to Jerusalem, and there be judged of these matters.
B044C025V021	44	25	21	But when Paul appealed to have his case reviewed for the decision of the Emperor, I ordered him to be detained until I could send him up to Caesar."
B044C025V022	44	25	22	"I should like to hear the man, myself," said Agrippa to Festus.  Festus answered, "You shall hear him tomorrow."
B044C025V023	44	25	23	So the next day Agrippa and Bernice came with great pomp, and took their places in the hall of audience, accompanied by the tribunes and men of high rank in the city. At the command of Festus Paul was brought in.
B044C025V024	44	25	24	"King Agrippa," said Festus, "and all men who are present with us,  you see here the man about whom the entire body of the Jews at Jerusalem, and here also, sent to me, crying out that he ought not to live any longer.
B044C025V025	44	25	25	"I could not find that he had done anything for which he ought to die; but as he himself has appealed to the Emperor, I have determined to send him.
B044C025V026	44	25	26	"Now I have nothing very definite to tell our sovereign about him.  So I have brought the man before you all, and especially before you,  King Agrippa, in order that, after examination, I may have something to write.
B044C025V027	44	25	27	"For it does seem to me unreasonable to send a person without signifying the charges against him."
B044C026V001	44	26	1	Then Agrippa said to Paul, "You are permitted to speak for yourself." So Paul stretched forth his hand and began to make his defense.
B044C026V002	44	26	2	"I think myself happy, King Agrippa, that I am to make my defense before you this day, in regard to all the accusations brought against me by the Jews;
B044C026V003	44	26	3	"especially since you are an export in all Jewish customs and questions. I pray you, expert in all Jewish customs and questions. I pray you, hear me with patience.
B044C026V004	44	26	4	"The kind of life I have lived from my youth upward among my own nation and at Jerusalem, all that early life of mine, is well known to all the Jews.
B044C026V005	44	26	5	"They know me of old, if they are willing to testify, how that according to the strict sect of our religion, I lived a Pharisee.
B044C026V006	44	26	6	"Today I am standing trial because of the hope of the promise made by God to our ancestors,
B044C026V007	44	26	7	"a promise which our twelve tribes, earnestly serving God night and day, hope to attain. It is concerning this hope, King Agrippa, that I am accused by the Jews.
B044C026V008	44	26	8	"Why is it deemed incredible by you all, if God raises the dead?
B044C026V009	44	26	9	"I indeed once thought with myself that I ought to do many things against the name of Jesus, the Nazarene.
B044C026V010	44	26	10	"And this also I did in Jerusalem. Armed with authority from the chief priests, I shut up many of the saints in prison, and when they were condemned to death I gave my vote against them.
B044C026V011	44	26	11	"In all the synagogues also I punished them oftentimes, and tried to make them blaspheme; and in my mad fury I was pursuing them even to foreign cities.
B044C026V012	44	26	12	"On this errand I was traveling to Damascus one day, armed with authority and commission of the chief priests,
B044C026V013	44	26	13	"when at noon, as I journeyed, O King, I saw a light from heaven,  brighter than the sun, shining around me and around those who journeyed with me.
B044C026V014	44	26	14	"We all fell to the ground; and I heard a voice saying to me in Hebrew. "Saul, Saul, why are you persecuting me? It is hard for you to kick against the goad.
B044C026V015	44	26	15	"Who are you, Lord? I said. "And the Lord said. I am Jesus whom you are persecuting.
B044C026V016	44	26	16	"But rise and stand on your feet, for I have appeared to you in order to appoint you my minister and my witness both of what you have already seen and of those things in which I will appear to you.
B044C026V017	44	26	17	"I will deliver you from the Jewish people, and from the Gentiles to whom I am sending you to open their eyes
B044C026V018	44	26	18	"so that they may turn from darkness to light, and from the power of Satan unto God, in order to receive remission of sins and an inheritance among those who are sanctified by faith in me.
B044C026V019	44	26	19	"So then, O King Agrippa, I was not disobedient unto the heavenly vision;
B044C026V020	44	26	20	"but I proceeded to preach, first to those in Damascus, and then in Jerusalem and throughout all the country of Judea, and also to the Gentiles, that they must repent and turn to God and do deeds worthy of repentance.
B044C026V021	44	26	21	"For this reason the Jews seized me in the temple, and tried to kill me.
B044C026V022	44	26	22	"But having obtained the help that comes from God, I stand even to this day witnessing both to small and great, saying nothing except what the prophets and Moses said should come;
B044C026V023	44	26	23	"how that the Christ must suffer, and how he should be the first to rise from the dead, and should bring a message of light to the Jewish people and to the Gentiles."
B044C026V024	44	26	24	As Paul thus made his defense, Festus exclaimed in a loud voice.  "Paul, you are raving mad; your great learning is driving you mad."
B044C026V025	44	26	25	"I am not mad, most noble Festus," said Paul,
B044C026V026	44	26	26	"I am speaking words of sober truth. For the King, to whom I am speaking freely, knows of these matters. I am persuaded that not one of these things has escaped his notice; for these things were not done in a corner.
B044C026V027	44	26	27	"King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you believe."
B044C026V028	44	26	28	Agrippa answered, "In short, you are doing your best to persuade me to become a Christian."
B044C026V029	44	26	29	"Long or short," answered Paul, "my prayer to God is that not only you but all who are my hearers this day might become such as I am,  save for these chains."
B044C026V030	44	26	30	Then the king rose, and Bernice, and those who were sitting with him.
B044C026V031	44	26	31	When they had withdrawn they continued talking to one another. "This man is doing nothing," they said, "for which he deserves death or imprisonment."
B044C026V032	44	26	32	And Agrippa said to Festus, "If he had not appealed to Caesar, he might have been set free."
B044C027V001	44	27	1	When it was decided that we should sail for Italy, they proceeded to hand over Paul and a few other prisoners to the custody of Julius, a centurion of the Imperial Regiment.
B044C027V002	44	27	2	We embarked in a ship of Adramyttium which was about to sail to the ports of the province of Asia, and put to sea. Aristarchus, a Macedonian of Thessalonica, accompanied us.
B044C027V003	44	27	3	The next day we touched at Sidon. There Julius treated Paul kindly,  and gave him leave to visit his friends and refresh himself.
B044C027V004	44	27	4	Putting to sea from thence we sailed under the lee of Cyprus,  because the winds were against us;
B044C027V005	44	27	5	and after sailing across the Cilician and Pamphylian waters, we came to Myra, in Lycia.
B044C027V006	44	27	6	And there the centurion found an Alexandrian ship bound for Italy,  and put us on board of her.
B044C027V007	44	27	7	For many days we sailed slowly, and then arrived with difficulty over against Cnidus; from this point, as the wind did not further favor us, we ran under the lee of Crete, off Cape Salmone;
B044C027V008	44	27	8	and coasting along with difficulty we reached a place called Fair Havens, not far from the town of Lasea.
B044C027V009	44	27	9	By this time the season was far advanced, and sailing had become dangerous (for the Autumn Fast was past); so Paul began to warn them.
B044C027V010	44	27	10	"Sirs," he said to them, "I perceive that the voyage will be attended with injury and serious loss, not only to the cargo and to the ship, but also to our own lives."
B044C027V011	44	27	11	But the centurion paid greater heed to the master and to the owner than to anything that was spoken by Paul;
B044C027V012	44	27	12	and as the harbor was ill adapted for winter quarters, the majority advised putting out to sea from thence, to see whether they could get to Phoenix and winter there, a harbor on the coast of Crete facing northeast and southeast.
B044C027V013	44	27	13	And when the south wind blew softly, supposing that they had obtained their purpose, they weighed anchor and sailed along Crete,  close in shore.
B044C027V014	44	27	14	But it was not long before a furious wind, called Euroclydon, rushed down from the island;
B044C027V015	44	27	15	when the ship was caught and could not face the wind, we gave way to it, and let her drive.
B044C027V016	44	27	16	Then we ran under the lee of a little island named Claudia, where with great difficulty we were able to secure the ships boat.
B044C027V017	44	27	17	After hauling it aboard, they used ropes to undergird the ship, and since they were fearful lest they should be driven upon the Syrtes,  they lowered the gear and lay to.
B044C027V018	44	27	18	And as we were being terribly battered by the storm, the next day they began to throw the freight overboard,
B044C027V019	44	27	19	and on the third day with their own hands they threw the ships tackling overboard.
B044C027V020	44	27	20	Then when for many days neither sun nor stars were seen, and a great tempest still beat upon us, all hope that we should be saved was now taken away from us.
B044C027V021	44	27	21	When for a long time they had been without food, Paul stood among them and said. "Men, you ought to have listened to me, and not have set sail from Crete, and so have spared yourselves this injury and loss.
B044C027V022	44	27	22	"But now take courage. There will be no loss of life among you, but only of the ship,
B044C027V023	44	27	23	"for last night an angel of the God whose I am and whom I serve,  stood by me and said.
B044C027V024	44	27	24	"Fear not, Paul; you must stand before Caesar. Behold, God has granted you the lives of all who are sailing with you.
B044C027V025	44	27	25	"So take courage, men! I believe God, I believe that things will turn out exactly as it has been told me.
B044C027V026	44	27	26	"But we must be cast upon a certain island."
B044C027V027	44	27	27	It was now the fourteenth night, and we were drifting through the Adriatic Sea when, about midnight, the sailors began to suspect that they were drawing near to some land.
B044C027V028	44	27	28	So they sounded and found twenty fathoms; and after a little they sounded again, and found fifteen fathoms.
B044C027V029	44	27	29	Then, fearing lest we should run ashore on the rocks, they threw out four anchors from the stern, and longed for day to come.
B044C027V030	44	27	30	And when the sailors were trying to flee from the ship, and had lowered the boat into the sea under pretext of laying anchors from the bow,
B044C027V031	44	27	31	Paul said to the centurion and to the soldiers, "Unless these men remain on the ship, you cannot be saved."
B044C027V032	44	27	32	Then the soldiers cut the ropes of the ships boat and let her fall off.
B044C027V033	44	27	33	And while day was dawning, Paul kept urging them all to take some food. "This is the fourteenth day," he said, "that you have been on the watch, fasting, having eaten nothing.
B044C027V034	44	27	34	"So I beg you to take some food, for this is for your safety. For there shall not a hair perish from the head of any one of you."
B044C027V035	44	27	35	When he had so said and had taken bread, he gave thanks to God before them all, and broke it and began to eat.
B044C027V036	44	27	36	Then they all cheered up and themselves took food.
B044C027V037	44	27	37	There were in the ship two hundred and seventy-six souls, all told.
B044C027V038	44	27	38	After eating a hearty meal, they began to lighten the ship by throwing the wheat overboard.
B044C027V039	44	27	39	When it was day they tried in vain to recognize the land, but they spied an inlet with a sandy beach, and they began conferring to see whether they could drive the ship into it.
B044C027V040	44	27	40	They cast off the anchors and left them in the sea, and unloosing at the same time the ropes that tied the rudders, they hoisted the foresail to the breeze, and headed for the beach.
B044C027V041	44	27	41	But coming to a place where two seas met, they ran the ship aground;  the bow struck and remained fixed, but the stern began to break up under the violence of the waves.
B044C027V042	44	27	42	Now the soldiers were planning to kill the prisoners, lest any of them should swim off and so escape.
B044C027V043	44	27	43	But the centurion kept them from their purpose, because he wished to save Paul. He gave orders that those who could swim should first jump overboard and get to land;
B044C027V044	44	27	44	and that the rest should follow, some on planks and some on other bits of wreckage. And so it came to pass that all escaped safe to the land.
B044C028V001	44	28	1	And when we were escaped, we ascertained that the island was called Malta.
B044C028V002	44	28	2	The foreign-speaking people showed us uncommon kindness, for they lighted a fire and made us all welcome, because of the rain and because of the cold.
B044C028V003	44	28	3	Now when Paul had gathered a bundle of sticks and thrown them on the fire, a viper crawled out because of the heat, and fastened on his hand.
B044C028V004	44	28	4	When the natives saw the reptile hanging on his hand, they began saying to one another, "No doubt this man is a murderer, whom, though he has escaped from the sea, yet justice does not allow him to live."
B044C028V005	44	28	5	However, he shook off the reptile into the fire and received no harm.
B044C028V006	44	28	6	But they kept expecting him to swell up or fall down dead suddenly.  But after waiting a long time, and seeing no harm come to him, they changed their minds, and said over and over that he was a god.
B044C028V007	44	28	7	Now in the neighborhood there were estates belonging to the governor of the island, whose name was Publius. He received us and entertained us for three days courteously.
B044C028V008	44	28	8	It happened however that the father of Publius was lying ill of fever and dysentery. So Paul went to see him and prayed and laid his hands on him and healed him.
B044C028V009	44	28	9	After this all the other sick people on the island came, and continued to be restored to health.
B044C028V010	44	28	10	These loaded us with many honors and, when at last we set sail, they put on board such things as we needed.
B044C028V011	44	28	11	Three months passed before we set sail an Alexandrian ship which had wintered in the island. Its name was "The Twin Brothers."
B044C028V012	44	28	12	And touching at Syracuse, we stayed there three days.
B044C028V013	44	28	13	From thence, tacking round, we reached Rhegium. Next day a south wind sprang up, which brought us in a day to Puteoli.
B044C028V014	44	28	14	There we found brothers who invited us to stay a week with them.  Then we reached Rome.
B044C028V015	44	28	15	From there the brothers, when they heard about us, came out to meet us as far as the Appian Forum and the Three Taverns. When Paul saw them he thanked God and took courage.
B044C028V016	44	28	16	When we finally entered Rome, Paul was allowed to live by himself with the soldier to guard him.
B044C028V017	44	28	17	Now three days later he called the leading Jews together, and when they were come together he said to them. "Brothers, I was delivered a prisoner from Jerusalem into the hands of the Romans, though I had done nothing against the people or the customs of your fathers.
B044C028V018	44	28	18	"Then when they had examined me they wanted to set me at liberty because there was no cause of death in me.
B044C028V019	44	28	19	"But when the Jews objected I was forced to appeal to Caesar, not that I had anything to accuse my nation of.
B044C028V020	44	28	20	This is the reason why I begged you to see and speak with me. For because of the hope of Israel I am bound with this chain."
B044C028V021	44	28	21	They said to him. "We neither received any letters about you from Judea nor has any brother come hither to report or speak any harm of you.
B044C028V022	44	28	22	"But we are eager to hear from you what it is that you believe; for we all know that as for this sect it is everywhere spoken against."
B044C028V023	44	28	23	So they arranged a day with him and came to him in his lodgings in great numbers. He expounded the matter to them; testifying to the Kingdom of God, and persuading them about Jesus, from morning till evening, both from the Law of Moses and from the Prophets.
B044C028V024	44	28	24	Some began to believe what he said, but some were unbelieving.
B044C028V025	44	28	25	Unable to agree among themselves, they began to go, but not before Paul had spoken a word to them, saying. "Right well did the Holy Spirit say to your ancestors, through the prophet Isaiah.
B044C028V026	44	28	26	"Go to the people and tell them, You will hear and hear, and by no means understand; And will look, and by no means see.
B044C028V027	44	28	27	For this peoples heart is grown obtuse, Their ears are heavy of hearing, Their eyes have they closed, Lest they should see with their eyes And hear with their ears, Lest they understand with their heart,  And turn again, and heal them.
B044C028V028	44	28	28	"Be fully assured, therefore, that this salvation of God is now sent unto the Gentiles. They will listen to it."
B044C028V029	44	28	29	When he finished speaking, the Jews departed, and reasoned among themselves.
B044C028V030	44	28	30	After this Paul lived for two whole years in his own rented house,  and used to receive all who came to see him.
B044C028V031	44	28	31	He continued to preach the kingdom of God, and to teach about the Lord Jesus Christ with all boldness, quite unmolested.
B045C001V001	45	1	1	From Paul, a slave of Jesus Christ, called to be an apostle, set apart for a gospel of God,
B045C001V002	45	1	2	which through his prophets he promised beforetime, in holy writings;
B045C001V003	45	1	3	this gospel is concerning his Son, Jesus Christ our Lord, who was born of Davids posterity in respect of his bodily nature,
B045C001V004	45	1	4	but was by his resurrection from the dead instated as Son of God,  with power, in respect of his spirit of holiness.
B045C001V005	45	1	5	It is through him, even Jesus Christ our Lord, that I received grace and apostleship to promote obedience to the faith among all the Gentiles, for his names sake;
B045C001V006	45	1	6	among whom you also are called to be Jesus Christs.
B045C001V007	45	1	7	To all that are in Rome, beloved of God, called to be saints. May God our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ, bless you, and give you peace.
B045C001V008	45	1	8	First I thank my God, through Jesus Christ, for all of you, because your faith is being proclaimed throughout all the world.
B045C001V009	45	1	9	God is my witness, to whom I render holy service in my spirit in the gospel of his Son, how unceasingly I am ever making mention of you in my prayers,
B045C001V010	45	1	10	always entreating him that now at length, if such be his will, the way may be made clear for me to come to you.
B045C001V011	45	1	11	For I am longing so to see you, in order to impart to you some spiritual gift, so that you may be established;
B045C001V012	45	1	12	that is, that I with you may be encouraged by you, each of us by the others faith, yours and mine.
B045C001V013	45	1	13	I want you to know, brothers, that many a time I have planned to come to you - though until now I have been hindered - so as to have some harvest-fruit among you also, even as I have among the rest of the Gentiles.
B045C001V014	45	1	14	To Greeks and to barbarians, to the cultured and to the uncultured,  I have a debt to discharge.
B045C001V015	45	1	15	So much as in me is, I am ready to preach the gospel to you also who are in Rome.
B045C001V016	45	1	16	FOR I AM PROUD OF THE GOSPEL. IT IS GODS SAVING POWER FOR EVERY ONE WHO BELIEVES. FOR THE JEW FIRST, AND ALSO FOR THE GENTILE.
B045C001V017	45	1	17	FOR IN IT IS BEING REVEALED A RIGHTEOUSNESS WHICH PROCEEDS FROM GOD,  FROM FAITH UNTO FAITH; AS IT IS WRITTEN.
B045C001V018	45	1	18	For Gods wrath is ever being revealed from heaven against all ungodliness and unrighteousness of men who smother the truth by their unrighteousness.
B045C001V019	45	1	19	This is so because that which may be known of God is manifest among them; for God has made it manifest to them.
B045C001V020	45	1	20	For ever since the creation of the world his invisible nature, even his everlasting power and divinity, has been clearly seen, being perceived through the things that are made. So they have no excuse.
B045C001V021	45	1	21	For although they knew God, yet they did not glorify him as God, nor give him thanks; but became vain in their reasoning, and their senseless minds were darkened.
B045C001V022	45	1	22	While they professed to be wise, they became fools,
B045C001V023	45	1	23	and exchanged the majesty of the imperishable God for an idol,  graven in the likeness of perishable man, or of birds and four-footed beasts and creeping things.
B045C001V024	45	1	24	So God gave them up in the lusts of their hearts to impurity, to the dishonoring of their own bodies;
B045C001V025	45	1	25	because they exchanged the truth of God for an untruth, and worshiped and served the creature, rather than the Creator who is blessed forever. Amen.
B045C001V026	45	1	26	That is why God has given them up to passions of dishonor; for on the one hand their women actually changed the natural function of sex into that which is against nature;
B045C001V027	45	1	27	and on the other hand their men likewise abandoned the natural use of women, and were ablaze with passion for one another; men with men practising shameless acts and receiving in their own person that recompense of their wrong-doing which necessarily followed.
B045C001V028	45	1	28	And just as they refused to continue to retain God in their knowledge, so did God cast them out to an outcast mind, to do those things which were indecent.
B045C001V029	45	1	29	They were overflowing with every kind of iniquity, depravity, greed,  and malice. They were full of envy, murder, quarreling, deceit, and malignity.
B045C001V030	45	1	30	They became whisperers, back-biters, hated of God, insolent,  haughty, boastful. They invented sins. They were disobedient to parents.
B045C001V031	45	1	31	They were without sense, without faith, without natural affection,  without mercy.
B045C001V032	45	1	32	Though they knew well the ordinance of God, that those who practise such vices are worthy of death, they not only continue to do the same, but were even applauding those who practise vice.
B045C002V001	45	2	1	You are therefore inexcusable, O man, whoever you are, that sits in judgment; for in judging another you are condemning yourself. You,  the judge, are habitually practising the very same things.
B045C002V002	45	2	2	"We know that Gods judgment against those who practise such vices is in accord with the truth," you say?
B045C002V003	45	2	3	Very well; and do you suppose, you who judge those that practise such vices, and are doing the very same, that you will elude the judgment of God?
B045C002V004	45	2	4	Or do you despise the riches of his kindness and forbearance and long patience? Do you not know that the kindness of God is leading you to repentance?
B045C002V005	45	2	5	In your hardness and impenitence of heart you are treasuring up for yourself wrath on the Day of Wrath, when the righteous judgment of God is revealed.
B045C002V006	45	2	6	For He will render to every man according to his works;
B045C002V007	45	2	7	eternal life to those who by patience in well-doing strive for glory and honor and immortality;
B045C002V008	45	2	8	but anger and wrath upon those who are self-willed and disobey the truth, but obey unrighteousness.
B045C002V009	45	2	9	Anguish and calamity will be upon every soul of man who practises evil, upon the Jew first, and also upon the Gentile;
B045C002V010	45	2	10	but glory and honor and peace to every man who does good, to the Jew first, and also to the Gentile.
B045C002V011	45	2	11	For there is no partiality with God.
B045C002V012	45	2	12	For all who have sinned without law will also perish without law;  and all who have sinned under law will be judged by law.
B045C002V013	45	2	13	For it is not the hearers of law who are righteous in the eyes of God; nay, it is the doers of law who will be accounted righteous.
B045C002V014	45	2	14	For when Gentiles, who have no law, obey by natural instinct the commands of the Law, they even though they have no law, are a law to themselves.
B045C002V015	45	2	15	For they show that the work of the Law is written in their hearts,  while their conscience bears them witness, as their reasonings accuse, or it may be defend, them,
B045C002V016	45	2	16	in the day when God will judge the secrets of men by Jesus Christ,  according to my gospel.
B045C002V017	45	2	17	Now if you bear the name of a Jew, and rely upon law, and boast yourself in God,
B045C002V018	45	2	18	and know his will, and can test the things that differ; if you are instructed out of the Law,
B045C002V019	45	2	19	and are confident that you yourself are a darkness,
B045C002V020	45	2	20	an instructor of the foolish, a teacher of the young, because you have in the Law the form of knowledge and of the truth - well then,  you who are teaching others, do you ever teach yourself?
B045C002V021	45	2	21	You who are preaching that a man should not steal, do you practise theft?
B045C002V022	45	2	22	You who keep saying that a man should not commit adultery, do you commit adultery? You who hold idols in abhorrence, are you plundering their temples?
B045C002V023	45	2	23	You who are making your boast in the Law, do you habitually dishonor God through your transgressions of the Law?
B045C002V024	45	2	24	For the name of God is continually blasphemed among the Gentiles because of you, even as the Scripture itself says.
B045C002V025	45	2	25	Circumcision does indeed profit, if you are obedient to the Law; but if you habitually break the Law, your circumcision is become uncircumcision.
B045C002V026	45	2	26	So if the uncircumcised keeps the ordinance of the Law, shall not his uncircumcision be reckoned equivalent to circumcision.
B045C002V027	45	2	27	And shall not those who are physically uncircumcised, but who keep the Law, condemn you who are a breaker of the Law, although you have a written law and circumcision?
B045C002V028	45	2	28	For the real Jew is not the man who is one outwardly, and the real circumcision is not outward in the flesh;
B045C002V029	45	2	29	but the real Jew is one inwardly, and real circumcision is heart-  circumcision, spiritual, not literal, praised not by men, but by God.
B045C003V001	45	3	1	What special privilege, then, has the Jew? Or what is the use of circumcision?
B045C003V002	45	3	2	Much in every way. First of all, because to them were entrusted the oracles of God.
B045C003V003	45	3	3	Supposing some of them have proved faithless?
B045C003V004	45	3	4	By no means! Be sure that God is ever true, though all mankind prove false. As it is written, That thou mayest be found just in thine argument, And gain thy cause when thou contendest.
B045C003V005	45	3	5	But if our unrighteousness thus brings out Gods righteousness, what shall we say? Is God unrighteous - I speak after the manner of men -  when he inflicts his anger on us?
B045C003V006	45	3	6	Be it far from us; for in that case how could God judge the world?
B045C003V007	45	3	7	But if by a falsehood of mine the truthfulness of God has been made to redound to his glory, why am I still tried as a sinner?
B045C003V008	45	3	8	And why not say (as I myself am slanderously reported to say), "Let us do evil that good may come out of it"? Such arguments are rightly condemned.
B045C003V009	45	3	9	What then? Are we Jews in a better position? Not at all, for I have already charged all, both Jews and Gentiles, with being under sin.
B045C003V010	45	3	10	As it is written. There is none righteous, no, not one;
B045C003V011	45	3	11	There is none that understands, none that seeks for God!
B045C003V012	45	3	12	All have swerved from the right path; Every one of them has become corrupt. There is none that practises good, no, not one.
B045C003V013	45	3	13	Their throat is an open grave; With their tongues they have used deceit. The venom of asps is under their lips.
B045C003V014	45	3	14	Their mouth is full of cursing and bitterness.
B045C003V015	45	3	15	Their feet are swift to shed blood.
B045C003V016	45	3	16	Destruction and ruin are in their paths;
B045C003V017	45	3	17	And the path of peace they have not known.
B045C003V018	45	3	18	Reverence for God is not before their eyes.
B045C003V019	45	3	19	Now we know that whatever the Law says, it speaks to those who are under the Law; so that every mouth may be shut, and all the world may be brought under the judgment of God.
B045C003V020	45	3	20	For no man will be justified in Gods sight by works of the Law; for through the Law comes the consciousness of sin.
B045C003V021	45	3	21	But now, quite apart from any law, a righteousness coming from God has been fully brought to light, continually witnessed to by the Law and the Prophets.
B045C003V022	45	3	22	I mean a righteousness coming from God through faith in Jesus Christ, for all who believe. For there is no distinction between Jew and Gentile,
B045C003V023	45	3	23	since all have sinned and lack the glory which comes from God;
B045C003V024	45	3	24	but they are now being justified by his free grace through the deliverance that is in Christ Jesus.
B045C003V025	45	3	25	For God openly set him forth for himself as an offering of atonement through faith, by means of his blood, in order to show forth his righteousness - since in his forbearance he had passed over the sins previously committed - to show forth his righteousness,
B045C003V026	45	3	26	I say, at this present time; that he himself might be just, and yet the justifier of him who has faith in Jesus.
B045C003V027	45	3	27	Then what becomes of boasting? It is shut out. What sort of law forbids it? A law of works? No, but a law of faith.
B045C003V028	45	3	28	For I conclude that a man is justified by faith, altogether apart from the deeds of the Law.
B045C003V029	45	3	29	Is God then the God of the Jews alone, and not of the Gentiles also?  He is God of the Gentiles also,
B045C003V030	45	3	30	since there is one God who will justify the circumcised through faith, and by their faith will he justify the uncircumcised.
B045C003V031	45	3	31	Do we then render law invalid through faith? Certainly not; on the contrary we make it stand.
B045C004V001	45	4	1	What then shall we say of Abraham, our ancestor in the flesh?
B045C004V002	45	4	2	For if Abraham was justified by works, he has something to be proud of, but not before God.
B045C004V003	45	4	3	For what does Scripture say? And Abraham believed God, and it was set down to his account as righteousness.
B045C004V004	45	4	4	Now if a man earn his pay by his work, it is not counted to him as a favor, but it is paid him as a debt;
B045C004V005	45	4	5	but a man who does not "work," but believes in him who justifies the ungodly, has his faith imputed to him for righteousness.
B045C004V006	45	4	6	Just as David also speaks of the blessedness of the man to whom God imputes righteousness apart from actions.
B045C004V007	45	4	7	Blessed he says are they whose iniquities have been forgiven, And whose sins have been covered.
B045C004V008	45	4	8	Blessed is the man to whom the Lord will not impute sin.
B045C004V009	45	4	9	Is this blessing, then, for the circumcised alone? or for the uncircumcised also? Abrahams faith, I say, was imputed to him for righteousness.
B045C004V010	45	4	10	How then was it imputed to him? When he was circumcised? or uncircumcised? Not in circumcision, but in uncircumcision;
B045C004V011	45	4	11	and he received circumcision as a sign, a seal of the faith-  righteousness which he had while he was in uncircumcision; in order that he might be the father of all who believe, even though they are uncircumcised; so that righteousness might be imputed to them.
B045C004V012	45	4	12	He is the father of circumcision to those who are not merely circumcised, but who also walk in the steps of that faith of our father Abraham which he held while he was as yet uncircumcised.
B045C004V013	45	4	13	For the promise that he should be heir of the world did not come to Abraham or to his posterity through law, but through faith-  righteousness.
B045C004V014	45	4	14	For if those who are righteous through law are heirs, faith is empty and the promise becomes void.
B045C004V015	45	4	15	For law works wrath; but where there is no law, neither is there transgression.
B045C004V016	45	4	16	This is why righteousness is of faith, that it may be a free gift;  so that the promise stands firm to all Abrahams posterity; not to his children of his faith. For in the sight of the God in whom he believed, who gives life to the dead, and calls into being that which is not, Abraham is the father of us all both Jews and Gentiles,
B045C004V017	45	4	17	as it is written, I have made you a father of many nations.
B045C004V018	45	4	18	For Abraham, hoping against hope, had faith to the end that he might become a father of many nations, according to that which had been spoken, So numberless shall your descendants be.
B045C004V019	45	4	19	Though he was about a hundred years old, his faith did not fail him when he regarded his own body, now as good as dead. and remembered Sarahs barrenness.
B045C004V020	45	4	20	Nor did he with regard to the promise of God waver in unbelief, but he waxed strong in faith, while he gave God glory,
B045C004V021	45	4	21	and was fully persuaded that what God had promised, he was able also to perform.
B045C004V022	45	4	22	And so his faith was reckoned to him for righteousness.
B045C004V023	45	4	23	Now these words were not written simply for his sake, but for us as well.
B045C004V024	45	4	24	For it will be "reckoned for righteousness." to us also, who believe on him that raised from the dead our Lord Jesus;
B045C004V025	45	4	25	who was betrayed to death for our transgressions, and raised again to life for our justification.
B045C005V001	45	5	1	Since we stand justified as the result of faith, let us continue to enjoy the peace we have with God through our Lord Jesus Christ.
B045C005V002	45	5	2	Through him also we have had our access into this grace in which we have taken our stand, and are exulting in hope of the glory of God.
B045C005V003	45	5	3	And not only so, but we are actually exulting also even in our troubles; for we know that trouble works fortitude,
B045C005V004	45	5	4	and fortitude character, and character, hope -
B045C005V005	45	5	5	a hope which never disappoints us. For through the Holy Spirit who has given to us, the "brimming river of the love of God" has overflowed in our hearts.
B045C005V006	45	5	6	For while we were still without strength, Christ died in due time for the ungodly.
B045C005V007	45	5	7	Why, a man will hardly give his life for another, even for a righteous man, though perchance for a good man one might even take it upon himself to die.
B045C005V008	45	5	8	But God gives proof of his love to us by the fact that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us.
B045C005V009	45	5	9	By how much more, then, being now justified in his blood, shall we be saved through him from the wrath of God.
B045C005V010	45	5	10	For if, when we were Gods enemies, we were reconciled to him through the death of his Son, how much more, now that we are reconciled, shall we be saved in his life.
B045C005V011	45	5	11	And not only that, but we exult in God through our Lord Jesus Christ, through whom we have now obtained our reconciliation.
B045C005V012	45	5	12	Thus, then, sin came into the world through one man, and through sin came death and so death spread to all men, because all had sinned.
B045C005V013	45	5	13	For prior to the Law, sin actually existed in the world, but sin was not set down to mans account when there was no law.
B045C005V014	45	5	14	Nevertheless, from Adam to Moses death reigned as king, even over those who had not sinned after the likeness of Adams transgression.  Now Adam is a type of Him who was to come.
B045C005V015	45	5	15	But the free gift is not like the transgression; for if through the transgression of that one man the rest on men died, much more did the grace of God and the gift given in his grace in the one Man, Jesus Christ, overflow unto the rest of men.
B045C005V016	45	5	16	And it is not with the free gift as it was through the one that sinned; for the judgment came from one transgression unto condemnation; but the free gift came from many transgressions unto acquittal.
B045C005V017	45	5	17	For if through the transgression of the one, death reigned as king through the one, much more shall those who receive the overflowing grace and gift of righteousness reign as kings in life through One,  through Jesus Christ.
B045C005V018	45	5	18	It follows then, as through the transgression of one man came condemnation unto all men, even so through the act of righteousness of One came acquittal and life to all men.
B045C005V019	45	5	19	For just as through the disobedience of one man the rest were made sinners; even so by the obedience of One shall all the rest be made righteous.
B045C005V020	45	5	20	Now law was brought in so that transgression might abound; but where sin abounded, grace super-abounded;
B045C005V021	45	5	21	in order that as sin has ruled as king in death, so also grace might rule as king in righteousness which issues in eternal life, through Jesus Christ our Lord,  - ours!
B045C006V001	45	6	1	What then shall we say? Shall we continue to abound in sin, in order that grace may come to abound?
B045C006V002	45	6	2	No indeed; how shall we who have died to sin still go on living in it any longer?
B045C006V003	45	6	3	For do you not know that all of us who have been baptized into Jesus Christ, have been baptized into his death?
B045C006V004	45	6	4	We have been buried together with him, then, through baptism into his death, in order that just as Christ was raised from the dead through the glory of the Father, so also we should live in a newness of life.
B045C006V005	45	6	5	For if we have become united with him in the likeness of his death,  so we shall also be united with him in the likeness of his resurrection.
B045C006V006	45	6	6	For this we know, that our old self was crucified with Christ, in order that the slave of sin might be destroyed; so that we should no longer be in slavery to sin -
B045C006V007	45	6	7	for he who is dead is set free from sin.
B045C006V008	45	6	8	Now if we have died with Christ, we believe that we shall also live with him;
B045C006V009	45	6	9	knowing that Christ, being raised from the dead, dies no more; death has no more dominion over him.
B045C006V010	45	6	10	For the death that he died, he died unto sin once for all; but the life that he lives he is living unto God.
B045C006V011	45	6	11	Even so count yourselves also to be dead unto sin, but alive unto God in Christ Jesus.
B045C006V012	45	6	12	Therefore let not sin rule as king in your mortal body, compelling you to obey its lusts.
B045C006V013	45	6	13	Do not continue to present any part of your body to sin to be used as a weapon of unrighteousness. On the contrary, be presenting yourselves to God, as alive from the dead, and the various parts of your bodies to be used as weapons of righteousness.
B045C006V014	45	6	14	For sin shall not lord it over you; for you are not under the rule of law, but under the rule of grace.
B045C006V015	45	6	15	What then? Shall we commit an act of sin because we are not under law, but under grace? Certainly not.
B045C006V016	45	6	16	Do you not know that when you surrender yourselves as slaves to any one to obey him, you are his slaves whom you obey; whether it be sin,  whose end is death, or obedience, whose end is righteousness?
B045C006V017	45	6	17	But God be thanked that you who were once the slaves of sin have obeyed from your hearts that type of teaching to which you were appointed;
B045C006V018	45	6	18	and being set free from sin, you became the slaves of righteousness -
B045C006V019	45	6	19	I speak in these homely figures because of the weakness of your fleshly nature - just as you once surrendered your faculties into slavery to impurity and to all lawlessness, so now you must surrender your faculties into slavery to righteousness, unto deeds of holiness.
B045C006V020	45	6	20	For when you were the slaves of sin, you were under no subjection to righteousness.
B045C006V021	45	6	21	What harvest-fruit then had you at that time in the things of which you are now ashamed? For the end of those things is death.
B045C006V022	45	6	22	But now that you have been set free from sin and become slaves of God, the harvest-fruit which you are reaping tends to produce holiness, and it ends is life eternal.
B045C006V023	45	6	23	FOR THE POOR WAGES OF SIN IS DEATH, BUT THE FREE GIFT OF GOD IS ETERNAL LIFE IN CHRIST JESUS, OUR MASTER.
B045C007V001	45	7	1	Surely, brothers, you know (for I am speaking to those who know what law means) that law governs a person only during his lifetime?
B045C007V002	45	7	2	For a married woman who has a husband is bound by law to her husband during his lifetime; but if her husband dies, she is released from the law of her husband.
B045C007V003	45	7	3	So then, if during her husband lifetime, she unites herself with another man, she will be counted an adulteress; but if her husband dies, she is free from the Law, so that she is no adulteress, even if she unites herself with another man.
B045C007V004	45	7	4	So also, my brother, you were made dead to the Law through the body of Christ; that you should be joined to another, even to Him who was raised from the dead that we might bear fruit for God.
B045C007V005	45	7	5	For while we were unspiritual, the sinful passions, aroused by the Law, were ever active in every part of our bodies, leading us to bear fruit unto death.
B045C007V006	45	7	6	But now we have been released from the Law, because we are dead to that in which we were held; so that we are now in thraldom in new and spiritual conditions, and not under the old written code.
B045C007V007	45	7	7	What shall we say then? Is the Law sin? Certainly not. On the contrary I should not have become acquainted with sin had it not been for the Law; for except the Law had repeatedly said, "Thou shalt not lust," I should never have known the sin of lust.
B045C007V008	45	7	8	But when sin had gained a vantage-ground, by means of the commandment, it stirred up within me all manner of lust; for where there is no law, sin is dead.
B045C007V009	45	7	9	Once I lived apart from the Law, myself; but when the commandment came, sin revived, and I died;
B045C007V010	45	7	10	and the very commandment which should have meant life, this I found to mean death.
B045C007V011	45	7	11	For sin, when it had gained a vantage-ground through the commandment, beguiled me, and through it slew me.
B045C007V012	45	7	12	So then the Law is holy, and the commandment is holy and righteous and good.
B045C007V013	45	7	13	Did then that which was good become for me death? Never! but sin did; that it might be manifest as sin, by that the unutterable malignity of sin might become plain through the commandment.
B045C007V014	45	7	14	For we know that the Law is spiritual; but as for me, I am a creature of flesh, bought and sold under the dominion of sin.
B045C007V015	45	7	15	For what I perform I know not; what I practise is not what I intend to do, but what I detest, that I habitually do.
B045C007V016	45	7	16	If then I habitually do what I do not intend to do, I am consenting to the Law, that it is right.
B045C007V017	45	7	17	And now it is longer I myself who do the deed, but it is sin which has its home in me.
B045C007V018	45	7	18	For I know that in me, that is in my flesh, no good thing has its home; for while to will is present with me, to carry out that which is right is not.
B045C007V019	45	7	19	For the good that I intend to do, I do not; but the evil which I do not; but the evil which I do not intend to do, that I am ever practising.
B045C007V020	45	7	20	But if I do the very thing I do not intend to do, it is no more I who practise it, but sin which has its home in me.
B045C007V021	45	7	21	I find, then, this law, that when I intend to do good, evil is ever present with me.
B045C007V022	45	7	22	For in my inmost self I delight in the law of God;
B045C007V023	45	7	23	but I find a different law in my bodily faculties, waging war with the law of my will, and taking me prisoner to that law of sin which is in my bodily faculties.
B045C007V024	45	7	24	Oh, wretched man that I am! Who shall deliver me from this slave of death?
B045C007V025	45	7	25	Oh, thank God! it is through Jesus Christ our Lord. So then I myself in my will am in thraldom to the law of God; yet in my animal nature I am in thraldom to the law of sin.
B045C008V001	45	8	1	Thus there is now no condemnation to those who are in Christ Jesus;
B045C008V002	45	8	2	for the law of the spirit of life in Christ Jesus has set me free from the law of sin and of death.
B045C008V003	45	8	3	For God has done what the Law could not do, weakened as it was by flesh. By sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh, and on account of sin, he condemned sin in the flesh;
B045C008V004	45	8	4	in order that the Law might be fulfilled in us who order our lives not after the flesh, but after the spirit.
B045C008V005	45	8	5	For they who live after the flesh, give their attention to the things of the flesh; But they who live after the spirit, give their attention to spiritual things.
B045C008V006	45	8	6	To be earthly minded means death; To be spiritually minded means life and peace.
B045C008V007	45	8	7	For to be earthly minded is enmity against God; For such a mind is not subject to the Law of God, Nor can it be;
B045C008V008	45	8	8	And they who are earthly minded cannot please God.
B045C008V009	45	8	9	But you are not earthly, but spiritual, if indeed the Spirit of God is really dwelling in you. If any one does not have the Spirit of Christ, he is none of his.
B045C008V010	45	8	10	But if Christ is in you, though your bodily self is dead because of sin, your spirit is full of life because of righteousness.
B045C008V011	45	8	11	But if the Spirit of Him who raised up Jesus from dead is dwelling in you, He who raised up Jesus from the dead is dwelling in you, He who raised up Christ Jesus from the dead will also make your dying bodily self live by his indwelling Spirit in your lives.
B045C008V012	45	8	12	Therefore, brothers, we are debtors - but not to the flesh, to live according to the flesh;
B045C008V013	45	8	13	for if you go on living according to the flesh, you are on the road to die; but if by the Spirit you keep putting to death the deeds of the body, you will live.
B045C008V014	45	8	14	For only those are sons of God who are led by Gods Spirit.
B045C008V015	45	8	15	For you have not received a spirit of slavery in order that you should once more be afraid; but you have received a spirit of adoption, in which we cry out, "My Father, my dear Father!"
B045C008V016	45	8	16	For his Spirit himself bears witness with our spirit, that we are children of God;
B045C008V017	45	8	17	and if children, then heirs, heirs of God and joint-heirs with Christ; but to share his glory, we must now be sharing his sufferings.
B045C008V018	45	8	18	For I count as nothing what we now suffer, in comparison with the glory which will soon be unveiled to us.
B045C008V019	45	8	19	All nature even is waiting with eager longing for the unveiling of the vision of Gods sons.
B045C008V020	45	8	20	For nature was subjected to imperfection, not by its own will, but by the will of Him who thus made it subject -
B045C008V021	45	8	21	yet not without the hope that some day nature itself also will be freed from the thraldom of decay, into the freedom which belongs to the glory of the children of God.
B045C008V022	45	8	22	For we know that all nature has been groaning and travailing together until this hour.
B045C008V023	45	8	23	And not only that, we ourselves, although we are grasping the first-  fruits of the Spirit, even we ourselves are inwardly groaning, while we are waiting for adoption, the redemption of our body.
B045C008V024	45	8	24	For by hope we are saved; but hope which is clearly seen is no longer hope.
B045C008V025	45	8	25	Who hopes for what he clearly sees? But if we hope for something that we do not see, we then patiently wait for it.
B045C008V026	45	8	26	In the same way the Spirit also takes hold with us in our weakness;  for we know knot how to pray as we ought; but the Spirit himself intercedes for us with groanings which cannot be uttered.
B045C008V027	45	8	27	And the Searcher of Hearts knows what the Sprits meaning is,  because his intercessions for the saints are according to the will of God.
B045C008V028	45	8	28	Now we know that all things continually work together for good to to those who love God, to those who have been the called according to his purpose.
B045C008V029	45	8	29	For whom he foreknew, he also foreordained to be conformed to the likeness of his Son, so that he might be the eldest of a great brotherhood;
B045C008V030	45	8	30	and whom he foreordained, those he also called; and whom he called,  those he also justified; and whom he justified, those he also glorified.
B045C008V031	45	8	31	What shall we say then, to these things? If God be for us, Who can be against us?
B045C008V032	45	8	32	He that spared not his own Son, But freely delivered him up for us all, How shall he not with him also freely give us all things?
B045C008V033	45	8	33	Who shall accuse Gods elect? God acquits them;
B045C008V034	45	8	34	Who is there to condemn them? Will Christ who died? Yes, and who rose from the dead, The Christ who is also at the right hand of God,  And is interceding for us?
B045C008V035	45	8	35	What shall separate us from the love of Christ? Shall anguish, or calamity, or persecution, or famine? Shall nakedness, or peril, or sword?
B045C008V036	45	8	36	Even as it is written. For thy sake we are killed all the day long;  We are accounted as sheep for the slaughter.
B045C008V037	45	8	37	Nay, in all these things we are more than conquerors Through Him who loved us.
B045C008V038	45	8	38	For I am fully persuaded that neither death nor life, Neither angels nor principalities, nor powers, Neither the present world nor the world to come, Nor the powers of Nature,
B045C008V039	45	8	39	Nor height, nor depth, Nor any other created thing, Shall be able to separate us from the love of God Which is in Christ Jesus our Lord.
B045C009V001	45	9	1	I am speaking the truth in Christ, it is no lie. My conscience bears me witness in the Holy Spirit that I have deep sorrow
B045C009V002	45	9	2	and incessant anguish in my heart.
B045C009V003	45	9	3	For I was on the point of praying to be accursed from Christ on behalf of my brothers, my kinsmen according to the flesh.
B045C009V004	45	9	4	For they are Israelites; to them belong the sonship, the Shekinah glory, the covenants, the giving of the Law; the service of the temple, and the promises;
B045C009V005	45	9	5	theirs are the patriarchs, and of them, as concerning the flesh, is Christ, who is over all, God, blessed forever, Amen.
B045C009V006	45	9	6	It is not, however, as though Gods word had failed! For they are not all Israel who have sprung from Israel;
B045C009V007	45	9	7	they are not all children of Abraham because they are Abrahams descendants. The promise was, In Isaac shall thy posterity be called.
B045C009V008	45	9	8	That is, it is not the children of the flesh who are children of God; but the children of the promise are counted as his posterity.
B045C009V009	45	9	9	For thus is the word of promise, According to this season I will come, and Sarah shall bear a son.
B045C009V010	45	9	10	And not only so, but when Rebecca was pregnant by our forefather Isaac, though one man was the father of both children,
B045C009V011	45	9	11	and even though they were still unborn, and had done nothing either good or bad, in order that the purpose of God might stand according to election, not of works, but of Him who called,
B045C009V012	45	9	12	it was said to her, The elder shall serve the younger.
B045C009V013	45	9	13	As it is written, Jacob have I loved, but Esau have I hated.
B045C009V014	45	9	14	What shall we say then? that there is injustice with God? No indeed.
B045C009V015	45	9	15	His words to Moses are. I will have mercy on whom I choose to have mercy; I will have compassion on whom I choose to have compassion.
B045C009V016	45	9	16	So then it is not a question of him who wills, nor of him who runs,  but of God who has mercy.
B045C009V017	45	9	17	For the Scripture says to Pharaoh, It is for this very purpose that I have raised you up, To show in you my power, And to proclaim my name far and wide, in all the earth.
B045C009V018	45	9	18	So then he has mercy on whom he will, and whom he will, he hardens.
B045C009V019	45	9	19	Then you will say to me. "Why does he still go on finding fault? Who can withstand his will?"
B045C009V020	45	9	20	"Nay, but who are you, O man, that replies to God? Shall the thing formed say unto him who formed it, "Why did you do me like this?"
B045C009V021	45	9	21	Or has not the potter power over the clay, to make out of the same lump one vessel for noble, and another for ignoble uses?
B045C009V022	45	9	22	But what if God, while intending to show forth his wrath, and to make known his power, yet endured, with much long-suffering, vessels of wrath, fitted to destruction?
B045C009V023	45	9	23	And what if he thus purposed to make known the riches of his glory upon vessels of mercy, which he had before prepared for glory?
B045C009V024	45	9	24	Now such are we whom he has called, not only from among the Jews,  but also from among the Gentiles.
B045C009V025	45	9	25	As he also said in Hosea. Those who were not my people I will call "my people," And her "beloved" who was not beloved;
B045C009V026	45	9	26	And in that very spot where it was told them, "You are not my people," There they shall be called "Sons of the living God."
B045C009V027	45	9	27	And in regard to Israel, Isaiah exclaims. Though the number of the sons of Israel be like the sands of the sea, it is but a remnant of those who shall be saved;
B045C009V028	45	9	28	for the Lord will execute his word upon the earth, finishing it and cutting it short.
B045C009V029	45	9	29	Even as in an earlier passage, Isaiah says, Except the Lord of Sabbath had us some few descendants, we should have become like Sodom, and should have fared like Gomorrah.
B045C009V030	45	9	30	What then shall we say? That Gentiles who never pursed righteousness have overtaken it, even the righteousness of faith?
B045C009V031	45	9	31	But that the descendants of Israel, who were in pursuit of a law of righteousness, did not arrive at that law?
B045C009V032	45	9	32	And why? Because they sought it not by faith, but thought to gain it by works. They stumbled at the stone of stumbling;
B045C009V033	45	9	33	even as it is written. Behold, I lay in Zion a stone of stumbling and a rock of offense; but he that believes on Him shall not be put to shame.
B045C010V001	45	10	1	Brothers, the longing of my heart and my prayer to God is for my countrymen, that they may be saved.
B045C010V002	45	10	2	For I bear them witness that they have a zeal for God, only it is a zeal without knowledge.
B045C010V003	45	10	3	For because they were ignorant of Gods righteousness, and sought to establish their own righteousness, they did not submit themselves to the righteousness of God.
B045C010V004	45	10	4	For to every believer Christ is an end of law as a means of righteousness.
B045C010V005	45	10	5	For Moses writes concerning the righteousness of the Law, saying,  The man that doeth it shall live by it.
B045C010V006	45	10	6	But the righteousness of faith speaks in this way. Say not in thine heart, "Who shall ascend to heaven?" - that is, to bring Christ down;
B045C010V007	45	10	7	Nor,"who shall descend into the abyss?" - that is, to bring Christ up from the dead.
B045C010V008	45	10	8	But what does it say? The word is near thee, even in thy mouth and in thy heart. That is the very word of faith which we preach;
B045C010V009	45	10	9	Confess with your mouth "Jesus is Lord," and believe in your heart that God actually raised him from the dead, and you will be saved.
B045C010V010	45	10	10	For with the heart man believes unto righteousness, and with the mouth confession is made unto salvation.
B045C010V011	45	10	11	The Scriptures say, Whoever believes in Him will not be put to shame.
B045C010V012	45	10	12	For there is no difference between Jew and Gentile, because the same Lord Jesus is all over, and is rich unto all who call upon Him;
B045C010V013	45	10	13	for Whoever will call upon the name of the Lord will be saved.
B045C010V014	45	10	14	How then shall thy call upon Him in whom they do not believe? And how are they to believe in One of whom they have never heard? And how shall they hear without a preacher?
B045C010V015	45	10	15	And how can men preach unless they are sent? As it is written, How beautiful are the feet of those who bring a glad gospel.
B045C010V016	45	10	16	And yet they did not all hearken to the good news; for Isaiah said,  Lord, who hath believed our message?
B045C010V017	45	10	17	So faith comes from a message heard, and the message comes from the teaching of Christ.
B045C010V018	45	10	18	But I ask, Did they fail to hear? Yes, truly, Their sound has gone out unto all the earth, And their words unto the ends of the world.
B045C010V019	45	10	19	But I say, Did Israel not know? First Moses says. I will provoke you to jealousy with that which is no nation; Against a Gentile nation,  void of understanding, will I anger you.
B045C010V020	45	10	20	But Isaiah speaks very boldly, I was found of those who were not seeking me, I was made manifest to those who were not asking for me.
B045C010V021	45	10	21	But to Israel he says, All day long I have been spreading out my hands unto a disobedient and contrary people.
B045C011V001	45	11	1	Then I ask, Did God cast off his people? No indeed. For I also am an Israelite, a son of Abraham, a member of the tribe of Benjamin.
B045C011V002	45	11	2	God did not cast off his people whom he foreknew. For do you not know what is said in the Scripture about Elijah? how he pleaded with God against Israel, saying,
B045C011V003	45	11	3	Lord, they have killed thy prophets, they have overthrown thine altars; And now I alone am left, and they seek my life.
B045C011V004	45	11	4	But what was the answer of God to him? I have reserved for myself seven thousand who have not bowed the knee to Baal.
B045C011V005	45	11	5	In the same way also at this time there is a remnant chosen by gift of grace.
B045C011V006	45	11	6	But if it is by grace, it is no longer of works; or else grace is no more grace.
B045C011V007	45	11	7	What then? that which Israel has been seeking for, that he has not obtained; but the chosen have obtained it, and the rest have been hardened.
B045C011V008	45	11	8	According as it is written, God has given them a spirit of slumber,  Eyes that they should not see, Ears that they should not hear, unto this day.
B045C011V009	45	11	9	As David says. Let their table be made a snare and a trap, And a stumbling-block and a recompense unto them;
B045C011V010	45	11	10	Let their eyes be darkened, that they may not see, And bow thou down their backs forever.
B045C011V011	45	11	11	I ask then, "Have they stumbled so as to fall?" No indeed; but by their lapse salvation has come unto Gentiles, "to provoke Israel to jealousy."
B045C011V012	45	11	12	Now if their stumbling enriches the world, and their loss enriches the Gentiles, how much more must their fulness do!
B045C011V013	45	11	13	For to you who are Gentiles I say that since I am an apostle to the Gentiles, I glorify my ministry,
B045C011V014	45	11	14	if by any means I might "provoke to jealousy" my kinsmen, and save some among them.
B045C011V015	45	11	15	For if their casting out is the reconciliation of the world to God,  what will their restoration be but life out of death?
B045C011V016	45	11	16	Now if the first-fruits of the dough Abraham and the Patriarchs are holy, so also is the whole mass their descendants. And if the root of a tree Abraham is holy, so also are the branches his descendants.
B045C011V017	45	11	17	Supposing that some of the branches have been broken off, and you,  although you were but a wild olive, have been grafted in among the branches and have become a partaker with them of the fatness of the olive tree, do not glory over the branches;
B045C011V018	45	11	18	or if you are glorying, remember that it is not you who uphold the root, but the root which upholds you.
B045C011V019	45	11	19	"Branches have been broken off," you say, "that I might be grafted in."
B045C011V020	45	11	20	True, through their unbelief they were broken off, and by your faith you stand. Do not be puffed up, but fear;
B045C011V021	45	11	21	for if God spared not the natural branches, neither will he spare you.
B045C011V022	45	11	22	Fix your gaze, therefore, on the goodness and the severity of God;  towards those who fell, severity, but towards you, Gods goodness, if you continue stedfast in his goodness; otherwise you, too, will be cut off.
B045C011V023	45	11	23	And they also those Jews, if they do not continue in their unbelief,  will be grafted in again; for God is able to graft them in again.
B045C011V024	45	11	24	For if you were cut out of that which is by nature a mere wild olive tree, and have been grafted, contrary to nature, into a fruitful olive tree, how much more shall these, the natural branches, be regrafted into their own olive tree?
B045C011V025	45	11	25	For I would not, my brothers, have you ignorant of this hidden truth, for fear that you become wise in your own conceits. that a hardening in part has befallen Israel, until the fulness of the Gentiles is come in.
B045C011V026	45	11	26	And so all Israel will be saved, as it is written. The deliver will come from Zion, He will banish all ungodliness from Jacob;
B045C011V027	45	11	27	This is my covenant with them, When I shall take away their sins.
B045C011V028	45	11	28	In relation to the gospel, the Jews are Gods enemies for your sake;  but in relation to the election, they are dearly loved for their forefathers sake.
B045C011V029	45	11	29	For no change of purpose can annul Gods free gift and call.
B045C011V030	45	11	30	And as in times past you were yourselves disobedient to God, but now, thanks to their disobedience, have obtained mercy;
B045C011V031	45	11	31	even so they also have now been disobedient, that by the mercy shown to you they also may now obtain mercy.
B045C011V032	45	11	32	For God has locked up all in the prison of disobedience, that upon all he may have mercy.
B045C011V033	45	11	33	Oh, the depths of the riches, both of the wisdom and the knowledge of God! How unfathomable are his judgments, and how unsearchable his paths!
B045C011V034	45	11	34	Who has known the mind of the Lord? Or who has been his counsellor?
B045C011V035	45	11	35	Who has first given to Him, So as to receive payment in return?
B045C011V036	45	11	36	For of him and through him, and for him, are all things. All glory to him forever and ever! Amen.
B045C012V001	45	12	1	I entreat you therefore, brothers, by the mercies of God, to present your bodies to Him as a living sacrifice, holy and acceptable to God.  This is your reasonable service of worship.
B045C012V002	45	12	2	And be not conformed to this world, but be transformed by the renewing of your minds, so that you may prove what is the good and acceptable and perfect will of God.
B045C012V003	45	12	3	For, through the grace that was given to me, I tell every man among you not to think of himself more highly than he ought to think; but so to think, as to think soberly, according to the measure of faith which God has given him.
B045C012V004	45	12	4	For even as we have many members in one body, and not all members have the same function;
B045C012V005	45	12	5	so we, who are many, are one body in Christ, and we are severally members of one another.
B045C012V006	45	12	6	But we have gifts differing according to the grace which was given to us. He that has the gift of prophecy, let him prophesy according to the proportion of his faith.
B045C012V007	45	12	7	If it is the gift of administration, let us give ourselves to our service.
B045C012V008	45	12	8	Let the teacher give himself to his teaching; and he who exhorts others to his exhortation. He who gives, let him do it in singleness of mind. He who rules, let him rule with diligence; and he who shows mercy must be cheerful.
B045C012V009	45	12	9	Let love be without insincerity. Abhor what is evil; wed yourselves to what is good.
B045C012V010	45	12	10	As for brotherly love, be tenderly affectionate one to another, in honor preferring one another.
B045C012V011	45	12	11	In your diligence be free from sloth. Be glowing in spirit. Slave for the master.
B045C012V012	45	12	12	Rejoice in hope; be patient under affliction; continue stedfast in prayer.
B045C012V013	45	12	13	Be liberal to needy saints. Practise hospitality.
B045C012V014	45	12	14	Bless your persecutors, bless, and curse not.
B045C012V015	45	12	15	Rejoice with those who rejoice, and weep with those who weep.
B045C012V016	45	12	16	Have full sympathy with one another. Set not your minds on high affairs, but associate with lowly folk. Do not be wise in your own conceits.
B045C012V017	45	12	17	Do not pay back evil for evil. Aim to do what is honorable in the eyes of all.
B045C012V018	45	12	18	If it be possible, so far as it lies with you, be at peace with all men.
B045C012V019	45	12	19	Never revenge yourself, beloved, but leave the field clear for Gods wrath; for it is written, "Vengeance is mine, I will repay," says the Lord.
B045C012V020	45	12	20	On the contrary, therefore, If your enemy is hungry, feed him; if he is thirsty, give him drink; for by so doing you will be heaping burning coals on his head.
B045C012V021	45	12	21	Do not be overcome by evil, but be overcoming evil with good.
B045C013V001	45	13	1	Every one should be in the higher authorities; for there is no authority apart from God. The authorities that now exist have been appointed by God.
B045C013V002	45	13	2	Therefore the man who rebels against authority is opposing the divine ordinances; and those who withstand will bring judgment on themselves.
B045C013V003	45	13	3	For rulers are no terror to good deeds, but to evil. Would you be fearless of the rulers authority? Do what is good, and you will have his praise.
B045C013V004	45	13	4	For the ruler is Gods minister appointed for your good. But if you are a wrong-doer, be afraid; he does not carry the sword to no purpose; he is Gods servant, appointed to vengeance upon the guilty.
B045C013V005	45	13	5	Wherefore you must needs be in subjection, not only because of fear,  but also for conscience sake.
B045C013V006	45	13	6	This too, is the reason why you pay taxes; because the authorities are ministers of Gods service, attending continually upon this very thing.
B045C013V007	45	13	7	Render to all their dues; taxes to whom taxes, customs to whom customs, respect to whom respect, and homage to whom homage is due.
B045C013V008	45	13	8	Never owe any one anything save the debt of brotherly love; for he who loves his neighbor has fulfilled the Law.
B045C013V009	45	13	9	For the Law which says, Thou shalt not commit adultery, thou shalt do no murder, thou shalt not steal, thou shalt not bear false witness, thou shalt not covet, and whatever other commandment there be - is all summed up in this one saying, Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.
B045C013V010	45	13	10	Love never wrongs his neighbor; therefore love is the fulfilment of the Law.
B045C013V011	45	13	11	Carry out these injunctions because you know the crisis that we are in, that now it is high time for you to awake out of sleep; for now is our salvation nearer than when we first believed.
B045C013V012	45	13	12	The night is far spent; The day is at hand. Let is therefore take off the deeds of darkness, Let us put on the armor of light.
B045C013V013	45	13	13	Let us live honestly, as in the day, Not in reveling and drunkenness, Not in lust and licentiousness, Not is strife and jealousy;
B045C013V014	45	13	14	But clothe yourselves with the Lord Jesus Christ, And make no provisions for your earthly nature And the gratification of its lusts.
B045C014V001	45	14	1	Welcome a man of weak faith, but not for the purpose of deciding doubtful points.
B045C014V002	45	14	2	One man has faith to eat anything; but he whose faith is weak, eats only vegetables.
B045C014V003	45	14	3	He who eats meat must not despise the man who abstains; and let not the man who abstains judge him who eats; for God has received him.
B045C014V004	45	14	4	Who are you just that judges the household-servant of another? To his own lord he stands or falls. And stand he will, for his Master has power to make him stand.
B045C014V005	45	14	5	There are some who esteem one day above another; there are others who esteem all days alike; let each other be fully persuaded in his own mind.
B045C014V006	45	14	6	He who regards the day, regards it unto his Lord; and he who regards it not, disregards it unto his Lord. He who eats meat, eats unto his Lord, for he gives God thanks; and he who abstains, abstains unto his Lord, since he, too, gives God thanks.
B045C014V007	45	14	7	For not one of us lives unto himself, and not one dies unto himself.
B045C014V008	45	14	8	If we live, we live unto our Lord; if we die, we die unto our Lord.  So then, whether we live or die, we belong to our Lord.
B045C014V009	45	14	9	For this purpose Christ died and became alive again, that he might be the Lord both of the dead and of the living.
B045C014V010	45	14	10	But you the abstainer, why do you pass judgment on your brother? Or you again the non-abstainer, why do you despise yours? For we shall all stand before the judgment-seat of God.
B045C014V011	45	14	11	For it is written, "As I live," says the Lord, "to me every knee shall bow, And to God shall every tongue confess."
B045C014V012	45	14	12	So then each one of us shall give account of himself to God.
B045C014V013	45	14	13	So let us no longer pass judgment on one another; rather let this be your judgment, that no one put a stumbling-block in his brothers way, nor any cause of falling.
B045C014V014	45	14	14	I know and am persuaded in the Lord Jesus that nothing is in itself unclean; but any food is "unclean" for one who considers it "unclean."
B045C014V015	45	14	15	If your brother is continually pained because of your food, you are not conducting yourself any longer in love. Do not, by what you eat,  persist in destroying a man for whom Christ died.
B045C014V016	45	14	16	Therefore do not let what is right, so far as you are concerned, be evil spoken of.
B045C014V017	45	14	17	For the kingdom of God is not a matter of eating and drinking, but of righteousness and peace and joy in the Holy Spirit.
B045C014V018	45	14	18	Those who are slaving for Christ devotedly in these ways, are well pleasing to God and highly commended by man.
B045C014V019	45	14	19	So then let is eagerly pursue the things that make for peace and the upbuilding of each other.
B045C014V020	45	14	20	Do not, for the sake of food, be tearing down Gods work. All food indeed is ceremonially clean, but a man is in the wrong if his food proves a stumbling-block.
B045C014V021	45	14	21	The right course is not to eat meat, nor to drink wine, nor to do anything through which your brother is made to stumble.
B045C014V022	45	14	22	Have you faith? Keep it to yourself as in the presence of God. He is a happy man who does not condemn himself in that which he approves.
B045C014V023	45	14	23	But he who has misgivings, and yet eats meat, is condemned already,  because his action is not based on faith; and whatever is not based on faith is sin.
B045C015V001	45	15	1	Now we who are strong ought to bear the infirmities of the weak, and not to seek our own pleasure.
B045C015V002	45	15	2	Let each one of us try to make his neighbor happy for his good, unto his upbuilding.
B045C015V003	45	15	3	For even Christ pleased not himself; but as it is written, The reproaches of those who were reproaching thee fell upon me.
B045C015V004	45	15	4	For everything that was written of old has been written for our instruction, that through patience, and through the comfort of the Scriptures, we might have hope.
B045C015V005	45	15	5	Now the God of patience and of comfort grant you to be in full sympathy with one another, in accordance with the example of Jesus Christ;
B045C015V006	45	15	6	so that with one heart and with one voice you may glorify the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B045C015V007	45	15	7	Wherefore always receive one another into fellowship, to the glory of God, even as Christ also received you.
B045C015V008	45	15	8	For I say that Christ has been made a minister of the Circumcision the people of Israel, in vindication of Gods truth, so that he may confirm the promises given to our forefathers;
B045C015V009	45	15	9	and so that the Gentiles also should praise God for his mercy, as it is written, Therefore I will offer praise to thee among the Gentiles,  And sing to thy name.
B045C015V010	45	15	10	Or again, Rejoice, O Gentiles, with his people.
B045C015V011	45	15	11	Or again, Praise the Lord, all ye Gentiles, And let all the people extol him.
B045C015V012	45	15	12	Or again, as Isaiah says. There shall be the root of Jesse, And he that arises to rule over the Gentiles; On him shall the Gentiles hope.
B045C015V013	45	15	13	Now the God of all hope fill you with all joy and peace in believing, that you may be overflowing with hope in the power of the Holy Spirit.
B045C015V014	45	15	14	And I myself also am confident regarding you, my brothers, that you yourselves are already full of goodness, filled with all knowledge,  and well able to give advice to one another.
B045C015V015	45	15	15	Still I have written unto you the more boldly, in part, by way of reminding you, because of that gift of grace which God bestowed upon me, in making me a priest of Jesus Christ unto the Gentiles.
B045C015V016	45	15	16	I act as priest of the gospel of God; so that the Gentiles, when offered before him, may be an acceptable sacrifice, because consecrated by the Holy Spirit.
B045C015V017	45	15	17	I have then my boast in Christ Jesus concerning the things of God.
B045C015V018	45	15	18	For I will not dare to speak of any thing except that which Christ has done through me to bring the Gentiles to obedience by word and deed,
B045C015V019	45	15	19	through the might of signs and wonders, in the power of the Holy Spirit. So that beginning at Jerusalem and its environs, I have proclaimed without reserve the gospel of Christ, even as far as Illyricum.
B045C015V020	45	15	20	My ambition has been, however, to preach the gospel where Christs name was not already known, so that I might not build upon another mans foundation.
B045C015V021	45	15	21	But, as Scripture says, He shall be seen by those to whom no news about him ever came, And those who have never heard of him shall understand.
B045C015V022	45	15	22	This is why I have been so hindered from coming to you.
B045C015V023	45	15	23	But now, since I have no more any "opening" in these parts, and since I have longed for many years to come to you
B045C015V024	45	15	24	whenever I go to Spain, I am hoping to see you on my way there, and to be set forward by you on my way there, and to be set forward by you on my journey thither, after I have enjoyed your company for a little while.
B045C015V025	45	15	25	Just now I am going to Jerusalem to serve the saints.
B045C015V026	45	15	26	For it has been the good pleasure of Macedonia and Achaia to make an offering for the poor among the saints at Jerusalem.
B045C015V027	45	15	27	Yes, it has been made their good pleasure, and their debt, too. For if the Gentiles have been made partakers of their spiritual riches,  they owe it to them also to minister to them the Jews in worldly goods.
B045C015V028	45	15	28	When, therefore, I have settled this, and have secured to them the poor at Jerusalem the fruit of this collection, I shall come on by you into Spain.
B045C015V029	45	15	29	And I know that when I come to you, I shall come in the fulness of the blessing of Christ.
B045C015V030	45	15	30	Brothers, I beseech you, by Jesus Christ our Lord, and by the love which the Spirit gives, to help me in my struggle by your prayers to God on my behalf,
B045C015V031	45	15	31	that I may be delivered from the disobedient in Judea; that my mission to Jerusalem may be favorably received by the saints;
B045C015V032	45	15	32	and that I may come to you in joy, by the will of God, and find rest together with you.
B045C015V033	45	15	33	The God of peace be with you all! Amen.
B045C016V001	45	16	1	I commend to you our sister Phoebe, who is a minister of the church at Cenchrae.
B045C016V002	45	16	2	I beg you to give her a Christian welcome, as the saints should; and to assist her in any matter in which she may have need of you. For she herself has been made an overseer to many people, including myself.
B045C016V003	45	16	3	Salute Priscilla and Aquila, my fellow laborers in the cause of Jesus Christ,
B045C016V004	45	16	4	who risked their own lives to save mine; who are thanked not only by me,
B045C016V005	45	16	5	but by all the churches among the Gentiles. Salute likewise the church that meets in their home. Salute Epaenetus, my dearly beloved,  the first man in Roman Asia to believe in Christ.
B045C016V006	45	16	6	Salute Mary, who toiled terribly for you;
B045C016V007	45	16	7	and Andronicus and Junia, my kinsfolk and fellow prisoners, who are notable among the apostles, and who became Christians before I did.
B045C016V008	45	16	8	Salute Amplias, my beloved in the Lord;
B045C016V009	45	16	9	and Urbanus, my fellow toiler in Christ; and Stachys, my dear, dear friend.
B045C016V010	45	16	10	Salute Apellas, tested and tried in Christ, and the household of Aristobulus,
B045C016V011	45	16	11	and Herodion, my kinsman. Salute the believing members of the household of Narcissus.
B045C016V012	45	16	12	Salute Trypheana and Tryphosa, who are ever toiling in the Lord.  Salute dear Persis, who has toiled terribly in the Lords service.
B045C016V013	45	16	13	Salute Rufus, the chosen in the Lord, and his mother and mine.
B045C016V014	45	16	14	Salute Asyncritus, Phlegon, Hermes, Patrobas, Hermas, and the brothers who are associated with them.
B045C016V015	45	16	15	Salute Philologus and Julia, Nereus and his sister, Olympas, and all the saints associated with them.
B045C016V016	45	16	16	Salute one another with a holy kiss. All the churches of Christ salute you.
B045C016V017	45	16	17	I exhort you, brothers, to keep watch of those who are causing the divisions among you, and occasions of stumbling, contrary to the teaching which you have learned.
B045C016V018	45	16	18	Turn away from them. For men of that stamp are not the slaves of Christ, but are slaves to their own appetites. By their smooth and fair speech they beguile the hearts of the innocent.
B045C016V019	45	16	19	I say this, for the tidings of your obedience have been told throughout the world. On your own behalf, then, I rejoice; but I want you to be wise unto the good, but innocents in evil.
B045C016V020	45	16	20	The God of peace will soon crush Satan under your feet. The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you.
B045C016V021	45	16	21	Timothy, my fellow worker, salutes you; so do my fellow countrymen Lucius, Jason, and Sosipater.
B045C016V022	45	16	22	I, Tertius, who write this letter, salute you in the Lord.
B045C016V023	45	16	23	Gaius, my host, and the host of the church, salutes you. Erastus,  the treasurer of the city, salutes you, and so does brother Quartus.
B045C016V024	45	16	24	The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all!
B045C016V025	45	16	25	Now I commend you to Him who is able to keep you stedfast, according to my gospel, and the proclamation of Jesus Christ, whereby is unveiled the secret truth which was kept secret through immemorial ages,
B045C016V026	45	16	26	but now has been brought to light, and by command of the eternal God made known to the Gentiles by the scriptures of the Prophets, so that the Gentiles might hold obedience of the faith.
B045C016V027	45	16	27	Unto Him, the only wise God, through Jesus Christ, be glory forever.  Amen.
B046C001V001	46	1	1	Paul, called by the will of God to be an apostle of Jesus Christ,  and Sosthenes, his brother.
B046C001V002	46	1	2	to the Church of God at Corinth, to those who are sanctified in Christ Jesus, called to be saints, together with all, wherever they are, who call upon the name of the Lord Jesus.
B046C001V003	46	1	3	Grace to you, and peace from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C001V004	46	1	4	I am always thanking God on your behalf, for the grace of God bestowed on you in Christ Jesus;
B046C001V005	46	1	5	that in everything you have been enriched in him, in all speech, and in all knowledge
B046C001V006	46	1	6	(for thus my witness for Christ was confirmed among you);
B046C001V007	46	1	7	so that you lack no divine gift, while you are waiting for the revelation of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C001V008	46	1	8	He will also keep you perfectly stedfast unto the end, so that you will be unreprovable in the Day of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C001V009	46	1	9	Faithful is the God by whom you were called into fellowship with his Son, Jesus Christ our Lord.
B046C001V010	46	1	10	Now I beg you, brothers, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ, to speak in accord, all of you, and to have no divisions among you, but to be knit together in a common mind and temper.
B046C001V011	46	1	11	For it has been plainly told me concerning you, my brothers, by Chloes people, that there are dissensions among you.
B046C001V012	46	1	12	I mean by this that one of you says, "I am a follower of Paul";  another, "I of Apollos"; another, "I of Cephas"; another, "I of Christ."
B046C001V013	46	1	13	Has Christ been divided? Paul, was he crucified for you? or was it into the name of Paul that you were baptized?
B046C001V014	46	1	14	I am thankful to God that I baptized none of you except Crispus and Gaius,
B046C001V015	46	1	15	so that no one can say you were baptized in my name.
B046C001V016	46	1	16	Yes, I did baptize the house of Stephanas also, but I do not think I baptized any one else.
B046C001V017	46	1	17	For Christ did not think I baptized any one else. For Christ did not send me forth to baptize, but to proclaim the gospel; and that not in philosophic words, lest the Cross of Christ should be made an empty thing.
B046C001V018	46	1	18	For the message of the Cross is indeed for those on their way to destruction, foolishness; but for us who are on our way to salvation it is the power of God.
B046C001V019	46	1	19	For thus it is written, I will destroy the wisdom of the philosophers, And the prudence of the prudent will I confound.
B046C001V020	46	1	20	Sage, rabbi, skeptic of this present age - where are they all? Has not God made foolish the philosophy of the world?
B046C001V021	46	1	21	For when, in the wisdom of God, the world by its philosophy knew not God, the world by its philosophy knew not God, it pleased God, by the foolishness of preaching, to save those who believe.
B046C001V022	46	1	22	Jews continue to ask for miracles and Greeks are ever wanting philosophy,
B046C001V023	46	1	23	but we come preaching a crucified Messiah - to Jews a stumbling-  block, to Greeks foolishness,
B046C001V024	46	1	24	but to those who are the called, whether Jews or Greeks, Christ, the power of God and the wisdom of God.
B046C001V025	46	1	25	For the foolishness of God is wiser than men, and the weakness of God is stronger than men.
B046C001V026	46	1	26	For consider your own calling, brothers, that not many wise in earthly wisdom, not many powerful, not many of noble birth, have been called.
B046C001V027	46	1	27	No, God has chosen the worlds folly to confound its philosophy; and the worlds weakness to confound its strength.
B046C001V028	46	1	28	The worlds base things has God chosen, and the things that are not,  to bring to naught the things that are;
B046C001V029	46	1	29	so that no mortal man should glory in his presence.
B046C001V030	46	1	30	It is of him that you are in Christ Jesus, whom God made unto us wisdom and righteousness and sanctification and redemption,
B046C001V031	46	1	31	so that as Scripture says, He that glories, let him glory in the Lord.
B046C002V001	46	2	1	And when I came to you, brothers, I came not to proclaim Gods great secret purpose in fine language of philosophy;
B046C002V002	46	2	2	for I determined to know nothing, while among you, but Jesus as Christ, and him a crucified Christ.
B046C002V003	46	2	3	In weakness and fear and great trembling came I among you.
B046C002V004	46	2	4	My message and my preaching were not in the persuasive language of philosophy, but in demonstration of the Spirit and of power;
B046C002V005	46	2	5	in order that your faith should rest, not on human philosophy, but on the power of God.
B046C002V006	46	2	6	Notwithstanding, among those who are mature I do teach philosophy;  though not the philosophy of the present age, nor of its rulers who are coming to nought.
B046C002V007	46	2	7	No, it is Gods wisdom that I utter, that hidden wisdom which God had decreed before the world began, unto our glory.
B046C002V008	46	2	8	None of the rulers of the present age understands it, for if they had, they would not have crucified the Lord of Glory.
B046C002V009	46	2	9	Nay, as it is written. Eye has not seen, Nor ear heard, Neither have entered into mans heart The things which God has prepared For those who love him.
B046C002V010	46	2	10	Yet God has unveiled them to us by his Spirit. For the Spirit fathoms everything, even the abysmal depths of God.
B046C002V011	46	2	11	For what man knows the depths of man except the mans own inner Spirit? Even so, also, the Spirit of God knows the deeps profound of God.
B046C002V012	46	2	12	But we have not received the spirit of the world, but the Spirit which comes forth from God, that we may realize the blessings freely given us by God.
B046C002V013	46	2	13	Of these high themes we speak in words not taught by human philosophy, but by the Spirit; interpreting spiritual things to spiritual men.
B046C002V014	46	2	14	The unspiritual man rejects the teachings of Gods Spirit; for him it is folly. He cannot understand it, for it is spiritually discerned,
B046C002V015	46	2	15	But the spiritual man discerns everything, yet is himself discerned by no one.
B046C002V016	46	2	16	For what man understands the mind of the Lord, that he should instruct Him?
B046C003V001	46	3	1	As for me, brothers, I could not talk to you as spiritual men, but as to creatures of flesh, mere babes in Christ.
B046C003V002	46	3	2	I fed you milk, not meat; for you were unable to bear it.
B046C003V003	46	3	3	You are not able even now, for you are still unspiritual. While there is among you jealousy and strife, are you not still unspiritual, and behaving like worldlings?
B046C003V004	46	3	4	When one says, "I follow Paul," and another, "I follow Apollos," are you not mere worldlings?
B046C003V005	46	3	5	What then is Apollos? What is Paul? Just ministers through whom you have believed, and each doing the work that the Lord gave him.
B046C003V006	46	3	6	I planted, Apollos watered, but God made the seed grow.
B046C003V007	46	3	7	So neither is he who planted anything, nor he who watered, but God alone, who is making the seed grow.
B046C003V008	46	3	8	Now, though he who plants and he who waters are one, each will receive his own reward, according to his own service.
B046C003V009	46	3	9	For we are Gods fellow workers; and you are Gods field, you are Gods building.
B046C003V010	46	3	10	According to the grace of God vouchsafed me, like a skillful master-  builder, I have laid a foundation; but another will be building upon it. Let each take heed how he builds on it.
B046C003V011	46	3	11	The foundation is already laid - Jesus Christ - and no man can lay another.
B046C003V012	46	3	12	On that foundation, if a man proceeds to build gold, silver,  precious stones, wood, hay, stubble, each mans work will be made manifest.
B046C003V013	46	3	13	The Day will disclose it, for it dawns in fire, and the fire will test each mans work, of what quality it is.
B046C003V014	46	3	14	If any mans work - the building he has made - stands the test, he will be rewarded.
B046C003V015	46	3	15	If any mans work is burned up, he will suffer loss, but he himself will be saved, as it were through the flames.
B046C003V016	46	3	16	Do you not know what you are Gods sanctuary, and that the Spirit of God is dwelling within you?
B046C003V017	46	3	17	If any one tear down Gods sanctuary, God will tear him down; for the sanctuary of God is holy, and that is what you are.
B046C003V018	46	3	18	Let no one deceive himself. If any one of you supposes that he is wise in the philosophy of the present age, let him become foolish, so that he may be wise.
B046C003V019	46	3	19	For the philosophy of this world is foolishness in Gods sight. It is written, He snares the wise in their own craftiness,
B046C003V020	46	3	20	and again, The Lord knows the reasonings of the wise, how futile they are.
B046C003V021	46	3	21	So let no one make boast in men. For all things are yours;
B046C003V022	46	3	22	Paul, Apollos, Cephas, the world, life, death, things present or things to come; all things are yours;
B046C003V023	46	3	23	and you are Christs, and Christ is Gods.
B046C004V001	46	4	1	Let any man look upon us as servants of Christ, and stewards of the secret truths of God.
B046C004V002	46	4	2	Now it is required of stewards, that a man be found faithful.
B046C004V003	46	4	3	But to me it matters very little that I am judged by you, or by any earthly court.
B046C004V004	46	4	4	Indeed I do not even judge myself; for though I know nothing against myself, yet that does not vindicate me; for he who judges me is the Lord.
B046C004V005	46	4	5	So make no hasty judgment until the Lord come, who will both bring to light the hidden things of darkness, and will make plain the purpose of mens hearts. Then each mans due praise will come to him from God.
B046C004V006	46	4	6	Now these things, brothers, I have applied in a figure to myself and to Apollos for your sakes; that in us you might learn not to go beyond what is written; that none of you be puffed up for the one,  against the other.
B046C004V007	46	4	7	For who makes you a differ, brother? Or what have you that you did not receive? But if you did receive it, why are you boasting as if you had not received it?
B046C004V008	46	4	8	But you, forsooth, are already full, are you? You are already rich?  Without us you are already reigning? Yes, and I would that you did reign, so that we also might reign with you.
B046C004V009	46	4	9	But it seems to me that God has exhibited us apostles, last of all,  like men doomed to death; for we are made a spectacle to the whole world, both to men and to angels.
B046C004V010	46	4	10	For Christs sake we are fools, but you are quite philosophic in Christ. We are weak, but you are strong; you are honorable, but we are outcast.
B046C004V011	46	4	11	Even to his very hour we are enduring hunger and thirst and nakedness and blows.
B046C004V012	46	4	12	Homeless men, we toil, working with our own hands.
B046C004V013	46	4	13	When reviled, we bless; when persecuted, we endure; when defamed, we conciliate. We have been made, as it were, scum-o-the-earth, the very refuse of the world, to this very hour!
B046C004V014	46	4	14	I am not writing this to shame you, but to admonish you, as my beloved children.
B046C004V015	46	4	15	For though you have ten thousand tutors in Christ Jesus, you can have but one father. For in Christ Jesus I begot you through the gospel.
B046C004V016	46	4	16	I beg you then to imitate my example.
B046C004V017	46	4	17	With this in mind I have sent Timothy to you. He is my dear and faithful son in the Lord, who will remind you of my ways in Christ;  the manner in which I ever teach everywhere in every church.
B046C004V018	46	4	18	Now some are puffed up, as though I were not coming to you.
B046C004V019	46	4	19	But come to you I will, and that soon, if it please the Lord, and then I shall learn not the talk of these boasters, but their power.
B046C004V020	46	4	20	For the kingdom of God is not in talk, but in power.
B046C004V021	46	4	21	Which do you want? Am I to come to you with a rod, or in a loving and tender spirit?
B046C005V001	46	5	1	It is actually reported that there is immorality among you, and such immorality as is not even among the heathen - that a man has taken his fathers wife!
B046C005V002	46	5	2	Yet you are puffed up instead of mourning and removing from among you the man who has done this thing.
B046C005V003	46	5	3	For I, although absent in body, yet present in spirit, have already passed sentence, by the authority of our Lord Jesus Christ, on him who has done this thing.
B046C005V004	46	5	4	When you are gathered together, and my spirit is with you together with the power of our Lord Jesus,
B046C005V005	46	5	5	I have handed over such a man to Satan for the destruction of his flesh, that his spirit may be saved, in the day of the Lord Jesus.
B046C005V006	46	5	6	Your glorying is not good. Do you not know that even a little leaven leavens all the lump?
B046C005V007	46	5	7	Then get rid of the old leaven, so that you may be like a new lump,  as you are now unleavened. For our Paschal Lamb has already been sacrificed, Christ himself.
B046C005V008	46	5	8	So let us keep the unending feast, not with any old leaven, neither with leaven of malice and vice, but with unleavened bread of sincerity and truth.
B046C005V009	46	5	9	I told you in my letter not to associate with the immoral.
B046C005V010	46	5	10	Not that in this world you were actually to have no contact with the immoral, the avaricious, the thievish, or with idolaters; for then you would have to leave the world, altogether.
B046C005V011	46	5	11	But what I wrote was that you were not to associate with any so-  called brother who is immoral, or avaricious, or idolatrous, or abusive, or a drunkard, or an extortioner. No, with such persons do not even sit at table.
B046C005V012	46	5	12	What have I to do with the judging of outsiders? Must not you judge those who are within the church, while God judges outsiders?
B046C005V013	46	5	13	Expel that wicked man from among you.
B046C006V001	46	6	1	Dare any one of you who has a grievance against his neighbor go to law before heathen judges, instead of before the saints?
B046C006V002	46	6	2	Do you not know that the saints will judge the world? And if the world is to be tried by you, are you unfit to try such trifling cases?
B046C006V003	46	6	3	Do you not know that we are to try angels? How much more, then, the affairs of life.
B046C006V004	46	6	4	Why then, if you have cases relating to earthly affairs which need to be decided, is it men who are absolutely nothing in the church whom you make your judges?
B046C006V005	46	6	5	I say this to shame you. Is it so that there is not among you a single wise man, capable of deciding between a man and his brother?
B046C006V006	46	6	6	Must brother go to law with brother, and that, too, before unbelievers?
B046C006V007	46	6	7	Indeed, to say nothing more, the fact that you have lawsuits with one another is altogether a defect in you. Why not rather suffer injustice? Why not rather endure being cheated?
B046C006V008	46	6	8	On the contrary, you yourselves are inflicting injustice and fraud,  and that upon your brothers.
B046C006V009	46	6	9	Do you not know that the wicked will not inherit the kingdom of God?  Do not be deceived. None who are immoral, or idolaters, or adulterers, or catamites, or sodomites,
B046C006V010	46	6	10	or thieves, or avaricious men, or drunkards, or foul-mouthed men, or extortioners will inherit the kingdom of God.
B046C006V011	46	6	11	Such were some of you, but you have washed away your stains, you have been consecrated, you have been justified in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ, and in the Spirit of our God.
B046C006V012	46	6	12	"All things are lawful for me"? Yes, but not all things are good for me. "All things are lawful for me"? Yes, but I will not let myself be enslaved by the power of any.
B046C006V013	46	6	13	"Food is meant for the stomach, and the stomach for food"? Yes, but God will soon put an end both to the one and to the other. The body,  however, exists not for immorality, but for the Lord, and the Lord for the body;
B046C006V014	46	6	14	and the God who raised up our Lord will up-raise us also by his mighty power.
B046C006V015	46	6	15	You know, do you not, that your bodies are members of Christ? Shall I then take the members of Christ, and make them members of a harlot?  God forbid!
B046C006V016	46	6	16	Do you not know that he who joins himself to a harlot is one with her in body? (For God says, The two shall become one flesh.)
B046C006V017	46	6	17	While a man who is united with the Lord is one with Him in spirit?
B046C006V018	46	6	18	Flee from immorality. Every other sin that a man commits lies outside the body, but the immoral man sins against his own body.
B046C006V019	46	6	19	Do you not know that your body is a sanctuary of the Holy Spirit who is within you, the Spirit whom you have from God?
B046C006V020	46	6	20	You are not your own; for you have been bought with a price,  therefore glorify God in your bodies.
B046C007V001	46	7	1	Now concerning the question in your letter. It is well for a man to have no intercourse with a woman,
B046C007V002	46	7	2	but because there is so much immorality let each man have his own wife; and let each women have her own husband.
B046C007V003	46	7	3	Let the husband give his wife her due, and likewise the wife her husband. The wife is not mistress of her own person,
B046C007V004	46	7	4	but her husband is; and in the same way the husband is not master of his own person, but his wife is.
B046C007V005	46	7	5	Do not refuse one another, unless it is only temporary and by mutual consent, so that you may devote yourselves to prayer. Then come together again, lest through your lack of self-control Satan begin to tempt you to sin.
B046C007V006	46	7	6	But what I have just said is by way of concession, not command.
B046C007V007	46	7	7	I would that every one lived as I do; but each man has his own special gift from God, one this, another that.
B046C007V008	46	7	8	But to the unmarried, and the widows, I say that it is well for them to remain as I am.
B046C007V009	46	7	9	If, however, they are not exercising self-control, by all means let them marry; for marriage is better than the fever of passion.
B046C007V010	46	7	10	But to those already married my commandment is - and not mine, but the Lords - that a wife is not to leave her husband;
B046C007V011	46	7	11	(or if she has already left him let her either remain as she is, or be reconciled to him), and also that a husband is not to put away his wife.
B046C007V012	46	7	12	To the rest it is I who am speaking, not the Lord. If any brother has a wife who is not a believer, if he is willing to live with her,  let him not send her away.
B046C007V013	46	7	13	And a woman whose husband is not a believer, if he is willing to live with her, let her not separate from him.
B046C007V014	46	7	14	For the unbelieving husband is consecrated through union with his believing wife; and the unbelieving wife, through union with her believing husband. Otherwise your children would be unholy, but now they are consecrated to God.
B046C007V015	46	7	15	But if the unbelieving partner be determined to leave, separation let it be. In such cases the believing husband or wife is not under bondage. But it is into peace that God has called us.
B046C007V016	46	7	16	For how do you know, wife, whether you will save your husband? Or how do you know, husband, whether you will save your wife?
B046C007V017	46	7	17	Only whatever be the lot in life to which God has assigned each one -  and whatever the condition in which he was living when God called him-  -in that let him continue. Such is the rule I give in all the churches.
B046C007V018	46	7	18	So, was any man called, being circumcised? Let him not become uncircumcised. Was any man called when he was uncircumcised? Let him not be circumcised.
B046C007V019	46	7	19	Circumcision is nothing, and uncircumcision is nothing. Keeping Gods commands in everything.
B046C007V020	46	7	20	Whatever be the condition of life in which he was called, in that let him continue.
B046C007V021	46	7	21	Were you called in slavery? Let not that trouble you; but if you can become free make use of the opportunity.
B046C007V022	46	7	22	For the slave who has been called in the Lord is the Lords freedman; and in the same way, the free man who is called is Christs slave.
B046C007V023	46	7	23	You have been brought with a price; do not become slaves to men.
B046C007V024	46	7	24	Where each man stood when he was called, there, brothers, let him stay, close to God.
B046C007V025	46	7	25	I have no command from the Lord to give you concerning unmarried women; but I give you my opinion, and it is that of a man who,  through the Lords mercy, is deserving of your confidence.
B046C007V026	46	7	26	I think then, that in view of the time of suffering now imminent, it is best for a man to remain as he is.
B046C007V027	46	7	27	Are you bound to a wife? Do not seek to be free. Are you free from the marriage bond? Do not seek for a wife.
B046C007V028	46	7	28	Yet if you do not marry, you have not done wrong; and if a girl marries, she has not done wrong. Such people, however, will have trouble in worldy affairs, and I wish to spare you.
B046C007V029	46	7	29	Indeed, brothers, the time that remains to us has been shortened; so let those who have wives live as if they had none,
B046C007V030	46	7	30	let those who weep be as though they did not weep, those who rejoice as though they did not rejoice, those who buy as though they did not possess,
B046C007V031	46	7	31	and those who use the world as though using it sparingly. For the present phase of the world is passing away.
B046C007V032	46	7	32	So I want you to be free from all anxieties. An unmarried man is anxious about the Lords business, how he may please the Lord;
B046C007V033	46	7	33	but a married man is anxious about worldly affairs, how he may please his wife, and he is divided in his mind.
B046C007V034	46	7	34	Again, the woman who is widow, or the maid, is anxious about the Lords business, how she may be pure in body and in mind; but the married woman is anxious about worldly affairs, how she may please her husband.
B046C007V035	46	7	35	It is in your own interest that I say this; not that I may entangle you in a snare, but that I may help you to serve the Lord with fitting and undistracted service.
B046C007V036	46	7	36	If, however, a father feels that he is not treating his virgin daughter in a seemly manner, in leaving her unmarried beyond the flower of her age, and so the matter is urgent, let him do what she desires; he commits no sin. Let the marriage take place.
B046C007V037	46	7	37	On the other hand, he who is firm in his purpose and is under no compulsion, but is free to carry out his own wishes, and who has determined to keep his daughter unmarried, does well.
B046C007V038	46	7	38	So he that gives his daughter in marriage is doing right, and he who keeps her unmarried will be doing right, and he who keeps her unmarried will be doing better.
B046C007V039	46	7	39	A wife is bound to her husband during his lifetime; but if her husband dies, she is free to marry whomever she will, provided it be in the Lord.
B046C007V040	46	7	40	But she is happier, in my judgment, if she remains as she is; and I think that I, too, have the Spirit of God.
B046C008V001	46	8	1	Now in regard to food which has been offered to idols, we are sure of course that "we all have knowledge." But knowledge puffs up, while love builds up.
B046C008V002	46	8	2	If a man thinks that he already has knowledge, he does not yet truly know as he ought to know;
B046C008V003	46	8	3	but if a man loves God, he is known by him.
B046C008V004	46	8	4	Now as to eating food that has been offered to idols, we know well that an idol has no real existence in the universe, and that there is no God but One.
B046C008V005	46	8	5	For though there be so-called "gods," celestial of terrestrial, as indeed there are gods many and lords many,
B046C008V006	46	8	6	yet for there is one God, the Father, from whom are all things, and we for him; and one Lord Jesus Christ, by whom are all things, and we by him.
B046C008V007	46	8	7	But that "knowledge" is not possessed by all; but some, accustomed until now to the idol, eat food as that which has actually been offered to an idol, and so their conscience, being still weak, is defiled.
B046C008V008	46	8	8	Now food does not bring us nearness to God. Neither if we eat do we gain any advantage, nor if we eat not, do we lose any.
B046C008V009	46	8	9	But see to it lest this right of yours become a stumbling-block to the weak.
B046C008V010	46	8	10	For if any one should see you, the possessor of "knowledge,"  reclining at table in an idols temple, would not his conscience, if he were weak, be emboldened to eat things sacrificed to idols?
B046C008V011	46	8	11	So he is lost, this weak man, lost by your "knowledge." this brother for whom Christ died.
B046C008V012	46	8	12	In so sinning against your brothers, and in ever and again wounding their weak consciences, you are sinning against Christ.
B046C008V013	46	8	13	Therefore, if what I eat makes my brother to stumble, I will never eat meat again, lest I make my brother to stumble.
B046C009V001	46	9	1	Am I not free? Am I not an apostle? Have I not seen Jesus our Lord?  Are you not my work in the Lord?
B046C009V002	46	9	2	Even if I am not an apostle to others, to you at least I am; for you are the seal of my apostleship in the Lord.
B046C009V003	46	9	3	This is my reply to my critics.
B046C009V004	46	9	4	Have I no right to claim food and drink?
B046C009V005	46	9	5	Have I no right to take a believing wife with me on my journey, as the rest of the apostles and the Lords brothers and Peter do?
B046C009V006	46	9	6	Are we the only ones, Barnabas and I, who have no right to give up manual labor?
B046C009V007	46	9	7	What soldier ever serves at his own expense? What farmer ever plants a vineyard and his flock and does not taste the milk?
B046C009V008	46	9	8	Am I saying this on human authority only, or does not the Law also say the same?
B046C009V009	46	9	9	Yea, in the Law of Moses it is written, Thou shalt not muzzle an ox while he is treading out the grain.
B046C009V010	46	9	10	Is it the oxen that God is thinking about, or is it really said for our sakes? It was written for us; because the plowman ought to plow in hope, and the thresher in hope of getting a share of the crop.
B046C009V011	46	9	11	If I have sown for you the seeds of spiritual good, is it a great thing if I reap from you temporal goods?
B046C009V012	46	9	12	If others share this authority over you, do not I far more? Yet I have not availed myself of it, but am patiently enduring; so that I may not in any way hinder the progress of Christs gospel.
B046C009V013	46	9	13	You know, do you not, that those who minister in the temple, and those who serve at the altar, get their portion of the sacrifices?
B046C009V014	46	9	14	Even so the Lord ordained that those who proclaim the gospel should get their living by the gospel.
B046C009V015	46	9	15	But for my part, I have never availed myself of any of these rights.  I do not say this to bring it about in my own case. I would rather die than let any one make void this boast of mine.
B046C009V016	46	9	16	Proclaiming the gospel gives me no ground of boasting; for necessity is laid upon me; woe is me if I preach not the gospel.
B046C009V017	46	9	17	For if I do this of my own accord, I have my pay; but if unwilling,  I have at least discharged my stewardship.
B046C009V018	46	9	18	What then is my wage? This, that I can make the gospel free where I carry it; and that I can refrain from using my rights as a preacher of the gospel.
B046C009V019	46	9	19	Though free from all men, I make myself the slave of all, that I may win the more.
B046C009V020	46	9	20	To the Jews I am become like a Jew, that I may win Jews; to those under the Law, like one under the Law, though I am not under the Law,  myself;
B046C009V021	46	9	21	to those outside the Law, as one outside the Law, to win those outside the Law (though I am not outside the law of God, but inside the law of Christ).
B046C009V022	46	9	22	I am become weak to the weak, to win the weak. I am become all these things to all men that, by any and by all means, I may save some.
B046C009V023	46	9	23	And I am doing it all for the gospels sake, that I may become a copartner in it.
B046C009V024	46	9	24	Do you not know that in a foot-race, though all run, only one receives the prize? So run that you may win.
B046C009V025	46	9	25	Every man who contends in the games continually trains himself by all manner of self-restraint. Now they do it to get a fading garland,  but we, one that is unfading.
B046C009V026	46	9	26	For my part, then, I run with no wavering to the goal. I box not as one beating the air,
B046C009V027	46	9	27	but I bruise my body and keep it in subjection, lest having called others to the contest, I should myself be disqualified.
B046C010V001	46	10	1	For I would not have you ignorant, brothers, how our fathers were all under the cloud, and all passed through the sea,
B046C010V002	46	10	2	and all were baptized into Moses in the cloud and in the sea.
B046C010V003	46	10	3	They all ate of the same spiritual bread,
B046C010V004	46	10	4	and all drank from the same spiritual stream, for they were drinking from a spiritual rock that followed them, and that Rock was Christ.
B046C010V005	46	10	5	But in most of them God was not well pleased, for they were laid low in the desert.
B046C010V006	46	10	6	Now this happened as a warning for us, that we might not long for evil things as they longed.
B046C010V007	46	10	7	And you must not be idolaters like some of them. as it is written,  The people sat down to eat and drink, And they rose up for idol dances.
B046C010V008	46	10	8	Nor must we act licentiously, as some of them did, and fell in a single day, twenty-three thousand of them.
B046C010V009	46	10	9	Neither must we presume upon the patience of our Lord, as some of them presumed, and were destroyed by the serpents;
B046C010V010	46	10	10	nor murmur, as some of them did, and were destroyed by the Destroying Angel.
B046C010V011	46	10	11	Now these things were happening to them typically, but were written down for our admonition who stand at the meeting of the ages.
B046C010V012	46	10	12	So then let him who imagines that he is standing so securely beware lest he fall.
B046C010V013	46	10	13	No temptation has overtaken you that is beyond mans power; but God is faithful, who will not let you be tempted beyond what you can bear, but will, with every temptation, provide the way of escape also, so that you may be able to withstand.
B046C010V014	46	10	14	So then, my beloved, continually flee from idolatry.
B046C010V015	46	10	15	I am speaking to men of sense; do you yourselves judge what I say.
B046C010V016	46	10	16	The cup of blessing which we bless, is it not a common participation in the blood of Christ? The bread which we break, is it not a common participation in the body of Christ?
B046C010V017	46	10	17	Because we who are many are one bread, one body, for we all do share in the one loaf.
B046C010V018	46	10	18	Look at Israel according to the flesh; are not those who eat the sacrifices in communion with the altar?
B046C010V019	46	10	19	What then shall we say? that an offering to an idol is anything? or that an idol is really anything?
B046C010V020	46	10	20	On the contrary, what the heathen sacrifice they sacrifice to demons and not to God, and I do not want you to have communion with demons.
B046C010V021	46	10	21	You cannot drink the cup of the Lord and also the cup of demons; you cannot be partakers in the Lords table and in the table of demons.
B046C010V022	46	10	22	What! would we provoke the Lord to jealousy? Are we stronger than he?
B046C010V023	46	10	23	"All things are lawful," you say? But not all things are expedient;  "all things are lawful"; but not all build up.
B046C010V024	46	10	24	Let not each one be always seeking his own, but rather his neighbors good.
B046C010V025	46	10	25	Eat anything that is for sale in the markets, asking no questions for conscience sake;
B046C010V026	46	10	26	for the earth and its fulness are the Lords.
B046C010V027	46	10	27	If one who is not a believer invites you to his house, and you wish to go, eat everything that is set before you, without asking questions for conscience sake.
B046C010V028	46	10	28	But if any one tells you, "This food has been offered in sacrifice,"  do not eat it, for the sake of him who told you,
B046C010V029	46	10	29	and for your conscience sake - his conscience, not your own. "But,"  you may object, "why should my freedom be decided upon anothers scruples of conscience?
B046C010V030	46	10	30	If I eat after giving thanks, why am I denounced for eating that for which I have given thanks?"
B046C010V031	46	10	31	Because whether you are eating or whether you are drinking, you are to do it all for the glory of God.
B046C010V032	46	10	32	Do not be a cause of stumbling either to Jews of to Gentiles, or to the church of God.
B046C010V033	46	10	33	For so I also try to please all men in every way, not by seeking my own good, but the good of the many, that they may be saved.
B046C011V001	46	11	1	Be imitators of me, as I am an imitator of Christ.
B046C011V002	46	11	2	Indeed I praise you for remembering me in everything, and because you are holding fast to the traditions just as you received them.
B046C011V003	46	11	3	But I wish you to understand that the head of every man is Christ,  and of a wife her husband is head; and that God is head of Christ.
B046C011V004	46	11	4	Every man who prays or prophesies with head veiled dishonors his Head;
B046C011V005	46	11	5	but every woman who prays or prophesies with her head unveiled dishonors her head (her husband). for it is one and the same thing as if she were shaven.
B046C011V006	46	11	6	If a woman does not wear a veil, let her also cut off her hair; now if it is a disgrace for a woman to have her hair cut off or her head shaved, let her be veiled.
B046C011V007	46	11	7	A man, indeed, ought not to have his head veiled, for he is an image and glory of God; but woman is a glory of man.
B046C011V008	46	11	8	For it is not man who was made from woman, but woman was made from man.
B046C011V009	46	11	9	And man was not created for woman, but woman for man.
B046C011V010	46	11	10	For this reason the woman ought to have authority over her head,  because of her guardian angels.
B046C011V011	46	11	11	However, in the Lord neither is woman independent of man, nor is man independent of woman;
B046C011V012	46	11	12	for just as the woman was made from the man, so also is the man born of the woman, while they both come from God.
B046C011V013	46	11	13	Judge of this for your own selves. It is fitting that a woman should pray to God with her head unveiled.
B046C011V014	46	11	14	Nor does nature itself teach you that it is a disgrace to a man to have long hair,
B046C011V015	46	11	15	but it is womans glory, because her hair has been given her instead of a veil.
B046C011V016	46	11	16	If, however, any one is inclined to be disputatious regarding such a custom, let him know that neither I nor the churches of God hold to such a custom.
B046C011V017	46	11	17	But in giving you the following instructions, I cannot praise you;  your solemn assemblies do more harm than good.
B046C011V018	46	11	18	To begin with, I am told - and I believe there is some truth in it -  that when you meet at a church there are divisions among you.
B046C011V019	46	11	19	For there must needs be also parties among you, in order that the good may be tested and made known.
B046C011V020	46	11	20	Again, when you meet together, there is no true eating of the Lords Supper;
B046C011V021	46	11	21	for each one of you begins to eat his own supper; one goes hungry,  while another gets drunk.
B046C011V022	46	11	22	What! Have you no houses in which to eat or drink? or do you wish to show your contempt for the church of God, and to shame those who have no homes to eat in? What shall I say to you? Shall I praise you? In this I certainly do not praise you.
B046C011V023	46	11	23	For I passed on to you the account, which I myself received from the Lord; how the Lord Jesus, on the very night he was betrayed, took bread,
B046C011V024	46	11	24	and when he had given thanks, he broke it, saying, "This is my body,  broken for you; this do in memory of me."
B046C011V025	46	11	25	In the same way also, he took the cup after supper, saying. "This cup is the new covenant in my blood; do this, whenever you drink it,  in memory of me."
B046C011V026	46	11	26	For as often as you eat this bread and drink this cup, you are proclaiming your Lords death until he come.
B046C011V027	46	11	27	So he that eats the bread or drinks the cup of the Lord unworthy must answer for a sin against the body and blood of the Lord.
B046C011V028	46	11	28	Let each man scrutinize himself, and thus let him eat of the bread and drink of the cup.
B046C011V029	46	11	29	For whoever eats and drinks without discerning the body, eats and drinks condemnation to himself.
B046C011V030	46	11	30	This is why many among you are feeble and sickly, and many sleep.
B046C011V031	46	11	31	If however, we were judging ourselves aright, we should not now be condemned;
B046C011V032	46	11	32	but through our condemnation by the Lord, we are trained so that we may not be condemned;
B046C011V033	46	11	33	So, my brothers, whenever you come together for this meal, wait for one another.
B046C011V034	46	11	34	If any one is hungry, let him eat at home, so that your meetings do not bring condemnation upon you. The other matters I will adjust when I come.
B046C012V001	46	12	1	Now concerning spiritual gifts, brothers, I do not wish you to be ignorant.
B046C012V002	46	12	2	You know that when you were heathen you went astray after dumb idols, wherever he be led.
B046C012V003	46	12	3	Wherefore I want you to understand that no one who speaks in the Spirit of God says, "Jesus is accursed," and no one can say, "Jesus is Lord," except in the Holy Spirit.
B046C012V004	46	12	4	Now there are varieties of gifts, but the same Spirit;
B046C012V005	46	12	5	there are various forms of service, and the same Lord;
B046C012V006	46	12	6	and varieties of work, and the same God, who works in all.
B046C012V007	46	12	7	Now to each man has been given his manifestation of the Spirit for the common good.
B046C012V008	46	12	8	For to one man by the Spirit has been given a word of wisdom, to another a word of insight by the same Spirit;
B046C012V009	46	12	9	to one man by the same Spirit is given faith, to another gifts of healing by the one Spirit;
B046C012V010	46	12	10	to another the powers which work miracles, to another prophecy, to another the discernment of spirits; to another varieties of tongues,  to another the interpretation of tongues.
B046C012V011	46	12	11	But the one and the same Spirit gives power to all, distributing his gifts to each as he wills.
B046C012V012	46	12	12	For just as the body is one and has many members, and all the members of the body, although they be many, are one body; so also is Christ.
B046C012V013	46	12	13	And we can see this, for in one Spirit we were all baptized into one body, whether Jew or Gentile, whether slave or free, and we were all made to drink of one Spirit.
B046C012V014	46	12	14	For the body is not one member, but many.
B046C012V015	46	12	15	If the foot should say, "Because I am a hand, I am not part a part the body," would it not indeed be a part of the body?
B046C012V016	46	12	16	Or if the ear should say, "Because I am not an eye, I am not a part of the body," would it be any less a part of the body?
B046C012V017	46	12	17	If the whole body were an eye, where were hearing? If all were hearing, where were smelling?
B046C012V018	46	12	18	But now God has set the members, each one of them, in the body as it has pleased him.
B046C012V019	46	12	19	If all were one member, where would the body be?
B046C012V020	46	12	20	But now there are many members, but one body.
B046C012V021	46	12	21	And the eye cannot say to the hand, "I have no need of you". nor again of head to the feet, "I have no need for you."
B046C012V022	46	12	22	On the contrary, we need those members of the body which seem to be weaker;
B046C012V023	46	12	23	upon those parts of the body which we esteem less honorable, we bestow more abundant honor, and our uncomely parts have more abundant comeliness.
B046C012V024	46	12	24	For whereas our comely parts have no need, God has tempered the body together, giving more abundant honor to that member in which lacked;
B046C012V025	46	12	25	that there should be no disunion in the body, but that members mutual care for one another.
B046C012V026	46	12	26	When one member suffers, all the others suffer with it; and when one member is honored, all the members are glad with it.
B046C012V027	46	12	27	Now you are the body of Christ, and individually members of it.
B046C012V028	46	12	28	And God has appointed those in the church to be first of all apostles, second, prophets, third, teachers. then workers of miracles, healers, helpers, administrators, users of various kinds of "tongues."
B046C012V029	46	12	29	Are all apostles? Are all prophets? teachers? workers of miracles?
B046C012V030	46	12	30	Have all gifts of healing? Do all speak with tongues? Do all interpret?
B046C012V031	46	12	31	Desire earnestly the greater gifts. And yet I will go on to show you a still more excellent way.
B046C013V001	46	13	1	Though I speak in the tongues of men and of angels, but have no love, I am become a clanging brass, or a clashing cymbal.
B046C013V002	46	13	2	Though I have the gift of prophecy and understand all mysteries and all knowledge, and have all faith, so that I could remove mountains,  but have not love, I am nothing.
B046C013V003	46	13	3	And though I sell all my goods to feed the poor, and though I give my body to be burned, but have not love, it avails me nothing.
B046C013V004	46	13	4	Love suffers long and is kind; love envies not; love makes no parade, is not puffed up,
B046C013V005	46	13	5	is not rude, nor selfish, nor easily provoked. Love bears no malice,  never rejoices over wrong-doing,
B046C013V006	46	13	6	but rejoices when the truth rejoices.
B046C013V007	46	13	7	It knows how to be silent, it is trustful, hopeful, patient, enduring.
B046C013V008	46	13	8	Love never fails; but though there are prophecies, they will fail;  though there are tongues, they will cease; though there is knowledge,  it will be superseded.
B046C013V009	46	13	9	For our knowing is imperfect, and our prophesying is imperfect;
B046C013V010	46	13	10	but when the perfect is come, then the perfect will be done away.
B046C013V011	46	13	11	When I was a child I spoke like a child, felt like a child, thought like a child; now that I am become a man, I have done with childish things.
B046C013V012	46	13	12	For now we see as in a mirror, and are baffled, but then face to face; now I know in fragments, but then shall I understand even as I also have been understood.
B046C013V013	46	13	13	Faith, Hope, Love endure - these three; but the greatest of these is Love.
B046C014V001	46	14	1	Hotly pursue this love, yet seek earnestly spiritual gifts, and chiefly that you may prophesy.
B046C014V002	46	14	2	For he who speaks in a "tongue" speaks not to man but to God, for no one understands him, but in the Spirit he utters secret truths.
B046C014V003	46	14	3	But he who prophesies addresses words to men that build up,  encourage, and console.
B046C014V004	46	14	4	He who speaks in a tongue upbuilds himself; but he who prophesies upbuilds the church.
B046C014V005	46	14	5	Now I should like you all to speak with "tongues"; but I should rather that you prophesied, For he who prophesies is greater than he who speaks with tongues, unless he interprets, so that the church may be built up.
B046C014V006	46	14	6	Now brothers, if I should come to you speaking with tongues, what should I benefit you, unless I speak to you some revelation, or knowledge, or prophecy, or teaching?
B046C014V007	46	14	7	For if lifeless instruments such as the flute or the harp give no distinction in the sounds, how shall it be known what is fluted or harped?
B046C014V008	46	14	8	Or, for example, if the trumpet give an uncertain sound, what soldier will be prepared for battle?
B046C014V009	46	14	9	In the same way with you, if you utter unintelligible words with your tongue, how can what you say be understood? You will be speaking to the winds!
B046C014V010	46	14	10	There are, let us say, so many languages in the world, and none without its meaning.
B046C014V011	46	14	11	If then I do not know the force of expression, I shall seem a barbarian to the one who uses it, and he will seem a barbarian to me.
B046C014V012	46	14	12	So also in your case, since you are ambitious for spiritual gifts,  seek to excel in them for the upbuilding of the church.
B046C014V013	46	14	13	So let him who speaks with tongues pray that he may interpret.
B046C014V014	46	14	14	For if I pray in an unknown tongue, my spirit prays, but my mind is barren.
B046C014V015	46	14	15	What then? I will pray with my spirit, and I will pray also with my mind. I will praise God with my spirit, but I will praise him with my mind, also.
B046C014V016	46	14	16	For if you in your spirit bless God, how shall he who fills the place of the unlearned say the Amen to your thanksgiving, when he does not know what you are talking about?
B046C014V017	46	14	17	You on the one hand offer a good thanksgiving, but the other is not built up.
B046C014V018	46	14	18	Thank God I speak with tongues more than you all,
B046C014V019	46	14	19	but in the church I would rather speak five words with my understanding, so as to instruct others, than ten thousand in an unknown tongue.
B046C014V020	46	14	20	Brothers, do not become children in understanding; be babes in malice, but in understanding become mature men.
B046C014V021	46	14	21	In the Law it is written. With men of other tongues, and by the lips of strangers, will I speak to this people, and even then they will not listen to me, says the Lord.
B046C014V022	46	14	22	So then the gift of tongues is for a sign, not to believers, but to unbelievers; but prophecy is not for unbelievers, but for those who believe.
B046C014V023	46	14	23	Accordingly, when the whole church assemblies, and everybody is speaking "with tongues," if there enter men unlearned or unbelieving,  will they not say that you are mad?
B046C014V024	46	14	24	But if all are prophesying when an unlearned or unbelieving man enters, he is convicted in conscience by your speaker, he feels himself judged by all,
B046C014V025	46	14	25	and the secret depths of his heart are laid open. So he will fall upon his face and worship God, saying, "Of a truth, God is with you."
B046C014V026	46	14	26	What follows, then, brothers? Whenever you meet together, each contributes something; a psalm, a sermon, a revelation, a tongue, an interpretation. Let all be done for edification.
B046C014V027	46	14	27	If any one speaks in an unknown tongue, let it be by two, or at the most by three, and that in turn, and let some one interpret.
B046C014V028	46	14	28	But if there is no one to interpret, let them keep silence in the church, and speak to themselves and to God.
B046C014V029	46	14	29	Let the prophets speak by two or three, and let the others exercise their judgment.
B046C014V030	46	14	30	But if to one as he sits there some revelation is made, let the first be silent.
B046C014V031	46	14	31	For you can all prophesy one by one; so that all may be learning,  and all may be encouraged.
B046C014V032	46	14	32	The spirits of prophets are subject to prophets,
B046C014V033	46	14	33	for God is not a God of confusion, but of peace. This custom prevails in all the churches of the saints.
B046C014V034	46	14	34	"In your congregation" you write, "as in all the churches of the saints, let the women keep silence in the churches, for they are not permitted to speak. On the contrary let them be subordinate, as also says the law.
B046C014V035	46	14	35	And if they want to learn anything, let them ask their own husbands at home, for it is shameful for a women to speak in church."
B046C014V036	46	14	36	What, was it from you that the word of God went forth, or to you only did it come?
B046C014V037	46	14	37	If any one thinks himself a prophet or spiritual, let him recognize that what I am now writing you is a command of the Lord.
B046C014V038	46	14	38	But if any one disregard it he will be disregarded.
B046C014V039	46	14	39	So, my brothers, be ambitious for the gift of prophecy, and speak not against the gifts of tongues.
B046C014V040	46	14	40	Let everything be done decently and in order.
B046C015V001	46	15	1	Now I am calling to your remembrance, brothers, the gospel which I preached to you, which you also received, and on which you have taken your stand, ;47 The first man is of the earth, earthly; the second Man is of heaven.
B046C015V002	46	15	2	by which also you are saved, if you are holding fast the message which I preached to you; unless indeed you have believed in vain.
B046C015V003	46	15	3	For the very first thing I taught you was that I had myself been taught, that Christ died for our sins according to the Scripture,
B046C015V004	46	15	4	that he was buried, and that he was raised the third day, according to the Scriptures,
B046C015V005	46	15	5	and was seen by Cephas, and then by the Twelve.
B046C015V006	46	15	6	Afterward he was seen at one time by more than five hundred brethren, most of whom are still alive, but some are fallen asleep.
B046C015V007	46	15	7	Then he was seen by James, then by all the apostles,
B046C015V008	46	15	8	and last of all, as by one born out of due time, he was seen by me also.
B046C015V009	46	15	9	For I am the least of the apostles, I who am not worthy to be called an apostle, because I persecuted the church of God.
B046C015V010	46	15	10	But by the grace of God I am what I am, and that grace of his,  bestowed upon me, did not prove ineffectual. I labored more abundantly than all the rest, yet not I, but by the grace of God that is with me.
B046C015V011	46	15	11	But whether it is I or they, thus do I preach, and thus you came to believe.
B046C015V012	46	15	12	If then, we are preaching Christ, that he rose from the dead, how are some of you saying that there is no resurrection from the dead?
B046C015V013	46	15	13	But if there is no resurrection from the dead, then not even Christ has been raised;
B046C015V014	46	15	14	and if Christ has not been raised, then our preaching is vain, and vain also is your faith.
B046C015V015	46	15	15	More than that, we are detected in bearing false witness against God; because we testified of God that he raised Christ from the dead,  whom he did not raise, if indeed the dead rise not.
B046C015V016	46	15	16	For if the dead rise not, neither has Christ arisen;
B046C015V017	46	15	17	and if Christ be not risen, your faith is vain, you are still in your sins.
B046C015V018	46	15	18	More than that, those who are sleeping in Christ have perished.
B046C015V019	46	15	19	If in this life only we have hope in Christ, we are of all mankind most pitiable.
B046C015V020	46	15	20	But now, now, Christ is risen from the dead, the first-fruit of those who have fallen asleep.
B046C015V021	46	15	21	For since by man came to death, by man came also the resurrection from the dead.
B046C015V022	46	15	22	For just as in Adam all die, so also in Christ all will be made alive.
B046C015V023	46	15	23	But each in his own order; Christ the first-fruits, then those who belong to Christ at his appearing.
B046C015V024	46	15	24	And then the end, when he shall hand over his kingdom to God his Father, after he has abolished all rule and authority and power.
B046C015V025	46	15	25	For he must rule until he has put all his enemies under his feet.
B046C015V026	46	15	26	The last enemy that will be destroyed is Death.
B046C015V027	46	15	27	For He hast put all things under his feet, but in that quotation All things are put under him, it is evident that God is excepted, who put all things under Him.
B046C015V028	46	15	28	For when everything is subjected to him, then the Son himself shall subject himself to Him who made them subject, that God may be all in all.
B046C015V029	46	15	29	Else what shall they do who are baptized for the dead? If the dead are really not raised, why are they baptized for them?
B046C015V030	46	15	30	Yes, and why am I myself exposed to danger every hour?
B046C015V031	46	15	31	Every day I am facing death, my brothers, I affirm it by that pride in you which I have through Christ Jesus our Lord.
B046C015V032	46	15	32	If after the manner of men I have fought with wild beasts at Ephesus, what good does it do me? If the dead do not rise, Let us eat and drink, For we shall be dead tomorrow.
B046C015V033	46	15	33	Do not deceive yourselves. Evil companions ruin good morals.
B046C015V034	46	15	34	Wake up, do justly, cease from sin; for I say to your shame that some of you have no acquaintance with God.
B046C015V035	46	15	35	But some one will ask. "How are the dead raised? and with what body are they coming?"
B046C015V036	46	15	36	Foolish man! The seed you sow does not come to life unless it dies.
B046C015V037	46	15	37	And when you sow the seed you are not sowing the body that it will become, but bare grain, of wheat perhaps, or some other grain.
B046C015V038	46	15	38	But God gives it what body he pleases, and to each kind of seed its own body.
B046C015V039	46	15	39	All flesh is not the same flesh; there is human flesh, another of fishes of animals, another of birds, another of fishes.
B046C015V040	46	15	40	There are both celestial bodies and bodies terrestrial; but the splendor of the celestial is one thing, and the splendor of the terrestrial is another.
B046C015V041	46	15	41	There is one glory of the sun, another of the moon, and another of the stars; for star differs from star in glory.
B046C015V042	46	15	42	So it is in the resurrection of the dead. It is sown in corruption,  It is raised in incorruption;
B046C015V043	46	15	43	Sown in weakness, It is raised in power;
B046C015V044	46	15	44	The body sown is animal The body is raised is spiritual. If there is an animal body, there is also a spiritual body.
B046C015V045	46	15	45	Thus it is written. The first man, Adam, became a living being, the last Adam, a life-giving Spirit.
B046C015V046	46	15	46	Now it is not the spiritual which is first, but the animal, and then the spiritual.
B046C015V048	46	15	48	Like him who was of earth, are the earthy; and like Him who is of heaven, are the heavenly;
B046C015V049	46	15	49	As we have borne the likeness of him who was of earth, so also let us bear the likeness of Him who is of heaven.
B046C015V050	46	15	50	I tell you this, brothers, that flesh and blood cannot inherit the kingdom of God; nor can corruption inherit incorruption.
B046C015V051	46	15	51	Lo, I tell you a secret truth. we shall not all be sleeping, but we shall be changed,
B046C015V052	46	15	52	in a moment, in the twinkling of an eye, when the last trumpet sounds. For the trumpet will sound, and the dead will be raised,  incorruptible, and we shall be changed.
B046C015V053	46	15	53	For this corruptible must be clothed with incorruption, and this mortal must be clothed with immortality.
B046C015V054	46	15	54	And when this mortal has been clothed with immortality, then will the words of Scripture come to pass, Death has been swallowed up in victory.
B046C015V055	46	15	55	Where, Death, is thy victory? Where, Death, is thy sting?
B046C015V056	46	15	56	Now the sting of death is sin, and the power of sin is the Law.
B046C015V057	46	15	57	But thanks be to God, who has given us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.
B046C015V058	46	15	58	So, my brothers beloved, stand firm, immovable, always abounding in work for the Lord, because you know that your toil is not fruitless in the Lord.
B046C016V001	46	16	1	Now concerning the offering for the saints, you also are to do as I directed the church of Galatia.
B046C016V002	46	16	2	On the first day of each week let each of you put aside something,  keeping it in store as he may prosper, so that when I come there may be no collections going on.
B046C016V003	46	16	3	On my arrival I will send those whom you may accredit by letter to carry your bounty to Jerusalem.
B046C016V004	46	16	4	And if it is worth while for me to go too, they will accompany me.
B046C016V005	46	16	5	Now I shall come to you after I have gone through Macedonia.
B046C016V006	46	16	6	I shall remain some time with you; possibly spending the winter, in order that you may help me forward in whatever journey I take.
B046C016V007	46	16	7	For I do not wish at this present time to see you merely in passing;  but if the Lord permits, I hope to remain some time with you.
B046C016V008	46	16	8	I am staying for the present in Ephesus, until Pentecost;
B046C016V009	46	16	9	for a door has opened to me, great and effectual, and the opponents are many.
B046C016V010	46	16	10	If Timothy come, see to it that he is among you without trepidation;  for he is doing the Lords work, as I am, so let no one disparage him.
B046C016V011	46	16	11	Whenever he comes to me, send him on his way in peace, for I am expecting him with the other brothers.
B046C016V012	46	16	12	As for our Apollos, I have many times urged him to go to you with the others, but he was always unwilling to go to you at this time. He will come, however, whenever he has a good opportunity.
B046C016V013	46	16	13	Be watchful, stand firm in the faith, be manly, be strong.
B046C016V014	46	16	14	Let all that you do be done in love.
B046C016V015	46	16	15	I beg you this, my brothers - you know the household of Stephanus,  that they were the first-fruits of Achaia, and that they devoted themselves to the service of the saints -
B046C016V016	46	16	16	so I want you also to show deference to such, and to every fellow worker, and laborer.
B046C016V017	46	16	17	I am glad that Stephanus and Fortunatus and Achaicus have arrived,  for they have made up for your absence.
B046C016V018	46	16	18	They refresh my spirit as they do yours. So cultivate the acquaintance of such men.
B046C016V019	46	16	19	The churches of Asia greet you. Aquila and Priscilla (Prisca), with the church that meets in their house, greet you heartily in the Lord.
B046C016V020	46	16	20	All the brothers send greetings. Greet one another with a holy kiss.
B046C016V021	46	16	21	The greeting of me, Paul, with my own hand.
B046C016V022	46	16	22	If any one does not love the Lord, let him be accursed. Our Lord is coming.
B046C016V023	46	16	23	The grace of our Lord Jesus be with you.
B046C016V024	46	16	24	My love be with you all in Christ Jesus.
B047C001V001	47	1	1	To the Church of God which is in Corinth, and to all the saints throughout Greece. from Paul, by Gods will an apostle of Christ, and from brother Timothy.
B047C001V002	47	1	2	Grace to you and peace from God our Father in the Lord Jesus Christ.
B047C001V003	47	1	3	Thanks be to the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father of tender mercies and the God of all comfort,
B047C001V004	47	1	4	who ever comforts me in all my troubles, so that I may be continually able to comfort those who are in any trouble by the comfort with which God is ever comforting me.
B047C001V005	47	1	5	For just as I have more than my share in the sufferings of the Christ, so also through the Christ I have more than my share of comfort.
B047C001V006	47	1	6	If I am afflicted, it is for your comfort and salvation; and if I am receiving comfort, it is for your comfort - a comfort produced within you by your patient fortitude, under the same sufferings which I also am enduring.
B047C001V007	47	1	7	My hope for you is firm; for I know that as you are comrades in my sufferings, so also are you comrades in my comfort.
B047C001V008	47	1	8	Now, brothers, I want you to know about the troubles which befell me in Asia; how I was burdened altogether beyond my strength, so that I renounced all hope even of life itself.
B047C001V009	47	1	9	Indeed, I had in myself, and still have, the sentence of death, in order that I might not rely on myself, but on God who raises the dead to life.
B047C001V010	47	1	10	He delivered me from such a death, and will deliver me. On him I have set my hopes that he will continue to deliver me,
B047C001V011	47	1	11	while all of you also are helping me by your prayers; so that from many lips thanksgiving may rise on my behalf for the blessings vouchsafed to me through the intercessions of many.
B047C001V012	47	1	12	For this is my proud boast, the testimony of my conscience, that it was in holiness and with pure motives before God, not in worldly wisdom, but in the grace of God, that I have conducted myself in the world, and above all in my relations with you.
B047C001V013	47	1	13	For I am writing to you nothing different from what you read aloud and very well recognize, and I hope will continue to recognize to the very end,
B047C001V014	47	1	14	as some indeed did recognize in part at last, that I am your cause of boasting, just as you will be mine on the Day of Jesus our Lord.
B047C001V015	47	1	15	And in this confidence I intended to visit you, before going elsewhere, that you might have a pleasure twice over.
B047C001V016	47	1	16	I intended to go by you into Macedonia, and to come again to you from Macedonia, and by you to be sent forward on my way to Judea.
B047C001V017	47	1	17	In purposing this did I display "caprice"? Or what I purpose do I purpose in a worldly way,so that it may mean either "Yes, yes," or "No, no"?
B047C001V018	47	1	18	As God is faithful, my message to you is not now "Yes," now "No."
B047C001V019	47	1	19	For Jesus Christ, Son of God, who was proclaimed among you by us,  that is, by Silvanus and Timothy and me, was not wavering between "Yes" and "No," but in him is the everlasting "Yes."
B047C001V020	47	1	20	For however many are the promises of God, in him they are "Yes."  Therefore also through him let the Amen be said by our voices to the glory of God.
B047C001V021	47	1	21	And he who has established me with you in the Anointed One, and has anointed me, is God.
B047C001V022	47	1	22	He has also set his seal upon me, and given me the pledge of his Spirit in my heart.
B047C001V023	47	1	23	But for my part I call God to witness, as my soul shall answer for it, that it was to spare you that I came not to Corinth
B047C001V024	47	1	24	(not that I am attempting to lord it over your faith, but rather to work with you for your happiness); for your faith is stedfast.
B047C002V001	47	2	1	I decided that I would not visit you again in grief;
B047C002V002	47	2	2	for if I cause you grief, who is there to cause me joy except those whom I have grieved?
B047C002V003	47	2	3	And for this very reason I wrote you, that I might not come only to be grieved by those who ought to give me joy; and because I trusted in you all, that my joy is the joy of all of you.
B047C002V004	47	2	4	For I wrote to you out of much affliction and anguish of heart,  through many tears; not to pain you, but to convince you of my love,  my abundant love for you.
B047C002V005	47	2	5	As to him who has been, and now is, causing pain, it is not I whom he has pained, but all of you - at least some of you (not to overstate the case).
B047C002V006	47	2	6	Sufficient for the offender is the punishment imposed by the majority;
B047C002V007	47	2	7	so that now you ought rather to forgive and comfort him, lest he should be overwhelmed by the excess of his grief.
B047C002V008	47	2	8	So I beg you to reinstate him in your love.
B047C002V009	47	2	9	For this very purpose also I wrote you (before), that I might test you, to see if you were obedient in every respect.
B047C002V010	47	2	10	If you forgive the man, I forgive him, too; for whatever I have forgiven has been forgiven in the presence of Christ,
B047C002V011	47	2	11	for your sakes, that I may not be overreached by Satan, for I am not ignorant of his devices.
B047C002V012	47	2	12	Now when I came to Troas to preach the gospel of Christ, although a door was opened to me in the Lord,
B047C002V013	47	2	13	I could get no peace of mind because I failed to find Titus, my brother. So I bade them good-bye and started off for Macedonia.
B047C002V014	47	2	14	But thanks be to God, who in every place is leading me in the train of Christs triumph, and is making manifest through me the knowledge of him, an odor of incense everywhere.
B047C002V015	47	2	15	I am Christs fragrance upwafted unto God, among those who are being saved and those who are perishing;
B047C002V016	47	2	16	to these latter an odor of death to death, to the former, of life to life. For such service as this, who is sufficient?
B047C002V017	47	2	17	I am; for I am not like most, trafficking in the word of God, but rather from a sincere heart, like a man of God, I speak in Christ, in the very presence of God.
B047C003V001	47	3	1	Am I beginning again to "recommend" myself? Or do I need, as some do, letters of commendation either to you or from you?
B047C003V002	47	3	2	You are my letter, written on my heart, known and read by all men.
B047C003V003	47	3	3	Since all can see that you are a letter of Christ transcribed by men, written not with ink, but with the Spirit of the living God, not on tablets of stone, but on human hearts as tablets.
B047C003V004	47	3	4	Such confidence I have through Christ before God.
B047C003V005	47	3	5	Not that I am sufficient in myself to reach any conclusion in my own wisdom; but my sufficiency is from God.
B047C003V006	47	3	6	It is he who has also made me sufficient as a minister of a new covenant; not of a letter but of a spirit; for the letter kills, but the spirit makes alive.
B047C003V007	47	3	7	If, however, the administration of death, written with letters and engraved on stones, began in glory, so that the children of Israel could not gaze steadily on the face of Moses, because of the glory of his face - a glory even then fading -
B047C003V008	47	3	8	how much more shall the ministry of the Spirit abide in glory?
B047C003V009	47	3	9	For if the ministry of condemnation had glory, far more is the ministry of righteousness radiant in glory.
B047C003V010	47	3	10	Indeed that which once was glorious has lost its glory, because of the glory which surpasses it.
B047C003V011	47	3	11	For if that which was fading came in glory, far more will that which ever abides be glorious.
B047C003V012	47	3	12	Therefore, cherishing such a hope, I use great freedom of speech.
B047C003V013	47	3	13	I do not do as Moses did, who used to cover his face with a veil to keep the children of Israel from beholding the passing of a fading glory.
B047C003V014	47	3	14	Nay, their minds were made dull; for to this very day, at the public reading of the Old Testament, the same veil rests thereon, because it is not revealed to them that in Christ the veil is taken away.
B047C003V015	47	3	15	Yes, to this very day, whenever Moses is read, a veil lies on their hearts;
B047C003V016	47	3	16	but when their heart turns to our Lord the veil is stripped away.
B047C003V017	47	3	17	(The Lord means the Spirit, and where the Spirit of the Lord abides there is freedom.)
B047C003V018	47	3	18	And we all, with unveiled faces, reflecting like a mirror the glory of the Lord, are ourselves continually being transformed into the same likeness, from glory to glory, as by the Lord, the Spirit.
B047C004V001	47	4	1	So then, as I have this ministry because of Gods mercy to me, I do not lose heart.
B047C004V002	47	4	2	I have renounced the hidden things of shame, not spending my life in craftiness, nor adulterating the word of God; but setting forth the truth openly, I strive to commend myself to every mans conscience as in the sight of God.
B047C004V003	47	4	3	But even if my gospel, too, is "veiled," it is among those who are on the way to perish that it is "veiled."
B047C004V004	47	4	4	Among them the god of this age has blinded the understanding of the unbelieving so that the sunshine of the gospel of God, should not dawn upon them.
B047C004V005	47	4	5	It is not myself that I proclaim, but Christ Jesus as Master, and myself that I proclaim, and myself your slave for Jesus sake.
B047C004V006	47	4	6	For God who said, "Out of darkness light shall shine," is he who has shone in my heart, that the sunrise of the knowledge of God may shine forth in the face of Christ.
B047C004V007	47	4	7	But I hold this treasure in an earthen vessel, in order that the surpassing greatness of the power may be from God, and not from myself.
B047C004V008	47	4	8	On every side I am hard pressed, yet not hemmed in; perplexed, but not in despair;
B047C004V009	47	4	9	persecuted, but not forsaken; struck down, but not destroyed.
B047C004V010	47	4	10	Wherever I go, I am always carrying about in my body the dying of Jesus, in order that the life also of Jesus may be made manifest in this body of mine.
B047C004V011	47	4	11	For, alive though I am, I am always given over to death for the sake of Jesus, that the life also of Jesus may shine forth in my dying flesh.
B047C004V012	47	4	12	So while death is working in me, life is working in you.
B047C004V013	47	4	13	But having the same spirit of faith of which it is written, I believed, and therefore have spoken, I also believe and so I speak.
B047C004V014	47	4	14	For I know that He who raised from the dead the Lord Jesus, will raise me also with Jesus, and set me at your side in his presence.
B047C004V015	47	4	15	For everything is for your sakes, so that more abundant grace,  because of the thanksgiving of many voices, might overflow to the glory of God.
B047C004V016	47	4	16	For this reason, as I have said, I do not lose courage, but even though my outward man is wasting away, my inward man is being renewed, day by day.
B047C004V017	47	4	17	For my light affliction, which is but for a moment, is working out for me a far more exceeding and eternal weight of glory,
B047C004V018	47	4	18	while I am gazing not at things seen, but at things unseen; for things seen are temporal, but things unseen are eternal.
B047C005V001	47	5	1	For I know, if this earthly tent of mine were struck, I have a mansion built by God, a house not made with hands, eternal in the heavens.
B047C005V002	47	5	2	For in this tent I am groaning, earnestly longing to be under the cover of my heavenly habitation; if so be that being so covered,
B047C005V003	47	5	3	I shall not be found naked.
B047C005V004	47	5	4	For in this tent of mine I am groaning in deep trouble; not that I wish to be unclothed, but to be clothed upon, that what is mortal may be swallowed up in life.
B047C005V005	47	5	5	And He who has wrought me out for this very end is God, who has given me his Spirit as pledge.
B047C005V006	47	5	6	Therefore I am always of good courage, because I well know that while I am at home in the body, I am in banishment from the Lord,
B047C005V007	47	5	7	for I am walking by faith, not by sight.
B047C005V008	47	5	8	So I have good courage, and am well pleased rather, to be in banishment from the body and to be at home with the Lord.
B047C005V009	47	5	9	And for this reason I also make it home with the Lord.
B047C005V010	47	5	10	For we must all be made manifest, in our true characters, before the Judgment-seat of Christ; so that each one may receive according to that which he has done in his body, whether good or evil.
B047C005V011	47	5	11	So, because I know the fear of God, I "persuade men." What I am is manifest to God, and I hope manifest also to your conscience.
B047C005V012	47	5	12	I am not "commending myself to you again," but I am giving you an occasion of boasting on my behalf, so that you may have an answer ready for those who boast in externals, and not in the heart.
B047C005V013	47	5	13	For if I was "beside myself," it was to God; of if I am now "of sound mind," it is for you.
B047C005V014	47	5	14	For the love of Christ overmasters me; because I thus judge that if One has died for all, then all have died;
B047C005V015	47	5	15	and that he died for all in order that the living may live no longer for themselves, but for Him who died and rose again for them.
B047C005V016	47	5	16	Therefore henceforth I know no one simply as a man - even if I have known Christ as a man, yet now I do so no longer.
B047C005V017	47	5	17	So there is a new creation when any man is in Christ. The old life has passed away, behold, the new is come.
B047C005V018	47	5	18	And all this is from God, who through Christ reconciled me to himself, and gave me the ministry of reconciliation;
B047C005V019	47	5	19	how that God was in Christ reconciling a world to himself, not reckoning to men their trespasses; and that to me he has entrusted the message of that reconciliation.
B047C005V020	47	5	20	On Christs behalf, then, I come as ambassador. It is as though God was entreating you, through me, on Christs behalf I beg you to be reconciled to God.
B047C005V021	47	5	21	Him who knew no sin, in our behalf he has made to be sin; so that in him we might become the righteousness of God.
B047C006V001	47	6	1	As a worker with him I beseech you not to receive the grace of God in vain.
B047C006V002	47	6	2	For he said. In an acceptable time have I heard thee, And in the day of salvation have I succored thee. Behold, now is the acceptable time! behold, now is the day of salvation!
B047C006V003	47	6	3	I am giving no one a cause of stumbling in order that my ministry may not be discredited;
B047C006V004	47	6	4	but in every way I am striving to commend myself as Gods minister by stedfast endurance, by afflictions, by troubles, by distresses,
B047C006V005	47	6	5	by floggings, by imprisonment; in riots, in labors, in sleepless watching, in hunger and thirst;
B047C006V006	47	6	6	with purity, understanding, patience, and kindness; by the Holy Spirit, by love sincere,
B047C006V007	47	6	7	by a true teaching and an energy divine; by the weapons of righteousness, for attack or for defense,
B047C006V008	47	6	8	amid honor or dishonor, amid evil report and good report; as a deceiver and yet true;
B047C006V009	47	6	9	as unknown and yet well known; as at deaths door, yet, strange to tell, I live on; as chastened, but not killed;
B047C006V010	47	6	10	as grieved, but always glad; as poor, but making many rich; as having nothing, yet possessing everything.
B047C006V011	47	6	11	O Corinthians, I am unsealing my lips to you; my heart is wide open to you.
B047C006V012	47	6	12	There is no narrowness in my love; but the narrowness is in your own.
B047C006V013	47	6	13	I pray you, therefore, in fair exchange (I speak as to my children),  let your hearts also be wide open to me.
B047C006V014	47	6	14	Be not unequally yoked with unbelievers; for what fellowship has righteousness with lawlessness? what communion has light with darkness?
B047C006V015	47	6	15	What concord has Christ with Belial? What portion has a believer with an unbeliever?
B047C006V016	47	6	16	And what compact has Gods temple with idols? For we are a temple of the living God, as he has said. I will dwell among them, and walk about among them; I will be their God, and they will be my people.
B047C006V017	47	6	17	Therefore, Come out from among them and separate yourselves, saith the Lord, touch not what is unclean;
B047C006V018	47	6	18	then I will receive you and will be to you a Father, and you shall be to me sons and daughters, saith the Lord Almighty.
B047C007V001	47	7	1	As these promises are ours, beloved, let us cleanse ourselves from every defilement of body and of spirit, and perfect our holiness in the fear of God.
B047C007V002	47	7	2	Make room for me in your hearts! I have wronged no man, I have ruined no man, I have defrauded no man.
B047C007V003	47	7	3	I am not saying this to blame you, for as I have already said, I hold you in my heart to live together and to die together.
B047C007V004	47	7	4	Great is my faith in you; great is my cheerful assurance in you. I am filled with comfort; in spite of all my troubles, my heart is overflowing with joy.
B047C007V005	47	7	5	For even after I reached Macedonia, my flesh had no rest, but I was troubled on every hand. Without were fights; within were, fears.
B047C007V006	47	7	6	But the God who comforts the down-hearted comforted me by the coming of Titus,
B047C007V007	47	7	7	and not alone by his coming, but also by the comfort you had been to him. For he told me of your eager longing, of your penitence, and of your zeal on my behalf, so that I was happier still.
B047C007V008	47	7	8	Even if I caused you pain by my letter, I do not regret; though I did regret it when I saw that my letter had caused you pain, even for a time.
B047C007V009	47	7	9	But now I am glad; not because you were pained; but because your pain led you to repentance.
B047C007V010	47	7	10	For your pain came from God, and so you took no harm from me. For the pain which is from God works repentance leading to salvation, a repentance never to be regretted. But the worlds pain works death.
B047C007V011	47	7	11	Note the results of this pain which God permitted; what earnestness it has called forth in you, what explanations, what indignation, what alarm, what longing, what fervor, what punishment of wrong. In every way you have proved yourselves innocent in the matter.
B047C007V012	47	7	12	So then, even if I did write to you, it was not for the sake of the wrong-doer, or of him who had been wronged, but to make clear to yourselves in the sight of God your earnest care for me.
B047C007V013	47	7	13	This is what comforts me. In addition to this comfort of mine, I have been made still happier by the happiness of Titus; because his spirit was refreshed by you all.
B047C007V014	47	7	14	Although I have been boasting a little to him about you, I have not been put to shame. But as in every matter I have spoken the truth to you, so also my boast to Titus has been proved to be the truth.
B047C007V015	47	7	15	And his tender affection is all the greater toward you, when he calls to mind the obedience of you all, and the fear and trembling with which you received him.
B047C007V016	47	7	16	I rejoice that I have complete confidence in you.
B047C008V001	47	8	1	Now, brothers, I wish to tell you about the grace of God which has been manifest in the churches of Macedonia.
B047C008V002	47	8	2	For although in heavy trial of affliction, their overbrimming happiness, even in spite of their deep poverty, abounded to the opulence of their unselfishness.
B047C008V003	47	8	3	For I can testify that according to their ability, and even beyond their ability, of their own free will, too, they have given help.
B047C008V004	47	8	4	With earnest entreaty they craved of me the privilege of a share in ministering to the saints in Jerusalem.
B047C008V005	47	8	5	And this not as I had expected, but in accordance with the will of God, they first gave themselves to God and to me.
B047C008V006	47	8	6	With the result that I have been begging Titus that, as he had been the one to begin the work with you, so he should complete among you this grace also.
B047C008V007	47	8	7	Now then, as you excel in everything, in faith and utterance and knowledge and all zeal and in your love to me, see to it that you excel in this grace also.
B047C008V008	47	8	8	I do not say this by way of command, but by the zeal of others I am trying to prove the reality of your love.
B047C008V009	47	8	9	For you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, how though he was rich, for your sakes he became poor, that you through his poverty might become rich.
B047C008V010	47	8	10	And I will give you my opinion in this matter; for this offering is fitting in your case, considering that you made a beginning before others, not only in the willingness to do something but also in actually doing something a year ago.
B047C008V011	47	8	11	So now complete the doing of it also, in order that just as there was the readiness to will, so there may be the accomplishment according to your means.
B047C008V012	47	8	12	For if there be first willing mind, the gift is accepted according to what a man has, and not according to what he has not.
B047C008V013	47	8	13	Nor are other people to be relieved, and you to be distressed;
B047C008V014	47	8	14	but burdens are to be equalized. Now your abundance at this present time present time is a supply for their want, in supply for your want; and so burdens be equalized,
B047C008V015	47	8	15	even as it is written, He who gathered much had nothing over, and he who gathered little did not lack.
B047C008V016	47	8	16	But thanks be to God who has inspired in the heart of Titus the same zeal on your behalf that I have.
B047C008V017	47	8	17	For he not only consented to my request, but being thoroughly in earnest, comes to you of his own accord.
B047C008V018	47	8	18	And I am sending with him that brother whose fame in the service of the gospel is spread through all the churches.
B047C008V019	47	8	19	More than that, he is the one chosen by the churches to accompany me on my journey, in administering this gift of yours for the Lords glory. And this has my full consent,
B047C008V020	47	8	20	because I am on my guard in this, that no one should blame me, in respect to this bounty which I am administering.
B047C008V021	47	8	21	For I aim at being above reproach, not only in the sight of the Lord, but also in the sight of men.
B047C008V022	47	8	22	With them I am sending our brother of whose zeal I have often had proof in many ways, and who is now zealous because of his great confidence in you.
B047C008V023	47	8	23	As for Titus, remember that he is a partner of mine, and is also my associate in labors for you. As for the other brothers, remember that they are delegates from the churches, men in whom Christ is glorified.
B047C008V024	47	8	24	So show to the churches an evidence of your love, and a justification to these brothers of my boasting about you.
B047C009V001	47	9	1	It is indeed unnecessary for me to write you in regard to the ministration to the saints at Jerusalem,
B047C009V002	47	9	2	for I know how ready you are, and am always boasting about you to the Macedonians, telling them that Greece has been ready for a year past; and your zeal has been a spur to the majority of them.
B047C009V003	47	9	3	Nevertheless I am sending the brothers in order that my boast about you may not prove vain in this instance; so that, as I kept saying,  you may be prepared.
B047C009V004	47	9	4	For if any Macedonians come with me and find you not ready, shame would come upon me (not to speak of you) in respect to this confidence.
B047C009V005	47	9	5	So I have thought that I must ask these brothers to visit you beforehand, and get your promised contribution ready in advance. I want it to be given of your bounty, not extorted from your covetousness.
B047C009V006	47	9	6	Mark this; he who sows sparingly will also reap sparingly; and he who sows bountifully will also reap bountifully.
B047C009V007	47	9	7	But let each give according to the purpose of his heart; not grudgingly of under compulsion. It is a cheerful giver that God loves.
B047C009V008	47	9	8	And God is able to give you an overflowing measure of every grace,  so that all your wants of every kind may be supplied at all times,  and you may give of your abundance to every good work;
B047C009V009	47	9	9	As it is written. He scattered broadcast, he gave to the poor; His almsgiving continues forever.
B047C009V010	47	9	10	He who ever supplies seed to the sower, and bread for the food of man, will supply and make plentous your seed, and increase the harvest springing up from your almsgiving.
B047C009V011	47	9	11	You yourselves will be enriched with all good things, that you may give ungrudgingly; and your gifts, of which I am the agent, will make men give thanks to God.
B047C009V012	47	9	12	Because the ministry of this contribution not only supplies the needs of the saints, but also overflows in many a thanksgiving to God.
B047C009V013	47	9	13	For this ministration proves you. On account of it men glorify God for your faithfulness to your professions of the gospel of Christ,  and for the liberality of your gifts to them and to all.
B047C009V014	47	9	14	Moreover, in their prayers for you they will be longing after you,  because of the exceeding grace of God that is resting upon you.
B047C009V015	47	9	15	THANKS BE TO GOD FOR HIS UNSPEAKABLE GIFT!
B047C010V001	47	10	1	Now I Paul, myself, appeal to you by the humble-heartedness and selflessness of Christ - Paul who "in your presence is humble, but bold enough when he is absent" -
B047C010V002	47	10	2	I beseech you, and I say, do not make me show my boldness, when I come in the boldness with which I think I shall show my courage against some who think that I am walking on the low level of the flesh.
B047C010V003	47	10	3	Though I do walk on the low level of the flesh, I do not make war as the flesh does;
B047C010V004	47	10	4	for the weapons of my warfare are not weapons of the flesh, but mighty for God, in pulling down all fortresses.
B047C010V005	47	10	5	For I pull down imaginations and every crag that lifts itself against the knowledge of God. And I carry every thought away into captivity and subjection to Christ;
B047C010V006	47	10	6	and I am fully prepared to punish every act of disobedience, when once your submission has been put beyond question.
B047C010V007	47	10	7	Look these facts in the face. If any man is fully persuaded as regards himself that he belongs to Christ, let him consider again with himself, that just as he is Christs, so also am I.
B047C010V008	47	10	8	If, however, I were to boast more loudly concerning the authority which the Lord gave me (not to cast you down, but to build you up), I should have no cause for shame.
B047C010V009	47	10	9	Let it not seem as if I were overawing you with my letters.
B047C010V010	47	10	10	"His letters indeed," says one, "are mighty and forcible, but his personality is weak, and his speech contemptible."
B047C010V011	47	10	11	Let such a man assure himself that my actions, when I am present,  will be just like my words in my letters when I am absent.
B047C010V012	47	10	12	I have not indeed the audacity to class myself among, or compare myself with, certain of the self-commenders; yet they are not wise in measuring themselves by one another and in comparing themselves with one another.
B047C010V013	47	10	13	I, however, will not indulge in undue boasting, but will confine it within the limits of the sphere to which God has assigned me - a sphere which reaches even to you.
B047C010V014	47	10	14	For I am not overstepping the limits of my authority, as though I reached you not; since I have already come even as far as Corinth to proclaim the gospel of Christ.
B047C010V015	47	10	15	I am not "boasting beyond measure in the labors of others," but it is my hope that, as your faith goes on increasing among yourselves,  by the enlargement of my appointed limits,
B047C010V016	47	10	16	I may carry the gospel to countries beyond you; and not be boasting of work made ready to my hand within another mans limit.
B047C010V017	47	10	17	Meanwhile. Let him who boasts, boast in the Lord.
B047C010V018	47	10	18	For a man is proved worthy, not by his self-commendation, but when he is commended by the Lord.
B047C011V001	47	11	1	Would that you could put up with a little "folly" from me! Nay, do bear with me.
B047C011V002	47	11	2	I have a divine jealousy on your behalf; for I betrothed you to one only husband, even to Christ, that I might present you to him, a chaste virgin.
B047C011V003	47	11	3	But I fear lest, just as the serpent beguiled Eve in his craftiness,  so your minds should be seduced from your single-mindedness and purity toward Christ.
B047C011V004	47	11	4	If indeed some one is coming to preach another Jesus, whom I did not preach, or you are receiving a Spirit other than you once received,  or another gospel which you did not accept before, you would do well to bear with me.
B047C011V005	47	11	5	For I reckon that I am in no respect behind your superapostolic apostles.
B047C011V006	47	11	6	Yes, though I be unskilled in speech, at least I am not in knowledge; indeed I made this perfectly plain to you in all things and among all men.
B047C011V007	47	11	7	Is it a sin, forsooth, that I humbled myself that you might be exalted, in preaching the gospel to you free of cost?
B047C011V008	47	11	8	Other churches I spoiled, and took their wages to do you service.
B047C011V009	47	11	9	Even when I lacked the actual necessities of life while I was with you, I was a burden to no one; for whatever I lacked, the brothers from Macedonia supplied, when they came. So I kept myself from being a burden to you in any way, and will continue to do so.
B047C011V010	47	11	10	As the truth of Christ is in me, this boasting of mine shall not be stopped within the boundaries of Greece!
B047C011V011	47	11	11	And why? Because I love you not? God knows I do.
B047C011V012	47	11	12	I am doing and will continue to do this in order to cut away the ground from under those who wish some cause for slander; and that the ground of their boasting may appear as does mine.
B047C011V013	47	11	13	For such fellows are sham apostles of Christ.
B047C011V014	47	11	14	No wonder! for Satan himself disguises himself as an angel of light.
B047C011V015	47	11	15	It is no great marvel, then, if his ministers also disguise themselves as ministers of righteousness. Their end will be according to their works.
B047C011V016	47	11	16	I say again, let no one think me a fool. Or, if you must, at least bear with me as a fool, that I, too, may do a little boasting.
B047C011V017	47	11	17	What I am about to say I am not speaking by the Lords command, but as it were in pure folly, in this boldness of boasting.
B047C011V018	47	11	18	Since so many are making worldly boasts, I shall boast, too!
B047C011V019	47	11	19	Although you are wise, you put up with fools willingly enough!
B047C011V020	47	11	20	You put up with it, though they make slaves of you, live on you,  seize your property, lord it over you, even strike you in the face,  in the way of degradation!
B047C011V021	47	11	21	I say that I was weak, and yet for whatever reason any one is bold (I speak in mere folly) I too am bold.
B047C011V022	47	11	22	Are they Hebrews? So am I. Are they descendants of Israel? So am I.  Are they descendants of Abraham? So am I.
B047C011V023	47	11	23	Are they ministers of Christ? (I speak as though I were beside myself), such, far, more, am I; in labors more abundant, in imprisonments also more abundant, in floggings beyond measure, in deaths often.
B047C011V024	47	11	24	Five times at the hands of the Jews, I have received one short of forty lashes.
B047C011V025	47	11	25	Three times I have been scourged by the Romans; once I have been stoned; three times have I been shipwrecked; a night and a day have I been adrift in the open sea.
B047C011V026	47	11	26	My journeys have been many; in perils of rivers, in perils of bandits; in perils from my countrymen, in perils in the city, in perils in the wilderness; in perils on the sea, in perils among false brothers;
B047C011V027	47	11	27	in toil and weariness, often in sleepless watching, in hunger and thirst, often without anything to eat; in cold and in nakedness.
B047C011V028	47	11	28	Not to mention other things, there is the crowding pressure of each day upon me, the care of all the churches.
B047C011V029	47	11	29	Who is weak, and I am not weak? Who is caused to stumble, but I burn with indignation?
B047C011V030	47	11	30	If boast I must, it shall be concerning my weakness.
B047C011V031	47	11	31	The God and Father of the Lord Jesus, he who is blessed forever,  knows that I am telling the truth.
B047C011V032	47	11	32	In Damascus, the governor under Aretas the King, kept guard over the city of the Damascus, to arrest me;
B047C011V033	47	11	33	but through an opening in the wall I was let down in a basket, and so escaped and out of his hands.
B047C012V001	47	12	1	I am forced to boast, though it is unprofitable, but I will go on to visions and revelations of the Lord. ;18 I urged Titus to go, and with him I sent our brother. Did Titus make gain of you? And did I not walk in the same spirit as he did? Did I not take the very same steps?
B047C012V002	47	12	2	I know a Christian man who, fourteen years ago (whether in the body I know not, or out of the body, I know not. God knows), was caught up-  -this man of whom I speak - even into the third heaven.
B047C012V003	47	12	3	And I know such a man (whether in the body or apart from the body I know not, God knows),
B047C012V004	47	12	4	who was caught up into Paradise, and heard unutterable words which no human being is permitted to utter.
B047C012V005	47	12	5	Of such a one I will boast; but on my own behalf I will not boast except in my weaknesses.
B047C012V006	47	12	6	If I should choose to continue boasting I should not be foolish, for I should be speaking the truth. But I refrain, lest by the stupendous grandeur of the revelation any one should estimate me beyond what he sees in me, or hears from me.
B047C012V007	47	12	7	It was for this reason, lest I should be over-elated, that there was given me a thorn in the flesh, a messenger of Satan, to buffet me,  lest I should be over-elated.
B047C012V008	47	12	8	Concerning this, three times over I supplicated the Lord that it might leave me;
B047C012V009	47	12	9	but he has answered me. "My grace is sufficient for you; it is in weakness that my power is perfected."
B047C012V010	47	12	10	Most gladly therefore will I boast rather of my weakness, that over me like a tent may be pitched the power of Christ. That is why I rejoice in weakness, in ill-treatment, in troubles, in persecutions and calamities for Christs sake. For when I am weak, then am I strong.
B047C012V011	47	12	11	I am become a fool - you have forced me to; for you yourselves ought to have been my vindicators. In no respect am I inferior to these superapostolic apostles, even though I am nothing.
B047C012V012	47	12	12	In truth the signs of the true apostle were wrought among you in all patience by signs and marvels and powers.
B047C012V013	47	12	13	In what respect, then, were you inferior to the other churches,  except that I myself was not a burden to you? Forgive me this wrong!
B047C012V014	47	12	14	And now for the third time I am preparing to visit you. I will not be a burden to you, for I am not seeking yours, but you. For the children ought not to lay up for the parents, but the parents for the children.
B047C012V015	47	12	15	For my part, I will most gladly spend, yea, and will myself be spent, for your souls. If I love you more abundantly, am I to be loved the less?
B047C012V016	47	12	16	But though it be granted that I was not a burden to you, yet, you say, this was my cunning with which I caught you by a trick.
B047C012V017	47	12	17	Did I make gain of you through any of those whom I sent to you?
B047C012V019	47	12	19	Do you think that all this time I am defending myself to you? It is before the presence of God that I am speaking in Christ; and all,  beloved, for your upbuilding.
B047C012V020	47	12	20	For I dread that perhaps, when I come, I may not find you to be such as I wish, and that I may be found by you such as you do not wish; I dread lest there should be quarrels, jealousy, tempers, party spirit,  slandering, gossip, arrogance, tumults;
B047C012V021	47	12	21	and lest when I come again my God may humble me before you, and lest I shall mourn for many those who have sinned before, and have not repented of the impurity and immorality and wantonness which they have practised.
B047C013V001	47	13	1	This will be my third visit to you. Out of the mouth of two or three witnesses shall every word be confirmed.
B047C013V002	47	13	2	I have said formerly, and I now forewarn you as when I was present the second time, so now when I am absent the second time, so now when I am absent, saying to those who had sinned before, and to all the rest, "If I come again, I will not spare,"
B047C013V003	47	13	3	Since you want a proof of Christ who is speaking in me, he who is not feeble toward you, but powerful among you.
B047C013V004	47	13	4	For though he was crucified through weakness, yet he now lives through the power of God. I also am weak, sharing in his weakness,  but I shall live with him by the power of God.
B047C013V005	47	13	5	Examine yourselves to see if you are in the faith; put your own selves to the proof. Or do you not know, your own selves, that Jesus Christ is in you, unless indeed you fail to abide the proof?
B047C013V006	47	13	6	But I hope you will find that I abide the proof.
B047C013V007	47	13	7	And my prayer to God is that you may do no evil; not in order that I may appear approved, but that you may do what is noble, though I should seem unable to abide the proof.
B047C013V008	47	13	8	For I have no power against the truth, but only in defense of the truth.
B047C013V009	47	13	9	For I am always glad whenever I am weak, but you are strong. For this also I am praying, for your perfect reformation.
B047C013V010	47	13	10	For this reason I am writing thus while absent, so that when I come,  I may not have to deal sharply, according to the authority which the Lord gave me for building up, and not for pulling down.
B047C013V011	47	13	11	Finally, brothers, farewell. Aim at perfection, take courage, be of one mind, live in peace; so shall the God of love and peace be with you.
B047C013V012	47	13	12	Salute one another with a holy kiss.
B047C013V013	47	13	13	All the saints salute you.
B047C013V014	47	13	14	The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, and the love of God, and the fellowship of the Holy Spirit be with you all.
B048C001V001	48	1	1	Paul, an apostle sent not from men nor by any man, but by Jesus Christ and by God the Father who raised him from the dead;
B048C001V002	48	1	2	with all the brothers who are with me. To the churches of Galatia greeting.
B048C001V003	48	1	3	Grace be to you, and peace from God our Father and our Lord Jesus Christ,
B048C001V004	48	1	4	who gave himself for our sins, that he might deliver us from this present evil age in accordance with the will of our God and Father,
B048C001V005	48	1	5	to whom be glory forever and ever. Amen.
B048C001V006	48	1	6	I am amazed that you are so soon shifting your ground, and deserting him who called you by the grace of Christ,
B048C001V007	48	1	7	for another gospel, which indeed is not another; only there are certain individuals who are troubling you, and desiring to pervert the gospel of Christ.
B048C001V008	48	1	8	But even though I myself or an angel from heaven were to preach any gospel other than that which I did preach to you, let him be accursed.
B048C001V009	48	1	9	I have said it before, and I now repeat it, if any one is preaching a gospel to you other than that which you have received, let him be accursed.
B048C001V010	48	1	10	Think you that I am now trying to conciliate men or God? Or am I "seeking to please men"? If I were still seeking to please men, I should not be a slave of Christ.
B048C001V011	48	1	11	For I would have you know, brothers, that the gospel I preach is not man-made;
B048C001V012	48	1	12	for neither did I myself receive it from man, nor by man was I taught it, but by a revelation an apocalypse of Jesus Christ.
B048C001V013	48	1	13	For you have heard of my former conduct in Judaism, how furiously I used to persecute the church of God, and how I kept seeking to root it out;
B048C001V014	48	1	14	and how in my zeal for Judaism I outstripped many of my own age and nation, in my special zeal for the traditions of my forefathers.
B048C001V015	48	1	15	But when God who had set me apart from my very birth,
B048C001V016	48	1	16	and had called me by his grace, was pleased to reveal his Son in me,  so that I might preach his gospel among the Gentiles, without consulting a human being,
B048C001V017	48	1	17	or even going up to Jerusalem to see those who had been apostles before me, I went off at once to Arabia, and on my return came back to Damascus.
B048C001V018	48	1	18	Then three years later I went up to Jerusalem to get acquainted with Peter, and spent two weeks with him.
B048C001V019	48	1	19	I saw no other apostle except James, the Lords brother.
B048C001V020	48	1	20	(In what I am now writing, I call God to witness that I am telling the truth.)
B048C001V021	48	1	21	Then I went into the districts of Syria and Cilicia.
B048C001V022	48	1	22	But to the churches of Christ in Judea I was personally unknown;
B048C001V023	48	1	23	only they used to hear it said, "He who was once persecuting us is now preaching the gospel of the very faith which he once tried to ruin."
B048C001V024	48	1	24	And they were giving glory to God on my account.
B048C002V001	48	2	1	Fourteen years later I went up to Jerusalem again, with Barnabas,  and took Titus also with me
B048C002V002	48	2	2	(I went up at that time in obedience to a revelation). And I laid before them the gospel which I am wont to preach among the Gentiles.  I did this privately before those in authority, lest by any means I should be running, or should already have run, in vain.
B048C002V003	48	2	3	But although Titus, my companion, was a Greek, they did not compel even him to be circumcised.
B048C002V004	48	2	4	Yet there were false brethren who had crept in to spy out the freedom we enjoy in Christ Jesus, in order to enslave us again.
B048C002V005	48	2	5	To them we did not yield submission even for an hour, in order that the truth of the gospel might abide unshaken among you.
B048C002V006	48	2	6	But those in authority - what they once were makes no difference to me; God is no respecter of persons - those I say who were in authority had no additions to make my message.
B048C002V007	48	2	7	On the contrary, when they saw that I had been entrusted with the gospel for the uncircumcised, just as Peter has with the gospel for the circumcised
B048C002V008	48	2	8	(for he who has equipped Peter for the apostleship to the circumcised, equipped me also for the apostleship to the Gentiles),
B048C002V009	48	2	9	and when they recognized the grace which had been given to me, James and Cephas and John, then thought to be pillars, gave to Barnabas and to me the right hand of fellowship. They agreed that we should go to the Gentiles and they to the Jews.
B048C002V010	48	2	10	They stipulated only that we should remember the poor, which very thing indeed I was quite eager to do.
B048C002V011	48	2	11	But when Cephas came to Antioch I resisted him to his face, because he stood self-condemned.
B048C002V012	48	2	12	For until certain men came from James he used to eat with the Gentile Christians, but when they came, he began to draw back and to separate himself, because he was afraid of the circumcision party.
B048C002V013	48	2	13	And the rest of the Jewish Christians also dissimulated with him, so that even Barnabas was carried away by their hypocrisy.
B048C002V014	48	2	14	But when I saw that they were not walking a straight path, in the presence of the truth of the gospel, I said to Cephas before them all. "If you, although you are a Jew, live like the Gentiles and not like the Jews, why do you try to compel the Gentiles to become Jews?
B048C002V015	48	2	15	"We are Jews by birth, and not Gentile sinners;
B048C002V016	48	2	16	"yet because we know that no man is justified by the works of the Law, but by the faith of Jesus Christ, we ourselves also have put our faith in Jesus Christ, that we might be justified by the faith of Christ, and not by the works of the Law; for "By the works of the Law shall no flesh be justified."
B048C002V017	48	2	17	But if while seeking to be justified in Christ we ourselves also have been found to be sinners, is Christ then a minister of sin? Far from it!
B048C002V018	48	2	18	For if I am rebuilding the very things which I destroyed, I am proving myself a transgressor.
B048C002V019	48	2	19	For it is through law I died to law, in order to live to God.
B048C002V020	48	2	20	I have been crucified with Christ, so it is no longer I who am living, but it is Christ who is living in me; and the life I am now living in the flesh, I am living in faith of the Son of God who loved me and gave himself up for me.
B048C002V021	48	2	21	I do not annul the grace of God; for if righteousness comes by way of the Law, then indeed Christ died Christ for nothing.
B048C003V001	48	3	1	O foolish Galatians, who has bewitched you? You, before whose very eyes Jesus Christ was placarded as crucified!
B048C003V002	48	3	2	Answer me this one question. "When you received the Spirit, was it from doing what the Law commands or from believing the message heard?"
B048C003V003	48	3	3	Are you so without sense? After beginning with the Spirit, will you now end with the flesh?
B048C003V004	48	3	4	Did you have such experience to no purpose - if indeed it was really to no purpose?
B048C003V005	48	3	5	Does he then who supplies you with his Spirit and works miracles among you, do it because you do what the law commands of because you believe the message heard?
B048C003V006	48	3	6	Even as Abraham believed God and it was counted to him for righteousness?
B048C003V007	48	3	7	Notice then that the true sons of Abraham are children of faith.
B048C003V008	48	3	8	And the Scripture, anticipating Gods justification of the Gentiles by faith, announced the gospel to Abraham beforehand in the words, In thee shall all the Gentiles be blessed.
B048C003V009	48	3	9	So then they who are children of faith are blessed with Abraham the faithful;
B048C003V010	48	3	10	but a curse rests on those who have their root in the works of the Law; for it is written. Cursed is every one that continues not in all the things written in the Book of the Law, to do them.
B048C003V011	48	3	11	And it is manifest that by the Law no man is justified in the sight of God. because The just shall live by faith,
B048C003V012	48	3	12	and the Law has nothing to do with faith, but declares, The man that has done these things shall live therein.
B048C003V013	48	3	13	Christ has redeemed us from the curse of the Law by becoming a curse for us (for it is written, Cursed is every one who is hanged upon a tree),
B048C003V014	48	3	14	to the end that in Christ Jesus the blessing of Abraham might come upon the Gentiles, so that through faith we might receive the promised Spirit.
B048C003V015	48	3	15	Let me illustrate, brothers, from every-day life. When once a human testament is made, and formally ratified, no one sets it aside or adds to it.
B048C003V016	48	3	16	Now it was to Abraham that the promises were spoken, and to his offspring. God did not say, "offsprings" as if speaking of many, but "and to your offspring," as of one; and this is Christ.
B048C003V017	48	3	17	I mean to say that the testament which God has already ratified could not be annulled by the Law which came four hundred and thirty years later, so as to make the Promise void.
B048C003V018	48	3	18	For if the inheritance comes from law, it no longer comes from a promise; but God did give it as a free gift to Abraham by a promise.
B048C003V019	48	3	19	To what purpose, then, was the Law? It was imposed later for the sake of transgressions, until the "Offspring" should come to whom the promise had been made. It was arranged through angels by the hand of a mediator.
B048C003V020	48	3	20	(Now a mediator implies more than one person, but God is only one.)
B048C003V021	48	3	21	Is the Law then opposed to the promises of God? Certainly not; for if a law had been given which could make alive, then righteousness would actually have come from law;
B048C003V022	48	3	22	but the Scripture has shut up the whole world in prison together under sin, in order that the promise due to faith in Jesus Christ might be given to those who have faith.
B048C003V023	48	3	23	Before the Faith came we were perpetual prisoners under the Law, in preparation for the destined faith about to be revealed.
B048C003V024	48	3	24	So the Law has been our tutor-slave our pedagogue to lead us to Christ, so that we may be justified by faith;
B048C003V025	48	3	25	but now that the Faith is come, we are no longer under a tutor-slave.
B048C003V026	48	3	26	You are all sons of God through your faith in Jesus Christ.
B048C003V027	48	3	27	For all of you who were baptized into Christ, have clothed yourselves with Christ.
B048C003V028	48	3	28	In him there is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither slave nor free, there is no male and female; for you are all one in Christ Jesus.
B048C003V029	48	3	29	And if you belong to Christ, then you are the descendants of Abraham, heirs according to the promise.
B048C004V001	48	4	1	What I mean is this. As long as the heir is a child, he differs in no respect from a slave, though he be the owner of the whole inheritance;
B048C004V002	48	4	2	but is under the control of guardians and trustees, until the time appointed by his father.
B048C004V003	48	4	3	So we Jews also, when we were children, were held in bondage under the empty externalities of the world.
B048C004V004	48	4	4	But when the fulness of time was come God sent forth his Son, born of a woman, born under law,
B048C004V005	48	4	5	to redeem from captivity those under law, in order that we might receive our sonship.
B048C004V006	48	4	6	And because you are sons, God sent forth the spirit of his Son into your hearts, crying, "Dear, dear Father!"
B048C004V007	48	4	7	So each one of you is no longer a slave, but a son, and if a son,  then an heir, too, through Gods grace.
B048C004V008	48	4	8	But once, when you Gentiles had no knowledge of God, you were slaves to gods which have no real being.
B048C004V009	48	4	9	Now, however, when you have come to know God, or rather to be known by God, how is it that you are beginning to turn back to those weak and beggarly externalities, eager to be in bondage to them again?
B048C004V010	48	4	10	You are scrupulous, are you, in observing "days" and "months" and "seasons" and "years"?
B048C004V011	48	4	11	I am alarmed about you for fear lest I may have bestowed labor on you to no purpose.
B048C004V012	48	4	12	Brothers, I beseech you, become as I am, because I also have become as you are. You never did me any wrong;
B048C004V013	48	4	13	on the contrary, you know that although it was illness which brought about my preaching the gospel to you at my first visit,
B048C004V014	48	4	14	and although my bodily affliction was a trial to you, you did not scoff at it nor spurn me, but welcomed me like an angel of God, like Christ Jesus himself.
B048C004V015	48	4	15	Why then did you account yourselves so happy? (For I bear you witness that if you could you would have torn out your own eyes and given them to me.)
B048C004V016	48	4	16	Am I then become your enemy, because I am telling you the truth?
B048C004V017	48	4	17	These men are courting your favor to no good purpose. They want to isolate you, so that you will be courting their favor.
B048C004V018	48	4	18	It is always an honorable thing to have your favor sought in an honorable cause, always, and not only when I am with you.
B048C004V019	48	4	19	O my little children, of whom I travail again in birth until Christ be formed within you!
B048C004V020	48	4	20	How I wish I could be with you now, that I might change my tone; for I am perplexed about you.
B048C004V021	48	4	21	Tell me, you who wish to be subject to the Law, why do you not listen to the Law?
B048C004V022	48	4	22	For it is written that Abraham had two sons, one by the slave woman and one by the free woman;
B048C004V023	48	4	23	but while the son by the slave woman was born according to the flesh, the son by the free woman was born in fulfilment of a promise.
B048C004V024	48	4	24	Now all this is an allegory, for these women are the two covenants;  one from Mount Sinai, which is Hagar bearing children into bondage
B048C004V025	48	4	25	(for the word Hagar stands for Mt. Sinai in Arabia and represents the present Jerusalem who with her children is in bondage.)
B048C004V026	48	4	26	But the Jerusalem that is above is free, and she is our mother.
B048C004V027	48	4	27	For it is written, Rejoice, O thou barren one who dost never bear,  Break forth in joy, thou that dost not travail; For the children of the desolate woman are many. Yea, more than hers who has a husband.
B048C004V028	48	4	28	But you, brothers, are like Isaac, children of the promise;
B048C004V029	48	4	29	but just as in old times the son born by the flesh used to persecute the son born by the power of the Spirit, so also it is now.
B048C004V030	48	4	30	But what does the Scripture say? Send away the slave-woman and her son; for the slaves son shall not be heir along with the son of the free woman.
B048C004V031	48	4	31	So, brothers, we are the children of no slave woman, but of free woman. For freedom did not Christ set us free;
B048C005V001	48	5	1	stand firm then, and do not be again entangled in a yoke of bondage.
B048C005V002	48	5	2	Listen to me! I, Paul, declare to you that if you are to continue to follow the rite of circumcision, Christ will be no profit to you.
B048C005V003	48	5	3	I solemnly testify to every man who submits to circumcision that he obligates himself to keep the whole Law.
B048C005V004	48	5	4	If you are being justified by law, you are cut off from Christ; you are fallen away from grace.
B048C005V005	48	5	5	But we are not, for we through the Spirit are eagerly waiting by faith for a hope of righteousness (a hope well founded);
B048C005V006	48	5	6	because in Christ neither circumcision has any value, nor uncircumcision, but faith which works through love.
B048C005V007	48	5	7	You were running your race nobly. Who hindered you from obeying the truth?
B048C005V008	48	5	8	The influence brought to bear does not come from him who is calling you.
B048C005V009	48	5	9	A little leaven is leavening the whole lump.
B048C005V010	48	5	10	As for me, I am fully trusting you in the Lord that you will be no otherwise minded; but he who is trying to unsettle you will have to bear his punishment, whoever he may be.
B048C005V011	48	5	11	But I, brothers, if I "still preach circumcision," why am I still persecuted? Then surely the stumbling-block of the Cross has ceased to be an obstacle!
B048C005V012	48	5	12	Would to God that those who are trying to unsettle you would even have themselves mutilated.
B048C005V013	48	5	13	For you, brothers, were called for freedom; only do not make your freedom an excuse for self-indulgence, but in love enslave yourselves to one another.
B048C005V014	48	5	14	For the whole Law has been fulfilled in this one precept, Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.
B048C005V015	48	5	15	But if you are always biting and devouring one another, take heed lest you be utterly consumed one by another.
B048C005V016	48	5	16	This is my meaning. Let your steps be guided by the Spirit, and you will not gratify the desires of the flesh.
B048C005V017	48	5	17	For the desire of the flesh is against that of the Spirit, and the desire of the Spirit is against that of the flesh, for they two are antagonistic, so that you may not do those things that you wish.
B048C005V018	48	5	18	But if you are habitually led by the Spirit you are not under law.
B048C005V019	48	5	19	Now the works of the flesh are manifest; such, for instance, as fornication, impurity, indecency,
B048C005V020	48	5	20	idol-worship, sorcery, quarrels, party-spirit, jealousy, passionate anger, intrigues, factions, sectarianism,
B048C005V021	48	5	21	envy, drunkenness, revelings, and things like these. I tell you beforehand, as I have already told you, that those who practise such sins shall not inherit the kingdom of God.
B048C005V022	48	5	22	But the harvest-fruit of the Spirit is love, joy, peace, long-  suffering, kindness, goodness, fidelity, gentleness, and self-control;
B048C005V023	48	5	23	against such there is no law.
B048C005V024	48	5	24	And those who belong to Christ have crucified the flesh with its passions and appetites.
B048C005V025	48	5	25	If we are living by the Spirit, let us also keep step in the Spirit.
B048C005V026	48	5	26	Let us not become conceited, provoking one another, envying one another.
B048C006V001	48	6	1	Even if any one should be overtaken in a fault, brothers, you that are spiritual ought, in a gentle spirit, to restore such a one, each one of you looking to himself, lest you too be tempted.
B048C006V002	48	6	2	Ever be bearing one anothers burdens, and so be fulfilling the law of Christ.
B048C006V003	48	6	3	If a man fancies himself to be somebody when he is really nobody he is deceiving himself.
B048C006V004	48	6	4	Let each one test his own work, and he will then have something to be proud of by comparing himself with himself, and not with any one else;
B048C006V005	48	6	5	for every one must carry his own pack load.
B048C006V006	48	6	6	He, however, who is being taught in the message, should always share with his instructor in all the good things which he possesses.
B048C006V007	48	6	7	Be not deceived. God is not mocked. Whatever a man sows, that will he also reap.
B048C006V008	48	6	8	The man who is sowing to his flesh will of the flesh reap corruption; but he who is sowing to the Spirit will of the Spirit reap life eternal.
B048C006V009	48	6	9	And let us not be weary in well-doing, for in due season we shall reap if we faint not.
B048C006V010	48	6	10	So then, as we have opportunity, let is do good to all men, but especially to those who are of the household of faith.
B048C006V011	48	6	11	See with what large letters I have written to you in my own handwriting!
B048C006V012	48	6	12	Those who are trying to compel you to be circumcised are such as wish to make a fair show in the flesh, only that they may not suffer persecution for the cross of Christ.
B048C006V013	48	6	13	Even those who are being circumcised, are not themselves keeping the Law, but they want you to be circumcised so that they may glory in your flesh.
B048C006V014	48	6	14	God forbid that I should glory in anything except in the cross of our Lord Jesus Christ, upon which the world has been crucified to me and I have been crucified to the world.
B048C006V015	48	6	15	For in Jesus Christ neither is circumcision anything, nor uncircumcision, but a new creation.
B048C006V016	48	6	16	On all who will govern their lives by this rule and on the Israel of God may peace and mercy rest.
B048C006V017	48	6	17	From this time forth let no one trouble me, for I bear branded in my body the marks of Jesus, my Master.
B048C006V018	48	6	18	May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit,  brothers. Amen.
B049C001V001	49	1	1	Paul, an apostle of Jesus Christ by the will of God, to the saints who are in Ephesus and to the faithful in Christ Jesus,
B049C001V002	49	1	2	grace to you and peace from God our father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B049C001V003	49	1	3	Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, who has blessed us in every spiritual blessing in the heavenly realms in Christ.
B049C001V004	49	1	4	Even as he chose us in him before the foundation of the world to be holy and without blemish in his sight.
B049C001V005	49	1	5	For in his love he predestined us (such was the good pleasure of his will) to adoption for himself as sons through Jesus Christ,
B049C001V006	49	1	6	and to the praise of his glorious grace which he graciously bestowed upon us in the Beloved.
B049C001V007	49	1	7	It is in him we have deliverance, the forgiveness of our trespasses,  through his blood;
B049C001V008	49	1	8	so abundantly did he lavish upon us the riches of his grace in all wisdom and understanding,
B049C001V009	49	1	9	when he made known to us, I say, that good pleasure which he purposed in himself
B049C001V010	49	1	10	for the government of the fulness of the ages, that all things in heaven and earth are alike should be gathered up in Christ, as Head.
B049C001V011	49	1	11	It is he in whom we Jews also have our inheritance, having been chosen beforehand according to the purpose of Him who executes all things according to the counsel of his will,
B049C001V012	49	1	12	that we who first hoped in Christ should be for the praise of his glory.
B049C001V013	49	1	13	And in him, because you listened to the proclamation of the truth,  the evangel of your salvation, and trusted it, you Gentiles too were sealed with the promised Holy Spirit,
B049C001V014	49	1	14	who for the praise of his glory is the pledge of our common heritage, unto the complete redemption of his purchased property.
B049C001V015	49	1	15	For this reason I also, from the time when I heard of the faith in the Lord Jesus which prevails among you, and your love to all the saints,
B049C001V016	49	1	16	do not cease to praise God for you, whenever I mention you in my prayers.
B049C001V017	49	1	17	I am praying that the God of our Lord Jesus Christ, the Father most glorious, may grant you a spirit of wisdom and revelation, through an intimate knowledge of himself;
B049C001V018	49	1	18	and that the eyes of your heart may be flooded with light so that you may understand what is the hope of his calling, what the wealth of the glory of his inheritance in the saints,
B049C001V019	49	1	19	and what the surpassing greatness of his might in us who believe, as seen in the energy of that resistless might
B049C001V020	49	1	20	which he exercised in raising Christ from the dead, and in seating him at his right hand in the heavenly heights,
B049C001V021	49	1	21	far above all hierarchies and authorities and powers and dominions and every name that is named, not only in this age but in that which is to come.
B049C001V022	49	1	22	God has put all things under Christs feet, and placed him as Head over all in the church,
B049C001V023	49	1	23	which is his body, the fulness of Him who fills the universe.
B049C002V001	49	2	1	And so God has given life to you Gentiles also, who were once dead in your trespasses and sins,
B049C002V002	49	2	2	in which you passed your lives after the way of this world, under the sway of the Prince of the Powers of the Air, the spirit who is now working among the sons of disobedience.
B049C002V003	49	2	3	And among them we all once passed our lives, indulging the passions of our flesh, carrying out the dictates of our senses and temperament, and were by nature the children of wrath like all the rest.
B049C002V004	49	2	4	But God, who is rich in mercy, because of the great love with which he loved us,
B049C002V005	49	2	5	even while we were dead in our trespasses, made us live together with Christ (it is by grace you have been saved).
B049C002V006	49	2	6	together with him He raised us from the dead, and together with Christ Jesus seated us in the heavenly realm,
B049C002V007	49	2	7	in order that he might show to the ages to come the amazing riches of his grace by his goodness to us in Christ Jesus.
B049C002V008	49	2	8	For by grace you have been saved through faith, and that not of yourselves; it is Gods gift.
B049C002V009	49	2	9	It is not of works, so that any one can boast of it;
B049C002V010	49	2	10	for we are his handiwork, created in Christ Jesus for good deeds,  which God predestined us to make our daily way of life.
B049C002V011	49	2	11	Do not forget then, that you Gentiles in the flesh, who are called "uncircumcision" by the "circumcision" made in flesh by mans hand,
B049C002V012	49	2	12	were once upon a time without Christ, aliens from the commonwealth of Israel, strangers to the covenants of the Promise, without hope and without God in the world.
B049C002V013	49	2	13	But now in Christ Jesus you who once were far away have been brought near in the blood of Christ.
B049C002V014	49	2	14	For he is our Peace, who has made the two of us Jew and Gentile one,  and has broken down the party-wall of partition between us.
B049C002V015	49	2	15	In his own body he abolished the cause of our enmity, the law of commandments contained in ordinances, in order to make the two into one new man in himself, so making peace.
B049C002V016	49	2	16	Thus he reconciled us both in one body to God by his cross, on which he slew our enmity.
B049C002V017	49	2	17	So he came preaching "Peace" to you Gentiles who were afar off, and "Peace" to us Jews who were near;
B049C002V018	49	2	18	because it is through him that we both have access in one spirit to the Father.
B049C002V019	49	2	19	Take notice then that no longer are you strangers and foreigners,  but you are fellow citizens with the saints and members of Gods household.
B049C002V020	49	2	20	You are built upon the foundation of the apostles and prophets,  Jesus Christ himself being the chief corner-stone.
B049C002V021	49	2	21	In him the whole building, fitly framed together, rises into a holy temple in the Lord;
B049C002V022	49	2	22	and in him you, too, are continuously built together for a dwelling-  place of God through his Spirit.
B049C003V001	49	3	1	For this reason I, Paul, the prisoner of Christ Jesus on behalf of you Gentiles -
B049C003V002	49	3	2	for surely you have heard of the stewardship of the grace of God entrusted to me for you?
B049C003V003	49	3	3	You have heard how by direct revelation the secret truth was made known to me, as I have already briefly written you.
B049C003V004	49	3	4	By reading what I have written, you can judge of my insight into that secret truth of Christ
B049C003V005	49	3	5	which was not disclosed to the sons of men in former generations, as it has now been revealed by the Spirit to his holy apostles and prophets,
B049C003V006	49	3	6	namely, that in Christ Jesus the Gentiles form one body with us the Jews, and are coheirs and copartners in the promise, through the gospel.
B049C003V007	49	3	7	It is of this gospel I became a minister according to the gift of the power of the grace of God, bestowed on me by the energy of his power.
B049C003V008	49	3	8	To me, who am less than the least of all saints, has this grace been given, that I should proclaim among the Gentiles the gospel of the unsearchable riches of Christ;
B049C003V009	49	3	9	and should make all men see the new dispensation of that secret purpose, hidden from eternity in the God who founded the universe,
B049C003V010	49	3	10	in order that now his manifold wisdom should, through the church, be made known to the principalities and powers in the heavenly sphere,
B049C003V011	49	3	11	according to his eternal purpose which he purposed in Christ Jesus our Lord.
B049C003V012	49	3	12	In him we have this fearless confidence and boldness of access through our faith in him.
B049C003V013	49	3	13	So I beg you not to lose heart over my tribulations in your behalf;  they are your glory.
B049C003V014	49	3	14	For this cause I bend my knees before the Father,
B049C003V015	49	3	15	from whom every fatherhood in heaven and earth is named,
B049C003V016	49	3	16	praying him to grant you according to the riches of his glory to be strengthened with might by his Spirit in your inmost being;
B049C003V017	49	3	17	that Christ may make his home in your hearts through your faith;  that you may be so deeply rooted and so firmly grounded in love,
B049C003V018	49	3	18	that you may be able to comprehend with all the saints what is "the breadth," "the length," "the depth," and "the height,"
B049C003V019	49	3	19	and may know the love of Christ which transcends all knowing, so that you may be filled with all the "plenitude" of God.
B049C003V020	49	3	20	Now unto him who, according to his might that is at work within us,  is able to do infinitely more than all we ask or even think,
B049C003V021	49	3	21	to him be the glory in the church and in Christ Jesus, to all generations, world without end, Amen.
B049C004V001	49	4	1	I summon you then, I the prisoner in the Lord, to live lives worthy of the calling to which you were called.
B049C004V002	49	4	2	With all humility and gentleness and long-suffering forbear with one another in love;
B049C004V003	49	4	3	and endeavor to preserve the unity of the Spirit in the bonds of peace.
B049C004V004	49	4	4	There is one body and one spirit, even as also you were called in one hope of your calling.
B049C004V005	49	4	5	There is one Lord, one faith, one baptism,
B049C004V006	49	4	6	one God and Father of all, who is over all, and through all, and in all.
B049C004V007	49	4	7	And to each one of us was grace given according to the measure of the munificence of Christ.
B049C004V008	49	4	8	Thus it is said, When he ascended on high, he led captivity captive and gave gifts to men.
B049C004V009	49	4	9	Now surely this "he ascended" implies that he also descended into the lower part of the earth.
B049C004V010	49	4	10	He who descended is he who ascended above the highest heaven, that he might fill the universe.
B049C004V011	49	4	11	It is he who made some men apostles, some prophets, some evangelists, and some pastors and teachers,
B049C004V012	49	4	12	in order to equip the saints for the work of serving, for the building up of the Body of Christ -
B049C004V013	49	4	13	till we all come in the unity of the faith and of the knowledge of the Son of God, to the maturity of manhood, to the measure of the stature of the fulness of Christ.
B049C004V014	49	4	14	So we shall no longer be children, tossed up and down, and blown about by every wind of teaching, tricked by the craft of men in the snares of misleading error;
B049C004V015	49	4	15	but holding the truth in love we shall grow up in every part into him who is our Head, even Christ.
B049C004V016	49	4	16	From him the whole body (knit together and compacted by all its joints) makes continual growth of the body so as to build itself up in love, through the energy of his bounteous provision, according to the need of each several part.
B049C004V017	49	4	17	This then I tell you and implore you in the Masters name, to pass your lives no longer as the Gentiles do in the perverseness of their minds;
B049C004V018	49	4	18	having their understanding darkened, alienated from the life of God through the ignorance that is in them, because of the hardening of their hearts.
B049C004V019	49	4	19	These being past feeling have given themselves over to sensuality,  in order to practise every form of impurity with greedy zest.
B049C004V020	49	4	20	But you have not so learned Christ,
B049C004V021	49	4	21	if indeed you have listened to him, and in him been taught the truth as it is in Jesus.
B049C004V022	49	4	22	You have learned to lay aside, with your former manner of living,  the old self who was on his way to ruin, as he followed the desires which deceive;
B049C004V023	49	4	23	and to be made new in the spirit of your mind,
B049C004V024	49	4	24	and to put on the new self, created after Gods likeness, in the uprightness and holiness of the truth.
B049C004V025	49	4	25	So then put away falseness and speak every man the truth to his neighbor, for we are members one of another.
B049C004V026	49	4	26	"Be angry and sin not"; let not the sun go down upon your anger.
B049C004V027	49	4	27	Give the devil no place.
B049C004V028	49	4	28	Let him who stole steal no more, but let him work, and in honest industry toil with his hands, so that he may have something to give to the needy.
B049C004V029	49	4	29	From your lips let no evil words come forth, but such as occasion warrants, such as are good for upbuilding and give a blessing to the hearers.
B049C004V030	49	4	30	And grieve not the Holy Spirit of God, in whom you have been sealed for the day of redemption.
B049C004V031	49	4	31	Banish from among you all bitterness and passion and anger and clamor and slander, as well as all malice;
B049C004V032	49	4	32	and be kind to one another, tender-hearted, forgiving one another,  even as God in Christ has forgiven you.
B049C005V001	49	5	1	Learn then to imitate God as his beloved children,
B049C005V002	49	5	2	and to lead lives of love, just as Christ also loved you and gave himself up for you, an offering and sacrifice unto God, for you, an offering and sacrifice unto God, for "an odor of sweetness."
B049C005V003	49	5	3	As for sexual vice and every kind of impurity or lust, it is unbecoming for you as Christians even to mention them;
B049C005V004	49	5	4	so too with vulgarity and buffoonery and foolish jesting. Such words become you not, but rather thanksgiving.
B049C005V005	49	5	5	For be well assured that no one guilty of fornication or impurity or covetousness which is idolatry, has any heritage in the kingdom of Christ and of God.
B049C005V006	49	5	6	Let no man deceive you with empty arguments, for it is these vices that bring down the wrath of God upon the sons of disobedience;
B049C005V007	49	5	7	therefore do not become sharers with them.
B049C005V008	49	5	8	For you were once darkness, but are now in the Lord.
B049C005V009	49	5	9	Lead the life of children of light, for the fruit of the light consists in every kind of goodness and uprightness and truth.
B049C005V010	49	5	10	Examine carefully what is well pleasing to the Lord,
B049C005V011	49	5	11	and have no fellowship with the unfruitful works of the darkness,  but rather expose them.
B049C005V012	49	5	12	For it is a shame even to speak of the things that are done by such men in secret;
B049C005V013	49	5	13	but all these things, when exposed, are by the light made manifest,  and what is made manifest is light.
B049C005V014	49	5	14	For this reason it is said, "Awake, thou sleeper! Arise from the dead; And Christ shall shine upon thee!"
B049C005V015	49	5	15	See to it, then, that you carry on your life carefully; not as foolish, but as wise men.
B049C005V016	49	5	16	Buy up opportunity, for the times are evil.
B049C005V017	49	5	17	For this reason do not be thoughtless, but learn to know what the Lords will is.
B049C005V018	49	5	18	Do not be drunk with wine, in which is riotous living, but drink deep in the Spirit,
B049C005V019	49	5	19	when you talk together; with psalms and hymns and spiritual songs,  singing and with all your hearts making music unto the Lord;
B049C005V020	49	5	20	and at all times for all things give thanks to God, the Father, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B049C005V021	49	5	21	Submit yourselves one to another out of reverence for Christ.
B049C005V022	49	5	22	Wives likewise to their husbands as to the Lord,
B049C005V023	49	5	23	because a husband is the head of his wife even as Christ is head of the church, his body, which he saves.
B049C005V024	49	5	24	But as the church submits itself to Christ, so also wives to their husbands in everything.
B049C005V025	49	5	25	Husbands, love your wives, just as Christ loved the church and gave himself for her,
B049C005V026	49	5	26	in order that after cleansing her in the bath of baptism, he might sanctify her by his word,
B049C005V027	49	5	27	so as to present her to himself, the church glorified, without spot or wrinkle or any such blemish; but on the contrary holy and faultless.
B049C005V028	49	5	28	That is how husbands ought to love their wives, as they love their own bodies. He who loves his wife loves himself.
B049C005V029	49	5	29	For no man ever yet hated his own flesh, but nourishes and cherishes it as Christ does the church;
B049C005V030	49	5	30	for we are members of his body.
B049C005V031	49	5	31	For this cause shall a man leave his father and his mother, and shall cleave unto his wife, and they two shall be one flesh.
B049C005V032	49	5	32	There is a deep mystery here - I am speaking of Christ and his church.
B049C005V033	49	5	33	But as for you individually, you must each one of you love his own wife exactly as if she were yourself; and the wife, on her part,  should reverence her husband.
B049C006V001	49	6	1	Children, obey your parents in the Lord; for this is right.
B049C006V002	49	6	2	Honor your father and mother (this is the first commandment with a promise attached),
B049C006V003	49	6	3	that it may be well with you, and that you may live long on the earth.
B049C006V004	49	6	4	And you fathers, do not irritate your children, but bring them up in the nature and admonition of the Lord.
B049C006V005	49	6	5	Slaves, be obedient to those who are your earthly masters, with reverence and humility, in singleness of heart as if to Christ himself;
B049C006V006	49	6	6	not with eye service, as men-pleasers, but as the slaves of Christ,  doing the will of God;
B049C006V007	49	6	7	slaving with good-will from your heart, as for the Lord and not for men;
B049C006V008	49	6	8	because you know that whatever good any man does, the same shall he receive from the Lord, whether he be slave or free man.
B049C006V009	49	6	9	And you masters, show the same spirit to your slaves, and stop threatening them; for you know that your masters and theirs is in heaven, and that there is no respect of persons with him.
B049C006V010	49	6	10	Finally, my brothers, let your hearts be strengthened in the Lord,  and in the power of his might.
B049C006V011	49	6	11	Put on all the panoply of God, so that you may be able to stand your ground against the stratagems of the devil.
B049C006V012	49	6	12	For our wrestling is not against flesh and blood, but against the despotisms, the empires, the rulers of this present darkness, the spirit-hosts of evil in the heavenly realm.
B049C006V013	49	6	13	Therefore take up the panoply of God, so that when the evil day comes you may be able to withstand them, and having overthrown them all, to stand your ground.
B049C006V014	49	6	14	Stand firm then, girt about with the belt of truth, and wearing the breastplate of righteousness,
B049C006V015	49	6	15	and having your feet shod with the stability of the gospel of peace.
B049C006V016	49	6	16	And take up to cover you the shield of faith, with which you will be able to quench all the flaming darts of the Evil One.
B049C006V017	49	6	17	Take likewise the helmet of salvation, and the sword of the Spirit,  which is the word of God.
B049C006V018	49	6	18	Continue to pray at all times, with all prayer and supplication in the Spirit, and watching for it with all perseverance and supplication for all saints;
B049C006V019	49	6	19	and for me, that utterance may be given me to open my mouth boldly,  and to make known the mystery of the gospel for which I am an ambassador,
B049C006V020	49	6	20	and in chains. Pray that I may proclaim it boldly as I ought to speak.
B049C006V021	49	6	21	But that you also may know my affairs and how I do, Tychicus, my beloved brother and faithful minister in the Lord, will make everything known to you.
B049C006V022	49	6	22	I have sent him to you for this very purpose, that you may know about us, and that he may cheer your hearts.
B049C006V023	49	6	23	Peace to the brothers and love, with faith from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B049C006V024	49	6	24	May grace be with all who love our Lord Jesus Christ with sincerity.
B050C001V001	50	1	1	Paul and Timothy, slaves of Christ Jesus, to all the saints in Christ Jesus who are in Philippi, and to the elders and deacons.
B050C001V002	50	1	2	Grace and peace to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B050C001V003	50	1	3	Upon every remembrance of you I am ever thanking my God for you all;
B050C001V004	50	1	4	in every petition of mine in your behalf I am offering my prayer with joy for your fellowship in forwarding the gospel,
B050C001V005	50	1	5	from the first day you heard it until now.
B050C001V006	50	1	6	Of this I am fully persuaded, that He who has begun a good work in you will go on completing it until the day of Jesus Christ.
B050C001V007	50	1	7	It is but just that I should be thus mindful of you all, because I have you in my heart, and because in these fetters of mine and in my defense and confirmation of the gospel you are all my fellow partners in the privilege.
B050C001V008	50	1	8	God is my witness how I yearn for you all in the tenderness of Christ Jesus.
B050C001V009	50	1	9	And it is my prayer that your love may abound yet more and more in intelligence and insight
B050C001V010	50	1	10	for testing things that differ, so that you may be pure and blameless until the day of Christ,
B050C001V011	50	1	11	being filled with the fruit of righteousness through Jesus Christ to the glory and praise of God.
B050C001V012	50	1	12	I want you to know, brothers, that what has happened to me has turned out rather to help than to the hindrance of the gospel.
B050C001V013	50	1	13	Throughout the whole Praetorian guard and among all the others it has become plain that these chains of mine are for the sake of Christ;
B050C001V014	50	1	14	and most of the brothers in the Lord, made confident in the Lord through my imprisonment, are much emboldened to speak Gods message with free and fearless confidence.
B050C001V015	50	1	15	Some indeed are preaching Christ out of envy and contentiousness,  but others from good-will.
B050C001V016	50	1	16	but the former preach Christ out of rivalry, not sincerely, because they think they are adding bitterness to my bonds.
B050C001V017	50	1	17	These latter out of their love, because they know that I am set here for the defense of the gospel;
B050C001V018	50	1	18	What of it? In any case, whether in pretence or in honest truth,  Christ is still preached, and in that I am rejoicing, yes, and will rejoice.
B050C001V019	50	1	19	For I know that these things will turn out to my salvation through your prayers and a rich supply of the Spirit of Jesus Christ.
B050C001V020	50	1	20	So it is my keen expectation and hope that I shall never feel ashamed, but that with fearless courage, now as hither to, Christ may be magnified in my body, whether by my life or by my death.
B050C001V021	50	1	21	For, with me, to live is Christ and to die is gain.
B050C001V022	50	1	22	But now, if life in the flesh, if this be the fruit of my toil - what to choose I do not know,
B050C001V023	50	1	23	but am in a quandary between the two. I am perplexed. I have a strong desire to break camp and to be with Christ, which is far better;
B050C001V024	50	1	24	but for your sakes it is more necessary that I should still live on in the body.
B050C001V025	50	1	25	And because I am convinced of this, I know that I shall live, and go on working side by side with you all for your progress and joy in the faith,
B050C001V026	50	1	26	so that you may find me fresh cause of exultation in Christ Jesus,  because of my presence among you once more.
B050C001V027	50	1	27	Only do lead lives worthy of the gospel of Christ; so that whether I come to see you or hear reports concerning you in my absence, I may know that you are standing firm in one spirit, with one soul,  enlisted in a common struggle for the faith of the gospel,
B050C001V028	50	1	28	and in no way terrorized by its enemies. For you fearlessness is a clear indication of coming ruin for them, but of salvation for you at the hands of God.
B050C001V029	50	1	29	For it has been granted you in Christs behalf, not only to believe on him, but also to suffer for his sake,
B050C001V030	50	1	30	while you wage the same conflict which you once saw in me, and now hear that I maintain.
B050C002V001	50	2	1	If then there is any comfort in Christ, if there is any persuasive power in love, if there is any companionship of the Spirit, if there is any tenderness or pity,
B050C002V002	50	2	2	I entreat you to make my joy overflow by living in harmony;  possessing the same love, and with one soul united in one purpose.
B050C002V003	50	2	3	Do nothing out of strife, nothing out of vanity, but let each one in true humility consider the others to be of more account than himself.
B050C002V004	50	2	4	Let each have an eye not only for his own interests, but also for the interests of others.
B050C002V005	50	2	5	Let this mind be in you which was also in Christ Jesus,
B050C002V006	50	2	6	who, though from the beginning he had the nature of God, did not reckon equality with God something to be forcibly retained,
B050C002V007	50	2	7	but emptied himself of his glory by taking the form of a slave, when he was born in the likeness of men.
B050C002V008	50	2	8	More than this, after he had shone himself in human form, he humbled himself in his obedience even to death; yes, and to death on a cross.
B050C002V009	50	2	9	And for this God highly exalted him, and graciously bestowed upon him the name which is above every name;
B050C002V010	50	2	10	that in the name of Jesus every knee in heaven, on earth, and under the earth should bend,
B050C002V011	50	2	11	and every tongue confess that "Jesus Christ is Lord," to the glory of God the Father.
B050C002V012	50	2	12	And so, my beloved, as you have always obeyed, not only in my presence, but now much more in my absence, with reverence and self-  distrust work out your own salvation;
B050C002V013	50	2	13	for it is God who, in his good-will is ever working in you both will and deed.
B050C002V014	50	2	14	Do everything without grumbling and disputes,
B050C002V015	50	2	15	that you may become blameless and innocent, the sons of God, without rebuke in the midst of a crooked and perverse generation, among whom you shine like stars in a dark world,
B050C002V016	50	2	16	holding out a message of life. Thus it will be my boast at the day of Christ that I have not run in vain, or toiled for nothing.
B050C002V017	50	2	17	Nay, even if my life is to be poured out as a libation upon the sacrifice and service of you faith,
B050C002V018	50	2	18	I will rejoice and congratulate you all; and in the same way you must rejoice and congratulate me.
B050C002V019	50	2	19	Now I hope in the Lord Jesus to send Timothy to you before long, so that I may be of good comfort when I learn the news concerning you.
B050C002V020	50	2	20	For I have no other like him with a genuine concern for your welfare,
B050C002V021	50	2	21	for they are all seeking their own interests, not those of Jesus Christ.
B050C002V022	50	2	22	And you know Timothys worth, how he has shared my servitude in furtherance of the gospel, like a son helping his father.
B050C002V023	50	2	23	So I hope to send him, as soon as ever I see how it will go with me;
B050C002V024	50	2	24	but I trust in the Lord that I also shall come shortly.
B050C002V025	50	2	25	Epaphroditus, my brother and coworker and fellow soldier, who is your messenger and minister to my needs, I have thought it necessary to send to you;
B050C002V026	50	2	26	for he has been homesick for you all, and distressed at your having heard of his illness.
B050C002V027	50	2	27	And indeed he was sick nigh unto death; but God had mercy on him,  and not on him only, but on me also so that I should not have sorrow upon sorrow.
B050C002V028	50	2	28	Therefore I have been the more eager to send him, in order that you may rejoice in seeing him again, and that I may have one sorrow less.
B050C002V029	50	2	29	Receive him then in the Lord with all joy, and hold in honor men like him;
B050C002V030	50	2	30	for it was through the work of the Lord that he came near to death;  for he hazarded his very life to supply what was lacking in the help you sent me.
B050C003V001	50	3	1	Finally, my brothers, continue to rejoice in the Lord. To write the same thing is not indeed wearisome to me, and it is safe for you.
B050C003V002	50	3	2	Beware of "these dogs," these mischievous workers, beware of the concision!
B050C003V003	50	3	3	For we are the true circumcision, who worship God in the spirit, and make our boast in Christ Jesus, and have no confidence in outward rites,
B050C003V004	50	3	4	although I myself might have confidence in outward rites. If any one else claims a right to trust in them, far more may I;
B050C003V005	50	3	5	circumcised the eighth day, of the stock of Israel, of the tribe of Benjamin, a Hebrew sprung from the Hebrews; as to the Law, a Pharisee;
B050C003V006	50	3	6	as to zeal, a persecutor of the church; as to the righteousness which comes through law, blameless.
B050C003V007	50	3	7	But what was once gain to me, that I have counted loss for Christ.
B050C003V008	50	3	8	In very truth I count all things but loss compared to the excellence of the knowledge of Christ Jesus my Lord. For his sake I have suffered the loss of all things, and esteem them but refuse that I may gain Christ,
B050C003V009	50	3	9	and be found in him; not having my own righteousness of the Law, but that alone which is through the faith of Christ, the righteousness which comes from God, founded upon faith.
B050C003V010	50	3	10	I long to know him in the power of his resurrection and the fellowship of his sufferings, by sharing the likeness of his death;
B050C003V011	50	3	11	if by any means I might attain to the resurrection from the dead!
B050C003V012	50	3	12	I do not say that I have already won, or am already perfect, but I am passing on to lay hold on the prize for which also Christ has laid hold of me.
B050C003V013	50	3	13	Brothers, I do not regard myself to have yet laid hold of it; but this one thing I do, forgetting what is behind me, but straining every nerve toward that which lies ahead,
B050C003V014	50	3	14	I am ever pressing on toward the goal, for the prize of Gods heavenward call in Christ Jesus.
B050C003V015	50	3	15	Let us all then, who are mature Christians, strive for this! God will make this clear to any of you who are striving for other goals;
B050C003V016	50	3	16	if only we guide our steps by the standards we have already attained.
B050C003V017	50	3	17	Brothers, be comrades in imitating me, and study those whose life and walk is according to the pattern I have set you.
B050C003V018	50	3	18	For there are many - as I used often to tell you, and am now telling you even with tears - who live and walk as the enemies of the cross of Christ.
B050C003V019	50	3	19	Their end is destruction, their belly is their god, their glory is in their shame, and their minds are set on earthly things.
B050C003V020	50	3	20	But commonwealth is in heaven; and it is from heaven also that we are anxiously awaiting a Saviour, the Lord Jesus Christ,
B050C003V021	50	3	21	who will change the fashion of the body of our abasement into the likeness of his glorious body by the energy with which he is able even to subject all things to himself.
B050C004V001	50	4	1	Stand fast then, brothers, dearly loved and longed for, my joy and my crown, so stand fast in the Lord, beloved!
B050C004V002	50	4	2	Euodia I entreat, and I entreat Syntyche, to be of the same mind of the Lord;
B050C004V003	50	4	3	yes, and I beg you also, my true yokefellow, to help them; for these women shared my toil in the furtherance of the gospel, together with Clement, and the rest of my fellow workers whose names are in the book of life.
B050C004V004	50	4	4	Rejoice in the Lord alway, and again will I say, rejoice!
B050C004V005	50	4	5	Let your reasonableness be recognized by every one. The Lord is near you.
B050C004V006	50	4	6	Do not worry about anything; but in everything by prayer and supplication, with thanksgiving, let your requests be made known to God;
B050C004V007	50	4	7	and the peace of God, which passes all understanding, will stand guard over your hearts and your thoughts in Christ Jesus.
B050C004V008	50	4	8	Finally, brothers, whatever is true, whatever is worthy of reverence, whatever is just, whatever is pure, whatever is lovely,  whatever is of good repute, if virtue is anything, if honor is anything, be always thinking about these.
B050C004V009	50	4	9	Put in practise also what you have learned and received and heard and seen in me; and the God of peace shall be with you.
B050C004V010	50	4	10	Moreover, I greatly rejoiced in the Lord that now once more your care for me blossomed afresh; though indeed you did take thought in this matter, but you lacked the opportunity of expression.
B050C004V011	50	4	11	Not that I speak as if I were in want, for at least have learned how to be content, whatever happens.
B050C004V012	50	4	12	I know how to live humbly, and I also know how to bear prosperity.  In every place and under all circumstances I have been initiated into the secret of fulness and of hunger, of prosperity and of want.
B050C004V013	50	4	13	I am strong for everything in Him who gives me strength.
B050C004V014	50	4	14	Notwithstanding, you have acted nobly in making yourselves comrades in my trouble.
B050C004V015	50	4	15	And you very well know, Philippians, that in the beginning of the gospel, when I had left Macedonia, no church but yourselves had fellowship with me in the matter of giving and receiving.
B050C004V016	50	4	16	For even while I was still in Thessalonica, you sent once and again for my needs.
B050C004V017	50	4	17	It is not your gifts I am eager for, but I am eager for the abundant profit that accrues to your divine account.
B050C004V018	50	4	18	But I give you a receipt in full for all things abound. I am amply supplied with what you sent by Epaphroditus - an odor of sweet fragrance, a sacrifice acceptable, well pleasing to God.
B050C004V019	50	4	19	All your own needs my God will fully supply, according to his riches in glory, in Christ Jesus.
B050C004V020	50	4	20	Now unto our God and Father be the glory, forever and ever. Amen.
B050C004V021	50	4	21	Salute every saint in Christ Jesus. The brothers who are with me salute you.
B050C004V022	50	4	22	All the saints salute you, and especially the slaves of the Emperors household.
B050C004V023	50	4	23	The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirits.
B051C001V001	51	1	1	Paul, an apostle of Jesus Christ, by the will of God, and Timothy our brother,
B051C001V002	51	1	2	to the holy and believing brothers in Christ who are in Colosse.  Grace to you, and peace, from God our Father.
B051C001V003	51	1	3	Whenever I pray for you I am continually thanking God, the Father of our Lord Jesus Christ
B051C001V004	51	1	4	(since I heard of your faith in Christ Jesus and your love to all the saints)
B051C001V005	51	1	5	because of the hope laid up for you in heaven. Long ago you heard of this hope in the message which came to you of the truth of the gospel.
B051C001V006	51	1	6	And just as it is spreading through the whole world, bearing fruit and increasing, so also is it among you, from the day in which you heard it, and came truly to know the grace of God,
B051C001V007	51	1	7	as you learned it from Epaphras, our dearly loved fellow slave. He is a faithful minister of Jesus Christ in your behalf,
B051C001V008	51	1	8	and it is he who has told me of your love for me in the spirit.
B051C001V009	51	1	9	For this reason from the day I heard of it I have never ceased to pray for you, asking God to fill you with the knowledge of his will with every kind of wisdom and spiritual insight;
B051C001V010	51	1	10	that you may walk worthy of the Lord in every kind of pleasing; that you may be fruitful in every kind of good work, and may increase in the knowledge of God;
B051C001V011	51	1	11	that you may be strengthened in every kind of strength by the might of his glory for every kind of patience and fortitude with good cheer.
B051C001V012	51	1	12	I ask that you may give thanks to the Father who has made us fit to receive our share of the heritage of the saints in the light.
B051C001V013	51	1	13	For he has delivered us out of the dominion of the darkness, and transplanted us into the kingdom of his dear Son,
B051C001V014	51	1	14	in whom we have redemption, the forgiveness of our sins.
B051C001V015	51	1	15	He is a visible image of the invisible God, the firstborn of all creation;
B051C001V016	51	1	16	for in him was the universe created, things in heaven and on earth,  the seen and the unseen, thrones, or dominions, or principalities, or powers; by him and for him all have been created;
B051C001V017	51	1	17	and HE IS before all, and in him all things subsist.
B051C001V018	51	1	18	He is the head of his Body, the Church. He is the beginning, the firstborn from the dead, in order that in all things he may become preeminent.
B051C001V019	51	1	19	For in him all the divine fulness chose to dwell;
B051C001V020	51	1	20	and by him it chose to reconcile all things alike on earth or in heaven to himself; making peace by him, through the blood of his cross.
B051C001V021	51	1	21	And you, alienated as you once were, hostile at heart in your evil deeds,
B051C001V022	51	1	22	he has now in his human body reconciled to God by his death, in order that he may bring you into his presence, holy and unblemished and irreproachable.
B051C001V023	51	1	23	And this he will do if, indeed, you continue in the faith, firmly founded and stedfast, and never moved away from the hope of the gospel which you heard, and which has been proclaimed to every creature under heaven, that gospel of which I, Paul, was made a minister.
B051C001V024	51	1	24	I am now rejoicing in my sufferings on your behalf; and I am filling up in my own body what is yet lacking of the sufferings of Christ in behalf of the church, his Body.
B051C001V025	51	1	25	It is of this I was made a minister, according to the stewardship entrusted to me by God for you, fully to declare Gods message;
B051C001V026	51	1	26	that secret truth, which, although hidden from ages and generations of old, has now been made manifest to his saints.
B051C001V027	51	1	27	To them God willed to make known among the Gentiles how glorious are the riches of that secret truth, which is "Christ in you, the hope of glory."
B051C001V028	51	1	28	Him I am ever proclaiming, warning every one and teaching every one,  in all wisdom; that I may bring every man into his presence, full grown in Christ.
B051C001V029	51	1	29	For that end I am ever toiling, wrestling with all that energy of his which is mightily at work within me.
B051C002V001	51	2	1	For I would have you know how great a contest I am waging for you and the brethren in Laodicea, and for all who have never seen my face.
B051C002V002	51	2	2	May their hearts be comforted! May they be knit together in love!  May they gain in all its riches the full assurance of their understanding! May they come to a perfect knowledge of the secret truth of God, which is Christ himself.
B051C002V003	51	2	3	In Him are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge!
B051C002V004	51	2	4	And this I say, lest any one should mislead you with enticing words.
B051C002V005	51	2	5	For though I am absent from you in body, I am with you in spirit,  happy to note your discipline and the solid front of your faith in Christ.
B051C002V006	51	2	6	As then you have received Jesus Christ, your Lord, in him live your lives;
B051C002V007	51	2	7	since you are rooted in him, and in him continually built up. Be firmly established in the faith as you were taught it, and continually abound in it with thanksgiving.
B051C002V008	51	2	8	Take care lest any man drag you away captive by his philosophy which is a vain deceit, following the traditions of men and the worlds crude notions, and not Christ.
B051C002V009	51	2	9	For it is in Christ that all the fullness of deity dwells bodily,
B051C002V010	51	2	10	and in him you have your fulness, and he is the Lord of all the principalities and powers.
B051C002V011	51	2	11	In him also you were circumcised with a circumcision not made with hands; even in putting off your sensual nature in Christs own circumcision,
B051C002V012	51	2	12	when you were buried with him in baptism. In baptism also you were raised with him, through your faith in the energy of that God who raised him from the dead.
B051C002V013	51	2	13	And you also, at one time dead in your trespasses and in the uncircumcision of your sensual nature, he has made alive together with himself. For he forgave us all our transgressions,
B051C002V014	51	2	14	blotted out the handwriting of ordinances that stood against us and was hostile to us, and took it out of our way, nailing it to his cross.
B051C002V015	51	2	15	Principalities and powers he disarmed, and openly displayed them as his trophies, when he triumphed over them in the cross.
B051C002V016	51	2	16	Therefore do not permit any one to sit in judgment on you in regard to what you may eat or drink, or in regard to feast-days or new moons or sabbaths.
B051C002V017	51	2	17	These were a shadow of things to come, but the substance belongs to Christ.
B051C002V018	51	2	18	Let no man at his will defraud you of your prize through his false humility and worship of the angels, taking his stand on the visions he has seen, and vainly puffed up by his material mind;
B051C002V019	51	2	19	instead of keeping connection with the Head from the whole body draws nourishment for all its needs by the joints which bind it; and is knit together, and grows with a divine growth.
B051C002V020	51	2	20	If you died with Christ to the worlds rudimentary notions, why, as if you still lived in the world, do you submit yourselves to dogmatisms found on teachings and doctrines of men -
B051C002V021	51	2	21	such as "Do not handle this," "You must not taste that," "Do not touch this" -
B051C002V022	51	2	22	all things which are intended to perish in the using?
B051C002V023	51	2	23	For these precepts, although they have a show of wisdom with their self-imposed devotions and fastings and bodily austerities, are of no real value against the indulgence of the carnal appetites.
B051C003V001	51	3	1	If you then are risen with Christ, seek those things which are above, where Christ abides, seated on the right hand of God.
B051C003V002	51	3	2	Set your heart on things above, not on earthly things;
B051C003V003	51	3	3	for you have died and your life is hidden with Christ in God.
B051C003V004	51	3	4	When Christ, who is our life, appears, then will you also appear with him in glory.
B051C003V005	51	3	5	So slay your baser inclinations. fornication, impurity, appetite,  unnatural desires, and the greed which is idolatry.
B051C003V006	51	3	6	These things are ever bringing down the wrath of God upon the children of disobedience,
B051C003V007	51	3	7	among whom you once led your daily life when you lived in them.
B051C003V008	51	3	8	But now you also must renounce them all. Anger, passion, and ill-  will must be put away; slander, too, and foul talk, so that they may never soil your lips.
B051C003V009	51	3	9	Lie not one to another, but strip off the old self with its doings,
B051C003V010	51	3	10	and put on that new self which is continually made over according to the likeness of its Creator, into full understanding.
B051C003V011	51	3	11	In it that new creation there is no "Greek and Jew," "circumcised and uncircumcised," "barbarian," "Scythian," "slave," "free man," but Christ is all, and in us all.
B051C003V012	51	3	12	Therefore, as Gods chosen people, consecrated and beloved, clothe yourselves with tenderness of heart, kindness, humility, gentleness,  good temper;
B051C003V013	51	3	13	bearing with one another and forgiving each other, if any one has a grievance against another. Just as Christ the Lord forgave you, so must you forgive.
B051C003V014	51	3	14	Over them all bind on love, which is the girdle of completeness.
B051C003V015	51	3	15	Let the peace of Christ, to which also you were called in one body,  rule in your hearts, and show yourselves thankful.
B051C003V016	51	3	16	Let the word of Christ have its home in you richly, in all wisdom.  Teach and admonish one another in psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, ever singing with grace in your hearts unto God.
B051C003V017	51	3	17	And whatever you do, whether in word of in deed, do all in the name of the Lord Jesus, giving thanks to God our Father through him.
B051C003V018	51	3	18	Wives, submit yourselves to your husbands, as is fitting for Christians.
B051C003V019	51	3	19	Husbands, be loving to your wives, and be not cross or surly with them.
B051C003V020	51	3	20	Children, obey your parents in everything, for this is well pleasing in Christians.
B051C003V021	51	3	21	Fathers, do not harass your children, lest you make them spiritless.
B051C003V022	51	3	22	Slaves, obey in all things your earthly masters, not with eye-  service, as men-pleasers, but in singleness of purpose, out of reverence for your Lord.
B051C003V023	51	3	23	And whatever you do, do it heartily as for the Lord, and not for men.
B051C003V024	51	3	24	You know that from the Lord you will receive reward of the inheritance, for you are the Lord Christs slaves.
B051C003V025	51	3	25	For he who wrongs another will be paid back for his wrong-doing, and there will be no favoritism.
B051C004V001	51	4	1	Masters, deal justly and fairly with your slaves, knowing that you also have a Master in heaven.
B051C004V002	51	4	2	Be unwearied in prayer, and keep awake in it when giving thanks.
B051C004V003	51	4	3	Keep on praying for me, too, that God may open for me a door of utterance to speak the secret truth of Christ, for which I am a prisoner.
B051C004V004	51	4	4	Pray that I may unfold it as I ought to speak.
B051C004V005	51	4	5	Conduct yourselves with wisdom toward those without, buying up your opportunities.
B051C004V006	51	4	6	Let your speech be always gracious, with a savor of salt, and learn how to give every man a fitting answer.
B051C004V007	51	4	7	Tychicus, my beloved brother and faithful minister and fellow slave in the Lord, will make known to you all that concerns me.
B051C004V008	51	4	8	I have sent him with Onesimus, the faithful and beloved brother, one of your own number, for this very purpose, to let you know how I am,  and to cheer your hearts.
B051C004V009	51	4	9	They will inform you of all that goes on here.
B051C004V010	51	4	10	Aristarchus, my fellow prisoner, salutes you, and Marcus, the cousin of Barnabas (about whom you received instructions; if he comes to you, make him welcome), and Jesus surnamed Justas.
B051C004V011	51	4	11	These are my only fellow workers for the kingdom of God, belonging to the circumcision, who have been any comfort to me.
B051C004V012	51	4	12	Epaphras, one of yourselves, salutes you, a slave of Christ who is always agonizing for you in his prayers, that you may stand firm,  mature, and fully assured in all the will of God.
B051C004V013	51	4	13	For I can testify to his deep interest in you and in those in Laodicea and Hierapolis.
B051C004V014	51	4	14	Luke, the beloved physician, salutes you, and so does Demas.
B051C004V015	51	4	15	Salute the brothers in Laodicea; Nympha also, and the church which meets at her house.
B051C004V016	51	4	16	And when this letter has been read to you, see that it is read also in the church of Laodiceans, and that you also read the letter from Laodicea.
B051C004V017	51	4	17	And tell Archippas to take heed to the ministry which he has received in the Lord, that he may fulfill it.
B051C004V018	51	4	18	I, Paul, add this farewell in my own handwriting. Do not forget these chains of mine. Grace be with you.
B052C001V001	52	1	1	Paul and Silas and Timothy. To the church of the Thessalonians which is in God our Father and our Lord Jesus Christ. Grace be to you, and peace.
B052C001V002	52	1	2	I am continually thanking God for all, always making mention of you in my prayers,
B052C001V003	52	1	3	as I call to mind your work of faith, and labor of love, and patience of hope in our Lord Jesus Christ, in the presence of our God and Father.
B052C001V004	52	1	4	For I know, O brothers, beloved of God, that he has chosen you;
B052C001V005	52	1	5	for my gospel did not come to you in word only, but in power also,  and in the Holy Spirit, and with deep conviction. For you know also the manner in which I behaved myself among you for your sakes.
B052C001V006	52	1	6	Moreover, you began to follow the pattern I set you, and the Lords also, receiving the word with joy in the Holy Spirit, although amid severe persecution.
B052C001V007	52	1	7	Thus you became a pattern to all the believers in Macedonia and Achaia.
B052C001V008	52	1	8	For the word of the Lord has been sounded forth from you, and its sound has been heard not only in Macedonia and Achaia, but also in every place where the tidings of your faith toward God have been spread abroad, so that I have no need to speak of it.
B052C001V009	52	1	9	For others, of their own accord, tell about the welcome I had from you, and how you turned to God from your idols, to be slaved of a true and living God,
B052C001V010	52	1	10	and to await for the coming of his Son from the heavens, the Son whom he raised from the dead, even Jesus, our Deliverer from the wrath to come.
B052C002V001	52	2	1	For you yourselves know, brothers, that my visit to you did not fail of its purpose;
B052C002V002	52	2	2	for you remember that although I had already borne ill-treatment and insult at Philippi, I took courage in my God to tell you the gospel of God, in the face of much opposition.
B052C002V003	52	2	3	For my preaching was not grounded on a delusion, or on impure motives, on in deceit.
B052C002V004	52	2	4	But as my fitness to be entrusted with the gospel has been tested and approved by God, I so speak, not to please men, but to please God, who is testing my motives.
B052C002V005	52	2	5	For as you well know, I never resorted to flattery, nor to any pretext for enriching myself. God is my witness!
B052C002V006	52	2	6	Now was I seeking glory from men, either yourselves or others,  although I might have exercised authority as Christs apostle.
B052C002V007	52	2	7	On the contrary I showed myself among you as gentle as a mother,  when she tenderly nurses her own children.
B052C002V008	52	2	8	So in my fond affection it was my joy to give you, not only the gospel of God, but my very life also, because you had become dear to me.
B052C002V009	52	2	9	You recall, brothers, my labor and toil; how, while working at my trade day and night, so as not to become a burden to any of you, I proclaimed to you the gospel of God.
B052C002V010	52	2	10	You are witnesses - and so is God - how pure and just and blameless was my behavior among you believers.
B052C002V011	52	2	11	You know how I was wont to treat each of you as a father treats his children,
B052C002V012	52	2	12	exhorting and imploring and adjuring each one among you to lead a life worthy of the God who called you into his own kingdom and glory.
B052C002V013	52	2	13	For this reason also I am giving continual thanks to God, because when you heard from me the spoken word of God, you received it not as the word of men, but as the word of God (which in truth it is), who himself is effectually at work in you believe.
B052C002V014	52	2	14	For you, brothers, began to follow the example of the churches of God in Judea, which are in Christ Jesus; and you in your turn suffered at the hands of your fellow citizens persecutions like to those which they endured from the Jews -
B052C002V015	52	2	15	The men who killed both the Lord Jesus and the prophets, and drove us out - they are displeasing to God, and are the enemies of all mankind.
B052C002V016	52	2	16	They forbid me to speak to the Gentiles with a view to their salvation. They continue always to fill up the measure of their sins;  but the wrath of God is come upon them to the full!
B052C002V017	52	2	17	But I, my brothers, although torn from you for a short season (in presence, not in heart), made eager efforts to behold you face to face with strong longing.
B052C002V018	52	2	18	For that reason I would fain have visited you - I, Paul, again and again - but Satan hindered me.
B052C002V019	52	2	19	For what is my hope, or joy? What is the victors wreath in which I exult? What but your own selves in the presence of our Lord Jesus, at his coming! For you are my pride and my delight.
B052C002V020	52	2	20	missing fehlt/missing
B052C003V001	52	3	1	And so, when I could no longer bear it, I made up my mind to be left behind at Athens, all alone.
B052C003V002	52	3	2	I sent Timothy, my brother and Gods fellow worker in the gospel of Christ, to strengthen you and to hearten you in your faith.
B052C003V003	52	3	3	So that no one should be shaken by these troubles-for you know well that we are appointed to troubles.
B052C003V004	52	3	4	For even when I was with you I used to tell you beforehand that I was to suffer affliction; and so it proved, as you know.
B052C003V005	52	3	5	So, when I could no longer endure it, I sent to find out about your faith, fearing that the tempter had tempted you and that my labor had been in vain.
B052C003V006	52	3	6	But now that Timothy has returned from you to me, and has brought good news of your faith and love, and that you are still holding me in affectionate remembrance, always longing to see me as I also am longing to see you.
B052C003V007	52	3	7	I have been comforted, my brothers, in regard to you, in spite of all my distress and affliction over your faith.
B052C003V008	52	3	8	For now I am really living, if you are standing firm in the Lord.
B052C003V009	52	3	9	For what thanksgiving can I render again to God in your behalf, in return for all the joy which you cause me in the presence of my God?
B052C003V010	52	3	10	Night and day I am praying earnestly that I may see you face to face, and may perfect whatever is yet lacking in your faith.
B052C003V011	52	3	11	Now may our God and Father himself, and our Lord Jesus Christ,  direct my path to you.
B052C003V012	52	3	12	Meanwhile, may the Lord cause you to increase and abound in love toward one another and toward all men, even as I do toward you.
B052C003V013	52	3	13	And so may he establish your hearts unblamable in holiness before our God and Father, at the coming of our Lord Jesus, with all his saints.
B052C004V001	52	4	1	Finally then, my brothers, I continue to beseech and exhort you in the Lord Jesus, that, as you learned of me how to walk so as to please God - and you are actually doing so - that you abound in it yet more and more.
B052C004V002	52	4	2	For you know what charges I laid upon you through the Lord Jesus.
B052C004V003	52	4	3	For this is Gods will, even your sanctification; that you should abstain from sexual vice.
B052C004V004	52	4	4	That each one should learn how to take a wife in purity and honor.
B052C004V005	52	4	5	Not in the passion of lust, like the Gentiles who know not God.
B052C004V006	52	4	6	That no man overreach or take advantage of his brother in such matters, because "the Lord takes vengeance" in all these things, as also I repeatedly forewarned you and testified to you.
B052C004V007	52	4	7	For God has not called us for uncleanness, but in holiness.
B052C004V008	52	4	8	So that he who rejects this is not rejecting man, but the God who gave you his Holy Spirit.
B052C004V009	52	4	9	It is not needed that I should write to you about brotherly love;  for you yourselves have been taught by God to love one another.
B052C004V010	52	4	10	As indeed you do love all the brothers in Macedonia. But I exhort you, brothers, to abound in this yet more.
B052C004V011	52	4	11	Also, that you endeavor to live quietly and to mind your own business, and to work with your hands (as I charged you).
B052C004V012	52	4	12	So that your conduct may be seemly toward those that are without,  and that you may not need help from any man.
B052C004V013	52	4	13	But I would not have you ignorant, brothers, about those who are falling asleep. You must not sorrow like other men, who have no hope.
B052C004V014	52	4	14	For if we really believe that Jesus died and rose again, so even so will God through Jesus bring with him those also who have fallen asleep.
B052C004V015	52	4	15	For this I tell you by the word of the Lord, that we who are living,  who survive unto the coming of the Lord, will in no wise precede those who have fallen asleep.
B052C004V016	52	4	16	For the Lord himself with a shout, with the voice of an archangel,  and with the trumpet of God will descend from heaven. Then the dead in Christ will rise first.
B052C004V017	52	4	17	And afterwards we who are alive, who remain, shall be caught up together with them in the clouds, to meet the Lord in the air; and so shall we ever be with the Lord.
B052C004V018	52	4	18	So comfort one another with these words.
B052C005V001	52	5	1	Now as to the times and the seasons, brothers, you have no need that anything be written to you.
B052C005V002	52	5	2	You yourselves know perfectly that the Day of the Lord will come as a thief in the night.
B052C005V003	52	5	3	While men are saying "Peace and safety," then, like birth-pangs upon a woman with child, destruction will come upon them suddenly. In no wise will they escape.
B052C005V004	52	5	4	But you, brothers, are not in darkness, that "the Day" should come upon you like a bandit.
B052C005V005	52	5	5	For you are all sons of light, and sons of day. We are not of night nor of darkness.
B052C005V006	52	5	6	So then let us not be sleeping as do the rest, but let us be watchful and self-controlled.
B052C005V007	52	5	7	For those who are sleeping, sleep in the night, and those who are drunken, are drunken in the night.
B052C005V008	52	5	8	But let us who are of the day be self-controlled, putting on the breastplate of faith and love; and for a helmet, the hope of salvation.
B052C005V009	52	5	9	For God did not appoint us to wrath, but to win salvation through our Lord Jesus Christ.
B052C005V010	52	5	10	He died for us, in order that whether we are keeping vigil in life or sleeping in death we may ever be living together with him.
B052C005V011	52	5	11	So comfort one another, and try to build one another up, as indeed you are doing.
B052C005V012	52	5	12	I entreat you, brothers, to acknowledge those who are toiling among you and are your leaders in the Lord, and give you counsel.
B052C005V013	52	5	13	Esteem them very highly in love for their works sake. Live in peace among yourselves.
B052C005V014	52	5	14	And, brothers, we urge you to admonish the disorderly, comfort the faint-hearted, sustain the weak, lose patience with none.
B052C005V015	52	5	15	Take care that none of you ever return evil for evil, but always pursue what is kind to one another and to all.
B052C005V016	52	5	16	Always be joyful.
B052C005V017	52	5	17	Pray without ceasing.
B052C005V018	52	5	18	Give thanks in every circumstance, for this is the will of God for you in Christ Jesus.
B052C005V019	52	5	19	Quench not the Spirit.
B052C005V020	52	5	20	Do not despise prophesyings.
B052C005V021	52	5	21	But try all, holding fast to the good.
B052C005V022	52	5	22	Hold aloof from every form of evil.
B052C005V023	52	5	23	May the God of peace consecrate you wholly; and may your spirit and soul and body be kept altogether faultless until the coming of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B052C005V024	52	5	24	He who calls you is faithful; he will fulfil my prayer.
B052C005V025	52	5	25	Brothers, pray for me.
B052C005V026	52	5	26	Greet all the brothers with a holy kiss.
B052C005V027	52	5	27	I adjure you, in the name of the Lord, to have this letter read to all the brothers.
B052C005V028	52	5	28	The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you.
B053C001V001	53	1	1	Paul and Silvanus and Timothy. To the church of the Thessalonians in God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C001V002	53	1	2	Grace to you, and peace from God the Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C001V003	53	1	3	I ought always to thank God for you, brothers, as is fitting because of the abundant growth of your faith and of the overflowing love with which every one of you is filled toward one another.
B053C001V004	53	1	4	So that I myself am boasting about you among the churches of God,  boasting of the stedfastness and faith which you are displaying in all the troubles and afflictions which you are enduring.
B053C001V005	53	1	5	They are an evidence of the righteous judgment of God, who will count you worthy of his kingdom, in behalf of which you are even now suffering.
B053C001V006	53	1	6	For truly Gods justice must render back trouble to those who are troubling you,
B053C001V007	53	1	7	and give to you, who are now troubled, rest, along with me at the unveiling "apocalypse" of the Lord Jesus from heaven, with his mighty angels,
B053C001V008	53	1	8	in flaming fire. Then shall he take vengeance on those who know not God, even on those who do not obey the gospel of our Lord Jesus.
B053C001V009	53	1	9	They shall suffer punishment, even an eternal destruction from the presence of the Lord, and from the brightness of his glorious majesty,
B053C001V010	53	1	10	when he comes to be glorified in his saints, and to be wondered at in all believers, on that Day; (for you also believed our testimony).
B053C001V011	53	1	11	To this end I am making my constant prayer for you, beseeching God to make you worthy of your calling, and to fulfil mightily every desire of goodness and effort of faith;
B053C001V012	53	1	12	so that the name of our Lord Jesus may be glorified in him,  according to the grace of our God and of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C002V001	53	2	1	Now concerning the coming of our Lord Jesus Christ and our gathering together to meet him, I entreat you, brothers,
B053C002V002	53	2	2	not to be "quickly shaken out of your wits" and not to be agitated either by a spirit or by a message, or by an epistle purporting to be from me, saying, "The Day of the Lord is at hand."
B053C002V003	53	2	3	Let no one deceive you by any means. For it will not come until after the Great Apostasy, and the revealing of the Man of Sin, the son of perdition,
B053C002V004	53	2	4	the adversary, who opposes and exalts himself against all that is called God, or is an object of worship; so that he takes his seat in the Temple of God, and vaunts himself as God.
B053C002V005	53	2	5	Do you not recall that I often told you this, when I was with you?
B053C002V006	53	2	6	And now you know what is holding him back, to the end that he may be revealed in his appointed time.
B053C002V007	53	2	7	For the mystery of lawlessness is already at work; only there is one who is hindering and will continue to hinder till he be removed;
B053C002V008	53	2	8	and then the lawless one will be revealed. Him the Lord will consume with the breath of his lips, and destroy with the brightness of his appearing;
B053C002V009	53	2	9	even he whose coming is according to the energy of Satan, in every power and sign and lying wonder,
B053C002V010	53	2	10	and with all deceit of unrighteousness for those who are perishing,  because they did not receive the love of the truth for their salvation.
B053C002V011	53	2	11	For this reason God is sending on them an energy of delusion, that they should put faith in a falsehood;
B053C002V012	53	2	12	so that they all should be condemned, who are faithless to the truth, but take pleasure in evil.
B053C002V013	53	2	13	But for you, brothers, whom the Lord loves, I ought to give thanks to God continually, because God has chosen you from the beginning for salvation in consecration of the Spirit and belief of the truth.
B053C002V014	53	2	14	For this he called you through my gospel, so that you might obtain the glory of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B053C002V015	53	2	15	So, brothers, stand fast, and hold fast the teachings which you have been taught by me, whether by word of mouth or by letter.
B053C002V016	53	2	16	And may our Lord Jesus Christ himself, and God our Father, who has loved us and given us eternal encouragement and a good hope in grace,
B053C002V017	53	2	17	comfort your hearts, and establish you in every good work and word.
B053C003V001	53	3	1	Finally, brothers, pray on for me, that Gods word may run swiftly,  and be glorified as in your own case,
B053C003V002	53	3	2	and that I may be delivered from unreasonable and wicked men; for all do not hold the faith.
B053C003V003	53	3	3	But the Lord is faithful; he will stablish you and guard you from the Evil One.
B053C003V004	53	3	4	Now we have fully fixed our faith on you in the Lord, that you are doing and will continue to do what we enjoin.
B053C003V005	53	3	5	May the Lord incline your hearts to the love of God and to the stedfastness of Christ.
B053C003V006	53	3	6	I summon you, in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ, to shun any brother who leads an idle and disorderly life, which is not according to the rule you received from me.
B053C003V007	53	3	7	For you know well how you must imitate me. For I did not lead an idle or disorderly life among you;
B053C003V008	53	3	8	I did not eat my food as a gift from any man, but in toil and travail, night and day, I worked, so that I might not be a burden to any of you.
B053C003V009	53	3	9	Not that I have no right to such support; it was simply to give you an example for you to imitate.
B053C003V010	53	3	10	For indeed when I was with you, I used to charge you, "If any man will not work, he shall not eat."
B053C003V011	53	3	11	But I hear that there are those of your number who are leading idle and disorderly lives, who are not busy, but mere busybodies.
B053C003V012	53	3	12	Now all such I command and entreat, by the authority of the Lord Jesus Christ, to work in quietness. and to earn their own living.
B053C003V013	53	3	13	But you, brothers, must not grow weary in well-doing.
B053C003V014	53	3	14	If any man does not give heed to what I have said in this letter,  mark that man; do not associate with him, so as to make him feel ashamed;
B053C003V015	53	3	15	and yet do not count him as an enemy, but admonish him as a brother.
B053C003V016	53	3	16	And may the Lord of peace himself give you peace at all times and in every way. The Lord be with you all.
B053C003V017	53	3	17	I, Paul, add this greeting in my own handwriting, which is my token in every letter. Thus I write -
B053C003V018	53	3	18	The grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with you all.
B054C001V001	54	1	1	Paul, and apostle of Jesus Christ by command of God our Saviour and Jesus Christ our Hope,
B054C001V002	54	1	2	to Timothy, my true son in the faith; Grace, mercy and peace from God, our Father, and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B054C001V003	54	1	3	As I begged you when I was setting out for Macedonia, stay where you are at Ephesus, and instruct certain individuals there not to be teaching heterodoxy,
B054C001V004	54	1	4	nor to be paying attention to myths and interminable genealogies,  which tend to promote discussions rather than a stewardship entrusted by God, a stewardship which is in faith.
B054C001V005	54	1	5	Now the end of the exhortation is love, out of a pure heart and a good conscience and an undissembled faith.
B054C001V006	54	1	6	Some have failed here, and have turned aside to empty argument.
B054C001V007	54	1	7	Although they desire to be teachers of the law, they understand neither the words they use nor the subjects they talk about.
B054C001V008	54	1	8	I know well that "the Law is good" if a man use it lawfully;
B054C001V009	54	1	9	but he must remember that the Law is not enacted for a good man, but for the lawless and rebellious, for the irreligious and sinful, for the godless and profane, for parricides and murderers,
B054C001V010	54	1	10	for the immoral, for sexual perverts, for slave dealers, liars,  perjurers, and whatever else is contrary to sound teaching,
B054C001V011	54	1	11	as laid down in the glorious gospel of the blessed God, which has been entrusted to me.
B054C001V012	54	1	12	And I am thankful to Christ Jesus our Lord, who has thus enabled me,  that he accounted me faithful, and appointed me to his service,
B054C001V013	54	1	13	although I had formerly been a blasphemer and a persecutor and a doer of outrage. But I obtained mercy because I acted ignorantly in unbelief.
B054C001V014	54	1	14	And the grace of our Lord overflowed with faith and love that is in Christ Jesus.
B054C001V015	54	1	15	Faithful is the saying, and worthy of all acceptation, that "Jesus Christ came into the world to save sinners"! And there is no greater sinner than I!
B054C001V016	54	1	16	Yet for this very cause I obtained mercy, so that in me, the chief of sinners, Jesus Christ might display all his boundless patience as an illustration for those who should later believe in him, and so gain life eternal.
B054C001V017	54	1	17	Now unto the King eternal, immortal, invisible, the only God, be glory and honor forever and ever. Amen!
B054C001V018	54	1	18	This charge then, I am laying upon you, Timothy, my son, according to the predictions formerly made concerning you. Fight the good fight in the spirit of these predictions,
B054C001V019	54	1	19	keeping fast hold of faith and a good conscience; which certain individuals have cast aside, and so made shipwreck of their faith.
B054C001V020	54	1	20	Among them are Hymenaeus and Alexander, whom I have given over to Satan, so that they may be taught not to blaspheme.
B054C002V001	54	2	1	First of all then, I am urging that supplications, prayers,  intercessions, and thanksgivings be offered regularly for all men;
B054C002V002	54	2	2	for kings and all who are in authority, in order that we may lead a tranquil and peaceful life in all godliness an gravity.
B054C002V003	54	2	3	For this is good and pleasing in the eyes of our Saviour God,
B054C002V004	54	2	4	whose will it is that all men should be saved, and come into full knowledge of the truth.
B054C002V005	54	2	5	For God is one; and one is mediator between God and man, the Man Christ Jesus,
B054C002V006	54	2	6	who gave himself as a ransom in behalf of all, to be attested in due time.
B054C002V007	54	2	7	It was for this testimony that I myself was appointed a herald and apostle (I am telling the truth, I am not lying), to be a teacher of the Gentiles in faith and truth.
B054C002V008	54	2	8	My wish, then, is that in every place the men should offer prayer,  lifting up holy hands, free from anger and disputation;
B054C002V009	54	2	9	in like manner also the women. I desire women to clothe themselves in suitable apparel, adorning themselves with reverence and self-  restraint; not with hair plaited with gold or pearls, or with expensive clothes,
B054C002V010	54	2	10	but (as becomes women proclaiming godliness) with the ornament of good deeds.
B054C002V011	54	2	11	Let a woman learn quietly in entire submission.
B054C002V012	54	2	12	I allow no woman to teach, or to exercise authority over a man; but let her keep quiet.
B054C002V013	54	2	13	It was Adam who was first formed, then Eve.
B054C002V014	54	2	14	And it was not Adam who was deceived; but it was the woman who was thoroughly deceived, and who became involved in transgression.
B054C002V015	54	2	15	Notwithstanding she will be saved by the Child-bearing; (so will they all), if they live in faith and love and holiness, with self-  restraint.
B054C003V001	54	3	1	This is a faithful saying, "If any man is seeking the office of a minister he is aspiring to a noble task."
B054C003V002	54	3	2	The minister should be a man of blameless character; he should be husband of but one wife; he should live a sober, self-restrained,  orderly life; he should be hospitable, skilled in teaching;
B054C003V003	54	3	3	no drinker or brawler; but forbearing, peaceable, and no money- lover;
B054C003V004	54	3	4	he should be a man who rules his own household well, and keeps his children ever under control and thoroughly well behaved.
B054C003V005	54	3	5	For if a man does not know how to rule his own household, how shall he take charge of a church of God?
B054C003V006	54	3	6	He must not be a recent convert, lest he be blinded with pride, and incur the doom of the devil.
B054C003V007	54	3	7	He should also have a good reputation among outsiders, lest he fall into reproach, and into a snare of the devil.
B054C003V008	54	3	8	Deacons, likewise, must be serious, not double-tongued, not given to much wine, not greedy of gain,
B054C003V009	54	3	9	holding the mystery of the faith in a pure conscience.
B054C003V010	54	3	10	They should first be tested, and after that, if they are found irreproachable, let them serve as deacons.
B054C003V011	54	3	11	Deaconesses likewise must be grave, not slanderers, sober, faithful in all things.
B054C003V012	54	3	12	Let deacons be the husband of but one wife, men who rule their children and their household properly.
B054C003V013	54	3	13	For those who have well discharged the duties of a deacon are gaining an honorable position for themselves, as well as much fearless confidence in the faith of Christ Jesus.
B054C003V014	54	3	14	Although I am hoping to come to you before long,
B054C003V015	54	3	15	I am writing this to you in case I should be detained, to let you see how you ought to behave in the household of God - the Church of the everliving God, the pillar and mainstay of the truth.
B054C003V016	54	3	16	Yes! without contradiction, great is the mystery of godliness!
B054C004V001	54	4	1	Now the Spirit distinctly declares that in latter days there will be some who will fall away from the faith, by listening to spirits of error, and to teachings of demons
B054C004V002	54	4	2	speaking lies in hypocrisy. These are men whose consciences have been seared as with a hot iron,
B054C004V003	54	4	3	who discourage marriage, and enjoin abstinence from foods which God created to be received with thankfulness, by those who believe, and have a clear knowledge of the truth.
B054C004V004	54	4	4	For everything that God has created is good, and nothing is to be rejected if only it is received with thankfulness.
B054C004V005	54	4	5	For it is sanctified by the Word of God and by prayer.
B054C004V006	54	4	6	As you lay all these things before the brothers, you will be a noble minister of Christ Jesus, nourishing yourself in the precepts of the faith and that noble teaching which you have followed.
B054C004V007	54	4	7	Ever reject these profane and old womanish myths; and continually train yourself for the contest of godliness.
B054C004V008	54	4	8	For physical training is of some small service, but godliness is of service in everything; since it carries with it a promise of life,  both here and hereafter.
B054C004V009	54	4	9	Faithful is the saying, and worthy of all acceptation.
B054C004V010	54	4	10	"We toil and agonize because our hopes are set on the ever-living God, who is the Saviour of all men. - of believers in particular.
B054C004V011	54	4	11	Keep preaching and teaching these things.
B054C004V012	54	4	12	Let no one despise you on account of your youth, but become an example for the faithful in word, in life, in love, in faith, in purity.
B054C004V013	54	4	13	Be applying yourself until I come to public reading, preaching, and teaching.
B054C004V014	54	4	14	Never neglect the gift within you, which was given in fulfilment of prophecy at the time of the laying on of hands by the elders.
B054C004V015	54	4	15	Let these things be your care, give yourself wholly to them, so that your progress may be manifest to all.
B054C004V016	54	4	16	Give heed to yourself and to your teaching. Persevere in these things, for by doing this you will save both yourself and your hearers.
B054C005V001	54	5	1	Do not reprimand an aged man, but continue pleading with him as if he were your father. Treat the young men as brothers,
B054C005V002	54	5	2	the older women as mothers, the younger women as sisters in all purity.
B054C005V003	54	5	3	Ever honor widows who are really widows;
B054C005V004	54	5	4	but if any widow has children or grandchildren, let these learn to show their piety first toward their own household, and to make some return to their parents, for that is pleasing in Gods sight.
B054C005V005	54	5	5	Now she who is a widow indeed, and desolate, has fixed her hope on God, and devotes herself to supplications and prayers, day and night.
B054C005V006	54	5	6	But she who lives in wantonness is dead even while she still lives.
B054C005V007	54	5	7	Keep admonishing them regarding these things, so that they may be irreproachable.
B054C005V008	54	5	8	But if any one fails to provide for his own, and especially for his kindred, he has denied the faith and is worse than an infidel.
B054C005V009	54	5	9	A widow, to be placed upon the list, must be not less than sixty years old, and one who has been the wife of but one husband.
B054C005V010	54	5	10	She must be well reputed for good works, as one who has brought up a family, received strangers with hospitality, washed the feet of the saints, relieved the distressed, and diligently followed every good work.
B054C005V011	54	5	11	But exclude from the list the younger widows; for where they have become wanton against Christ, they desire to marry,
B054C005V012	54	5	12	and incur condemnation because they have broken their first troth.
B054C005V013	54	5	13	Moreover, they learn to be idle, wandering about from house to house, and are not only idlers, but gossips also, and busybodies,  repeating things they ought not.
B054C005V014	54	5	14	It is my wish, then, that the younger widows marry, bear children,  rule their houses, and give no occasion to our adversary for railing.
B054C005V015	54	5	15	For already some widows have gone astray after Satan.
B054C005V016	54	5	16	Any believing woman, who has widowed relatives, ought to relieve them and not let the church be burdened with them; so that the church may relieve the really destitute widows.
B054C005V017	54	5	17	Let the elders who fill their offices well, be held worthy of twofold honor; especially those who have the task of preaching and teaching.
B054C005V018	54	5	18	For the Scripture says, You must not muzzle an ox when he is treading out the grain, and The worker is worth his wages.
B054C005V019	54	5	19	Do not receive an accusation against an elder, except on the testimony of two or three witnesses.
B054C005V020	54	5	20	Rebuke offenders publicly, so that others also may take warning.
B054C005V021	54	5	21	I charge you solemnly in the presence of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ and of the elect angels, that you observe these things without prejudice against any man, and do nothing out of partiality.
B054C005V022	54	5	22	Never ordain any one hastily, nor take part in the wrong-doing of others. Keep yourself pure.
B054C005V023	54	5	23	Do not continue to drink nothing but water, but take a little wine for your stomachs sake, and your frequent attacks of illness.
B054C005V024	54	5	24	Some mens sins are notorious, and lead them straight on the way to condemnation; but others sins follow them up.
B054C005V025	54	5	25	So also noble deeds are conspicuous, and even if otherwise, they cannot be kept hidden.
B054C006V001	54	6	1	Let those who are under the yoke as slaves esteem their masters as worthy of all honor, so that the name of God and the teachings be not blasphemed.
B054C006V002	54	6	2	Those whose masters are Christian believers must not treat them with disrespect, because they are brothers; nay, rather slave for them the better because those who get the benefit of their services are believing and beloved. Continue to teach and preach this.
B054C006V003	54	6	3	If any one teaches heterodoxy, and refuses to consent to the wholesome words of the Lord Jesus Christ, and to the teachings of religion,
B054C006V004	54	6	4	he is puffed up with conceit and knows nothing, but is doting about disputations and a strife of words. These give rise to envy,  quarrels, railings, evil suspicions,
B054C006V005	54	6	5	and wrangling between men whose minds are corrupt and destitute of the truth; who suppose that godliness is a source of gain.
B054C006V006	54	6	6	Now godliness with contentment is truly gainful;
B054C006V007	54	6	7	for we have brought nothing into the world, and it is certain we can carry nothing out!
B054C006V008	54	6	8	So if we have food and shelter, let us be content with that.
B054C006V009	54	6	9	Those who desire to be rich fall into the snares of temptation and many foolish and hurtful lusts, which drown men in destruction and perdition.
B054C006V010	54	6	10	For the love of money is a source of all kinds of evil; and in their eager desire to be rich some have been led astray form the faith, and have pierced themselves with many sorrows.
B054C006V011	54	6	11	But you, O servant of God, flee from these things, and run after integrity, piety, faith, love, stedfastness, gentleness.
B054C006V012	54	6	12	Keep contending in the noble contest of the faith; seize hold on eternal life, to which you were called when you confessed the good confession in the presence of many witnesses.
B054C006V013	54	6	13	In the presence of God who gives life to all, and of Christ Jesus who bore witness to the good confession before Pontius Pilate,
B054C006V014	54	6	14	I charge you, keep your commission spotless and irreproachable until the appearing of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B054C006V015	54	6	15	For in his own good time this will be brought about by that blessed and only potentate, King of kings and Lord of lords,
B054C006V016	54	6	16	who alone possesses immortality, who dwells in light that none can approach, whom no man has ever seen or can see; to whom be honor and power everlasting. Amen.
B054C006V017	54	6	17	Charge the rich of this world not to be supercilious, nor to trust in uncertain riches, but in God, who provides all things richly for our use.
B054C006V018	54	6	18	Charge them to practise benevolence, to be rich in good works, to be open-handed and generous,
B054C006V019	54	6	19	laying up right good treasure for themselves in the world to come,  in order that they may obtain the Life which is life indeed.
B054C006V020	54	6	20	O, Timothy, guard the treasure which is committed to you. Shun the profane babblings and contradictions of the falsely called "knowledge"
B054C006V021	54	6	21	which some professing have erred from the faith. Grace be with you.
B055C001V001	55	1	1	Paul, an apostle of Christ Jesus, by the will of God, sent forth to proclaim the promise of the life which is in Christ Jesus.
B055C001V002	55	1	2	To Timothy, my beloved child; Grace mercy, and peace to you from God our Father and Christ Jesus our Lord.
B055C001V003	55	1	3	I give thanks to God whom I worship with a pure conscience as my fathers did, when I remember you unceasingly in my prayers.
B055C001V004	55	1	4	Night and day when I recall your tears I am longing to see you, that my happiness may be complete.
B055C001V005	55	1	5	I have been reminded of that sincere faith which is in your heart;  which dwelt first in your grandmother Lois and in your mother Eunice,  and, I am fully persuaded, dwells in you also.
B055C001V006	55	1	6	For this reason let me remind you to keep ever blazing that gift of God which is in you through the laying on of my hands.
B055C001V007	55	1	7	For God has not given us a spirit of cowardice, but a spirit of power and of love and of self-control.
B055C001V008	55	1	8	Do not then be ashamed to bear witness for our Lord, nor for me, his prisoner. Nay, join with me in suffering for the gospel by the power of God.
B055C001V009	55	1	9	He has saved us and called us with a holy calling, not dealing with us according to our works,but according to his purpose and grace which he gave us in Christ Jesus before the beginning of time.
B055C001V010	55	1	10	This has now been made manifest through the appearing of our Saviour Christ Jesus, who has put an end to death, and brought life and immortality to light through the gospel.
B055C001V011	55	1	11	Of the gospel I was appointed a herald, apostle, and teacher; and that is the reason I am now undergoing these sufferings.
B055C001V012	55	1	12	But I am not ashamed; for I know whom I have fully believed, and I am thoroughly persuaded that he is able to keep what I have given him until the Day.
B055C001V013	55	1	13	Hold fast the pattern of sound teaching you have heard from me in faith and love which is in Christ Jesus.
B055C001V014	55	1	14	Guard the glorious trust which has been committed to you by the aid of the Holy Spirit who makes his home in us.
B055C001V015	55	1	15	You already know that all the Christians in Roman Asia forsook me,  among them Phygellus and Hermogenes.
B055C001V016	55	1	16	The Lord show mercy to the house hold of Onesiphorus; for many a time he refreshed me, and was not ashamed of my chain.
B055C001V017	55	1	17	But when he came to Rome he sought for me until he found me.
B055C001V018	55	1	18	The Lord grant him to find mercy form the Lord in that Day! And you know better than I how many services he rendered in Ephesus.
B055C002V001	55	2	1	Do you then, my son, strengthen you heart in the grace which is in Christ Jesus.
B055C002V002	55	2	2	The teachings which you have heard from me, attested by many witnesses, deliver into the keeping of faithful men, who in their turn will be able to teach others also.
B055C002V003	55	2	3	Take your share in suffering as a good soldier of Jesus Christ.
B055C002V004	55	2	4	A soldier in active service avoids entangling himself in the every-  day affairs of life, so that he may please his commander.
B055C002V005	55	2	5	And again, an athlete is not crowned unless he obeys the rules of the game.
B055C002V006	55	2	6	The farmer who has done the work should be the first to get a share of the crop.
B055C002V007	55	2	7	Reflect on what I am telling you. The Lord will give you understanding in everything.
B055C002V008	55	2	8	Always remember that Jesus Christ, a descendant of David, has been raised from the dead according to the gospel I proclaim.
B055C002V009	55	2	9	For preaching it I am suffering, and am even put in chains as a malefacter.
B055C002V010	55	2	10	But Gods message is no prisoner. That is why I endure everything for the sake of the chosen, that they also may obtain the salvation which is in Christ Jesus with eternal glory.
B055C002V011	55	2	11	Faithful is the saying. "If we have died with him, we shall also live with him.
B055C002V012	55	2	12	If we endure suffering, we shall also reign with him. If we disown him, he too will disown us.
B055C002V013	55	2	13	If we prove faithless. he abides faithful, for he cannot be false to himself."
B055C002V014	55	2	14	Always call these truths to mens mind; adjuring them in the presence of God to avoid controversy. It is a useless thing, and subverts those who listen to it.
B055C002V015	55	2	15	Strive earnestly to present yourself unto God, tested and proved worthy by trial, a workman unashamed, ever cutting a straight path for the message of the truth.
B055C002V016	55	2	16	but avoid profane babble; for people will go farther and farther in impiety,
B055C002V017	55	2	17	and their teaching will spread like a gangrene.
B055C002V018	55	2	18	Among such are Hymenaeus and Philetus, who have gone astray concerning the truth by declaring that the resurrection is already past; and they are undermining the faith of some.
B055C002V019	55	2	19	Nevertheless Gods firm foundation stands unshaken, bearing this inscription, THE LORD KNOWS THOSE WHO ARE HIS, and this also, LET EVERY ONE WHO NAMES THE NAME OF THE LORD RENOUNCE WICKEDNESS.
B055C002V020	55	2	20	Now in a great house there are not only vessels of gold and silver,  but also of wood and clay, some for noble, some for ignoble uses.
B055C002V021	55	2	21	If then a man keeps himself clear of these latter, he will be a vessel for honor, consecrated, useful to the Master, prepared for every good work.
B055C002V022	55	2	22	Flee from the passions of youth, but run after righteousness, faith,  love, and peace, in company with those who out of a pure heart call upon the Lord.
B055C002V023	55	2	23	Ever shun foolish and puerile discussions, for you know that they lead to quarrels.
B055C002V024	55	2	24	The Lords slave must not quarrel, but must be kind to all men; a skilful teacher, patient of wrong.
B055C002V025	55	2	25	He must be gentle when instructing opponents; for possibly God may give them a change of mind for the recognition of the truth,
B055C002V026	55	2	26	and they may come to their senses again, and escape the snare of the devil, as they are restored to life by God to do his will.
B055C003V001	55	3	1	But of this be sure. In the last days grievous times will come.
B055C003V002	55	3	2	For men will be selfish, mercenary, boastful, haughty, blasphemous,  disobedient to parents, ungrateful, irreligious,
B055C003V003	55	3	3	without natural affection, merciless, slanderous, dissolute, and brutal.
B055C003V004	55	3	4	They will hate goodness, they will be treacherous, reckless, blinded with pride, lovers of pleasure, rather than lovers of God.
B055C003V005	55	3	5	For although they keep up the outward form of religion, they deny its power.
B055C003V006	55	3	6	Turn away from all such. Some of them creep into private houses and lead captive silly women who, laden with sins,
B055C003V007	55	3	7	and led captive by ever-changing impulses, are always learning but never able to arrive at knowledge of truth.
B055C003V008	55	3	8	As Jannes and Jambres withstood Moses, so also do these men withstand the truth; being corrupt in mind and worthless in all that concerns the faith.
B055C003V009	55	3	9	But they will not get on; for their folly will be made as openly manifest to all as was that of Jannes and Jambres.
B055C003V010	55	3	10	But you, Timothy, have followed my teaching, my conduct, my aims, my faith, patience, love, endurance,
B055C003V011	55	3	11	as well as the persecutions and sufferings which befell me at Antioch, Iconium, and Lystra. You know all the persecutions I endured, and how the Lord delivered me out of them all!
B055C003V012	55	3	12	Yes, and all who purpose to live a godly life in Christ Jesus will be persecuted.
B055C003V013	55	3	13	But wicked men and impostors will go on from bad to worse, deceiving others, and being themselves deceived.
B055C003V014	55	3	14	But do you hold fast what you have learned and have held to be true.  You know those from whom you have learned it,
B055C003V015	55	3	15	and how from a child you have known the Holy Scriptures, which are able to make you wise unto salvation through faith in Christ Jesus.
B055C003V016	55	3	16	Every Scripture, seeing that it is God-breathed, is also profitable for teaching, for refutation, for correction, and for training in righteousness,
B055C003V017	55	3	17	so that the man of God may himself be complete, and completely equipped for every good work.
B055C004V001	55	4	1	I adjure you in the presence of God and of Christ Jesus who is about to judge the living and the dead - by his appearing and his kingdom,  I adjure you - ;11 Luke only is with me. Pick up Mark, and bring him with you, for he is useful to me in my ministry.
B055C004V002	55	4	2	proclaim the message, be urgent in season and out of season;  convince, rebuke, encourage, with never-failing patience and teaching.
B055C004V003	55	4	3	For a time will come when they will not listen to wholesome teaching, but wanting to have their ears tickled, they will heap up for themselves teachers upon teachers to satisfy their own fancies.
B055C004V004	55	4	4	They will turn away their ears from the truth, and turn aside to myths.
B055C004V005	55	4	5	But as for you, be always self-controlled, face hardships, do the work of a missionary, discharge all the duties of your ministry.
B055C004V006	55	4	6	I for my part am a libation already being poured in sacrifice; and the time of my unmooring is at hand.
B055C004V007	55	4	7	I have fought in the glorious contest; I have run the race; I have kept the faith.
B055C004V008	55	4	8	Henceforth there is laid up for me the garland of righteousness which the Lord, the righteous Judge, will award to me on that Day,  and not to me only, but also to all those who have loved his appearing.
B055C004V009	55	4	9	Do your best to come to me speedily,
B055C004V010	55	4	10	for Demas has deserted me for love of this present world, and is gone to Thessalonica; Crescens is gone to Galatia; Titus to Dalmatia.
B055C004V012	55	4	12	Tychicus I have sent to Ephesus.
B055C004V013	55	4	13	When you come, bring the cloak I left in Troas with Carpus; also my books, but especially my parchments.
B055C004V014	55	4	14	Alexander, the coppersmith, manifested bitter hostility toward me.  The Lord will requite him according to his works.
B055C004V015	55	4	15	Be also on your guard against him, for he has violently opposed my arguments.
B055C004V016	55	4	16	At the time of my first defense no one stood by me; on the contrary they all deserted me - may it not be laid to their charge!
B055C004V017	55	4	17	Nevertheless the Lord Jesus stood by me, and strengthened my heart,  that through me full proclamation of the gospel might be made, and the Gentiles might hear it; and I was rescued from the lions jaws.
B055C004V018	55	4	18	And the Lord will rescue me from every evil assault, and will preserve me for his heavenly kingdom. To him be the glory forever and ever! Amen!
B055C004V019	55	4	19	Give my greetings to Prisca and Aquila, and the household of Onesiphorus.
B055C004V020	55	4	20	Erastus remained at Corinth; Trophimus I left behind me ill at Miletus.
B055C004V021	55	4	21	Do try to come before winter. Eubulus greets you, and so do Pudens and Linus and Claudia and all the brotherhood.
B055C004V022	55	4	22	The Lord Jesus be with your spirit. Grace be with you all.
B056C001V001	56	1	1	To Titus, my true son in a common faith, from Paul, a slave of God,  and an apostle of Jesus Christ, according to the faith of Gods elect, and to the knowledge of the truth which goes with piety;
B056C001V002	56	1	2	I write in hope of life eternal which God who never lies, promised before times eternal,
B056C001V003	56	1	3	but manifested in his own time; that word of his in proclaiming which I have been entrusted by command of God our Saviour.
B056C001V004	56	1	4	Grace and peace from God the Father and Christ Jesus our Saviour.
B056C001V005	56	1	5	I left you in Crete for this reason, that you might set right the things left unfinished, and appoint presbyters in every city as I had instructed you;
B056C001V006	56	1	6	men who are blameless, the husband of one wife, with believing children who are not accused of riot or insubordination.
B056C001V007	56	1	7	For indeed a presiding officer, as Gods steward, ought to be blameless, not self-willed or quick-tempered, not a drunkard or violent, or greedy of filthy lucre;
B056C001V008	56	1	8	but he must be hospitable, a lover of the good, sober-minded, just,  holy, self-controlled.
B056C001V009	56	1	9	He must hold to the faithful word according to the teaching, so that he may be able both to encourage by sound teaching, and to confute our opponents.
B056C001V010	56	1	10	For there are many individuals who are unruly, empty talkers and deceivers, particularly those of the circumcision, whose mouths must be stopped;
B056C001V011	56	1	11	for they upset whole households and, for filthy lucres sake, teach what they ought not to teach.
B056C001V012	56	1	12	By one of their own number, by a prophet of their own, it has been said, "Cretans are always liars, evil beasts, idle gluttons."
B056C001V013	56	1	13	This testimony is true. So rebuke them sharply,
B056C001V014	56	1	14	so as to make them sound in the faith, not giving heed to Jewish myths and commandments of men who turn away from the truth.
B056C001V015	56	1	15	All things are pure to the pure; but to the contaminated and the faithless nothing is pure, nay, their very minds and consciences are tainted.
B056C001V016	56	1	16	They profess to know God, but by their deeds they disown him; in that they are detestable, disobedient, and reprobate for good work of any sort.
B056C002V001	56	2	1	But do you, on your part, speak what becomes sound teaching;
B056C002V002	56	2	2	that the older men be self-controlled, serious and sober-minded,  sound in faith, in love, in patience;
B056C002V003	56	2	3	that older women likewise be reverent in demeanor, not slanderers or slaves to much wine, but teachers of what is right.
B056C002V004	56	2	4	They should train the younger women to love their husbands and children,
B056C002V005	56	2	5	to be sober-minded, chaste, workers at home, kind and submissive to their husbands, in order that Gods message be not maligned.
B056C002V006	56	2	6	The younger men exhort to be sober-minded; in every respect showing yourself an example of good works.
B056C002V007	56	2	7	In your teaching be serious and sincere.
B056C002V008	56	2	8	Let the instruction that you give be sound and above reproach, so that our opponents may be ashamed because they find no evil things to say about us.
B056C002V009	56	2	9	Exhort slaves to be obedient to their own masters, and to be well-  pleasing to them in every respect;
B056C002V010	56	2	10	not to contradict nor pilfer, but to exhibit praiseworthy trustworthiness in every thing, that they may adorn the doctrine of God our Saviour in all things.
B056C002V011	56	2	11	"For Gods grace has shined forth bringing salvation to all men
B056C002V012	56	2	12	And schooling us to renounce impiety and evil passions, And to live soberly, righteously, and godly in this present age;
B056C002V013	56	2	13	While we look for the blessed hope and epiphany of the glory of our great God and Saviour, Jesus Christ.
B056C002V014	56	2	14	He gave himself for us to redeem us from all iniquity, and to purify unto himself a people zealous of good works."
B056C002V015	56	2	15	Thus speak, exhort, reprove with all authority. Let no one despise you.
B056C003V001	56	3	1	Remind them to be submissive to their rulers and authorities; let them be obedient, ready for every good work;
B056C003V002	56	3	2	they must speak evil of none, they must not be quarrelsome, but gentle, showing perfect meekness toward all.
B056C003V003	56	3	3	For we were ourselves once foolish, disobedient, deceived, slaving for various lusts and pleasures, passing our lives in malice and envy. We were hateful, and we hated one another.
B056C003V004	56	3	4	But when the kindness of God our Saviour, And his love toward men shined forth,
B056C003V005	56	3	5	He saved us, not because of any deeds that we had done in righteousness, But because of his own pity for us. He saved us by that washing of regeneration and renewing of the Holy Spirit
B056C003V006	56	3	6	which he poured out upon us richly, through Jesus Christ our Saviour;
B056C003V007	56	3	7	In order that being justified by his grace, We might be made heirs according to the hope of eternal life.
B056C003V008	56	3	8	This saying is trustworthy. On this I want you to firmly insist;  that those who have faith in God must be careful to maintain honest occupations. Such counsels are good and profitable for men.
B056C003V009	56	3	9	But avoid foolish questionings and genealogies and dissensions and wranglings about the law; for these are unprofitable and empty.
B056C003V010	56	3	10	After a first and second admonition, refuse a man who is causing divisions;
B056C003V011	56	3	11	you may be sure that such a man is perverted and sinning, and is self-condemned.
B056C003V012	56	3	12	As soon as I send Artemas or Tychicus to you, join me in Nicopolis as quickly as you can, for I have arranged to winter there.
B056C003V013	56	3	13	Speed Zenas the lawyer, and Apollos, on their journey diligently.
B056C003V014	56	3	14	Let them want nothing, and "let our people learn to devote themselves to honest work to supply the necessities of their teachers," so that they be not unfruitful.
B056C003V015	56	3	15	All who are with us salute you. Salute those who love me in faith.  Grace be with you all.
B057C001V001	57	1	1	To my beloved friend and coworker Philemon,
B057C001V002	57	1	2	to my sister Apphia, to my fellow soldier Archippus, and to the church which meets at Philemons house. From Paul, a prisoner of Jesus Christ, and brother Timothy.
B057C001V003	57	1	3	Grace and peace be to you from God our Father and the Lord Jesus Christ.
B057C001V004	57	1	4	I am ever mentioning you in my prayers, and giving thanks to God,
B057C001V005	57	1	5	because I am hearing of your love and of the faith which you hold,  not only toward the Lord Jesus Christ, but toward all the saints.
B057C001V006	57	1	6	And I pray that your participation may become effectual, as you come to acknowledge every good thing which is in you to Christ.
B057C001V007	57	1	7	For I have great joy and comfort in your love, my brother, because the hearts of the saints have been refreshed.
B057C001V008	57	1	8	And so, although I might be bold in Christ to dictate to you what is fitting,
B057C001V009	57	1	9	yet for loves sake, I rather beseech you, I, Paul, an old man, and now a prisoner for Christ Jesus!
B057C001V010	57	1	10	I beseech you for my son, Onesimus, whom I have begotten in these chains.
B057C001V011	57	1	11	Once you found him "unprofitable," but now he is "profitable" to you and to me.
B057C001V012	57	1	12	I am sending him back to you, he himself, that is, my very heart!
B057C001V013	57	1	13	I could wish to retain him at my side, so that he might minister to me in your stead, in my bonds for the gospel.
B057C001V014	57	1	14	But without your consent I was unwilling to do anything, so that your kindness to me might be of your own free will, and not of compulsion.
B057C001V015	57	1	15	Perhaps for this reason you were separated from him for an hour, in order that you might have him back forever,
B057C001V016	57	1	16	no longer as a slave, but more than a slave, as a brother beloved;  especially dear to me, but how much more to you, both as a man and a fellow Christian.
B057C001V017	57	1	17	If then you count me as a partner, receive him as you would me.
B057C001V018	57	1	18	And if he has wronged you at all, or is owing you anything, charge that to me.
B057C001V019	57	1	19	I Paul am writing this in my own handwriting, "I will repay you."  But I will not mention that you owe me, over and over, your very soul.
B057C001V020	57	1	20	Come my brother, let me have joy in the Lord because of you! Refresh my heart in Christ!
B057C001V021	57	1	21	Because I am thoroughly persuaded of your obedience, I have written you, knowing full well that you will do by me what I am asking.
B057C001V022	57	1	22	Please also prepare for me a lodging, for I am hoping by your prayers to be restored to you again.
B057C001V023	57	1	23	Epaphras, my fellow prisoner in Christ Jesus, sends you greeting;
B057C001V024	57	1	24	so do Mark, Aristarchus, Demas, and Luke, my fellow workers.
B057C001V025	57	1	25	May the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit. Amen.
B058C001V001	58	1	1	God, who in ancient days spoke to our ancestors in the prophets, at many different times and by various methods,
B058C001V002	58	1	2	has at the end of these days spoken to us in a Son whom he appointed heir of all things; through whom also he made the universe.
B058C001V003	58	1	3	He being an emanation of Gods glory and stamp of his substance, and upholding the universe by the utterances of his power, after by himself making purification of our sins, has taken his seat on the right hand of the Majesty on High.
B058C001V004	58	1	4	He is as much superior to the angels as the name that he has inherited surpasses theirs.
B058C001V005	58	1	5	For to what angel did God ever say, Thou art my son; this day have I become thy Father? and again, I will be a father to him, and he shall be to me a son?
B058C001V006	58	1	6	And further, when he brought the firstborn into the habitable world,  he said, Let all the angels of God worship him.
B058C001V007	58	1	7	While of the angels he said, He makes his angels into winds, His ministering servants into flames of fire.
B058C001V008	58	1	8	But to the Son he says. Thy throne, O God, is forever and ever, And the scepter of thy kingdom is the scepter of justice.
B058C001V009	58	1	9	Thou hast loved righteousness and hated lawlessness; Therefore did God, thy God, anoint thee with the oil of gladness beyond thy comrades.
B058C001V010	58	1	10	And, Thou, O Lord, in the beginning didst lay the foundations of the earth, And the heavens are the work of thy hands.
B058C001V011	58	1	11	They will perish, but thou remainest; They all will grow old like a garment,
B058C001V012	58	1	12	Like a mantle thou wilt fold them up, And like a garment they will be changed. But thou art the same, And thy years will never fail.
B058C001V013	58	1	13	To which of the angels has he ever said, Sit at my right hand, Till I make thy foes a footstool for thy feet?
B058C001V014	58	1	14	Are they not all ministering spirits, sent forth for service in behalf of those who are about to inherit salvation?
B058C002V001	58	2	1	For this reason we must pay the more earnest heed to the things which we have heard, for fear we should drift away.
B058C002V002	58	2	2	For if the word uttered through angels stood firm, so that every transgression and act of disobedience met with its just retribution,  how shall we escape if we neglect so great a salvation?
B058C002V003	58	2	3	Which having begun to be spoken by the Lord, was confirmed to us by those who heard him;
B058C002V004	58	2	4	God himself corroborating their testimony by signs and wonders and a variety of miraculous powers, and by gifts of the Holy Spirit imparted in accordance with his own will.
B058C002V005	58	2	5	It is not to angels that God subjected the age to be, of which we are speaking.
B058C002V006	58	2	6	But some one, somewhere, testified, saying. What is Man, that thou art mindful of him? Or any man, that thou carest for him?
B058C002V007	58	2	7	Thou hast made him only a little lower that the angels; With glory and honor hast thou crowned him; And hast set him to govern the works of thy hands;
B058C002V008	58	2	8	Thou hast put all things under his feet. For this putting all things under man means leaving nothing not subject to him. But we do not yet see all things subject to him.
B058C002V009	58	2	9	What we do see is Jesus, who was made for a time a little lower than the angels, now crowned with glory and honor, because of the suffering of death, in order that through Gods grace he might taste death for every man.
B058C002V010	58	2	10	For it befitted him, for whom and through whom all things exist, in bringing many sons to glory, to make the Pioneer of their salvation perfect through sufferings.
B058C002V011	58	2	11	For both he who sanctifies and those whom he is sanctifying are all from One; for which reason he is not ashamed to call them brothers,  saying.
B058C002V012	58	2	12	I will proclaim thy name to my brothers; In the midst of the Church I will hymn thy praises.
B058C002V013	58	2	13	And again, I myself will put my trust in God. And again, Lo, I and the children God has given me.
B058C002V014	58	2	14	Therefore, since the children are sharers in flesh and blood, he also similarly partook of the same, in order that through death he might render powerless him that had the power of death, that is, the devil;
B058C002V015	58	2	15	And might deliver those who through fear of death had been subject to life-long bondage.
B058C002V016	58	2	16	For assuredly it is not angels, nay, it is the offspring of Abraham,  whom he is ever taking by the hand.
B058C002V017	58	2	17	And so it was necessary that he should in all points be made like his brothers, so that he might become a compassionate and faithful high priest, in all that relates to God, to make reconciliation for the sins of the people.
B058C002V018	58	2	18	For inasmuch as he himself has suffered, being tempted, he is also able instantly to succor those who are tempted, he is also able instantly to succor those who are tempted.
B058C003V001	58	3	1	Therefore, holy brothers, comrades of a heavenly calling, fix your thoughts then upon Jesus, the Apostle and High Priest of our confession.
B058C003V002	58	3	2	How faithful he was to the God who appointed him! For while Moses also was faithful in all Gods house,
B058C003V003	58	3	3	Jesus has been counted worthy of greater glory than Moses, inasmuch as he who has built a house has higher honor than the house itself.
B058C003V004	58	3	4	For every house has its builder; but he who built the universe is God.
B058C003V005	58	3	5	And Moses indeed was faithful in all his house as a servant, bearing testimony to a witness about to be spoken;
B058C003V006	58	3	6	but Christ as a Son in his own house; and we are that house, if we retain the cheerful courage and pride of our hope firm unto the end.
B058C003V007	58	3	7	Therefore, as the Holy Spirit says. If you hear Gods voice today,
B058C003V008	58	3	8	Continue not to harden your hearts as in the Provocation, On the day of temptation in the wilderness,
B058C003V009	58	3	9	When your forefathers tried my forbearance And saw my deeds for forty years.
B058C003V010	58	3	10	For this reason I was sore displeased with that generation, And said, "They are always wandering in their hearts; They have never learned my ways";
B058C003V011	58	3	11	So I swore in my wrath, "They shall never enter into my rest."
B058C003V012	58	3	12	See to it, brothers, that there shall never be in any one of you an evil and unbelieving heart, manifesting itself in apostasy from the living God.
B058C003V013	58	3	13	On the contrary, encourage each other daily, so long as there is a "Today," so that no one of you is hindered by the deceitfulness of sin.
B058C003V014	58	3	14	For we are become comrades of the Christ, if we hold our first title deed firm until the very end.
B058C003V015	58	3	15	In the words of Scripture, Today, if you hear his voice, Do not continue to harden your hearts as at the Provocation.
B058C003V016	58	3	16	For who were they that heard and yet provoked him? Was it not all who came out of Egypt under the leadership of Moses?
B058C003V017	58	3	17	And with whom was he grieved for forty years? Was it not with those who had sinned, and whose dead bodies fell in the wilderness?
B058C003V018	58	3	18	And to whom did he swear that they should never enter into his rest,  if not to those who had proved faithless? So you see that it was through unbelief that they were not able to enter in.
B058C003V019	58	3	19	missing fehlt/missing
B058C004V001	58	4	1	Let us be on our guard, then, though there is a promise still standing of being admitted to his rest, lest any one of you should be found to have come short of it.
B058C004V002	58	4	2	For the Good News is come to us just as it did to them. But the message they heard was of no benefit to them, because they did not share the faith of those who gave heed to it.
B058C004V003	58	4	3	We are actually entering into that rest, we who have believed, as God has said, -In my wrath I swore - "They shall not enter into my Rest," although his works were finished since the foundation of the world.
B058C004V004	58	4	4	For he has said, somewhere, regarding the seventh day, And God rested on the seventh day from all his work.
B058C004V005	58	4	5	And again in this passage, They shall not enter into my rest.
B058C004V006	58	4	6	Since, then, it remains that some should enter into it, and since those who formerly had the Good News preached to them did not enter in because of unbelief,
B058C004V007	58	4	7	he again fixes a day, saying long afterward by Davids lips, in words already quoted, Today if you hear his voice, Continue not to harden your hearts.
B058C004V008	58	4	8	For if Joshua had given them rest, he would not have spoken afterward of another day.
B058C004V009	58	4	9	So there remains a Sabbath Rest for the people of God.
B058C004V010	58	4	10	For whoever has entered into his rest has rested from his works,  just as God did from his.
B058C004V011	58	4	11	Let us, then, be earnest to enter into that rest, so that no one may fall into the same example of disobedience.
B058C004V012	58	4	12	For living is the Word of God, and active, and sharper than any two-  edged sword, piercing even to the severance of soul form spirit, of both joints and marrow, and is a discerner of the very thoughts and conceptions of the heart.
B058C004V013	58	4	13	And there is not a creature hidden form him, but all things are naked and laid prostrate before the eyes of him with whom we have to do.
B058C004V014	58	4	14	Inasmuch, then, as we have a great High Priest, Jesus, the Son of God, who has passed through the heavens, let us hold fast our confession of faith.
B058C004V015	58	4	15	For we have not a High Priest who cannot sympathize with our weaknesses, but one who has been tempted in all points like as we are, yet without sin.
B058C004V016	58	4	16	Let us, then, draw near with glad boldness to the throne of grace,  that we may receive mercy, and find grace to help us in our times of need.
B058C005V001	58	5	1	For every high priest chosen from time to time from among men is appointed on behalf of men, in matters relating to God, to offer both gifts and sacrifices on behalf of sins.
B058C005V002	58	5	2	He is able to deal gently with the ignorant and erring, since he himself also is encompassed with moral weakness,
B058C005V003	58	5	3	and because of this weakness he is bound to offer sin-offerings not only for the people, but also for himself.
B058C005V004	58	5	4	Again no one takes this honorable office for himself, but he is called by God, just as Aaron was.
B058C005V005	58	5	5	So even the Christ was not raised to the high glory of the priesthood by himself, but on the contrary by Him who said to him.  Thou art my Son; this day have I become thy Father;
B058C005V006	58	5	6	and again, Thou art a priest forever, after the order of Melchisedek.
B058C005V007	58	5	7	In the days of his flesh, with better cries and weeping Jesus offered up prayers and supplications to Him who was able to save him out of death; and he was heard because of his devout submission.
B058C005V008	58	5	8	Though he was a son, yet learned he obedience through the things which he suffered;
B058C005V009	58	5	9	and by being thus made perfect, he became the source of enduring salvation to all who obey him,
B058C005V010	58	5	10	while God himself pronounced him High Priest according to the order of Melchisedek.
B058C005V011	58	5	11	Concerning him I have much to say, and much that is hard to make clear to you, because you have grown dull of hearing.
B058C005V012	58	5	12	And this too, although you ought by this time to be teaching others,  you are still needing some one to teach you the very rudiments of divine revelation. You need milk, not solid food.
B058C005V013	58	5	13	For every one who feeds on milk is inexperienced in the word of righteousness. He is still an infant.
B058C005V014	58	5	14	But solid food is for adults, that is, for those who by constant practise have their faculties trained to discriminate between good and evil.
B058C006V001	58	6	1	So let us get beyond the teaching of the elementary doctrines of Christ, and let us be borne along toward what is mature. Let us not be continually laying again a foundation of repentance from dead works,
B058C006V002	58	6	2	of faith in God, of the teaching regarding ablutions and the laying on of hands, of the resurrection of the dead, and of eternal judgment.
B058C006V003	58	6	3	And this we will do, if God permit.
B058C006V004	58	6	4	For in the case of those who have been once for all enlightened and have tasted of the heavenly gift,
B058C006V005	58	6	5	and become partakers of the Holy Spirit, and tasted the good word of God, and the powers of the Future Age,
B058C006V006	58	6	6	and then fallen away, it is impossible to renew them again unto repentance. For they repeatedly crucify to themselves the Son of God afresh, and expose him to an open shame.
B058C006V007	58	6	7	For land that has drunk the showers that now and again fall upon it,  and produced vegetation useful for those for whom it was tilled,  receives a blessing from God;
B058C006V008	58	6	8	but if it produces thorns and thistles, it is considered worthless,  and is in danger of being cursed, and its end will be to be burned.
B058C006V009	58	6	9	But though we thus speak, we are persuaded better things of you,  beloved, and things that accompany salvation.
B058C006V010	58	6	10	For God is not unjust; he will not forget your work and the love you showed for his cause, in sending help to your fellow Christians, as you are still doing.
B058C006V011	58	6	11	but I am longing that each of you continue to show the same diligence to realize the fulness of your hope, even to the end.
B058C006V012	58	6	12	Then do not become slack, but be imitators of those who through faith and patience are inheriting the promises.
B058C006V013	58	6	13	For when God make the promise to Abraham, since he could swear by none greater, he swore by himself, saying.
B058C006V014	58	6	14	Surely I will bless you, and bless you; I will increase you, and increase you.
B058C006V015	58	6	15	And so by patiently waiting, Abraham obtained the promise.
B058C006V016	58	6	16	I am referring to the oath because men swear by what is greater than themselves, and in every dispute of theirs the oath is final for confirmation.
B058C006V017	58	6	17	On which principle God, wishing to show more convincingly to the heirs of the promise the immutability of his purpose, mediated with an oath;
B058C006V018	58	6	18	that by means of two immutable things - his promise and his oath - in which it is impossible for God to break faith, we refugees may have strong encouragement to grasp the hope set before us.
B058C006V019	58	6	19	This hope we have as an anchor of the soul, secure and strong, and passing into the sanctuary which is beyond the veil;
B058C006V020	58	6	20	whither Jesus himself is entered as a forerunner on our behalf,  having become a priest forever, after the order of Melchisedek.
B058C007V001	58	7	1	It was this Melchisedek, King of Salem and Priest of the Most High God, who met Abraham returning from the slaughter of the kings and blessed him;
B058C007V002	58	7	2	and it was to him that Abraham apportioned a tithe of all the spoil.  He was first, as his name signifies, King of righteousness, and then King of Salem, that is, King of Peace;
B058C007V003	58	7	3	without father or mother, without lineage, having neither beginning of days nor end of life, but resembling the Son of God, he remains a priest in perpetuity.
B058C007V004	58	7	4	But observe how great this man was, to whom even Abraham, the Patriarch, gave a tenth part of the spoils.
B058C007V005	58	7	5	Now those of the sons of Levi who are appointed to the priesthood,  are authorized by the Law to take tithes of the people, that is, of their brothers, and that too, although these are descended from Abraham.
B058C007V006	58	7	6	But this man who had no Levitical genealogy actually took tithes of Abraham, and blessed him to whom the promises belong.
B058C007V007	58	7	7	Now it is beyond all controversy that the inferior is always blessed by the superior.
B058C007V008	58	7	8	Again it is mortal men who receive tithes in the one case; while in the other it is he of whom it is attested, "He lives."
B058C007V009	58	7	9	And even Levi, who is the receiver of tithes, so to speak, paid tithes through Abraham;
B058C007V010	58	7	10	for Levi was yet in the loins of his father, when Melchisedek met Abraham.
B058C007V011	58	7	11	Now if there were perfection through the Levitical priesthood, (and it was under it that the people received the Law) why was it still necessary for another kind of priest to arise, after the order of Melchisedek, instead of being reckoned according to the order of Aaron?
B058C007V012	58	7	12	For when the priesthood changes, of necessity the law also changes.
B058C007V013	58	7	13	He who is thus described belonged to another tribe, not one member of which has ever served at the altar.
B058C007V014	58	7	14	For it is evident that our Lord was descended from Judah, a tribe of which Moses said nothing concerning the priesthood.
B058C007V015	58	7	15	And this is yet more abundantly clear if, after the likeness of Melchisedek, there arises another Priest,
B058C007V016	58	7	16	who has become such, not according to the law of a transitory enactment, but according to the energy of an indissoluble life.
B058C007V017	58	7	17	For the words are in evidence, Thou art a priest forever after the order of Melchisedek.
B058C007V018	58	7	18	For there is a setting aside of a foregoing commandment, because of its weakness and unprofitableness
B058C007V019	58	7	19	(for the Law brought nothing to perfection); and there is the bringing in of a better hope by which we draw near to God;
B058C007V020	58	7	20	mightier because it was not promised apart from an oath.
B058C007V021	58	7	21	For although those priests became such without an oath, He had an oath form God who said to him, The Lord hath sworn and will not change, Thou art a priest forever.
B058C007V022	58	7	22	And by so much Jesus becomes the guarantor of a better covenant.
B058C007V023	58	7	23	And they indeed have been made priests, many in number, because they have been prevented by death from continuing;
B058C007V024	58	7	24	but he, because of his abiding forever, holds his priesthood inviolable.
B058C007V025	58	7	25	Hence also he is able to continue saving to the uttermost those who are ever drawing near to God through him, seeing that he is ever living to intercede for them.
B058C007V026	58	7	26	For we needed just such a high priest, holy, innocent, undefiled,  separated from sinners, and exalted above the heavens;
B058C007V027	58	7	27	one who has no need, like the high priests, to offer up daily sacrifices, first for his own sins, then for those of the people. For his sacrifice was made once for all, when he offered up himself.
B058C007V028	58	7	28	For the Law appoints human beings to be high priests, men with all their weakness; but the word of the oath, which was later than the Law, appoints a Son, perfected forevermore.
B058C008V001	58	8	1	The pith of all that we have been saying is this; we do have such a High Priest; and he has taken his seat on the right hand of the throne of Majesty in the heavens,
B058C008V002	58	8	2	a minister of the sanctuary and of the true tabernacle, which the Lord pitched, not man.
B058C008V003	58	8	3	For every high priest is appointed to offer both gifts and sacrifices; whence it follows that this High Priest also must have some offering to make.
B058C008V004	58	8	4	Now were he on earth, he would not even be a priest, since there are here those who present the gifts according to the Law -
B058C008V005	58	8	5	those priests who serve a mere outline and shadow of the heavenly reality, just as Moses was divinely instructed when he was about to build the Tabernacle. "See", he says, "that you make everything on the pattern showed you on the mountain."
B058C008V006	58	8	6	But Jesus has obtained a better ministry, by so much as he is also Mediator of a better covenant, which has been enacted upon better promises.
B058C008V007	58	8	7	For if the first covenant had been faultless, there would have been no need for a second.
B058C008V008	58	8	8	But finding fault with them, He says. "There are days coming," says the Lord, "When I will establish with the house of Israel and with the house of Judah a new covenant;
B058C008V009	58	8	9	Not according tot he covenant which I made with their forefathers,  On the day when I took them by the hand to lead them forth out of the land of Egypt; For they did not continue in my covenant, And therefore I disregarded them," says the Lord.
B058C008V010	58	8	10	"For this is the covenant which I will covenant with the house of Israel, After these days," says the Lord; "I will put my laws into their minds, And upon their hearts will I write them; And I will be their God, And they shall be my people;
B058C008V011	58	8	11	And they shall not teach every man his fellow citizen, And every man his brother, saying, Know the Lord; For all shall know me, From the least to the greatest of them.
B058C008V012	58	8	12	For I will have mercy upon their wrong-doings, And their sins I will remember no more."
B058C008V013	58	8	13	By calling the covenant "new," He has made the first one obsolete;  and whatever is becoming obsolete and aged, is near to vanishing.
B058C009V001	58	9	1	Now even the first covenant had its ordinances of public worship,  and its sanctuary, a material one.
B058C009V002	58	9	2	For a tent was built, the outer one called the Holy Place, in which were the lamp and the table and the loaves of the Presence;
B058C009V003	58	9	3	and behind the second veil was the tent called the Holy of Holies.
B058C009V004	58	9	4	In it was the golden altar of incense, and also the Ark of the Covenant covered all over with gold, in which was a golden pot holding the manna, and Aarons rod that budded, and the tables of the covenant;
B058C009V005	58	9	5	while above it, overshadowing the mercy-seat, were the cherubim of glory. But I must not speak about these in detail.
B058C009V006	58	9	6	Such then were the arrangements. Into the outer tent the priests enter continually in the performance of their duties;
B058C009V007	58	9	7	but into the inner tent the high priest only goes alone, once a year, and that not without blood, which he offers for himself and for the ignorances of the people.
B058C009V008	58	9	8	The Holy Spirit teaching by this that the way into the Holiest has not yet been disclosed while the first tent is still standing.
B058C009V009	58	9	9	This is a parable, for the present time, according to which gifts and sacrifices are offered that are not able, as far as conscience is concerned, to perfect the worshiper;
B058C009V010	58	9	10	since they consist only in meats and drinks and various ablutions,  carnal ordinances, imposed until the time of reformation.
B058C009V011	58	9	11	But when Christ came, a High Priest of good things to come, he passed through the greater and more perfect tent not made with hands,  that is to say, not of this material creation,
B058C009V012	58	9	12	not taking the blood of goats and oxen, but his own blood, and entered once for all into the Holy Place, obtaining for us an eternal redemption.
B058C009V013	58	9	13	For if the blood of bulls and goats and the ashes of a heifer sprinkled on those who have been defiled, sanctify to the cleansing of the flesh,
B058C009V014	58	9	14	how much more shall the blood of Christ, who through his eternal spirit offered himself free from blemish to God, cleanse your conscience from dead works unto the service of an ever-living God!
B058C009V015	58	9	15	And because of this he is the Mediator of a new testament, in order that, since a death has taken place to atone for offenses committed under the first testament, those who have been called may receive the promise of the eternal inheritance.
B058C009V016	58	9	16	For where there is a testament, there must also be brought forward in evidence the death of the testator.
B058C009V017	58	9	17	For a testament is only of force in case of the dead, being never valid so long as the testator lives.
B058C009V018	58	9	18	Accordingly we find that not without blood was the first testament enacted.
B058C009V019	58	9	19	For after every commandment according to the law had been spoken by Moses to the people, he took the blood of calves and goats, and scarlet wool and hyssop, and sprinkled both the book itself and all the people.
B058C009V020	58	9	20	saying, This is the blood of that testament which God commanded in regard to you.
B058C009V021	58	9	21	Moreover the tabernacle and all the vessels of service he sprinkled likewise, and indeed, according to the Law,
B058C009V022	58	9	22	almost everything is purified by blood, and without the shedding of blood there is no remission of sins.
B058C009V023	58	9	23	While, then, it was necessary that the copies of the heavenly things should be cleansed by such sacrifices, the heavenly things themselves required nobler sacrifices than these.
B058C009V024	58	9	24	For it was not into a Sanctuary made by hands, a mere type of the reality, that Christ entered, but he entered into heaven itself, now to appear in the very presence of God on our behalf.
B058C009V025	58	9	25	Nor did he enter to offer himself repeatedly, as the high priest entered into the sanctuary, year after year, with blood that was not his own; (for in that case he would have needed to suffer repeatedly,  ever since the foundation of the world;)but now, once for all, at the end of the ages, he has appeared to abolish sin, but the offering of himself.
B058C009V027	58	9	27	And since it is appointed to men once to die, and after that the judgment;
B058C009V028	58	9	28	so also the Christ, after being once for all offered to bear the sins of many, will appear a second time, without sin, to those who wait for him for salvation.
B058C010V001	58	10	1	For the Law, being only a shadow of the good things to come, and not their very substance, its priests cannot with the same sacrifice which year after year they offer continually, make perfect those who draw near.
B058C010V002	58	10	2	Otherwise would they not have ceased to be offered? Because the worshippers having been once cleansed, would have had no more consciousness of sin.
B058C010V003	58	10	3	But on the other hand, in these sacrifices sins are called to memory, year after year.
B058C010V004	58	10	4	For it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sin.
B058C010V005	58	10	5	It is for this reason that the Christ, on coming into the world,  declared. Sacrifice and offerings thou dost not desire, But a body didst thou prepare for me;
B058C010V006	58	10	6	In whole burnt offerings and sin offerings Thou hast taken no pleasure.
B058C010V007	58	10	7	Then I said, "I am come - in the roll of the book it is written of me-  -To do thy will, O God."
B058C010V008	58	10	8	First when it is said, Thou hast no longing for, thou takest no delight in Sacrifices and offerings, or whole burnt offerings and sin offerings,
B058C010V009	58	10	9	(offerings regularly made under the law), and then it is added, Lo,  I come to do thy will, he does away with the first, in order that he may establish the second.
B058C010V010	58	10	10	And it is by this will that we have been sanctified by the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all.
B058C010V011	58	10	11	For while every priest stands, day after day, at his ministrations,  and many times repeats the same sacrifices, which can never take away sins,
B058C010V012	58	10	12	this Priest, after offering one Sacrifice for sins, sat down forever on Gods right hand;
B058C010V013	58	10	13	henceforth waiting until his enemies be put as the footstool of his feet.
B058C010V014	58	10	14	For by one single offering he has perfected forever those whom he is sanctifying.
B058C010V015	58	10	15	And the Holy Spirit also gives his testimony, when he said.
B058C010V016	58	10	16	"This is the covenant I will make with them After those days," says the Lord. "I will set my laws upon their hearts, And I will inscribe them on their minds."
B058C010V017	58	10	17	Then he adds, And their sins and their iniquities will I remember no more.
B058C010V018	58	10	18	But when these have been remitted, there is no more any offering for sin.
B058C010V019	58	10	19	Since, then, we have a cheerful confidence, brothers, to enter into the Holiest by the blood of Jesus,
B058C010V020	58	10	20	by the way which he dedicated for us, that new and living way,  through the veil (that is, his flesh);
B058C010V021	58	10	21	and since we have a great High Priest over the house of God;
B058C010V022	58	10	22	let us draw near with a true heart, in full assurance of faith, our hearts sprinkled from and evil conscience, and our bodies bathed in pure water.
B058C010V023	58	10	23	Let us hold fast the confession of our hope, unwavering (for He is faithful who promised);
B058C010V024	58	10	24	and let us consider one another, to provoke unto love and good works;
B058C010V025	58	10	25	not forsaking the assembling of ourselves together, as is the custom of some, but exhorting one another; all the more as you behold the Day drawing near.
B058C010V026	58	10	26	For if we sin wilfully, after we have received the knowledge of the truth, there no longer remains any other sacrifice for sins,
B058C010V027	58	10	27	but a certain fearful expectation of judgment, and a fiery indignation which is about to devour the adversaries.
B058C010V028	58	10	28	Any one who set at naught the law of Moses was put to death without pity, on the testimony of two or three witnesses.
B058C010V029	58	10	29	How much surer, think you, will be the punishment of one who has trodden under foot the Son of God, and has profaned that covenant blood with which he was sanctified, and has done despite to the spirit of grace?
B058C010V030	58	10	30	For we know Him who said, Vengeance is mine, I will repay, and again, The Lord will judge his people.
B058C010V031	58	10	31	IT IS A FEARFUL THING TO FALL INTO THE HANDS OF THE LIVING GOD!
B058C010V032	58	10	32	But ever call to mind the former days, in which, after having been enlightened, you endured a great conflict of sufferings;
B058C010V033	58	10	33	partly by being made a public spectacle in reproaches and afflictions, and partly by sharing the fortunes of those that were so used.
B058C010V034	58	10	34	For you did sympathize with the prisoners, and you did take joyfully the confiscation of your goods; conscious that you had for yourselves greater, even lasting possessions.
B058C010V035	58	10	35	Now do not fling away your bold confidence, for it has a great recompense of reward.
B058C010V036	58	10	36	For you need stedfastness, so that after having done the will of God, you may receive the promise,
B058C010V037	58	10	37	For yet a very, very little while, and then The Coming One will have come, without delay.
B058C010V038	58	10	38	But it is by faith that my Righteous One will live, And if he draws back, my soul takes no pleasure in him.
B058C010V039	58	10	39	"But we are not of defections unto perdition, but of faith unto the gaining of the soul."
B058C011V001	58	11	1	Now faith is the title-deed of things hoped for; the putting to the proof of things not seen.
B058C011V002	58	11	2	For by it men of old times had witness borne to them.
B058C011V003	58	11	3	By faith we understand that the world was fashioned by the Word of God, so that what we see was not made out of what is visible.
B058C011V004	58	11	4	By faith Abel offered to God a sacrifice more acceptable than that of Cain, through which he had witness borne to him that he was righteous, God giving the testimony by accepting his gifts; and through it he, although he is dead, still speaks.
B058C011V005	58	11	5	By faith Enoch was translated so that he should not see death; and he was not found, because God had translated him. Before his translation he had witness borne to him that he pleased God.
B058C011V006	58	11	6	now without faith it is impossible to please him; for he who comes to God must believe that he is, and that he ever rewards those who are seeking.
B058C011V007	58	11	7	By faith Noah, warned of God of things not yet seen, reverently gave heed, and built an ark for the saving of his house; by which he condemned the world, and became an heir of the righteousness which is of faith.
B058C011V008	58	11	8	By faith Abraham obeyed when he was called to go out unto a place which he was to receive for an inheritance; and he went out, not knowing whither he went.
B058C011V009	58	11	9	It was by faith that he sojourned in the promised land as an alien,  living in tents with Isaac and Jacob, his fellow heirs of the same promise.
B058C011V010	58	11	10	For he continually looked for the city which has foundations, whose builder and maker is God.
B058C011V011	58	11	11	By faith even Sarah herself received power to conceive seed,  although she was past the age for child-bearing, because she counted Him faithful who had promised;
B058C011V012	58	11	12	and thus there sprang from one man, and him practically dead, a nation like the stars in the heavens in multitude, or grains of sand upon the seashore, innumerable.
B058C011V013	58	11	13	These all died in faith, not having yet received the promises; nay,  but they saw them from afar, and hailed them, and confessed that they were strangers and pilgrims on the earth.
B058C011V014	58	11	14	For those who say such things make it plain that they are seeking a Fatherland.
B058C011V015	58	11	15	And if they had cherished the memory of that land from which they went out, they would have found an opportunity to return;
B058C011V016	58	11	16	but now they are longing for a better homeland, that is, a heavenly.  Therefore God is not ashamed to be called their God; and he has prepared a city for them.
B058C011V017	58	11	17	By faith Abraham, when he was put to the test, was on the point of offering up Isaac; yes, he who had received the promise was about to offer up his only son,
B058C011V018	58	11	18	of whom it had been said, It is through Isaac that your posterity will be traced.
B058C011V019	58	11	19	For he accounted God able even to raise from the dead, from whence,  figuratively speaking, he did indeed receive him back again.
B058C011V020	58	11	20	By faith Isaac blessed Jacob and Esau, even concerning things to come.
B058C011V021	58	11	21	By faith Jacob, when he was dying, blessed each of Josephs sons,  and worshiped, leaning on the top of his staff.
B058C011V022	58	11	22	By faith Joseph, when his end was nigh, made mention of the exodus of the children of Israel, and gave instructions in regard to his bones.
B058C011V023	58	11	23	By faith Moses, when he was born, was hid three months by his parents, because they saw that he was a beautiful child, and they were not afraid of the kings decree.
B058C011V024	58	11	24	By faith Moses, when he was grown up, refused to be called the son of Pharaohs daughter,
B058C011V025	58	11	25	choosing rather to share ill-treatment with the people of God, than to enjoy the pleasures of sin for a season.
B058C011V026	58	11	26	He accounted the obloquy of Christ to be greater than the treasures of Egypt; for he fixed his eyes on the reward.
B058C011V027	58	11	27	By faith he left Egypt, not because he feared the wrath of the king,  but he endured as seeing Him who is invisible.
B058C011V028	58	11	28	By faith he established the Passover, and the sprinkling with blood,  in order that the Destroying Angel might not touch the firstborn.
B058C011V029	58	11	29	By faith the people crossed over the Red Sea as on dry land; and when the Egyptians tried to do this they were swallowed up.
B058C011V030	58	11	30	By faith the walls of Jericho fell down after they had been encircled seven days.
B058C011V031	58	11	31	By faith Rahab, the harlot, perished not with the disobedient,  because she had received the spies in peace.
B058C011V032	58	11	32	And what more shall I say? for time would fail me to tell of Gideon,  of Barak, of Samson, and of Jeptha; of David and Samuel and the prophets,
B058C011V033	58	11	33	who through faith conquered kingdoms, wrought righteousness,  obtained promises, stopped the mouths of lions,
B058C011V034	58	11	34	quenched the power of fire, escaped the edge of the sword, out of weakness were made strong, proved valiant in warfare, and routed armies of aliens.
B058C011V035	58	11	35	Woman received their dear ones alive from the dead; and others were broken on the wheel, not accepting the offered deliverance, in order that they might obtain a better resurrection.
B058C011V036	58	11	36	Others again bore trial of mockings and scourgings, yes, even of chains and imprisonment.
B058C011V037	58	11	37	They were stoned, they were sawn asunder, they were tempted, they were slain with the sword, they wandered about in sheepskins and goatskins, being destitute, persecuted, tormented -
B058C011V038	58	11	38	of whom the world was not worthy - wandering in deserts and mountains and caves and holes in the ground.
B058C011V039	58	11	39	Yet, though these all had witness borne to them by their faith, they received not the promise;
B058C011V040	58	11	40	since it was for us that God had in store some better thing, so that apart from us they should not be perfected.
B058C012V001	58	12	1	Seeing then that we are encircled with this great cloud of witnesses, let us also lay aside every weight, and the sin that clings about us. Let us run with patience the race that is set before us,
B058C012V002	58	12	2	looking unto Jesus, the pioneer and perfecter of our faith, who for the joy that was set before him endured a cross, despising shame, and has now taken his seat at the right hand of the throne of God.
B058C012V003	58	12	3	Compare yourselves with him who endured such hostility against himself at the hands of sinners, lest you grow weary, fainting in your souls.
B058C012V004	58	12	4	Not yet have you resisted unto blood in your fight against sin;
B058C012V005	58	12	5	and have you forgotten the exhortation which reasons with you as sons? My son, do not despise the training of the Lord, Nor faint when he corrects you;
B058C012V006	58	12	6	For it is those whom he loves that he disciplines, And he scourges every son whom he acknowledges.
B058C012V007	58	12	7	It is for discipline that you are enduring these sufferings. God is dealing with you as sons. For what son is there whom his father does not discipline?
B058C012V008	58	12	8	If you are left without discipline, in which all children share,  then are you bastards and not sons.
B058C012V009	58	12	9	Furthermore, our earthly fathers used to discipline us, and we gave them reverence. Shall we not much rather be in subjection to the Father of spirits, and live?
B058C012V010	58	12	10	For they only disciplined us for a few days, as seemed good to them;  but he does it for our profit, that we may share his holiness.
B058C012V011	58	12	11	Now no discipline seems for the present to be joyous, but grievous;  but afterward it yields the peaceable fruits of righteousness to those who have been trained under it.
B058C012V012	58	12	12	Wherefore lift up your listless hands, strengthen your feeble knees;
B058C012V013	58	12	13	make straight path for your feet, so that what is lame may not be put out of joint, but rather be healed.
B058C012V014	58	12	14	Run swiftly after peace with all men, and holiness, without which no man shall see the Lord.
B058C012V015	58	12	15	Look carefully that there be no one who falls back from the grace of God; that no root of bitterness springs up to trouble you, and by its means many become defiled.
B058C012V016	58	12	16	Take care lest there be any fornicator or scorner like Esau among you, who for one meal sold his birthright.
B058C012V017	58	12	17	For you know that even when he afterward desired to inherit the blessing, he was rejected; he found no room for repentance, though he sought it earnestly, with tears.
B058C012V018	58	12	18	For you are not come to a palpable and enkindled fire,
B058C012V019	58	12	19	nor to gloom and darkness and tempest and the blare of a trumpet and an audible voice. Those who heard that voice entreated that no word more should be spoken to them.
B058C012V020	58	12	20	For they could not endure that which was enjoined, Even if a wild beast touches the mountain it shall be stoned to death;
B058C012V021	58	12	21	and so terrible was the scene that Moses said, I exceedingly fear and tremble.
B058C012V022	58	12	22	On the contrary you are come to Mount Zion, the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem, to innumerable hosts of angels,
B058C012V023	58	12	23	to the festal assemblage and church of the firstborn, registered in heaven, to a Judge who is God of all, to the spirits of just men made perfect,
B058C012V024	58	12	24	to Jesus the Mediator of the New Covenant, and to his sprinkled Blood whose message cries louder than that of Abel.
B058C012V025	58	12	25	See that you do not refuse him who is speaking. For if they did not escape punishment when they refused to listen to their instructor on earth, much less shall we escape if we turn away from him who is teaching us from heaven;
B058C012V026	58	12	26	whose voice then shook the earth, but now he has promised, saying,  Once again, once for all, I make not only earth, but heaven also to tremble.
B058C012V027	58	12	27	That phrase, "Once again," signifies the removal of the things which can be shaken, created things, in order that the things which cannot be shaken may remain.
B058C012V028	58	12	28	Wherefore since we are receiving a kingdom which is unshakable, let us give thanks, and so offer acceptable worship to God, with holy awe and fear,
B058C012V029	58	12	29	FOR INDEED OUR GOD IS A CONSUMING FIRE.
B058C013V001	58	13	1	Let brotherly love continue.
B058C013V002	58	13	2	Do not neglect to show hospitality; for by it some have even entertained angels unawares.
B058C013V003	58	13	3	Remember those who are in prison, as if you were fellow prisoners;  remember too, those who are being ill-treated, since you too, are in the body.
B058C013V004	58	13	4	Let marriage be held in honor by all, and the marriage bed be undefiled; for fornicators and adulterers will God judge.
B058C013V005	58	13	5	Let your life be untainted by love of money; be content with such things as you have; for God himself has said, I will never leave thee; I will never forsake thee.
B058C013V006	58	13	6	So that we can say with confidence, The Lord is my helper; I will not be afraid. What can man do to me?
B058C013V007	58	13	7	Remember your leaders, the men who spoke the message of God to you;  consider the issue of their lives, and imitate their faith.
B058C013V008	58	13	8	Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today, and forever.
B058C013V009	58	13	9	Do not allow yourselves to be swept away by various and strange teachings. For it is a beautiful thing to be established in heart by grace, and not by regulations regarding food, from which those that occupied themselves with them have derived no benefit.
B058C013V010	58	13	10	We Christians have an altar from which those have no right to eat who minister in the Tabernacle.
B058C013V011	58	13	11	For the bodies of the animals whose blood is carried by the High Priest into the Holy Place are burned outside the camp,
B058C013V012	58	13	12	and so Jesus suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people by his own blood.
B058C013V013	58	13	13	Let us then go forth to him outside the camp, bearing his reproach.
B058C013V014	58	13	14	For we have not here an abiding city, but we are earnestly seeking the city that is to be.
B058C013V015	58	13	15	In his name, then, let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God, that is the fruit of lips that confess his name.
B058C013V016	58	13	16	And forget not to be kind and liberal; for with that sort of sacrifice God is well pleased.
B058C013V017	58	13	17	Obey your leaders and submit to them; for they are keeping watch over your souls, as those who must give account; that they may do thus with joy and not with lamentation, for this would be unprofitable to you.
B058C013V018	58	13	18	Keep on praying for me. I am persuaded that I have a clear conscience, and I desire in every way to live nobly.
B058C013V019	58	13	19	I the more earnestly ask for your prayers, that I may be the more speedily restored to you.
B058C013V020	58	13	20	Now the God of peace, who brought up from the dead our Lord Jesus,  that great Shepherd of the sheep, by the blood of an eternal covenant,
B058C013V021	58	13	21	equip you in every good deed for the doing of his will, doing in you what is well-pleasing in his sight, through Jesus Christ. To him be the glory unto the ages of the ages! Amen!
B058C013V022	58	13	22	But I entreat you, brothers, bear with my word of exhortation, for I have written to you briefly.
B058C013V023	58	13	23	You know that our brother Timothy has been set free. If he comes soon, I will see him with you.
B058C013V024	58	13	24	Salute all your leaders and the saints. The brothers from Italy send you greeting.
B058C013V025	58	13	25	Grace be with you all, Amen.
B059C001V001	59	1	1	James, a slave of God and of the Lord Jesus Christ, sends greeting to the twelve tribes that are scattered abroad.
B059C001V002	59	1	2	My brothers, when you are beset by various temptations, count it all joy,
B059C001V003	59	1	3	because you know that the testing of your faith is working out endurance.
B059C001V004	59	1	4	But let endurance have its perfect work, so that you may be perfect and entire, not lacking in anything.
B059C001V005	59	1	5	If any one of you is lacking in wisdom, let him ask it from the God who gives to all men freely and without upbraiding; and it will be given to him.
B059C001V006	59	1	6	But let him ask in faith, without wavering; for he who wavers is like a surge of the sea, wind-driven and tossed.
B059C001V007	59	1	7	Such a man need not suppose that he will receive anything from the Lord,
B059C001V008	59	1	8	double-minded as he is, unstable at every turn.
B059C001V009	59	1	9	Let a brother in humble circumstances glory in his exaltation;
B059C001V010	59	1	10	but a rich brother, in his humiliation; because like the flower of the grass the rich man will pass away.
B059C001V011	59	1	11	For as the sun comes up with a burning heat, it withers the grass,  and its flowers fall, and the grace of the fashion of it perishes; so also shall the rich man fade away amid his pursuits.
B059C001V012	59	1	12	Blessed is the man who endures temptation; for when he has stood the test he will receive the crown of life which the Lord has promised to those who love him.
B059C001V013	59	1	13	When he is being tempted, let no one say, "It is God who tempts me,"  for God cannot be tempted with evil, nor does he tempt any man.
B059C001V014	59	1	14	But each man is tempted by his own lusts that allure and entice him.
B059C001V015	59	1	15	Then lust conceives and gives birth to sin; and sin, when it is mature, brings forth death.
B059C001V016	59	1	16	Do not be deceived, my brothers!
B059C001V017	59	1	17	Every good gift and every perfect boon is from above, and is ever coming down to us from the Father of the heavenly lights, with whom is no variation nor shadow of eclipse.
B059C001V018	59	1	18	Because he willed, he gave us birth through the word of truth, so that we should be a kind of first-fruits among his creatures.
B059C001V019	59	1	19	Mark this well, my dear brothers. Let every man be swift in hearing, slow in speaking, slow in growing angry;
B059C001V020	59	1	20	for a mans anger does not further the righteous purpose of God.
B059C001V021	59	1	21	So strip off all filthiness and superfluity of wickedness, and in meekness receive the implanted Word, which is able to save your souls.
B059C001V022	59	1	22	And become doers of the Word, and not merely hearers, deceiving yourselves.
B059C001V023	59	1	23	Because if any one is a hearer of the Word and not a doer, he is like a man who looks at his natural face in a mirror;
B059C001V024	59	1	24	for after he has looked carefully at himself, he goes away, and at once forgets what he is like.
B059C001V025	59	1	25	But the man who looks closely into the perfect law - the law of liberty - and continues looking, this man will be blessed in his deed because he is not a hearer who forgets, but a doer who does.
B059C001V026	59	1	26	If a man thinks himself to be religious, and yet does not bridle his tongue, but deceives his own religion,
B059C001V027	59	1	27	and undefiled before our God and Father, to look after orphans and widows in their affliction, and ever to keep himself unspotted from the world.
B059C002V001	59	2	1	My brothers, do not hold the faith of the Lord Jesus, the Lord of Glory, in a spirit of caste.
B059C002V002	59	2	2	Suppose a man comes into your synagogue with a gold ring and dazzling clothes, and suppose a poor man comes in, also, in shabby clothes,
B059C002V003	59	2	3	and you look up to him who wears the fine clothing, and say to him,  "Sit here in this fine place!" and to the poor man you say, "Stand there!" or "Sit on the floor at my feet!"
B059C002V004	59	2	4	are you not drawing distinctions among yourselves, and have you not become judges with evil thoughts?
B059C002V005	59	2	5	Listen, my dear brothers, has not God chosen the poor of this world to be rich in faith, and to inherit the kingdom which he has promised to those who love him?
B059C002V006	59	2	6	But you have dishonored the poor man. Do not the rich oppress you and drag you to court?
B059C002V007	59	2	7	Are they not blaspheming that glorious Name by which you are called?
B059C002V008	59	2	8	If you are keeping the royal law, which says, Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thou dost thyself, you are doing well.
B059C002V009	59	2	9	If you have the spirit of caste you are committing sin, and are convicted by the Law as transgressors.
B059C002V010	59	2	10	For if a man keeps the whole of the Law, and yet stumbles in one point, he is guilty of all.
B059C002V011	59	2	11	For he who said, Do not commit adultery, said also, Do not Kill. Now if you do not commit adultery, but if you do kill, you have transgressed the Law.
B059C002V012	59	2	12	So speak and act like men who are to be judged by the law of liberty.
B059C002V013	59	2	13	For judgment is without mercy to the man who has showed no mercy.  but mercy glories in the face of judgment.
B059C002V014	59	2	14	My brothers, what good is it if any one says that he has faith, if he has no deeds? Can such faith save him?
B059C002V015	59	2	15	If a brother or sister be naked and in need of daily food,
B059C002V016	59	2	16	and one of you says to them, "Depart in peace, find warmth and food for yourselves," but at the same time you do not give the necessaries of the body, what good would that do them?
B059C002V017	59	2	17	In just the same way faith, if it have not deeds, is by itself a lifeless thing.
B059C002V018	59	2	18	Some one indeed may say, "You have faith, and I have deeds." "Then show me your faith," I answer, "apart from any deeds, and I will show you my faith by my deeds."
B059C002V019	59	2	19	You believe that God is one? You do well; even the demons believe,  and they shudder.
B059C002V020	59	2	20	But do you want to be convinced, O foolish man, that faith apart from deeds is barren?
B059C002V021	59	2	21	Was not Abraham our ancestor justified by deeds, in that he offered up Isaac, his son, upon the altar?
B059C002V022	59	2	22	You see how faith was cooperating with deeds, and faith was made perfect by deeds.
B059C002V023	59	2	23	And the Scripture was fulfilled which said, And Abraham believed God, and this was imputed to him as righteousness, and he was called Gods friend.
B059C002V024	59	2	24	You see, then, that it is by his deeds a man is justified, and not simply by his faith.
B059C002V025	59	2	25	In like manner was not Rahab, the harlot, justified by her deeds, in the fact that she received the messengers and sent them forth by another way?
B059C002V026	59	2	26	So just as the body without a spirit is dead, so faith is dead without deeds.
B059C003V001	59	3	1	Do not become many teachers, my brothers, because you know well that we teachers shall be judged by a severer standard than others.
B059C003V002	59	3	2	For in many respects we often stumble. If any man never stumbles in speech, the same is a perfect man, able to bridle the whole body as well.
B059C003V003	59	3	3	When we put bits in the mouths of horses to make them obey us, we control their whole body also.
B059C003V004	59	3	4	Look at the ships too, though they are so large, even when driven by fierce winds they are turned by a very small rudder, wherever the impulse of the helmsman wills.
B059C003V005	59	3	5	So also the tongue is a small member and makes great boasts. Behold,  how great a forest is set on fire by a little spark!
B059C003V006	59	3	6	And the tongue is a fire; it is a very world of iniquity among our members, defiling the whole body, and setting on fire the wheel of nature, and is itself set on fire by hell.
B059C003V007	59	3	7	For while every kind of beast and bird, and of reptiles and sea-  creatures are tamable, and actually have been tamed by mankind,
B059C003V008	59	3	8	no man can tame the tongue, restless evil that it is, full of deadly poison.
B059C003V009	59	3	9	With it we continually bless our Lord and Father, and with it we are accustomed to curse men made in the image of God.
B059C003V010	59	3	10	From out of the same mouth pour forth blessings and cursings! My brothers, this ought not to be so.
B059C003V011	59	3	11	Does a spring pour forth from the same opening sweet water and bitter?
B059C003V012	59	3	12	Can a fig tree, my brothers, bear olives; or a grape-vine, figs? No more can salt water yield fresh water.
B059C003V013	59	3	13	Who among you is wise and intelligent? Let him show his deeds by his good life, in the meekness of wisdom.
B059C003V014	59	3	14	But if you have bitter jealousy and faction in your heart, do not be boasting of that, and be false to the truth.
B059C003V015	59	3	15	Such wisdom is not that which is descending from on high, but is earthly, sensual, demonlike.
B059C003V016	59	3	16	For wherever jealousy and faction exist, there is confusion and every evil deed.
B059C003V017	59	3	17	But the wisdom which comes from on high is first pure, then peaceable, gentle, conciliatory, overflowing with mercy and good fruits, without partiality and without insincerity.
B059C003V018	59	3	18	And the fruit of righteousness is being sown in peace by those who are working peace.
B059C004V001	59	4	1	Where do the conflicts and quarrels that go on among you come from?  Do they not come from your passions which are always making war among your bodily members?
B059C004V002	59	4	2	You continually crave and do not obtain; you are killing and coveting and cannot acquire; you are fighting and at war. You do not have, because you do not ask.
B059C004V003	59	4	3	You continue to ask and do not receive, because you are asking with a wrong purpose, in order to spend it upon your pleasures.
B059C004V004	59	4	4	You adulteresses, do you not know that the friendship of the world is enmity to God? Whoever, then, desires to be a friend of the world,  makes himself and enemy of God.
B059C004V005	59	4	5	Or do you suppose that it is in vain that the Scripture says, "The spirit which has its home in us yearns over us unto jealousy?"
B059C004V006	59	4	6	But he gives more and more grace. therefore it is said, God ever resists the proud; but to the humble he gives grace continually.
B059C004V007	59	4	7	So then ever be subject to God, Ever resist the devil and he will flee from you.
B059C004V008	59	4	8	Draw near to God And he will draw near to you. Cleanse your hands,  you sinners, And purify your hearts, you double-minded.
B059C004V009	59	4	9	Lament and mourn, and weep aloud! Let your laughter be turned into mourning, And your joy into gloom!
B059C004V010	59	4	10	Humble yourselves before the Lord, And he will raise you up.
B059C004V011	59	4	11	Do not be talking against each other, brothers. He who is talking against a brother and condemning his brothers is talking against the Law and condemning the Law. But if you are condemning the Law, you are not a doer of the Law, but a judge.
B059C004V012	59	4	12	But One is your Lawgiver and Judge - he who is able to save and to destroy. But you, who are you, to be condemning your neighbor?
B059C004V013	59	4	13	Go to now, you who say, "Today or tomorrow we shall journey to such a city and spend a year there, and trade and make money,"
B059C004V014	59	4	14	when all the time you do not know what will happen on the morrow.  For what is your life? You are but a mist, appearing for a brief time, and then vanishing.
B059C004V015	59	4	15	You ought instead to say, "If the Lord wills it, we shall live and do this or that."
B059C004V016	59	4	16	But now you are glorying in these insolent boastings of yours; all such glorying is evil.
B059C004V017	59	4	17	So to him who knows how to do right and does not do it, to him it is sin.
B059C005V001	59	5	1	Go to now, you rich men! Weep aloud, howl for the miseries which are about to come upon you!
B059C005V002	59	5	2	For your riches lie rotting, and your clothing has become moth-eaten.
B059C005V003	59	5	3	Your gold and silver are rusted. and their rust will be for a testimony against you, and it will eat your flesh. For you have been storing up fire in these last days!
B059C005V004	59	5	4	Look! the wages of the laborers who mowed your fields, which you have been keeping back by fraud, are crying aloud! And the cries of the reapers have entered into the ears of the Lord of Sabaoth!
B059C005V005	59	5	5	You have lived luxuriously on earth, you have taken your pleasure,  you have fattened your hearts for a day of slaughter.
B059C005V006	59	5	6	You have condemned, you have murdered the righteous man unresisting!
B059C005V007	59	5	7	Be patient, then, brothers, till the coming of the Lord. Behold the farmer who waits for the precious fruit of the earth, being patient over it, until it gets the early and the latter rains.
B059C005V008	59	5	8	So you also must be patient. Stablish your hearts; for the coming of the Lord is at hand!
B059C005V009	59	5	9	Do not make complaints against each other, brothers, lest you yourselves be condemned. Behold the Judge is standing before the very door!
B059C005V010	59	5	10	Take, my brothers, for an example the suffering and the patience of the prophets who spoke in the name of the Lord.
B059C005V011	59	5	11	Remember we count those that were stedfast happy. You have heard of the stedfastness of Job, and have seen the end of the Lord with him,  seen how the Lord is full of tenderness.
B059C005V012	59	5	12	Again, above all things, my brothers, swear not at all, neither by the heavens, nor by the earth, nor by any other oath. Let your "yes"  be "yes," and your "no," "no," so you will not fall under condemnation.
B059C005V013	59	5	13	Is any one of you in trouble? Let him pray.
B059C005V014	59	5	14	Is any in good spirits? Let him sing unto his harp. Is any one of you ill? Let him send for the elders of the church, and let them pray over him, after anointing him with oil in the name of the Lord;
B059C005V015	59	5	15	and the prayer of faith will restore the sick, and the Lord will raise him up. And if he has committed sins, it will be forgiven him.
B059C005V016	59	5	16	So confess your sins one to another, and pray for one another, that you may be healed. For the fervent prayer of a righteous man is mighty in its working.
B059C005V017	59	5	17	Elijah was a man of like passions with us, and he prayed again, and the sky gave rain, and the earth brought forth her fruit.
B059C005V018	59	5	18	Then he prayed again, and the sky gave rain, and the earth brought forth her fruit.
B059C005V019	59	5	19	My brothers, if any one of you strays from the truth, and some one brings him back,
B059C005V020	59	5	20	let him know that he who brings a sinner back from the error of his ways, saves his soul from death, and hides a multitude of sins.
B060C001V001	60	1	1	Peter, an apostle of Jesus Christ, to the elect who are sojourners of the dispersion in Pontus, Galatia, Cappadocia, Roman Asia, and Bithynia,
B060C001V002	60	1	2	according to the foreknowledge of God the Father, in the sanctification of the spirit, unto obedience and sprinkling of the blood of Jesus Christ; Grace and peace be multiplied to you.
B060C001V003	60	1	3	Blessed be the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ, by whose great mercy we have been born anew into a living hope, through the resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead;
B060C001V004	60	1	4	and into an inheritance imperishable and undefiled and fadeless,  which has been kept in heaven for you
B060C001V005	60	1	5	who, through faith, are continuously guarded by the power of God for a salvation, ready to be revealed in the last days.
B060C001V006	60	1	6	Exult in this, though now for a brief moment, if need be, you have suffered many hardships.
B060C001V007	60	1	7	These are in order that the test of your faith, more precious than gold that is perishable and yet is tested by fire, may redound to praise and glory and honor, at the revelation of Jesus Christ.
B060C001V008	60	1	8	Him you love, though you have never seen him; in him you ever believe, though even now you see him not, and you are rejoicing with joy unspeakable and full of glory,
B060C001V009	60	1	9	as you continually receive the reward of your faith, even the salvation of your souls.
B060C001V010	60	1	10	Concerning this salvation the Prophets who prophesied regarding the grace intended for you, diligently sought and searched.
B060C001V011	60	1	11	They were searching to know to what time, or to what manner of time the Spirit of Christ which was in them kept pointing, when he ever testified beforehand concerning the sufferings of Christ and the glories that would follow.
B060C001V012	60	1	12	It was revealed to them that it was not for themselves, but for you,  that they were ministering the truths which have now been announced to you, by those who preached the gospel to you, through the help of the Holy Spirit sent forth from heaven - truths into which angels long to look.
B060C001V013	60	1	13	So then brace up your minds, be steady in spirit, and fix your hope firmly in the grace that is coming to you, at the revelation of Jesus Christ.
B060C001V014	60	1	14	Like obedient children, do not fashion yourselves according to the former passions of your days of ignorance,
B060C001V015	60	1	15	but become yourselves holy in your whole manner of living, as He who has called you is holy,
B060C001V016	60	1	16	as the Scripture says, You shall be holy, because I am holy.
B060C001V017	60	1	17	And since you call upon him as Father, who impartially judges each one according to his deeds, pass the time of your sojourning here in reverence.
B060C001V018	60	1	18	For you well know that not with perishable things, with silver or gold, were you redeemed from the emptiness of your manner of life,  received by tradition from your ancestors;
B060C001V019	60	1	19	but with precious blood, like that of a lamb without spot or blemish, even the blood of Christ.
B060C001V020	60	1	20	He was indeed foreknown before the foundation of the world, but was manifested at the end of the times for your sake.
B060C001V021	60	1	21	Through him you believe in God who raised him from the dead and gave him glory; so that your faith and hope are now in God.
B060C001V022	60	1	22	Now that by obedience to the truth you have purified your lives for a brotherly love without hypocrisy, you must love one another from your hearts, fervently.
B060C001V023	60	1	23	For you have been born anew, not of perishable, but of imperishable seed, by the living, lasting word of God.
B060C001V024	60	1	24	For, All flesh is grass And all its glory like the flower of the grass. The grass fades, The flower falls,
B060C001V025	60	1	25	But the word of the Lord abides forever. And this is the word of the gospel which has been told to you.
B060C002V001	60	2	1	Therefore put away all malice, all deceit, insincerity, jealousy,  and slander of every sort.
B060C002V002	60	2	2	Like new-born babes long for the pure spiritual milk to make you grow up into salvation;
B060C002V003	60	2	3	since you have tasted that the Lord is gracious.
B060C002V004	60	2	4	Come to him then, that living Stone, rejected indeed by men, but chosen by God, and precious.
B060C002V005	60	2	5	And yourselves like living stones be built into a spiritual house,  to be a holy priesthood offering spiritual sacrifices, acceptable to God, through Christ Jesus.
B060C002V006	60	2	6	For, as Scripture says. Behold, I lay in Zion a chief corner-stone,  elect, precious, And he who believes on Him shall never be put to shame.
B060C002V007	60	2	7	For you, then, that believe, is the preciousness; but for those who do not believe, A stone which the builders rejected, The same has become the head stone of the corner,
B060C002V008	60	2	8	and, A stone of stumbling, and a rock of offense. They stumble over it because they are disobeying Gods word, and to this they were also appointed.
B060C002V009	60	2	9	But you are an elect race, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, a purchased people, that you may show forth the virtues of Him who has called you out of darkness into his marvelous light -
B060C002V010	60	2	10	you who once were not a people, but now are the people of God; who were once without mercy, but now you have found mercy.
B060C002V011	60	2	11	I beseech you, beloved, as pilgrims and exiles, to abstain from passions of the flesh that war upon your souls.
B060C002V012	60	2	12	Let your manner of life before the Gentiles be honest; so that,  although they are now slandering you as evil-doers, they may, by beholding your noble conduct, come to glorify God, in the day of visitation.
B060C002V013	60	2	13	Submit yourselves, for the Lords sake, to every human authority;  whether it be to the Emperor as supreme ruler,
B060C002V014	60	2	14	or to governors as sent by him for the punishment of evil-doers and for the encouragement of well-doers.
B060C002V015	60	2	15	For it is the will of God that by well-doing you should silence the ignorant talk of foolish men.
B060C002V016	60	2	16	Live like free men; and yet do not make your freedom a cloak for misconduct, but be the slaves of God.
B060C002V017	60	2	17	Honor all men. Love the brotherhood. Reverence God. Honor the Emperor.
B060C002V018	60	2	18	Household slaves, submit yourselves to your masters in all reverence; not only to the kind and gentle, but also to the unreasonable.
B060C002V019	60	2	19	For it is an acceptable thing to God, if from a sense of duty to him, a man endures a wrong, even suffering unjustly.
B060C002V020	60	2	20	For what credit is it if, when you are struck for a fault, you take it patiently? But if when you are doing well and suffer for it, you always take it patiently, this is acceptable with God.
B060C002V021	60	2	21	For this is your calling; because Christ also suffered for you,  leaving you an example, so that you should follow in his footsteps;
B060C002V022	60	2	22	He committed no sin, Neither was guile found in his mouth.
B060C002V023	60	2	23	He was reviled, and reviled not back. When he suffered he never threatened but always committed his cause to the One who judges rightly.
B060C002V024	60	2	24	He bore our sins in his own body upon the tree, in order that we might become dead to sins, and be alive unto righteousness. By his wounds you have been healed.
B060C002V025	60	2	25	For you were straying like lost sheep, but you are now returned to the Shepherd and Guardian of your souls.
B060C003V001	60	3	1	In the same way you wives must be submissive to your own husbands;  so that if some of them will not believe the message, they may apart from the message be won over by the behavior of their wives,
B060C003V002	60	3	2	when they see how pure and reverent you are.
B060C003V003	60	3	3	Your adornment ought not to be the outward adornment of plaited hair and golden jewels and the wearing of beautiful dresses;
B060C003V004	60	3	4	but rather that hidden personality of the heart, the imperishable ornament of a quiet and gentle spirit, which in the sight of God is indeed precious.
B060C003V005	60	3	5	For in this way in the olden time the holy women also, who put their trust in God, used to adorn themselves. They were ever in submission to their own husbands;
B060C003V006	60	3	6	thus, for example, Sarah obeyed Abraham, calling him lord. And you are daughters of Sarah, if you do what is right, and permit nothing to make you afraid.
B060C003V007	60	3	7	In the same way you husbands live with your wives, according to knowledge, honoring your wife as of the weaker sex, yet as an heir with yourself of the grace of life; so that your prayers may not be hindered.
B060C003V008	60	3	8	Finally, you should all be harmonious, sympathetic, loving as brothers, tender-hearted, humble-minded;
B060C003V009	60	3	9	not paying back evil for evil or abuse for abuse, but on the contrary giving a blessing. Because for this you have been called - to inherit a blessing.
B060C003V010	60	3	10	He who would love life and enjoy happy days, Let him keep his tongue from evil, And his lips from speaking guile;
B060C003V011	60	3	11	Let him turn from evil and do good, Let him seek peace, and pursue it.
B060C003V012	60	3	12	For the eyes of the Lord are upon the righteous, And his ears are open to their cry; But the face of the Lord is set against evil-doers.
B060C003V013	60	3	13	Yet who will harm you if you become zealous for the good?
B060C003V014	60	3	14	But even if you should suffer in behalf of righteousness, you are happy. Do not be afraid of their terror, neither be troubled.
B060C003V015	60	3	15	But consecrate Christ in your hearts, as Lord. Be always in readiness to make and answer to any one who asks you a reason for the hope that is within you, yet with gentleness and reverence.
B060C003V016	60	3	16	See that you have a clear conscience, so that, although they speak of you as evil-doers, these libelers of your good Christian lives may be ashamed.
B060C003V017	60	3	17	For it is better that you suffer for doing right, if such be Gods will, than for doing wrong;
B060C003V018	60	3	18	because Christ also once for all suffered for sins, the just for the unjust, that he might bring us to God. He was put to death in the flesh, but make alive in spirit.
B060C003V019	60	3	19	(It was in spirit that he went and preached the Word to the spirits who were in prison,
B060C003V020	60	3	20	who in old times had been disobedient, when Gods longsuffering was waiting in the days of Noah, while an ark was building, in which a few persons - eight in number - were saved by water.)
B060C003V021	60	3	21	Baptism, the counterpart of that, now saves you (not the washing off of the filth of the flesh, but the prayer for a good conscience toward God), through the resurrection of Jesus Christ.
B060C003V022	60	3	22	He is gone into heaven, and is on the right hand of God; to Him angels and authorities and powers have been made subject.
B060C004V001	60	4	1	Since, then, Christ suffered in the flesh, do you also ever arm yourselves with the same mind (because he who has suffered in the flesh has done with sin),
B060C004V002	60	4	2	so that in future you may not spend your life in the flesh according to mens desires, but in the will of God.
B060C004V003	60	4	3	For the time past of life may suffice us to have worked the will of the Gentiles, when we spent our life in lasciviousness, lusts, hard drinking, revelry, banqueting, and abominable idol worship.
B060C004V004	60	4	4	They are astonished at this, that you do not run into the same excesses of profligacy as they do; and they speak evil of you.
B060C004V005	60	4	5	But they must render account to Him who stands ready to judge the living and the dead.
B060C004V006	60	4	6	The gospel was preached for this cause to those who were dead also,  that they might be judged according to men in flesh, but live according to God in spirit.
B060C004V007	60	4	7	But the end of all things is close at hand; so be sober, watch and pray.
B060C004V008	60	4	8	Above everything have fervent love to one another; for love veils a multitude of sins.
B060C004V009	60	4	9	Be hospitable to one another, without grudging.
B060C004V010	60	4	10	Whatever the gifts which each has received, use them for one another, as good stewards of the manifold grace of God.
B060C004V011	60	4	11	If any one preaches, let him always preach as one who utters Gods truth; if any one serves another, let it be with the strength which God supplies; so that in every way God may be glorified through Jesus Christ, to whom be glory and dominion for ever and ever, Amen.
B060C004V012	60	4	12	Do not think it strange, beloved, that a fiery ordeal has come to test you, as though some surprising thing had befallen you.
B060C004V013	60	4	13	But be glad in the degree in which you share in the sufferings of Christ; so that when his glory shall be revealed, you too may be glad with triumphant gladness.
B060C004V014	60	4	14	If you are being reproached for the name of Christ, you are blessed,  for the spirit of glory and of God is resting upon you.
B060C004V015	60	4	15	But let none of you suffer as a murderer, or as a thief, or as an evil-doer, or as a spy upon other peoples business.
B060C004V016	60	4	16	But if any man is suffering as a Christian, let him not be ashamed;  but let him ever glorify God in this Name.
B060C004V017	60	4	17	It is time for judgment to begin with the household of God; and if it first begin with us, what shall be the end of those who are disobedient to the gospel?
B060C004V018	60	4	18	If the righteous man is scarcely saved, where shall the ungodly and the sinner appear?
B060C004V019	60	4	19	So let those who are suffering according to the will of God commit the keeping of their souls to him in well-doing, as unto a faithful Creator.
B060C005V001	60	5	1	Now to you who are presbyters I make this appeal; for I am myself a presbyter, and was a witness of the sufferings of Christ, and also a partaker of the glory about to be revealed.
B060C005V002	60	5	2	Be shepherds to your flock of God; take charge of them willingly,  and not through compulsion; not for filthy lucre, but with a willing mind;
B060C005V003	60	5	3	not by way of lording it over your heritage, but by becoming examples to the flock.
B060C005V004	60	5	4	Then, when the Chief Shepherd shall appear, you too will receive the fadeless wreath of glory.
B060C005V005	60	5	5	You younger men must submit to the presbyters; and all of you must put on the garment of humility and serve one another, for God resists the haughty, But gives grace to the humble.
B060C005V006	60	5	6	So humble yourselves under Gods mighty hand, so that he may exalt you in due time.
B060C005V007	60	5	7	Cast all your care upon him, for he ever cares for you.
B060C005V008	60	5	8	Be temperate, be vigilant; because your enemy, the devil, is prowling about like a roaring lion, seeking whom he may devour.
B060C005V009	60	5	9	Resist him, standing firm in the faith, knowing well that the same afflictions are being accomplished in your brothers that are in the world.
B060C005V010	60	5	10	But the God of all grace, who has called us by Christ Jesus to share his eternal glory, will, after you have suffered a while, make you perfect, stablish, strengthen, settle you.
B060C005V011	60	5	11	His is the dominion forever and ever; Amen.
B060C005V012	60	5	12	By Sylvanus, a faithful brother of yours, as I suppose, I have written you briefly, to comfort you, and to testify that this is the true grace of God. In this stand fast.
B060C005V013	60	5	13	Your sister church in Babylon, elect with you, sends you salutations, and so does Marcus, my son.
B060C005V014	60	5	14	Salute one another with a kiss of love. Peace be to you all who are in Christ Jesus.
B061C001V001	61	1	1	Simon Peter, a slave and apostle of Jesus Christ, to those who have obtained an equally precious faith with us in the righteousness of our God and Saviour Jesus Christ.
B061C001V002	61	1	2	Grace and peace be multiplied to you by the God and Father of Jesus our Lord.
B061C001V003	61	1	3	For his power divine has granted to us everything needful for life and godliness, through the knowledge of him who called us by his own glory and virtue.
B061C001V004	61	1	4	By these he has granted his promises to us, precious and splendid;  so that through them you may become partners of the divine nature,  now that you have escaped the corruption that is in the world through lust.
B061C001V005	61	1	5	For this very reason do your best to add to your faith manliness,  and to manliness knowledge,
B061C001V006	61	1	6	and to knowledge self-control, and to self-control stedfastness, and to stedfastness piety,
B061C001V007	61	1	7	and to piety brotherly love, and to brotherly love, love itself.
B061C001V008	61	1	8	For if these virtues are yours in abounding measure, they render you not idle nor unfruitful, until you come into the full knowledge of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B061C001V009	61	1	9	For the man who lacks these virtues is blind, short-sighted,  forgetful of his cleansing from his old sins.
B061C001V010	61	1	10	So, brothers, take diligent care to make your calling and election sure; for if you do this, you will never stumble.
B061C001V011	61	1	11	For so the entrance into the eternal kingdom of our Lord and Saviour Jesus Christ will be richly supplied to you.
B061C001V012	61	1	12	I shall therefore be always ready to remind you of all this, even though you know it, and are firmly founded in the truth which is with you.
B061C001V013	61	1	13	So I think it right, as long as I am in this "tent," to rouse you by way of reminding you,
B061C001V014	61	1	14	since I know that the time for me to strike tent comes swiftly on,  even as our Lord Jesus Christ pointed out to me.
B061C001V015	61	1	15	So I will do my best to enable you, even after my departure,  continually to call these things to mind.
B061C001V016	61	1	16	For we were not following cunningly devised fables, when we told you of the power and presence of our Lord Jesus Christ, but we had been eye-witnesses of his Majesty.
B061C001V017	61	1	17	For he did receive honor and glory from God the Father, when there was borne such a voice to him from the Majestic Glory, This is my Son, my Beloved, in whom I delight;
B061C001V018	61	1	18	and this voice we ourselves heard, borne to us out of heaven, when we were with him on the holy hill.
B061C001V019	61	1	19	And so we possess the word of prophecy made yet more sure. Unto this you do well to give heed as to a lamp shining in a dark place, till the day dawns and the morning star rises in your hearts.
B061C001V020	61	1	20	But first be assured of this - that no prophecy of Scripture is of private interpretation.
B061C001V021	61	1	21	For no prophecy was ever brought by the will of man; but moved by the Holy Spirit, men spoke for God.
B061C002V001	61	2	1	But there were false prophets, too, among the people, just as among you also there will be false teachers. These will secretly bring in destructive sects, denying even the Master who bought them, and bringing swift ruin upon themselves.
B061C002V002	61	2	2	Then there will be many who will follow their immorality, because of whom the Way of the Truth will be maligned.
B061C002V003	61	2	3	In their covetousness, with cunning words, they will make merchandise of you; those whose doom has not been idle from of old,  and whose destruction has not been slumbering.
B061C002V004	61	2	4	For if God did not spare angels when they sinned, but cast them down to Tartarus, and committed them to chains of darkness, and reserved them for judgment;
B061C002V005	61	2	5	if he did not spare the ancient world, but preserved Noah, a herald of righteousness, with seven others, when he brought a flood upon an ungodly world;
B061C002V006	61	2	6	if he condemned the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah and reduced them to ashes, thus holding them up as a warning to all who would live ungodly;
B061C002V007	61	2	7	and he delivered righteous Lot who was worn out by the lascivious life of the wicked
B061C002V008	61	2	8	(for that righteous man, living among them, tormented his righteous soul in seeing and hearing, day after day, their lawless deeds),
B061C002V009	61	2	9	then be sure that the Lord knows how to deliver the godly out of temptation, and to keep the wicked (who are even now enduring punishment) for the "Day of Judgment";
B061C002V010	61	2	10	especially those who spend their lives following the flesh in the lust of defilement, and in despising all authority. Audacious and wilful, they feel no awe in railing against dignities;
B061C002V011	61	2	11	even where angels, though surpassing them in strength and might, do not bring a railing judgment against them before the Lord.
B061C002V012	61	2	12	But these men, like irrational creatures, mere animals, born to be taken and destroyed, continually rail about matters of which they know nothing. In their corruption they will surely be destroyed,
B061C002V013	61	2	13	suffering wrong as the wage of wrong which they have done. These are men who count it pleasure to carouse in open daylight; they are spots and blemishes reveling in their deceit, even while they are feasting with you.
B061C002V014	61	2	14	They have eyes full of harlots, eyes that cannot stop sinning. They entice unsteady souls. Their heart is trained in greed. They are an accursed generation.
B061C002V015	61	2	15	They have forsaken the right way; they have lost their way, and followed the road of Balaam, the son of Beor, who loved the wages of wrong-doing.
B061C002V016	61	2	16	He was, however, rebuked for his own transgression; a dumb ass spoke with a mans voice, and stopped the madness of the prophet.
B061C002V017	61	2	17	Such men are like waterless springs, or mists storm-driven; for them the blackness of darkness has been reserved.
B061C002V018	61	2	18	For speaking great swelling words of vanity, they entangle, by their lasciviousness, in the lusts of the flesh, those who are just about to escape from the men that live in misconduct.
B061C002V019	61	2	19	They promise them liberty, while they themselves are slaves of rottenness! (For indeed a man is the slave of anything which masters him.)
B061C002V020	61	2	20	For if, after having escaped the pollutions of the world, through the knowledge of our Lord and Saviour Jesus Christ, men are again entangled in them and overpowered, their last state is become worse than their first.
B061C002V021	61	2	21	Indeed it would have been better for them not to have known the Way of Righteousness, than, after knowing it, to turn back from the holy command delivered to them.
B061C002V022	61	2	22	In their case it has happened according to the true proverb, The dog returns again to his own vomit, and The sow, after washing, to her wallowing in the mire.
B061C003V001	61	3	1	This is now my second letter to you, beloved. In both of them I am stirring up your pure minds by putting you in remembrance.
B061C003V002	61	3	2	I want you to recollect the words that were foretold by the holy prophets, and the command of your Lord and Saviour, given you through your apostles.
B061C003V003	61	3	3	Know this first, that mockers will come in the last days, in their mockery, men who walk the way of their own lusts
B061C003V004	61	3	4	and say, "Where is the promise of His coming? For since the day that our fathers fell asleep everything continues as it was from the beginning of the creation."
B061C003V005	61	3	5	For they willingly ignore the fact that there were heaven, from of old, and an earth formed out of water and through water, by the word of God;
B061C003V006	61	3	6	and that by the same means the world which then existed was destroyed by a deluge of water.
B061C003V007	61	3	7	But the heavens and earth that now are, by the same word of God,  have been reserved for fire, and are being kept for the Day of Judgment, and for the destruction of ungodly men.
B061C003V008	61	3	8	Do not forget this one thing, beloved, that one day is with the Lord as a thousand years, and a thousand years as one day.
B061C003V009	61	3	9	The Lord does not loiter over his promise, as some men esteem loitering; but he is longsuffering toward you, not purposing that any should perish, but that all should pass on to repentance.
B061C003V010	61	3	10	But the Day of the Lord will come like a thief; and on that Day the heavens will vanish with a crash, the heavenly bodies will melt with fervent heat, and the earth and all its works will be burned up.
B061C003V011	61	3	11	Now since all things are in the process of dissolution, what kind of men ought you to be, in all holy living and piety;
B061C003V012	61	3	12	while you look for and hasten the coming of the Day of God. At its coming the heavens, being on fire, will be dissolved, and the heavenly bodies will melt with fervent heat.
B061C003V013	61	3	13	But according to his promise, we are looking for new heavens and a new earth, in which righteousness makes her dwelling.
B061C003V014	61	3	14	And so, beloved, since you are looking for these things, continually give diligence that you may be found in peace, unspotted and blameless in his sight.
B061C003V015	61	3	15	Regard our Lords longsuffering as salvation; even as our dear brother Paul also wrote to you, according to the wisdom given to him.
B061C003V016	61	3	16	It is the same in all his letters when he speaks of these things.  There are indeed some things in his letters hard to understand, which the ignorant and the shifty wrest, as also they do the other Scriptures, to their own destruction.
B061C003V017	61	3	17	Do you therefore, beloved, because you know these things beforehand,  be on your guard lest you be led astray by the error of the wicked,  and so fall from your own stedfastness.
B061C003V018	61	3	18	But grow continually in the grace and knowledge of our Lord and Saviour Jesus Christ. To Him be the glory both now and unto the Day of Eternity, Amen.
B062C001V001	62	1	1	It is of what has existed from the beginning, of what we have listened to, of what we have seen with our own eyes, of what we have witnessed and touched with our own heads, it is concerning the Logos of Life that we are now writing.
B062C001V002	62	1	2	And the Life was made visible, and we have seen it and are bearing witness, and are bringing you word of that Eternal Life which was face to face with the Father and was made visible to us.
B062C001V003	62	1	3	It is what we have seen and heard that we are announcing to you, in order that you also may have partnership with us; and our partnership is with the Father and with his Son, Jesus Christ.
B062C001V004	62	1	4	And we are writing all this to you that our joy may be complete.
B062C001V005	62	1	5	This, then, is the message that we have heard from him, and are announcing to you, that God is light, and no darkness what ever is in him.
B062C001V006	62	1	6	If we say, "We have partnership with Him," when we are passing our life in the darkness, we are lying and are not doing the truth.
B062C001V007	62	1	7	But is we are passing our life in the light, as he is in the light,  we ever have partnership with one another, and the blood of Jesus Christ is cleansing us from every sin.
B062C001V008	62	1	8	If we say, "We have no sin," we are deceiving ourselves and the truth is not in us.
B062C001V009	62	1	9	But if we confess our sins, faithful is he and just to forgive us our sins, and to cleanse us from all wrong-doing.
B062C001V010	62	1	10	If we say, "We have not sinned," we are making him a liar, and his word is not in us.
B062C002V001	62	2	1	My children, I am writing this to you that you may not continue to sin; but if any one sin, we ever have a Comforter before the Father,  Jesus Christ the Righteous.
B062C002V002	62	2	2	And he is the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only, but also for those of the whole world.
B062C002V003	62	2	3	This is how we may know that we have come to know Him, by always keeping his commandments.
B062C002V004	62	2	4	He who says, "I know Him," but does no continue obeying his commandments, is a liar,
B062C002V005	62	2	5	and the truth is not in him; bit if any man obey his word, in him truly is the love of God made perfect. By this we come to know that we are in him.
B062C002V006	62	2	6	By who says he "remains in him" ought to spend his life as he spent his.
B062C002V007	62	2	7	Beloved, I am not writing a new commandment to you, nay, and old commandment, which you have had from the beginning. That old commandment is the message to which you have listened.
B062C002V008	62	2	8	Yet again it is a new commandment which I am writing to you, which is true in him and is you; because the darkness is passing away, and the true light is already shining.
B062C002V009	62	2	9	He who says he is in the light, and hates his brother, is in darkness even until now.
B062C002V010	62	2	10	But he who loves his brother is abiding in the light, and in it there is no cause of stumbling.
B062C002V011	62	2	11	But he who hates his brother is in the darkness, and is spending his life in the darkness, and does not know where he is going, because the darkness has blinded his eyes.
B062C002V012	62	2	12	I am writing to you, little children, because you sins are forgiven you for his names sake.
B062C002V013	62	2	13	I am writing to you, fathers, because you have come to know him who is from the beginning. I am writing to you, young men, because you have fully overcome the Evil One. I have written to you, little children, because you have learned to know the father.
B062C002V014	62	2	14	I have written to you, fathers, because you have learned to know him who is from the beginning. I have written to you, young men, because you are strong, and the word of God is abiding in you, and you have fully overcome the Evil One.
B062C002V015	62	2	15	Love not the world, neither the things that are in the world. If any man love the world, the love of the Father is not in him.
B062C002V016	62	2	16	For all that is in the world, the lust of the flesh, and the lust of the eyes, and the proud glory of life, is not from the Father, but from the world;
B062C002V017	62	2	17	and the world and its lusts are passing away, but he who ever does the will of God abides forever.
B062C002V018	62	2	18	My children, this is the last hour, and as you have heard that an antichrist was coming, and now many antichrists are already risen,  whence we may know that it is the last hour.
B062C002V019	62	2	19	They came forth from us, but they did not belong to us. If they had belonged to us they would certainly have remained with us, but they went out that they might be manifest that they all are not of us.
B062C002V020	62	2	20	Now you have an anointing from the Holy One, and you know all things.
B062C002V021	62	2	21	I am not writing to you because you do not know the truth, but because you do know it, and know that no lie is of the truth.
B062C002V022	62	2	22	Who is the liar if not the man who denies that Jesus is the Christ?  This is the Antichrist, even he who disowns the Father and the Son.
B062C002V023	62	2	23	Whoever denies the Son, the same has not the Father; but he who confesses the Son has the Father also. As for you, let what you have heard from the beginning abide in you.
B062C002V024	62	2	24	If what you have heard from the beginning is abiding in you, you also will ever abide in the Son and in the Father.
B062C002V025	62	2	25	And this is the promise which he has promised to us even life eternal.
B062C002V026	62	2	26	I have written this to you concerning those who would lead you astray.
B062C002V027	62	2	27	As to you, the unction you received from him remains ever in you,  and you need no teaching from any one. But since his unction teaches you concerning all things and is true, and is no lie, abide continually in him, as it has taught you to do.
B062C002V028	62	2	28	And now continue to abide in him, my children, so that when he shall appear we may have cheerful confidence and not be ashamed before him at his coming.
B062C002V029	62	2	29	If you know that he is righteous you know also that every one who habitually practises righteousness has been born of him.
B062C003V001	62	3	1	Behold what manner of love the Father has given us in allowing us to be called "Children of God!" And that is what we are. For this reason the world does not recognize us, because it did not know him.
B062C003V002	62	3	2	We are Gods children now, beloved; what we shall be has never yet been made manifest. But we know that when he is manifested we shall be like him; for we shall see him even as he is.
B062C003V003	62	3	3	And every one who is holding this hope in him is purifying himself,  even as he is pure.
B062C003V004	62	3	4	Every one who commits sin commits also lawlessness. Sin is lawlessness.
B062C003V005	62	3	5	And you know that he was manifested to take away sins; and in him is no sin.
B062C003V006	62	3	6	Whoever continually abides in him does not habitually sin; whoever lives in sin has not seen him, nor come to know him.
B062C003V007	62	3	7	My children, let no one deceive you; he who is working righteousness is righteous, just as he is righteous.
B062C003V008	62	3	8	He who is committing sin is of the devil, because from the beginning of the devil is sinning. It was for this cause that the Son of God was manifested, that he might destroy the works of the devil.
B062C003V009	62	3	9	Whoever is a child of God cannot go on sinning, because his seed is abiding in him; and he cannot go on sinning because he is a child of God.
B062C003V010	62	3	10	In this the children of God are manifest, and the children of the devil; for every one who does not work righteousness is not a child of God, nor is he who does not love his brother.
B062C003V011	62	3	11	For this is the message that you have listened to from the beginning, "WE ARE TO LOVE ONE ANOTHER."
B062C003V012	62	3	12	We are not to be like Cain, who belonged to the Evil One, and murdered his brother. And why did he murder him? It was because his own deeds were evil, and his brothers, righteous.
B062C003V013	62	3	13	Do not wonder, brothers, if the world continues to hate you.
B062C003V014	62	3	14	We know that we have migrated, out of death into life, because we love our brothers. He who has no love is abiding in death.
B062C003V015	62	3	15	Every one who is hating his brother is a murderer, and you know that no murderer has eternal life abiding in him.
B062C003V016	62	3	16	By this we learn to know love, because he laid down his life for us;  so we ought to lay down our lives for our brothers.
B062C003V017	62	3	17	But whoever has this worlds goods, and beholds his brother in need,  and shuts up his heart against him, how can the love of God continue to abide in him?
B062C003V018	62	3	18	My children, let us not love in word nor in talk, but in deed and in truth.
B062C003V019	62	3	19	By this we shall come to know that we are really of the truth,
B062C003V020	62	3	20	and shall persuade our heart in his presence whenever our heart condemns us, because God is greater than our heart and knows all things.
B062C003V021	62	3	21	Beloved, if our heart condemn us not, we have confidence toward God,
B062C003V022	62	3	22	and whatever we ask we are receiving from him, because we are keeping his commandments and doing those things that are pleasing in his sight.
B062C003V023	62	3	23	His commandment is this, that we should believe in the name of his Son, Jesus Christ, and love one another as he has commanded us to do.
B062C003V024	62	3	24	He who keeps his commandments is abiding in Him, and Christ in him.  By this we know that Christ is abiding in us, by the Spirit which he has given us.
B062C004V001	62	4	1	Do not believe every spirit, beloved, but test the spirits to see whether they are of God; for many false prophets are gone out into the world.
B062C004V002	62	4	2	By this you know the Spirit of God; every spirit that confesses that Jesus Christ is come in the flesh is from God;
B062C004V003	62	4	3	and every spirit which confesses him not, is not from God. And this is that spirit of Antichrist of which you have heard that it is coming, and that now it is already in the world.
B062C004V004	62	4	4	My little children, you are of God and have conquered them; because he that is within you is greater than he that is in the world.
B062C004V005	62	4	5	They are of the world, and for this reason they speak as of the world, and the world listens to them.
B062C004V006	62	4	6	But you are of God. He who is beginning to know God listens to us;  he who is not of God does not listen to us. By this we may distinguish the spirit of truth from the spirit of error.
B062C004V007	62	4	7	Beloved, let us love one another; for love is of God; and every one that loves us a child of God.
B062C004V008	62	4	8	He who does not love, does not know God; for God is love.
B062C004V009	62	4	9	In this was the love of God clearly shown toward us, by his sending his only Son into the world, so that we might live through him.
B062C004V010	62	4	10	In this is love, not that we loved God, but that he loved us, and sent his Son to be a propitiation for our sins.
B062C004V011	62	4	11	If God so loved us, beloved, we also ought to love one another.
B062C004V012	62	4	12	No man has ever gazed on God; but if we love one another, God ever abides in us, and his love is perfected in us.
B062C004V013	62	4	13	By this we come to know that we are abiding in him, and he in us,  because he has given us of his Spirit;
B062C004V014	62	4	14	and we have beheld and do testify that the Father has sent the Son to be the Saviour of the world.
B062C004V015	62	4	15	If any man confesses that "Jesus is the Son of God." God is abiding in that man, and he in God.
B062C004V016	62	4	16	And we do know and have believed the love which God has for us. God is love; and he who is abiding in love is abiding in God, and God is abiding in him.
B062C004V017	62	4	17	In this is love made perfect with us, so that we may have cheerful confidence in the Day of Judgment, because we are living in this world as He lives.
B062C004V018	62	4	18	Fear does not exist in love; but love, when it is perfect, drives out fear. For fear has always torment, and he who has fear is not yet perfected in love.
B062C004V019	62	4	19	We love because He loved us first.
B062C004V020	62	4	20	If any one says, "I love God," and yet hates his brother, he is a liar; for he who does not love his brother whom he has seen, cannot possibly love God, whom he has not seen.
B062C004V021	62	4	21	And we have this command from God. HE WHO LOVES GOD IS TO LOVE HIS BROTHER ALSO.
B062C005V001	62	5	1	Every one who believes that Jesus is the Christ is a child of God;  and every one who loves the Father, loves him also who is the Fathers Child.
B062C005V002	62	5	2	By this we know that we love the children of God, when we love God and obey his commandments.
B062C005V003	62	5	3	For love to God means obeying his commandments; and his commandments are not irksome.
B062C005V004	62	5	4	For whoever is a child of God is overcoming the world; and our faith is the victory that has overcome the world.
B062C005V005	62	5	5	And who it the one that is overcoming the world if not the man who believes that Jesus is the Son of God?
B062C005V006	62	5	6	Jesus Christ is he who came by water and blood, not by the water only, but by the water and by the blood. The spirit is he who bears testimony, because the Spirit is the truth.
B062C005V007	62	5	7	For there are three who bear testimony, the Spirit, and the water,
B062C005V008	62	5	8	and the blood; and the three are one.
B062C005V009	62	5	9	If we accept mens testimony, the testimony of God is greater; for this is the testimony of God, that he has borne testimony concerning his Son.
B062C005V010	62	5	10	He who believes on the Son of God has the testimony in himself. He who does not believe God, has made him a liar, because he has not believed in the testimony that God has borne concerning his Son.
B062C005V011	62	5	11	And the testimony is this, "God has given us eternal life, and this life is in his Son."
B062C005V012	62	5	12	He who has the Son has the life; he who has not the Son of God has not the life.
B062C005V013	62	5	13	I have written these words to you so that you may know that you have eternal life, you who believe in the name of the Son of God.
B062C005V014	62	5	14	Now the confidence which we have in him is this, that he listens to us whenever we ask anything that is in accordance with his will.
B062C005V015	62	5	15	And if we know that he is listening to us in what ever we are asking, we know that we obtain the petitions which we have made to him.
B062C005V016	62	5	16	If any one sees his brother committing a sin that is not deadly, he shall ask, and God will give him life, for any one who is not committing a deadly sin. There is a deadly sin; concerning that I do not say that he should pray.
B062C005V017	62	5	17	All unrighteousness is sin; and there is sin that is not deadly.
B062C005V018	62	5	18	We know that whoever is a child of God is not habitually committing sin; but he who is Gods child guards himself, and the Evil One never touches him.
B062C005V019	62	5	19	We know that we are of God, and the whole world is lying in the Evil One.
B062C005V020	62	5	20	And we know that the Son of God is come, and has granted us and understanding, so that we may come to know him who is true. And we are in him who is true, even in his Son Jesus Christ. This is the true God, and life eternal.
B062C005V021	62	5	21	My little children, guard yourselves from idols.
B063C001V001	63	1	1	The Elder to the Elect Lady and her children, whom I love in truth,  and not only I, but also all those who have come to know the truth.
B063C001V002	63	1	2	I love you for the sake of the truth which is abiding in us and will be with us forever.
B063C001V003	63	1	3	Grace, mercy, and peace will be with us from God the Father, and from Jesus Christ the Fathers Son, in truth and love.
B063C001V004	63	1	4	I am greatly rejoiced to find some of your children leading their lives in truth, even as we received commandment from the Father.
B063C001V005	63	1	5	And now I am entreating you, Lady, not as though I were writing some new commandment to you, but one which we have had from the beginning,  let us love one another.
B063C001V006	63	1	6	And this is love, that we should lead our lives according to his commandments. This is the commandment, even as you heard from the beginning, that you should pass your life in love.
B063C001V007	63	1	7	I say this because many deceivers are gone forth into the world,  those who deny the coming of Jesus Christ in the flesh. This is the deceiver and the Antichrist.
B063C001V008	63	1	8	Watch yourselves, that you do not lose what we have wrought, but that you receive a full reward.
B063C001V009	63	1	9	Whoever is going ahead, and is not abiding in the teachings of Christ, does not possess God; but he who is abiding in the teaching possesses both the Father and the Son.
B063C001V010	63	1	10	If any one come to you and does not bring this teaching, do not receive him into your house, nor give him any greeting.
B063C001V011	63	1	11	For the man who greets him shares in his wicked work.
B063C001V012	63	1	12	I have many things to write to you, but I would not write them with paper and ink. I hope to come to you and to talk with you face to face, so that your joy may be full.
B063C001V013	63	1	13	The children of your elect sister send you greeting.
B064C001V001	64	1	1	The Elder to the beloved Gaius, whom I love in the truth.
B064C001V002	64	1	2	I pray that you may prosper, beloved, in every way, and be in good health, even as your soul is prospering.
B064C001V003	64	1	3	For I was glad when brothers came and bore testimony to your truth,  as indeed you are passing your life in truth.
B064C001V004	64	1	4	I have no greater joy than this, to hear that my children are passing their lives in the truth.
B064C001V005	64	1	5	You are acting faithfully, beloved, in whatever you are doing for the brothers and the strangers.
B064C001V006	64	1	6	They have borne testimony to your love before the church. You will do well to speed them on their way worthily of God;
B064C001V007	64	1	7	since for the sake of the Name they have started out, taking nothing from the Gentiles.
B064C001V008	64	1	8	Hence we ought to support such, so that we may become fellow workers for the truth.
B064C001V009	64	1	9	I have written somewhat to the church; but Diotrephes, who love to take the lead among them, does not receive me.
B064C001V010	64	1	10	Do them when I come I will recall to mind the deeds which he is doing, prating against me with wicked words. Not satisfied with that,  he refuses to receive the brothers, forbids those that would receive them, and excommunicates them from the church.
B064C001V011	64	1	11	Do not imitate what is evil, beloved, but that which is good. He who does good is of God; he who does evil has never gazed on God.
B064C001V012	64	1	12	All men bear testimony to Demetrius, and so does the truth itself. I also bear testimony to him; and you know that my testimony is true.
B064C001V013	64	1	13	I have a great deal to write to you, but I do not want to write you with pen and ink.
B064C001V014	64	1	14	I am hoping soon to see you, and then we shall talk face to face.  Peace be to you! The friends send their salutation. Salute the friends by name.
B065C001V001	65	1	1	Jude, a slave of Jesus Christ, and a brother of James. To those who are in God, the Father beloved, kept for Jesus Christ, and called.
B065C001V002	65	1	2	May mercy and peace and love be multiplied to you.
B065C001V003	65	1	3	Beloved, although I was making all haste to write to you in regard to our common salvation, I am compelled to write you an appeal to defend the faith once for all committed to the saints.
B065C001V004	65	1	4	For certain men have crept in stealthily - men predestined in ancient prophecies for this condemnation - impious ones! They pervert the grace of our God into licentiousness, and deny Jesus Christ, our sole Master and Lord.
B065C001V005	65	1	5	I wish to remind you of what you already know right well, that although the Lord once saved a people out of the land of Egypt, he afterward destroyed those who did not believe;
B065C001V006	65	1	6	while the angels who did not keep their first domain but left their proper abode, are held by him in blank darkness, in everlasting chains, in preparation for the judgment of the Great Day.
B065C001V007	65	1	7	So also Sodom and Gomorrah and the near-by cities which in like manner glutted themselves in sensuality and unnatural vice, are exhibited as a warning of the eternal fire, in the punishment they undergo.
B065C001V008	65	1	8	Yet in just the same way these dreamers also defile the flesh, while they set at naught dominion and scoff at dignities.
B065C001V009	65	1	9	But Michael, the Archangel, when in contending with the devil, he was disputing about the body of Moses, did not dare to pronounce sentence for blasphemy, but said, "The Lord rebuke you."
B065C001V010	65	1	10	Yet these men blaspheme about matters of which they know nothing,  while they use such things as they do understand by instinct (like the animals who have no reason) for their own destruction.
B065C001V011	65	1	11	Alas for them! They have walked in the path of Cain; for the sake of gain they have rushed headlong into Balaams error, and have perished in Korahs rebellion.
B065C001V012	65	1	12	These are they who are stains upon your love-feasts; when they feast sumptuously without scruple, looking after none but themselves. They are clouds without water, driven along by the winds; trees of autumn,  fruitless, doubly dead, torn up by the roots,
B065C001V013	65	1	13	wild waves of the sea, foaming out their own shame; wandering stars,  for whom is reserved the blackness of darkness forever.
B065C001V014	65	1	14	It was to these, too, that Enoch, the "seventh in descent from Adam," prophesied, saying, "Lo! the Lord is come with myriads of his saints,
B065C001V015	65	1	15	to execute judgment upon all, and to convict all the ungodly of all the ungodly deeds which in their ungodliness they have committed; and of all the hard things which they have spoken against Him, ungodly sinners that they are!"
B065C001V016	65	1	16	For these are murmurers, always complaining. They always go where their passions lead, and their mouth speaks great swelling words,  while they pay court to men for the sake of the advantage they can get.
B065C001V017	65	1	17	But as for you, dearly beloved, remember the words spoken before by the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ,
B065C001V018	65	1	18	how they used to say to you, "In the last times there will be scoffers who will be led only by their godless passions."
B065C001V019	65	1	19	These are the men, sensual and unspiritual, who cause divisions.
B065C001V020	65	1	20	But you, beloved, continually building yourselves up on your most holy faith, and ever praying in the Holy Spirit,
B065C001V021	65	1	21	must keep yourselves in the love of God, while waiting for the mercy of our Lord Jesus Christ, which ends in life eternal.
B065C001V022	65	1	22	Pity some who are wavering, and save by dragging them out of the fire;
B065C001V023	65	1	23	others pity, but with caution, hating even the garment spotted by the flesh.
B065C001V024	65	1	24	Now unto Him who has power to guard you from stumbling, and to make you stand in the presence of his glory, faultless and exultant,
B065C001V025	65	1	25	to the only God, our Saviour, through Jesus Christ our Lord, be ascribed glory, majesty, might, and authority, as it was before time began, is now, and ever shall be to all the ages. Amen.
B066C001V001	66	1	1	\ul1 THE UNVEILING APOCALYPSE OF JESUS CHRIST\ul0  which God gave him to show to his slaves the things which must soon come to pass; and he sent and made it known by his angel to his slave John.
B066C001V002	66	1	2	He bore witness of the Word of God, and of the testimony of Jesus Christ, even of all the things that he saw.
B066C001V003	66	1	3	Blessed is he who reads, and they who hear the words of the prophecy, and keep what is written in it. \ul1 FOR THE CRISIS IS AT HAND\ul0 .
B066C001V004	66	1	4	From John to the seven churches that are in Asia the Roman Province. Grace to you, and peace from Him that is and was and is to be, and from the Seven Spirits that are before his throne,
B066C001V005	66	1	5	and from Jesus Christ, the faithful witness, the firstborn of the dead, and the Ruler of the kings of the earth. To Him who loves us and has loosed us from our sins in his own blood;
B066C001V006	66	1	6	and has made us to be a kingdom of priests unto his God and Father;  to him be the glory and the dominion forever and ever, Amen.
B066C001V007	66	1	7	Behold, he is about to come among the clouds; and every eye will see him, and all the tribes of the earth will mourn over him. So shall it be, Amen.
B066C001V008	66	1	8	"I am the Alpha and the Omega," says the Lord God, who is, and who was, and who is to come, the Almighty.
B066C001V009	66	1	9	I, John, who am your brother and who share with you in the woes and kingdom and stedfastness of Jesus, found myself in the island called Patmos, for the sake of the word of God and the testimony of Jesus.
B066C001V010	66	1	10	I was in the Spirit on the Lords day, and I heard a loud voice behind me, like a trumpet,
B066C001V011	66	1	11	saying, "Write in a book what you see, and send it to the seven churches; to Ephesus and to Smyrna and to Pergamum and to Thyatira and Sardis and Philadelphia and Laodicea."
B066C001V012	66	1	12	And I turned to see the Voice which was speaking to me, and as I turned I saw seven golden candlesticks;
B066C001V013	66	1	13	and in the midst of the candlesticks One like to a son of man,  clothed with a robe down to the feet, and with a golden girdle round his breast.
B066C001V014	66	1	14	His head and his hair were as white as wool, as white as snow; his eyes were like a flame of fire,
B066C001V015	66	1	15	and his feet like burnished brass, as if molten in a furnace; and his voice like the voice of many waters.
B066C001V016	66	1	16	In his right hand he held seven stars; and out of mouth went a sharp, two-edged sword, and his face was as the sun shining in his strength.
B066C001V017	66	1	17	When I saw him, I fell at his feet as one dead. And he laid his right hand upon me, saying. "Fear not; I am the first and the last,  and the Living One.
B066C001V018	66	1	18	I was dead, and behold, I am alive forevermore; and hold the keys of death and of Hades.
B066C001V019	66	1	19	So write the things which you saw, and the things which are, and the things that will come to pass hereafter.
B066C001V020	66	1	20	The mystery of the seven stars which you saw in my right hand, and the seven golden candlesticks, is this. The seven stars are the angels of the seven churches, and the seven candlesticks are the seven churches."
B066C002V001	66	2	1	To the angel of the Church in Ephesus, write. These are the words of Him who holds the seven stars in his right hand, and who walks among the seven golden candlesticks.
B066C002V002	66	2	2	I know your works and your toil and stedfastness, and that you cannot endure evil men, and that you tested those who called themselves apostles, though they are not, and how you found them false.
B066C002V003	66	2	3	You are holding fast, and have borne up for my namess sake, and have not grown weary.
B066C002V004	66	2	4	But I have this against you, that you have left your first love.
B066C002V005	66	2	5	Remember whence you have fallen, and turn again, and do your first works. Otherwise I am coming to you and will remove your candlestick out of its place, unless you repent.
B066C002V006	66	2	6	But this you have, that you hate the works of the Nicolaitans, which I hate.
B066C002V007	66	2	7	He who has an ear, let him listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches. To him that overcomes, to him will I give to eat from the tree of life which is in the garden of God.
B066C002V008	66	2	8	And unto the angel of the Church in Smyrna, write. These are the words of the First and the Last, he who died and has returned to life.
B066C002V009	66	2	9	I know your persecution and your poverty - but you are rich! I know the reviling of those who say that they themselves are Jews, when they are not, but are a synagogue of Satan.
B066C002V010	66	2	10	Fear not what you are about to suffer! Behold, the devil is indeed going to put some of you in prison, that you may be tested, and you will have persecution for ten days. Be faithful even unto death, and I will give you the crown of life.
B066C002V011	66	2	11	Let him who has ears, listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches. He that overcomes shall not be hurt of the second death.
B066C002V012	66	2	12	And to the angel of the Church in Pergamum, write These are the words of Him who holds the sharp two-edged sword.
B066C002V013	66	2	13	I know where you dwell, where the throne of Satan is; and yet you are holding fast my name, and you have not denied my faith, even in the days of Antipas, my witness, my faithful one, who was slain among you, where Satan has his dwelling.
B066C002V014	66	2	14	But I have a few things against you, because you have there some who hold to the teaching of Balaam, who taught Balak to put a stumbling-  block before the sons of Israel, to eat food offered to idols, and to practise immorality.
B066C002V015	66	2	15	So you have also some who hold the teaching of the Nicolaitans.
B066C002V016	66	2	16	Repent; if you do not I will very soon come to you, and will make war upon them with the sword of my mouth.
B066C002V017	66	2	17	He who has ears, let him listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches. To him that overcomes I will give of the hidden manna, and I will give him a white stone, and upon the stone a new name written,  which no man knows, but he that receives it.
B066C002V018	66	2	18	And to the angel of the Church in Thyatira, write. These are the words of the Son of God, who has his eyes like a flame of fire, and his feet like burnished brass.
B066C002V019	66	2	19	I know your works and your love and faith and service and endurance;  I know that your last works are more than the first.
B066C002V020	66	2	20	But I have this against you, that you are tolerating that woman Jezebel, who calls herself a prophetess, and she is teaching and leading my slaves astray, leading them to practise immorality, and to eat food which has been sacrificed to idols.
B066C002V021	66	2	21	I have given her time for repentance; but she is determined not to turn from her immorality.
B066C002V022	66	2	22	Behold, I will lay her on a sick bed, and bring great distress upon those who have committed adultery with her, unless they turn away from her works.
B066C002V023	66	2	23	And moreover, her children will I kill with pestilence. And all the churches shall know that I am he who searches the hearts and souls of men. I will give to each of you according to his works.
B066C002V024	66	2	24	But to the rest of you in Thyatira, those who do not hold his teaching, and who do not know the "deep things" of Satan (as they call them),
B066C002V025	66	2	25	I say that I am imposing upon you no fresh burden; only hold fast what you have till I come.
B066C002V026	66	2	26	To him that overcomes and perseveres in my works to the end, will I give authority over the nations.
B066C002V027	66	2	27	And he shall shepherd them with a rod of iron, shattering them like earthen vessels (as I myself have received from my Father),
B066C002V028	66	2	28	and I will give him the Morning Star."
B066C002V029	66	2	29	Let him who has an ear, listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches.
B066C003V001	66	3	1	To the angel of the Church at Sardis, write. These things says He who has the seven Spirits of God and the seven stars. I know your works, that you have the name of being alive, but are really dead.
B066C003V002	66	3	2	Be continually on the watch, and establish the things that remain,  which were ready to die. For I have not found your works perfected before my God.
B066C003V003	66	3	3	Call to mind, then, what you have received and heard, and hold to it, and repent. Unless you are on the watch, I will come as a thief,  and you will never know at what hour I am coming upon you.
B066C003V004	66	3	4	Yet you have a few names in Sardis that have not defiled their garment; and they shall walk with me in white, for they are worthy.
B066C003V005	66	3	5	He who overcomes shall thus be clad in white raiment; and I will in no wise blot out his name from the book of life, and I will own his name before my Father, and before his angels.
B066C003V006	66	3	6	Let him who has an ear, listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches.
B066C003V007	66	3	7	Write also to the angel of the Church in Philadelphia. These things says He who is holy, he who is true, he who has the key of David, he who opens, and no one shall shut; and who shuts, and no one opens.
B066C003V008	66	3	8	I know your works. Lo, I have set before you an open door, which none can shut; for though you have only a little strength, you have kept my word, and have not denied my name.
B066C003V009	66	3	9	Behold, I am making those of the synagogue of Satan, those who say they are Jews, but are not, but are lying; behold, I will make them to come and bow in reverence before your feet, and to know that I have loved you.
B066C003V010	66	3	10	Because you have kept the word of my patience, I also will keep you from that hour of trial which is about to come upon the whole inhabited earth, to test those who dwell on the earth.
B066C003V011	66	3	11	I am coming quickly. Hold fast what you have, that no one may take your crown.
B066C003V012	66	3	12	He that overcomes, I will make him a pillar in the temple of my God;  and he shall go out from it nevermore. And I will write upon him the name of my God, and the name of the city of my God, the new Jerusalem, which is coming down from my God out of heaven, and my own new name.
B066C003V013	66	3	13	He that has an ear, let him listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches.
B066C003V014	66	3	14	To the angel of the Church in Laodicea, write. These things says the Amen, the witness, faithful and true, the beginning of the creation of God.
B066C003V015	66	3	15	I know your works, that you are neither hot nor cold.
B066C003V016	66	3	16	Would that you were either cold or hot. So because you are lukewarm,  and neither hot nor cold, I am about to spew you out of my mouth.
B066C003V017	66	3	17	For you keep saying, "I am rich, and have become wealthy, and have need of nothing," and do not know that you are the wretched one, and pitiable and beggared and blind and naked.
B066C003V018	66	3	18	I advise you to buy of me gold refined by fire, that you may become rich; and white raiment to clothe yourself, so that the shame of your nakedness may not be made manifest; and eye-salve to anoint your eyes, in order that you may see.
B066C003V019	66	3	19	All whom I love I reprove and discipline; therefore be full of zeal and repent.
B066C003V020	66	3	20	Behold, I am standing at the door and knocking! If any one listens to my voice, and opens the door, I will come to him, and sup with him, and he with me.
B066C003V021	66	3	21	To him who overcomes, I will grant to sit down with me on my throne,  as I myself have overcome and have taken my seat with my Father on his throne.
B066C003V022	66	3	22	Let any one who has an ear listen to what the Spirit is saying to the churches.
B066C004V001	66	4	1	After this, in my vision, I saw a door opened in heaven! And the first voice that I heard speaking with me was like a trumpet, saying,  "Come up hither, and I will show you the things that must come to pass hereafter."
B066C004V002	66	4	2	Immediately I was in the Spirit; and behold, there stood a throne in heaven, and upon the throne One sat;
B066C004V003	66	4	3	and he who sat was in appearance like a jasper stone and a sardius;  and there was a rainbow round about the throne, like an emerald to look upon.
B066C004V004	66	4	4	And round about the throne were four and twenty Elders seated, who were clothed in white raiment, with golden crowns upon their heads.
B066C004V005	66	4	5	From the throne issued lightning and voices and thunders. Seven blazing lamps were burning before the throne; these are the seven Spirits of God.
B066C004V006	66	4	6	And in front of the throne as it seemed, a glassy sea like crystal;  and in the midst of the throne and encircling it are four Living Creatures, full of eyes before and behind.
B066C004V007	66	4	7	The first creature was like a lion, and the second like a calf, and the third creature had a face like a mans, and the fourth creature was like an eagle flying.
B066C004V008	66	4	8	And the four Living Creatures, each one with six wings, are full of eyes round about and within; day and night they are chanting ceaselessly. "Holy, holy, holy is the Lord God, the Almighty. Who was, and who is, and who is to come."
B066C004V009	66	4	9	And whenever the Living Creatures give glory and honor and thanks to Him who sits on the throne, to Him who lives forever and ever,
B066C004V010	66	4	10	the four and twenty Elders fall down before Him who sits on the throne, and worship Him who lives forever and ever, and cast their crowns before the throne, saying.
B066C004V011	66	4	11	"Worthy art thou, our Lord and our God, To receive the glory and the honor and the power; For thou didst create all things, And because of thy will they came into being And were created."
B066C005V001	66	5	1	Then I saw lying upon the right hand of Him who sat upon the throne,  a book written within and on the back, close sealed with seven seals.
B066C005V002	66	5	2	And I saw a strong angel proclaiming with a loud voice, "Who is worthy to open the book, and to loose its seals."
B066C005V003	66	5	3	And no one in the heavens or on the earth, or under the earth, was able to open the book, or to look into it.
B066C005V004	66	5	4	so I began to weep bitterly because no one was found worthy to open the book, or to look into it.
B066C005V005	66	5	5	But one of the Elders said to me. "Do not weep! Behold, the Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has conquered, and so can open the book with its seven seals."
B066C005V006	66	5	6	Then I beheld a Lamb standing as if slain in the midst of the throne and of the four Living Creatures, and in the midst of the Elders. He had seven horns and seven eyes (which are the seven Spirits of God,  sent forth into all the earth).
B066C005V007	66	5	7	And he went, and now he has taken the book out of the right hand of Him who was seated on the throne.
B066C005V008	66	5	8	When he took the book, the four Living Creatures and the four and twenty Elders fell down before the Lamb. And each had a harp and a golden bowls full of incense, which are the prayers of the saints.
B066C005V009	66	5	9	And they sang a new song, saying, "Worthy art thou to take the book And to open its seals; For thou wast slain and didst ransom for God Men out of every tribe and tongue and people and nation;
B066C005V010	66	5	10	Thou hast made them kings and priests unto our God, And they shall reign on earth."
B066C005V011	66	5	11	Then I looked and heard a voice of many angels encircling the throne and a voice of the Living Creatures and of the Elders; and the number of them was ten thousand times ten thousand, and thousands of thousands,
B066C005V012	66	5	12	singing aloud, "Worthy is the Lamb who has been slain, To receive power and riches and wisdom And might and honor and glory and blessing."
B066C005V013	66	5	13	And I heard every created thing that is in heaven, or on earth, or beneath the earth, or on the sea, and all things that are in them,  saying, "To him who sits on the throne, And to the Lamb, Be the blessing and the honor, And the glory and the power, Forever and ever!"
B066C005V014	66	5	14	And the four Living Creatures kept saying, "Amen!" And the Elders fell down and worshiped.
B066C006V001	66	6	1	And I saw, when the Lamb opened one of the seven seals, and I heard one of the four Living Creatures say, with a voice like thunder,  "Come!"
B066C006V002	66	6	2	And I saw, and lo, a white horse, and he who sat on him had a bow;  and there was given him a crown; and he went forth conquering, and to conquer.
B066C006V003	66	6	3	And when he opened the second seal, I heard the second Living Creature say, "Come!"
B066C006V004	66	6	4	And another horse come forth, a red horse. To him who sat on it, it was allowed to take peace from the earth, and to cause men to kill one another; and a great sword was given to him.
B066C006V005	66	6	5	And when he opened the third seal, I heard the third Living Creature say, "Come!" And I saw, and lo, a black horse! He who sat on him had a balance in his hand.
B066C006V006	66	6	6	And I heard the semblance of a voice in the midst of the four Living Creatures, saying. "A quart of wheat for a shilling, and three quarts of barley for a shilling; but do not harm the oil and the wine."
B066C006V007	66	6	7	And when he opened the fourth seal, I heard the voice of the fourth Living Creature calling, "Come!"
B066C006V008	66	6	8	So I liked, and lo, a pale horse; and he who sat on him was named Death; and Hades was following after him. To them was given authority over the fourth part of the earth, to kill with the sword, and with famine, and with death, and with the wild beasts of the earth.
B066C006V009	66	6	9	And when he opened the fifth seal, I saw underneath the altar the souls of those who had been slain for the word of God, and for the testimony which they bore.
B066C006V010	66	6	10	And with a loud voice they cried, saying, "O Master, holy and true,  How long dost thou not judge And avenge our blood On those who dwell on the earth?"
B066C006V011	66	6	11	And there was given to each one of them a white robe; and they were told that they should rest for yet a little time, until the number should be completed by their fellow slaves and their brethren who were about to be put to death as they had been.
B066C006V012	66	6	12	And I looked when he opened the sixth seal, and there was a great earthquake; and the sun became black, like sackcloth, and the full moon became like blood;
B066C006V013	66	6	13	and the stars of the sky fell to earth, as a fig tree shaken by a gale drops its unripe figs.
B066C006V014	66	6	14	And the sky parted asunder like a rolled-up scroll; and every mountain and island was moved out of its place;
B066C006V015	66	6	15	and the kings of the earth, and the princes, and the generals, the rich and the mighty, both slaves and freemen, every one of them hid themselves in the caves and among the rocks of the mountains.
B066C006V016	66	6	16	And they began to say to the mountains and to the rocks. "Fall upon us and hide us From the face of him who is seated upon the throne,  And from the wrath of the Lamb;
B066C006V017	66	6	17	For the Great Day of their wrath has come, And who is able to stand?"
